It's a bit ironic because the Airpods feel as though they move around more in your ear more than the Elite 65t, but because the stem acts as an anchor they stay in. I miss the Android compatibility and great features of the Elite 65t, but at least the Airpods serve the primary goal.

All this would lead me to a 2 star review. However, after owning these for about 2.5 months, they ceased to work and the primary bud (the right one) no longer turns on or charges. I've contacted Jabra support but not heard back from them (I only just contacted them, so I'm not holding the response time against them). I'll think about upgrading my rating if the customer support is really good.

Bottom line: these aren't ready for prime time again.

title: Great Headphones
content: Love these, had them for about six months now and easily my favorite headphones I've ever possessed. High quality and great sound, look great. No issues connecting to my iphone or my personal computer.

title: Cuts off while walking
content:
The product sounds good, the app is good, the microphones are decent.

However, the Bluetooth connectivity cuts off when you're walking and you have your phone in your pocket. It sounds like an old CD player and it's really annoying.

If you are thinking on enjoying music while walking, don't get these. I'm thinking on returning.

title: Won't stay put
content: I have a really hard time keeping them in my ears. I tried changing the size of the plastic piece. Over the last month of use I have dropped them several times. I am certain I will lose one one of these days. It's incredibly frustrating given how much I spent for them. I will say that they seem to have held up well given how many times they have hit the concrete.

title: The sounds
content: My wife loves them...

title: NOT for bass heads! Questionable ambient noise reduction!
content: Don't expect bass from these earbuds. The audio is clear,  great separation between buds but zero bass (no matter how you fiddle with the app's so-called sound customization). Secondly, I don't understand their ambient noise reduction claim. Recently, I was in an airport waiting area listening to techno. I could hear the conversation of the couple next to me as well as all flight announcements. I found no difference when I turned on the"hearthrough" feature. Now for the good: They actually stay in my ears! I've always had a problem with any earbuds fitting, but Jabra has done a great job ergonomically. Sometimes, after an hour so, my ears tire and I need to adjust the buds  slightly. I have a Google Pixel 2 and the earbuds consistently connect to my bluetooth the second they are out of their box. The carrying case is also small enough to fit in front pocket of my slim fit without looking too bulky.  And a feature not advertised: You can turn them on/off manually without using the case (in case you want to leave the case at home). Calls are clear per friends. Overall, this is a competent set of earbuds. But if this is one of the best, there's a lot of room for improvement in the wireless earbud market.

title: Did not work. Had it returned. They reimbursed the entire amount
content: It was a gift to a friend. We tried pairing it to our phones it as per instructions. However, it just refused to connect. On IoS or Android. Had it returned.

title: light and easy to use
content: very good wireless Bluetooth headphone. sound quality is great, and battery last long

title: Great EarPods, highly recommend
content:
These have been amazing!!! I bought these after researching several different brands of earbuds, and these had the best reports of voice quality on phone calls,  and the ability to only use one of the pods.
  Plus whether I’m at the gym, driving, running down the road, or mowing the yard I have no problems hearing my music!

title: These are Awesome
content: Nothing about these I don’t like. I use one side only for calls and put the other side in for music.  Battery life is great. Sound is great.  Couldn’t be happier.

title: Good
content: Would recommend

title: Wanted to Love this Product | Don’t buy they’re a waste of money
content:
I bought this product mainly for the microphone capabilties. I travel a lot for work and these seemed to be a better alternative to the Apple AirPods. The product failed to meet my expectations. While the sound quality and noise blocking is great for listening to music, watching movies, etc.. This product is marketed as great for phone calls as well. Let me be clear it’s horrible for phone calls.

The microphone does exactly the opposite of what its intend to do. It picks up ambient noise instead of blocking ambient noise. I first noticed this when talking to my wife on the phone while at a coffee shop. She asked me where I was and said that she could hear the bartisa making drinks like I was standing right next to them. In reality I was about 10-15 feet away. Normal headphones without ambient noise blocking microphones wouldn’t even pick that up.

I contacted Jabra support about this issue. They told me to update the firmware and unpair and repair with my devices. I did this and nothing has changed. I contacted support again as follow up and received a canned reply. So essentially contacting support is worthless.

If you’re looking for headphones to just listen to music while working out these might be ok, just make sure you get a good deal as they’re priced to do more than that.

title: Fantastic quality ear buds
content: Great sound (make sure you set the EQ in the app - before I did these didn't have much bass - once I set the sound up how I wanted it, they have plenty bass. These fit comfortably, snugly, and securely in my ears. I have yet to run out of battery - mostly because I charge often, but I have had a few period of listening at high volumes for nearly 4 hours. Very pleased with this purchase. Worth the money.

title: Good, but not great
content:
I got this on prime day sale, which made it a pretty good purchase.
Pros:
1. good sound quality, not the greatest but very good. I like the noise cancellation that comes with the item.
2. easy interface - Has a built in app to set the device to how you like your music and etc.
3. product detail - looks nice on the outside.
Cons:
1. while wearing the earbuds - they are not the most comfortable ear buds for someone with small ears they're kind of bulky.
2. appearance on smaller ears (gold) I think it looks bulky on someone with smaller ears, some things might be more noticeable because of the beige but if it was black wouldn't really be noticeable. The color may make a different, I notice that there aren't much pictures of the gold color on the models ears. If I had a chance to exchange the black one with gold I would do it.

They are good if you can get them at a discount. They look like hear aids lols. They are bulkier so if you have smaller ears, I would look somewhere else because they dont feel that great after long periods of use.

title: Long lasting comfortable ear buds.
content: Very comfortable fit, they actually go inside your ear tightly rather than just awkwardly sitting loosely around/in them. They last about 6 hours per charge.

title: Good Product, awful service
content: After having this product for a very long time one of the earbuds ceased working. This was after about two years of ownership so needless to say I had no complaint. However, the reason that it stopped working was sweat which, to my joy, was covered by a three year warranty. Now the reason I am giving such a negative review to such a great product is due to how I was treated after I attempted to get a warranty that I was owed. I stated the warranty process THREE MONTHS AGO and have not had the chance to communicate with an actual human until possibly a week ago. However, im still skeptical whether or not the person who emailed me was actual a human because even though I emailed them a week ago I have received no response. The communication is terrible and I have no idea whether or not im at a standstill. Unfortunately as well I have no way to check as the website makes it impossible to check into the warranty process once you have requested a ticket. Its an amazing product but when you buy it you subject yourself to the incompetence of jabra support. For that, I will never be returning to Jabra.

title: Defective, Broken, Junk
content: I purchased from Amazon Wharehouse on July 1st. As I am deployed to Iraq I had them shipped to my home and my wife shipped them to me overseas. That took right at a month. It is now Sep 13th, I have attempted to use the earbuds three different times, and they will not charge. More than 24 hours on the charger with flashing green light every time. Every time at between 9 and 10 min into music I get the first low battery warning. 10 min later I get it again. 2 minutes after that and the earbuds die and shut off and cannot be restarted. Might be great when bought new but I have to assume these were returned and sold through the Amazon Wharehouse at a slightly discounted price for this exact defect. Now I guess I am stuck trying to get some resolution from the manufacturer because I am outside of the Amazon 30 day return window. Don't know if it is across the board but the pair I received from Amazon Wharehouse was defective, broken, junk. Buyer beware.

title: Poor sound quality - returned
content: I bought these for my husband for work,  returned them immediately.  Sound quality is very poor

title: OK, but not great for exercise. Volume too low.
content:
These are OK. They seem to work for phone conversations and quiet listening, but the volume is too low and they are not ideal for exercise.

- Running: The earbuds stay put in my ears well, but their slight movement while running makes annoying "booming" noises when my feet hit the ground.

- Bicycling: The wind noise is terrible above about 8 MPH.

- Volume: The max volume is too low to be comfortably audible while lawn mowing with an electric mower.

- Phone conversation: works fine

- Charger: The pods in the charger are not symmetrical so you have to make sure to place the correct earbud into the correct hole.

- Bluetooth connection: is fast and stays connected, with only a few occasional brief dropouts. The "status" audio messages when connecting/disconnecting are startling and annoyingly loud. I bought these to replace my first attempt at bluetooth earbuds, TOZO T10 https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07J2Z5DBM  In terms of bluetooth connection, these Jabra Elite Active 65t earbuds work *much* better than the TOZO T10 ones - which used to drop out frequently.

- Battery life: good

title: Outstanding
content: The sound.

title: Some of the best overall earbuds at the moment
content:
I like them a lot but they have some things you just have to live with. I would say these are the best overall but it depends on what you’re looking for.

Pros
- Good sound
- Rather comfortable
- the app is nice
- battery life is standard
- Hearthrough feature is a nice item  necessary in some occasions

Cons
- The charging case. It’s not magnetic and sometimes difficult to open
- you have to use a finger hold so you don’t push the volume down back into your ear. This is to be expected though in this design
- it takes some time to learn your fit
- I wish you could add more profiles in the app but 3 is enough

title: Unstable Bluetooth Connection
content:
TL;DR; Avoid at all costs unless you love constantly resetting devices.

I want to love these, but the Bluetooth connection to my iPhone 7 (ios 12.4) is unstable at best. It seems there's no rhyme or reason to when and to which apps they will connect. For instance, if I'm listening to NPR via the NPR app, and then decide to switch to Spotify, the Bluetooth sync will inevitably fail between the two apps, and I'll need to either turn off the headphones and turn them back on, or reset the device by putting them back into their charging case. Sometimes, they'll fail to connect all together. The user experience of these is terrible, and leaves me more frustrated than any other piece of technology which I currently own. The sound quality when they are working is pretty good, and they feel pretty comfortable when they're in my ears.

title: Not value for money
content: Not value for money

title: Pretty good overall
content:
Got these in today.  They came charged and worked fine out of the box.  Easy pairing.  Needed the Jabra Sound+ App to control some of the settings.

Seems to fit pretty well in my ears.

Audio quality isn't as great as I was hoping for.  Definitely not great on the bass side.  Sounds better after adjusting the EQ in the app but still not super great.

I did test with some videos and not seeing any video sync issues people see with other true wireless headphones.

Physical controls are a little awkward. Need to push into your ear which can be uncomfortable.  Switching to the larger adapters seems to make it a bit more comfortable.

title: Pretty good headphone
content: Like them so far. Although I seem to have different shapped ears since the left one doesnt fit quite as well as the right ear piece.

title: Jabra proves wireless technology has come a far way, still has room for slight improvements.
content:
As an audiophile, I was very skeptical about diving into bluetooth technology as fundamentally, it does not carry full details of sound to your ears. I have always used flagship earphones/IEMs such as Sennheiser IE8's or Westone 3 etc and been very satisfied with sound. But over the years, even they have suffered wire damage due to repeated tugging and untangling during commutes or sweat around the ear and no matter that tangle-free technology they try, wires always tangle even in the best earphones. So recently after lot of friends shared positive experience with true wireless earphones, I thought of giving them a try.
I wanted to try Sennheiser momentums but they are too large and they have several software and battery drain issues which haven't been fixed so far..battery drain is a straight dealbreaker as my main reason for not going wireless was low battery..its a shame if your headphones now die before your smartphones battery.
Jabra repeatedly came up in all reviews and all suggestions and decided to simply order them.
Do note..These are not balanced armatures as used on most sound blocking high end IEMs ..but use dynamic drivers..which produce more bass but lack intricate details of sound in general in comparison.

Sound is great, Bass is full and nice punch to it....in the first few days..theres certain distortion to sound in bass heavy songs but it goes down as dynamic driver breaks in...but its still there in certain songs. The highs are crisp although missing details and loudness of my westone 3. The vocals are clear with accurate tonality of the singer.
Overall, they sound very good for bluetooth earphones and sound like a $80 pair of dynamic driver wired earphones out of the box....but these provide true freedom..i can walk around house, move my head freely..no microphonics of wired earphones.
There is clear stereo separation which is very impressive as most cheap earphones make sound feel 'in your head'.
The passive sound blocking is also very good as their snug ear anatomical fit blocks out noise in the trains.

The app EQ settings allow decent adjustments to sound and usually 'Energise' setting gives nice U-shape sound ideal for noisy commute as higher bass blocks out noise and elevated highs bring out life to the song.

The call quality is impressive as callers could hear me talk clearly even in a noisy city street.

My 2 main complaints:
- the earphones dont stick to case with a magnet..this is scary as opening case gives the feeling they might fall out or if some friend unknowingly tries to open them.
- the dynamic driver is small..and this results in bass not being as good as really expensive earphones and it can get muddy at times in very bass heavy songs...a larger sound driver in future models will solve this problem...but i guess jabra wanted small design hence they went with the choice.
- the buttons are very intuitively located and easy to use but they need to be softer or touch sensitive i guess as pressing volume button on left earphone pushes the earphone uncomfortably deeper into your ear.

I am keeping them now as they are the perfect commuter earphones and fun for lounging at home also...i will see how durable they are with test of time.

title: I wanted to like them
content:
On paper, these should be exactly what I have been looking for. High quality, wear all the time, especially workouts ear buds. In practice, they are just weird. First lesson - do NOT connect them to multiple devices. They may claim that works, but the management is really bad - switching from my iPhone to my PC arbitrarily. They are also pretty bad with phone calls - the microphone is very noisy and it stops working in the middle of conversations. This happened multiple times when I wasn't even near the PC. I was hoping for a more general solution. Instead, now I have them set to just my phone. Another issue is the left/right balance seems to be off. The left side seems to be lower volume and I can't fix it. I have to take out the right bud just to make sure the left is working. My base line comparison is the Bose QC20s. I love these earbuds, but I hate the wire. A similar price, but the Jabra does not have noise cancellation, and the sound quality seems much lower to me.
I will see how that works out, but it is a disappointment so far. I should be using them for my next call, but I am  still using the Bose.

title: Good but.....
content: Looked around - compared a range of BT earbuds.  J65T did everything well.  Sound quality very good.  BT connection stable.  Mic use during phone calls very good.  Software adequate but lots of minor annoyances (I'm a software engineer).  Excellent ergonomics.  Case is perfect size - love the case based recharge.  Bottom line: I use these earbuds all the time whereas in the past I only used earbuds on occasion.  Reason for my 4 star review - that's about as high as I go - I reserve 5-star for exceptional products.  4 star is very high praise.  One major issue:  Left earbud occasionally fails - take it out of the case and it won't connect.  (FYI: right earbud is "master"; it maintains the BT connection to source device; left earbud has nfc connection to right.)  Problem doesn't occur often but when it does it is very annoying.  Talked with Jabra support.  They were nice but weren't able to offer a definitive solution....problem remains.  When they don't connect I go thru the dance of power cycling - putting back in case, etc...eventually they connect but process takes 10 min or longer which is unacceptable.  Might force me to return or exchange.

title: Not all ears are the same
content: I want to love these unconditionally especially for what I paid for them.  They fit well and I don't feel like they're going to fall out of my ear.  However, after a little while wearing them, I feel this pressure on one spot on my ear.  Ears are basically the same shape, but mine are apparently not the same shape as these ear buds.  The sound is great.  I like the option to only wear one because when I run I like to be able to still have my situational awareness so it's nice that I can utilize that.  I wish either bud would functional independently of each other, but it's probably a technical nightmare to make that happen.  At the end of the day, I want to love these, but I only like them mostly because at the end of the day my ear needs a break from having it in.

title: Jabra vs Aria
content: I do like the Jabra, but once I got the Aria, the comparison is night and day, plus the Aria was $100, and waterproof... and fuller sound, better volume... connectivity is perfect...  the Jabra may have better range though.

title: Just accidentally dropped these in the toilet and they're still alive. What troopers!!
content:
I was about to write a raving review about how much I've been enjoying my headphones for the past 2 weeks, but something came in the way.

Not so fun story, but I was just peeing and had my headphones in the pocket (not a wise idea). As you can see this story gets tragic, with my right earbud falling straight into the toilet. I am so glad I didn't mechanically flush the toilet, but in stead recovered (almost in tears). I washed it off, wiped it off, and didn't want to wait to see if it was dead or not. It wasn't. Nothing is wrong with it. It is working perfectly fine and here I am completely in awe. I love these!

PS: never put devices into your jeans pockets and sit down to pee.

title: Great sound quality and comfortable fit
content: I love my wireless earbuds and keep them close always.  Sound is amazing and they are very comfortable in my ears.  The battery life lasts exactly as stated, although I wish it could be longer.  I’d like to wear a whole day and charge at night.  This was the gift I decided to purchase for myself from gift cards received.  Im happy and satisfied and use daily for the past two months.

title: I can run with them.
content:
Ok I've bought 4 different earbuds all less then $130. These being used and the most expensive. I can say this. They stay in my ears. I ran 7 - 1/2 miles with them in and had not one single signal loss or falling out of my ears.

My review. I synced these ear buds to my Samsung Galaxy S8 plus. Used the Google music app, and put the phone in my Camelback and on my back. Everything worked as it was designed. Now I can saw this. It's very important that you test the different size ear insert pieces. I didn't like any that came with. I have the hard rubber insert and size small. They seem to work best for my ear canals.

These are on the large size for earbuds. However they are not heavy and after an hour of continued use, I didn't have any soreness in my ears. I found them to be very comfy. Phone calls seem to not be an issue at all.

One thing that I had to get use to. And again this review is based on one 7.50 mile run. I had the feeling in my left ear that the earbud was getting loose or about to fall. When I checked, the Bud was still securely in place. I think it had not to do with the style of ear insert. There was absolutely no movement or need to re adjust during my entire run. I had flawless sound for a little over an hour run.  I even use one ear bud sometimes as a Bluetooth for phone calls while walking around. So bottom line. Yes it's a good buy. I got mine slightly cheaper used in like new condition. And I could not tell they were used so the discount price was perfect. I did get a cheap set no name brand of wish app. Used them once on some Hill sprints and they didn't fall out. My advice do your research on YouTube and try a few different options. Find what works for your lifestyle and budget. Again this is a one run review mild temperature and moderate sweating. Good luck, cheers.

title: Bummed I bought this..what a waste..going back to Platronics
content: The point of a phone call is so people can hear you. The noise cancellation is horrible. Everyone I talk to can't hear me and hear all the background noise. I never had this issue with Platronics. I could have my stereo on in the car and have a conversation with Platronics and no one would hear the stereo. This headset from Jabra, everyone noise is amplified. I have to take them off and go to speaker phone for people to hear me.

title: Great quality, superb battery life, BUT...
content:
Full disclosure: I only use headphones at the gym. I don't jog around town with earbuds, travel on a subway, or sit at a desk with headphones. Just the gym. And these earbuds were the first true-wireless bluetooth headphones I've ever purchased. (I've been rocking $20 Sony wired earbuds for my entire life)

PRO's:
- Super super easy to set up/pair/update firmware.
- Physical quality of the earbuds are fantastic.
- Battery life is craaaazy good.
- Fit is amazing. Even though it looks like they may fall out of your ears (due to no wing-tip-type things) they are IN THERE, even if I'm blasting away on the treadmill.
- Sound quality is about what I expected. Everything is real "bouncy" which I enjoy. Bass is there but not overpowering. But overall, real good.

CONs:
- Jesus Christ on the cross, there is a persistent hissing sound in the left earbud that apparently is just there forever. I'm actually on my second pair of earbuds because I thought the hissing was maybe a defective earbud, so after speaking with Jabra customer service, I was sent a replacement set. (It took way too long for the replacement to arrive, but that's a different story). To my sadness, the left earbud still has the faint hissing. Oh well. Maybe it's an issue that plagues all bluetooth headphones? Maybe I'm just a jerk who is too picky? There is no hissing in my $20 Sony wired earbuds...

CONLUSION:
It's great to not be encumbered by wires danging everywhere while I work out. The Jabra Elite 65t's sound great, they fit great, and I don't have to worry about ever running out of batteries (I keep the charging case in my car and just pop the earbuds back in there every day).

However... the hiss will slowly drive me insane. To be fair, my buddy has Jabra Elite 65t's (the non-active version) and he says he has no hiss. At any rate, would I recommend them? Yes, I would. If you want wireless earbuds, get these. They're great, and maybe your unit won't have that soft hiss. And if you're an audiophile, well, you probably aren't looking at wireless bluetooth earbuds.

title: Great product
content: Previous Bose owner.  These have great sound and will NOT fall out!!  Wish the battery would last a little longer but not a deal breaker.

title: LOVE THEM!
content: These wireless earbuds has took the place of my Beatz3 and I was not disappointed. I love them, audio exactly, battery life great and I only charged them once a week in wall port. great product.

title: Sound balance issue continues to be a problem even w/ latest 2.25.0 firmware
content:
Pros:
- Great battery life
- Compact case
- Amazing noise isolation (even better than Sony SP-700N active cancellation)
- Sound+ app is well designed
- Stable connection

Cons:
- Major issue is with the sound balance (google: "Elite 65t balance"). The issue persists even with the latest 2.25.0 firmware and seems to be more pronounced in the higher frequency range, meaning simply re-balancing amplitude left to right still doesn't feel balanced.
- The ear tips are shallow and feel insecure

title: JabraJunk Stay away quality of phone calls is poor
content: I have worked with Jabra and tried 3 different sets, all have the same problem of an "echo" and quality of sound on  a phone call at my end or the other end. I would not purchase these again or recommend them

title: Awesome
content: Great product

title: Can't get over the constant static
content:
Pros:
Good battery life
Nice design
Super convenient to not have cords

Cons:
Mediocre sound quality
Annoying static noises in earbuds

I bought these at Best Buy, but wanted to leave a review here to warn people about my experience with these headphones. First off, it's really nice not having cords. These are my first wireless earbuds, and it's super convenient. They are designed well and stay in your ear, and the battery life seems good.

The main issue is the static. I thought at first I had a defective pair of earbuds. Whenever the earbuds are active, they emit a somewhat subtle but definitely annoying static noises, especially from the right earbud. I don't like listening to my music particularly loud, so I constantly hear it over everything playing. After pausing audio I still hear it for about 20 seconds, and then it snaps off (I assume it goes into some power saving mode at that time). I exchanged the first pair for a new set (after going through all the firmware updates, resetting, blah blah etc etc troubleshooting), and they have the exact same problem. Either the hissing noise is on all units, or quality control is poor on this product - either way is not good.

Besides that, I probably wouldn't recommend this purely on the sound quality. It's just not that good. I'm not an audiophile by any means, but I've gotten $20 wired earbuds from Amazon that sound better than these. For $160, that's just not acceptable.

Would not recommend these. Not worth the money as you will a) be stuck with annoying background static on everything you listen to, or b) have spent $160 on mediocre sounding earbuds, which just feels bad.

title: Poor Fitting
content: I've tried with multiple custom earbuds to get these to stay in place while working out (walking is ok, but lifting or running when you start sweating and they pop out).  Controls for the device take a little getting use to and are ok.  Phone calls were clear and the sound are comparable to PowerBeats.

title: The greatest earbuds ever sold.
content: The greatest product I've ever purchased on Amazon. Look no further for headphones. I've been using these earbuds forever and God knows I love them. Excellent quality, superior battery life. I use them every day.

title: They are not suited for all working environments
content: This may be a scam company clearly. They clame these ear pods to be truly wireless but they are clearly not. If you run into a magnetic field they will stop to work properly. I tried to reach out to their technical support team and they offered me no solution other than a discount in other jabra products. Shameful

title: The quality of the ear-buds is unparalleled! Too bad the case designer wasn't the same!
content:
I would have given them 4 stars - but can't --- read-on:

I own two sets of these ear-buds - one for me and one for my son. The sound quality, and sound-cancelling quality, are unparalleled. I've tried Bose, Apple, Plantronics - and these are the best - by far - the very best. I use them in my work for electronic ear-plugs - and they work better than any ear plug I've ever had. Listening to the radio while mowing - fantastic- quality sound and above-par noise-blocking. You won't find better. They fit firmly and don't stick out like some bad scene from Star Trek like the Bose headsets that I took back after one day... That's the good!

The bad? THE CASE! It's horrible!! It's small, black, smooth, crappy latch, doesn't 'tell' the phone where it's located --- just generally crap. More than once I've accidentally dropped the glass-smooth black case - and it pops right open and the ear-buds go shooting out of the case as they're basically spring-loaded against the charging contacts inside the case - and then I go hunting for them.

So - To help guard the $80 case and the $100 headphones, I've 'augmented' mine with a piece of blaze-orange heavy-nylon strip, zip-tied to a sticky-back that's super-glued to the back of the case - with a Tile that's zip-tied to the nylon strap. The case itself has a velcro cable-strap that's super-glued to the case back-and-bottom that then wraps around one end of the case when it's closed.

But then again, maybe Jabra meant the case to be so crappy so people would lose them and have to go buy more?!

title: Very Disappointing Sound
content: Very poor sound quality in my pair. I kept getting intermittent, loud, staticky pops from these. I get much better sound from a $25 pair of Anker Bluetooth headphones.

title: Nice product
content: Just received them yesterday.  So far love them.  Found they have an app to control and better instructions.  The instructions that came with them is pretty vague. Love that you are able to control how much noise cancellation you need. .

title: Too expensive for what you get
content:
I was looking for a pair of well built wireless headphones with quality sound to use while running.  They stay in place, feel sturdy (well-built), and seem to be made from quality materials.  However, I expect much better sound quality for the price.  Either using tidal streaming service, or high quality digital audio files (no less than 44.1 kHz), they sound no different than poorly ripped mp3s.

I would recommend spending less money on a different brand

title: Eare pain
content: The quality is very good but it's not comfortable for using all the day and I get ear pain after using whole day even via small plugs

title: They get the job done
content: I like them. They stay in your ear while doing cardio, running specifically. They have great sound quality and let u adjust bass, treble etc accordingly and the hearthrough feature work great to act like u cant hear the outside world but you can still hear great

title: Highly recommended don't make my mistake.
content: When I first put these in the fit was very bad so uncomfortable. I was ready to send them back within the hour....DUH! I had them in backwards, left in right. right in left. Once corrected these are the most awesome stupendous earbuds I have ever used. They are my first wireless.

title: Solid ear buds
content:
I like em.  The app is a nice tool and I am using the step counter.  For something you stick in your ear they are comfortable

  Highly recommend.

title: Good headsets if you manage to get a non-defected pair
content:
I bought these on Black Friday when they were on sale and immediately noticed a static sound in the left earpiece. I was told to update the earbuds, which they were so I re-pushed the update. It still did not fix the issue. I went and got a newer pair but alas, that one had the same issue! Here were some of the things I noticed,
 - The static sounds goes away when there is nothing playing and the phone is not being used
 - As soon as I play something or use my phone, the static sound is continuous
 - The static sound is louder when the volume goes over the recommended volume

I enjoyed the headsets while I used them but I did not want to go back and get it replaced over and over again. I am going to return these and look elsewhere.

title: A good buy under 100$ probably.  Not worth 150$ in 2019.
content: I’ve owned many different true wireless earbuds and these were ok.  They just weren’t 100$ better than my JLab JBuds Air and that’s why they went back.  The Jabras also stretched my ear out when I put them in which was somewhat uncomfortable at first.

title: Return
content: I really liked the product at first and for use around the house but when I took it to the gym is when the disappointment came on. I don’t know what it was but the left earbud had a lot of static and cutting out. This only happened at the gym and changed as I turn my head in different directions.

title: Ok, but not as great as advertised
content: The Bluetooth connection was spotty at times and they didn’t stay in my ear all that well. They were alright, but not for the price I paid for them. I ended up returning them and purchasing from Bose.

title: The World's Off Switch
content: I bought these because I needed something that would make my inner audiophile happy while I could maintain situational awareness in the world around me(the Airpod memes convinced me). These things are amazing at what they do. Imagine, if you will: You are chilling in your favorite coffee shop listening to your music in the background, still able to hear the keystrokes on your laptop as you type up an amazon review and waiting to hear for your coffee order to come out. You hear the sweet sound of your name being called and you're thinking of the beautiful caffeinated liquid you're about to receive, when suddenly your favorite song comes on. A simple double tap of the right ear bud and you're transported to a delightful world of audio tranquility unparalleled by any other. These things are truly a miracle. They don't completely tone out obnoxiously loud people around you, but they certainly will make the annoyance that is the human existence significantly less noticeable.

title: Best Wireless Bluetooth Earbuds on the market
content: I have tried several brands of BT earbuds, one from a recent Kickstarter project, and found them all to be poor quality.  You really get what you pay for.  I use these for running and when I travel to Asia.  They are comfortable, thanks to the many choices in ear pads. The sound quality is superb and battery life fits my requirements. Unlike all the other buds I have used these remain paired with the source at all times, an annoying feature of low cost units. Don't waste your time and money on inferior earbuds, these are the top of the line.

title: Wayyy better that airbuds
content:
The sound quality is far superior to the airpods.  I love that they stay in your ear when exercising and also filters out the ambient noise in the gym, you know the crappy gym music that they blare forgetting that fact that EVERYONE is listening to their own music.  FYI they even have a feature that allows the ambient sounds to filter in if you want.

Also, you can answer the phone with your voice, just say "answer" or "ignore" through the Earbuds.

title: They stay in my ear!!
content: I've done super sweaty long runs with these and they are super comfortable! I'm very surprised that they stay in my ear the entire time, don't bother my ears, and have great sound quality. I'm really happy I purchased these.

title: Ok but room for improvement
content:
Pros:  pairs with devices easily and quickly.  included features are great and like the app features as well.  the sound quality is clear but not loud or bassy.  The case is nice and small.

Cons: Looks good but feels cheap.  For the price, need more comfy in-ear thingy to swap.  The sound quality is ok but could use a boost in both volume and sound quality.

title: Bad interference and terrible customer support
content: For $180, I expected much more from the actual product and from the company itself with customer service issues.  Originally, I had issues with terrible interference with these (wasn't an occasional skip...my podcasts or songs would be jumbled and would stop for minutes at a time).  After calling/writing customer service, I received a generic/template response on how to reset the earbuds...surprise, surprise - it didn't work.  I was planning on returning, but unfortunately, I dropped and damaged the right earbud.  Instead of being out the full $180, decided to purchase a replacement right earbud for $60.  My color (Blue/Copper) was apparently on "backorder" for single earbuds, but when purchasing, it specifically said "It will be shipped out 2-3 weeks or sooner".  It has been almost 8 weeks.  I have sent 3 or 4 support emails where I don't get any type of response other than a "we've received your email" type reply. And after calling customer service 3 times the past few weeks, I only get an acknowledgement that it's still on back order and they have no idea when it will be received.  Keep in mind that full new sets have been in stock this entire time.  For a customer who's spent $240 in the past 3 months on poorly functioning earbuds, a company should be attempting to make this right (send me a new full set, or remove the right one from one of the new sets).  Either way, we're venturing into customer service treatment comparable to dealing with a cable company or cellphone carrier, where it's a complete waste of time and extremely frustrating with no resolution.  I commute for work and exercise multiple times a week, so my earbuds are important to my everyday routine.  I really wish I had gone with another brand originally and really wish I hadn't accidentally damaged mine to then feel like I need to buy the replacement part or lose out on the full $180.  I strongly encourage people to take their business elsewhere.

title: The Perfect Set of Wireless Earbuds!
content: I've used Jabra products over the years - mainly for wireless headsets with my cell phone.  After trying Beats and Koss wireless headsets for music (two ear pieces with a connecting wire/controls), I just didn't care for the fit and lack of comfort - especially at the gym.  I finally decided to try the Jabra Elite 65t earbuds and COULD NOT BE HAPPIER!! The sound quality is pretty darned amazing … the smartphone app is easy and powerful (try the Hear-Through feature for extra coolness!) … they are super-comfortable, even when working out hard at the gym.  I use a single earbud at the office and it's comfortable and not overtly obvious when I need to speak with a colleague. I cannot recommend these highly enough!  Definitely not the cheapest, but definitely worth the investment!

title: Extreme durability!!
content:
I purchased these headphones in November 2018 and been using them everyday since
Pros:
They have a comfortable and secure fit.
Easy pairing with multiple devices.
Great sound quality.
Great battery life, I listen for about 2 hours a day and I charge the case once a week.

Cons:
The pass through sound feature is not great. Most times it blocks out ambient sounds even when I want to be able to hear them.
The microphone is not great, you have to speak quite loudly to have a good conversation.
The volume and track buttons are on the earbuds and you have to press on them. This is not comfortable as you end up pushing the ear piece into your ears. A touch style interface would have been better.

Importantly, I am writing this review because I am surprised by its durability. I accidentally put these through a full wash cycle. The earpieces (minus the case) were washed. I had no hopes they would work. However, they paired with my phone after a brief charge. I let them dry in the sun for a day and no the speakers work great. The sound is even better than before as I am guessing some of my ear wax was washed off the speakers. It’s amazing!

5 stars for durability!!!

title: Outstanding Sound and Voice
content: I researched, debated, researched again and decided to go with the Jabra Elite Active 65t (instead of having something that looked like a Q-Tip dangling from my ear).  The Jabra's are very discreet.  It was the right choice - I love these earbuds!  Pairing with multiple devices was easy and the controls are simple and straightforward - no multiple buttons to push.  Three sizes of ear tips are included.  The trick for a good fit seems to be inserting the earbud and twisting down gently.  The sound is excellent and the "hearthrough" option allows you to adjust how much outside sound you want to hear while wearing them.  Since the right earbud is the "master" to the left "slave", I often just wear the right one for phone calls.  People have told me that the voice quality is perfect and they weren't even able to tell when I put in the earbud and switched from phone to the Jabra during a call.  They have a good range and there is an audible tone when I walk out of range so I know when I get too far from the phone.  I'm surprised how much I like these and have recommended them to others.

title: Nice Quality with Amazing sound
content: I have had these ear buds for 24 hours now and have listened to about 10 hours of music threw them and let me say... These sound amazing.  They fit good in the ear and don't wanna fall out even when I am moving around.  They have good bass and they feel like high quality which is to be expected for the price of this item.  The only thing I do not like about them is that when I take one of them out of my ear it pauses my music.  I'm hoping the Jabra App will allow me to change those settings but its not that big of a deal just a little annoying.

title: Fit great and awesome sound!
content: Fit great and awesome sound

title: Great sounding workout ear buds
content: Great for working out at the gym, but not so great for phone calls.  Picks up wind and background noise during phone calls.

title: Perfect for the active college student
content: I am a busy college student and my two main focuses are studying and exercise. These earbuds are perfect for both. They provide a fairly comfortable feel while staying securely in the ear while jogging/running. The option of being able to hear the surrounding noise is fantastic for when jogging on a busy road. The battery life is fantastic and will last all day. The feel of the earbud does take some getting used to but it will work. The design is also fantastic. The navy and copper color scheme is an asthetically pleasing one. My onlys complaint are that the charging case does not have magnets to hold the buds in place and that the case is difficult to open at first. Other than that they are phenomenal earbuds that provide fantastic sound quality and a secure fit. Worth every penny

title: Great value, battery life, good sound quality, nice app with extra features
content:
I'm coming from mid-range earbuds that I've been using for several years, and these have really impressed me on all fronts.
Sound quality is great for my usage (probably 75/25 podcasts/music), I'm no audiophile but everything sounds great.
Comfort is so-so, which depends highly on the size & shape of your ears. These fit snugly with the default silicon tips for me, though on longer runs they sometimes shift out of place, which causes discomfort & requires a re-adjustment. Not a deal-breaker, but should be noted.
Noice cancellation is good for a set of earbuds (as opposed to on- or over-the-ear headphones). Its minor, but its there. What's really helpful for me is the sound passthru which sends outside sounds into the earbuds. This helps increase my awareness when running around town - I can hear cars approaching, for instance - but still can easily hear my music or podcasts.
Button controls are just OK. They work, but sometimes using them moves the buds around in your ear, either causing discomfort or requiring re-positioning. Still, they work but require some learning too, like any similar set.
Battery life is great, as-advertised for the most part from what I can tell. The case is great for storage & charging.
Other notable features:
-pairing is super easy (iPhone), and re-pairing is great. You simply remove them from the case, they automatically power on and pair to the device if its in range. You're ready to go in a couple seconds.
-Call quality is great, as is the mic quality from what people have told me. However, sometimes my phone gets confused and gets into a mode where nothing is accepting my voice; the earbuds, the phone, or the speakerphone. I can hear the other person, but no matter what input I switch to, they cannot hear me. It doesn't happen every time, but it has happened about 10% of the time, which is strange.

title: Callers report there is an echo on their end.
content:
Update****
The issue with the echo ended up being the "fit" to my ear. The ear buds come with a medium rubber insert that was very uncomfortable so I swapped to the small which apparently was the root of the issue. I swapped back to the medium and although uncomfortable the echo problem is resolved.

I have had these for about 6 months. I bought these specifically to travel and talk for the noise cancelling. Several callers reported back to me that they hear themselves talk when they speak but hear me fine and I do not hear it. I have completed firmware updates and finally and had the first pair replaced. No change. They are poor sound quality for music as well. I recommend staying away from these.

title: first blush
content:
unbox and go: everything worked except the left earbud had no audio. test was amazon music app.
 i avoided the mobile app (3.1 stars). i plugged the box/battery in, put the earbuds in the box, and waited 3 minutes.
tried them over again, without pushing any buttons. both buds just worked.

optimistic, but: have not yet tried calls, etc.
update: i took delivery of this, the new product, not the refurbished.  photos over there. oops.

tl;dr
the unboxing revealed great intelligence. packaging frustration-free by default, yet highly protective of the electronics inside.
there is only a QuickStart guide; why use up paper on “slow, complicated start”, imo.

title: Good tech for a fair price
content: I was nicely surprised of how these fit out of the box, didnt have to fiddle with them just put them right on and started listening after installing the app. Tweaked the eq a bit and they sound great for BT earbuds, and I own Westone W80 and 64audio U18t so i know what good stuff sounds like. The case I'm not a fan of as it should have a mechanism together opened ad it's quite hard to open them sometimes.

title: A couple of problems
content:
I've had the Jabra Elite Active 65t ear buds for about 3 months. Most of that time I have enjoyed the product however there are some huge downsides that had I know from the beginning would have lead me to chose a different pair.
1) These ear phones are not comfortable. The thing about these ear pieces is that they are huge! So huge my wife can't even use them. I spent the first month of owning these headphone getting used to the way these earbuds stretched out my ear, often painfully. If you have large ears, this wouldn't be a problem but if getting used to these will be painful if you have average or smaller ears.
2) The biggest problem is their bluetooth connectivity just fails randomly. I just spent about 30 minutes this morning trying to get the device to connect to either my phone or laptop. The earbuds of course were screaming in my ear to go to my bluetooth settings and connect. But the device could not make a connection to either device, Yes the could find it and even pair but not connect. After a while I gave up, turned the earbuds off for a while and when I came back they worked immediately. This is not an isolated experience either as similar scenarios have occurred 4 or 5 times since I bought these.
3) The microphones on the device are not great. While making a phone call through the earbuds is not usually a problems. The earbuds are relatively sound proof but boast a hear through feature to allow you to pay attention to your surroundings. Unfortunately, the microphones don't even pick up enough for you to have a decent face to face conversation with some one. While I personally take out earbuds when talking face-to-face to people, this translates to other the hear through feature failing miserably on more difficult tasks like when someone is trying to get your attention or a person is walking up behind you.

title: Not for people with small ear holes!
content: I really wanted these to work for me. I was looking for a relatively discrete pair of wireless earbuds for filming videos while receiving feed and for walking and talking. And these we recommended as top of the line. I dished out the cash...but no good.  Even though I tried all of the ear plug sizes,they wouldn't stay in my ears and they were very painful...which has been a common problem for me with all small earbuds. I guess I never realized how small my ear holes are. You really don't walk around comparing ear hole sizes, now do you? Ahhh well... I'm going back to over the ear phones. If you have big ear holes and you don't want to be active when you use these, these may be perfect for you. Good luck!

title: Comfortable to wear and very well made
content: Awesome sound and comfortable to wear. They seem like they are very well made. Extremely happy with the purchase.

title: Best earbuds offered anywhere!
content: Amazing headphones, sound quality is amazing and the bluetooth is quick on the draw. Connects immediately and charges well, I use them daily for work and the phone calls have great sound and others can hear me really well. The reviews made me a little nervous but I wanted to try them as they're the top of almost every chart I found for comparing true wireless earbuds online. The microphones a little sensitive in my opinion as callers can hear every small sound around me, but I can only assume that's to help being able to hear as the microphones far back from your mouth. Amazing product, will definately buy again if anything happens and my warranty is up.

title: Great battery life, very good sound and sound dampening
content:
I've been using these all summer, mainly while I mow my lawn for 45 minutes or so once or twice a week. What a difference it makes having no cable connecting headphones to a device. These earbuds fit my ears just right with the larger silicone tip and once they've settled in It feels like sound is just emanating into my ears with no source. They're very light and comfortable - your mileage may vary, of course, as ear shapes are all different.

They pair just like any other bluetooth device and the connection is pretty solid. I've only had a couple of instances where they simply would not connect to my iPhone, as if one of the devices forgot about the other. Don't fight it, trust me - it won't work. Just remove the entry for the Jabra headphones and re-pair.

Sound quality is very good. I personally don't hear any degradation in the sound due to being transmitted over bluetooth but other, maybe younger ears may pick up on what other reviewers are hearing. They're a little bass-heavy, but the Jabra app that needs to be installed on your device gives you an adjustable EQ which helps personalize things.

The app also allows you to set up pass-through sound, which means you can vary how much outside sound makes it through to your ears. I don't personally need this feature - if someone wants to talk to me, I feel like I need to remove my headphones and actually appear to be tuned in to them. I keep this off for my lawn mowing duties - I really don't want to listen to that!

The charger-case is great as well. The headphones slip right into their spot and there's only one way they'll fit, so the charging spots will always connect. There's also a light between the headphones that will appear when they connect to the case, and if you miss that, there's another light on the bottom when the lid is close to show that it is charging. Somehow, with about 10 weeks of mowing, I have yet to need to charge this case, so the battery life of 15 hours seems pretty legit.

title: Extremely poor app. Low Volume
content: Extremely poor app. Low Volume,Sub par bass. 5.0 my ass. Disconnects halfway across the dam house. I saved up for these.I'm pissed.They are going back.  The Treblab X2 BLOW THEM AWAY. I am a consumer not a paid reviewer.

title: Best wireless buds for workouts!!
content: Best wireless device for workouts. Great for running and at the gym, didnt get to touch or adjust during my recent 6 mile run with all sweat. Battery life is great as well

title: Worth the money.
content: Was a bit hesitant buying due to price but is well worth the money.  I use it on all my plane trips.

title: Hubby loves them!
content: Purchased these for my husband in hopes they would drown out my snoring! Not so good for that but he loves the sound and quality for music!

title: Like that you can turn volume up or down while in ear.
content: Really like these.

title: Too many complaints about a bud going dead.  Mine did as well.
content: Initially the earbuds worked great. It never had that great of bass but got used to that. Sound clarity was good and could still ambient sounds fairly well.  After 5 months of use the right earbud sound quality declined all of a sudden.  I could barely hear anything out of that right bud. The left seemed fine.  The third party sales company said sorry and the original manufacturer said the same. So overall I can’t use them anymore because they no longer serve the original purpose and cant return it. Its a shame.

title: Outstanding
content: These earbuds are outstanding. Great sound and comfort and the bluetooth connection hasn't failed. I have purchased 3 pairs for me and my family.

title: They're Worth What I Paid...
content:
After a few days of research and development, overall I am pleased with the Elite Actives. I got these on sale for $159 plus 20% additional cash back, so essentially I only paid $128. Let me say however, these are not worth the regular price of $189.

Fit is very good for me. I've read many reviews citing a poor fit, or they don't stay in. I've not had that problem, even while sweating profusely in the rain. The finish on the actives makes all the difference, and I am thoroughly impressed thus far.

I'm satisfied with the sound, but I don't feel they sound as good as my Jaybird Freedom X3's, or even the Bose Soundsport Free. They do sound better than the Airpods though. Sound+ app is necessary so you can adjust the equalizer to meet your preference. You won't be blown away by the bass, but it's decent enough. With an asking price of $189, I expect the sound to be better. The hearthrough feature is good as well, but it does sound somewhat 'tinny'. I find myself using it often because it saves me from having to pop a bud out when my coworker is talking to me.

Many reviews have commented that the sound levels of the left/right buds are off, or the right bud is much quieter than the left one, or one of the buds stopped working completely after a short time...
Lest I forget the hundreds of reviews mentioning the poor/horrible customer support from Jabra.
For now, I've yet to experience any of these issues. This particular copper/black pair, exclusive to Amazon, came from the fresh batch that they received last week. I'm hoping some of the recurring issues have been solved, and I will update this review in the future if something happens.

I would recommend the Jabra Elite Actives if you can manage to get them on sale. If you're an audiophile, you'll probably be disappointed by the sound, but that's not to say they don't sound good. True wireless tech is still in it's infancy stage, and the sound quality will continue to get better. That said, the Jabra Elite Active 65t's are in my opinion one of the current front runners.

title: Great but need an accessory
content:
Love these buds,
Better than Apple’s
But when I get in and out of my wheelchair they fall out of my ears. Do you have any suggestions or accessories to help me???

title: Best of all possible worlds
content:
After being sorely disappointed by a pair of Revols brand wireless earbuds on a Kickstarter campaign, I went in search of a replacement.  When the Revols were first up on Kickstarter, they had a lot of unique, advanced features.  But they took 2+ years to deliver, and the market caught up to them.  These earbuds do everything the Revols promised me,often better than the Revols, and they cost less.

They pair effortlessly, and will even connect to multitple devices simultaneously with no complaints.  Every so often, if I take them out & leave them on my desk (not in the charging case) for a while, the left bud doesn't come back to life with the right when I reinsert them & continue playing my content.  A quick insertion into the case seems to fix this.

And that's my biggest complaint.  Sound quality is very good.

People I speak with on the phone tell me they have no clue I'm on earbuds.  I expected this from Jabra- part of the reason I chose them- and they appear to have delivered.

The ability to let some outside sound in is handy in an office, walking city streets, etc.

All buttons/functions work flawlessly.  Power, volume up/down, etc.  No issues whatsoever.

Batteries seem to give me 4+ hours on initial charge.  This is enough for most days in the office.  If you remember to put them back in the charging case when you step away from your desk for break, etc., they last well beyond all day, even with near constant use.

Biggest problem with the Revols was that even the small size molding tips were way too large for my ears, and the outside of my ears would be sore after a few hours of use.  (They didn't use the outside of the ear canal as the pressure point, but the cartilage of the outer ear.. long story)  These cause me no discomfort, and despite the fact that they do use the outer ear canal for the pressure/anchor point, they are VERY difficult to shake out.  I imagine if you took a header while jogging, you might lose them, but short of trauma, they're stable & secure.

Highly recommend these if they are within your price range.  Zero significant complaints or issues, good sound quality, and feature rich.

title: Terrible connectivity
content: The connection kept breaking up and sometimes while walking for a few seconds at a time. The connectivity issue was just not acceptable. Retuned the product within 3 days of receipt. Definitely would not recommend buying these

title: Great Headphones so far!
content: I just received these headphones yesterday and I used them for about an hour yesterday working out. They worked great! I was looking for something that wouldn't fall out when working out and these stay put! I read the reviews and that is what I based my decisions off of. The reviews were mixed, but I decided to try anyways and they have been working great!

title: Great fit
content: Doesn't come out. Good sound.  Extreme noise canceling, cant hear any road noise

title: Distance is greater than I expected.
content: I have never used a pair of wireless earbuds before so I was pleasantly surprised by the distance. It says 35 feet but I had it connected to my phone, which was in one side of the house and I was listening to music on the other-side (I was in the back yard) with no exact measurements if I had to guess I'd say 65 feet. No disconnects.  Can't beat that.

title: Perfect commuter earbuds
content: Nothing to complain about. The negative reviewers work for Sennheiser ;-)

title: Moderate product
content: Still slips the ears ... noise cancellation is average

title: Overall Good Product
content:
I like these headphones so far (had them for two days). As one reviewer said, they're the best out there but they do have their flaws. On the good side, they stay connected to the phone quite well (I have an iPhone 7 with IOs 12) and I enjoy being able to walk around the room while on a call. They're very easy to use, and they do a decent job of passively blocking outside noise when listening to music. They fit in my ears very nicely and I don't have to worry about them falling out. I also love that when I receive a call, they tell me who is calling so I don't have to take the phone out of my pocket.

As for sound quality, they're good for what they are. They are not going to excite an audiophile and I won't be using them to mix an album. But the sound of music is clear and strong and it's fine for listening to music on the commute. They don't have a very strong bass, but the cool part is you can customize the EQ using the app to your preferences including more bass. I did find that the connection stutters a bit when the phone is in my pocket and I take a big step or do something that shakes the phone (like stepping off of a high curb). Doesn't happen with smaller movements.

As for quality of phone calls, I'm not amazed but they work well enough indoors. I live in NYC and had hoped they would allow me to have a conversation while walking on the street. It's extremely loud here so I wouldn't expect a miracle, but the person on the other end couldn't hear anything I was saying and only heard street noise. The phone was in my pocket and the reception was poor, which I don't think should happen and it's a downside of these headphones. For calls in a car, or an my office, they work really well and I can walk around the room without a problem. They pick up a good amount of noise including typing which can be annoying on a call.

This product is not perfect, but from reading many reviews by experts and non-experts, it seems they're the best thing out there in a field of products that are pretty new. It will get better. It's really nice to not have a wire hanging out, catching on things, pulling the headphones out of my ear and out of the phones. You'll have to decide for yourself if the benefits outweigh the limitations.

title: The Jabra Elite are awesome!!!!!
content: They work excellent. A good product I recommend them.

title: Not worth the money...
content: These are not worth the price.  I run outdoors and as soon as I start to sweat they fall out.  I ran 4 miles today and they fell out twice.  I also have problems getting them to stay connected.  Not worth the hassle.

title: Great earbuds with a few caveats
content:
These are the best earbuds I've owned, but they're still a ways from perfect

1. It helps to have average or above sized ears
2. They fit very tightly and that'll cause discomfort until your ears get used to it
3. They don't always hit the right angle on the ear canal. When they don't, they feel more like earplugs than headphones
4. The app is flukey. It stopped being able to "see" the connected buds after about a week and I uninstalled it for now (iOS)
5. The gold looks nice but the plastic around it is the color of a 1990s computer. If I had to order again, I'd go with the blacks
6. Like all true wireless earbuds, they'll lose the left-right connection if left idle for too long. You'll need to put them back in the charger case, close the case, then take them out again to fix it. This is probably okay since it'll reinforce the habit of always putting the earbuds in their case so you don't lose one.
7. Like all self-charging cases, this one is a bit clunky. It'll fit in my pocket but has a noticeable bulge.

These are, overall, great headphones. They will connect to my iPhone and Apple Watch at the same time ("two devices connected"), hold a good charge, and they stay in during a hard workout (amazing, really) despite having no ear hooks. The sound isn't exactly that of a reference monitor but they're literally earbuds. This s*** was sci-fi ten years ago. Stop complaining.

title: Fantastic Earbuds!!!!
content: I got these as a gift from my girlfriend and must say that I love them. I am the person that believes Apple overprices certain items and they are not worth it. I did not like the look of the AirPods and how they literally hangout your ear. These I will say get the job done. It works seamlessly with the iPhone. Some people complained about static issues and I have yet to have that issue and I got these for Xmas. I will say my one complaint will be that they do not stay in my ear as initially hoped. Idk if it is because I have small ears or what but they tend to pop out when I start sweating. That is about the only negative for me right now. But overall a great product and none of you guys will be disappointed!

title: I'm really enjoying these wireless earbuds!
content: I've had them for almost 2 weeks and they are great.  I was worried about sound pic up from the mic but no issue so far and I've used them in the car, in my home and in the office.  I can't wear them all day though - comfort but that's not a problem.  The charging case is effective.  I do wish it didn't always have to be the right earbud that stays in if you wanted to leave one out and still use.  Maybe on a future model they could fix that?  Overall - great product for the price.

title: Great, for the three months they work.
content: Bought my pair as a birthday treat for myself in October 2018, by the new year my left earbud went dead. I tried contacting Jabra about it, filed a claim and everything but the customer service is terrible. After taking over a week to contact me through email, they had me troubleshoot the problem but nothing worked. I tried to get a replacement pair but the company just kept trying to troubleshoot the problem. After 5 minutes on Reddit I found there is a common problem with the charging case where a magnet shifts out of place so it does not charge the earbud. It is over a year after I originally bought the Jabra Elite 65t earbuds and now both earbuds do not work, and I have switched to a new brand. I am dissatisfied with spending over $150 on a pair of earbuds that do not even last a year.

The Jabra was louder and sounded a bit better, and aren't as bulky, but they still disconnect from time to time.  In addition, I'm a big guy and sweat a lot, so I had to order larger foam earcups.  This worked, however with the larger earcups you can't fit the earbuds into the charging cradle (sigh).  Switching back to Jaybird X3s until the tech gets better.

title: They fall out, get scratched easily, has bugs, and you can't just use left one/share one piece
content:
They fall out - When I strain at the gym, I tend to contract my facial muscles. When I do, it wiggles the earbuds out of my ear and I keep having to adjust them. This doesn't happen with other earbuds, only this one.

They get scratched easily - The plastic used on the earbuds and the case get surface scratches very easily.

They have bugs - Sometimes the buttons stop working when the earbuds are on, and I have to put them into the case and take them out to reset them. They sometimes make a subtle clicking noise/lose connection for a brief moment even with the phone within 3ft range.

You can't just use left one/share one piece - If you decide to use just one earpiece, it has to be the right one. You cannot do that with the left piece. You also can't share music with someone else unless they're within 1 ft of each other and not moving around.

title: Satisfied so far - one month in. Primarily used for workouts
content:
After my stock apple ear pods gave up the ghost, I spend a long time researching true wireless buds.  I have a pair of ATH M50x over-ear headphones for my work music & focus fix that has served me well but are unsuitable for active wear.  I was willing to spend a bit extra to get a bit extra, and the form of the Jabra Elite Active 65t's, their weight, and the reviews of their sound quality/ workout niche all checked the right boxes.  The price point was still a smidgen too high but I decided to go ahead and purchase.  Glad I did!

My Pros:
- small carrying case: I really like the size.  It is about the size of 3 chapsticks put side by side.
- firm case latch:  other reviews dislike the lack of magnetic locking mechanism, and the Elite 65t case apparently didn't' close as well.  This case has a satisfying snap when closing that does not fall open in my pocket or gym bag, but also can be opened with one hand (thoughI have larger hands)
-decent passive noise isolation
-good voice/call quality
-good sound
-the hear-through feature is amazing, especially when I am biking and need to be aware of surroundings while still enjoying my beats.
-great connectivity with my iPhone 7.  Bluetooth range is fantastic.
-slim profile
-ability to control the playback from earbud buttons.  TBH I don't use this feature very much, though yesterday it was convenient while biking to be able to turn the volume down without pulling out my phone.

Cons:
-the buttons:  They are a bit stiff.  perhaps this will change with time but pushing them without holding the earbud from the other side mashes the Jabra Elite Active 65t further into my ear canal.  Not a fun sensation.
-difficult to find the right fit.  I give credit to Jabra for including the separate tips but it still took me a solid 2 weeks to finally figure out the set up that gives me the best comfort/sound.
-adjustment required:  They are not always just pop in and forget about them.  I need to adjust them every so often to tweak with the comfort level or the sound
-moisture wicking:  perhaps I am an exceptionally sweaty person, yet while the Elite Active's "grip" the ear firmly they sometimes slide out especially during mat exercises.  It's not a huge deal because I am already lying down and can easily find them, but still a noteworthy.

Overall I am very pleased with these headphones. It has only been 6 weeks so I will update later should something drastic happen but for what I need them for -workouts and activities that are unsuitable for my headphones, these are great.

The Jabra App is pretty cool too letting me customize i.e. how much sound I want to be piped in with the hear-through feature.

I would recommend this to anyone who wants something less obtrusive than the Air-Pods, that still has great connectivity and better sound.

title: Appeared to be the perfect design but proved to be deeply flawed.
content: I was really excited to get these headphones.  I'd been looking for an in-ear wireless solution that was sleek and would stay in my ears while running or working out.  The great reviews from the wirecutter and on amazon had me convinced that these were my solution.  However, it didn't take long for the problems to surface.  My biggest problem was that these hurt your ears.  I tried all of the different attachments but could never find something comfortable.  Generally, I would run for the first mile with no problems but by mile 2 I had to take them out cause they were giving me such a bad ear ache.  The same tended to be true at the end of a workout.  Having them in too long just got too uncomfortable for the compact design to be worth it.  My second major complaint ended up being the sound quality.  After 5-7 uses the audio started to get crackley.  Pretty soon they sounded more like a $40 set.  Better to pay up for the Bose wireless or the Platronics wrap arounds if you are a bit more price sensitive and don't mind the aesthetic.  Might be that these just didn't work for my ears but I can't recommend at this point.

content: I've had these for two days now. I have the original Samsung Iconix which was nice but the battery life was horrible but everything else was superb. I saw where the Jabra gave you 5 hours of battery life plus two full charges so I decided to give them a try. The sound quality is very good, not great. If you like "heavy bass" with your music then these might let you down but for "in ear earbuds" they sound very good. The build quality is excellent, so far they feel great in my ear and I have yet to suffer from "ear fatigue." The case does not "easily pop open" like others suggest but the air buds themselves are not magnetic so when you do open the case be careful they do not fall out. To help with the sound quality I recommend you down load the Jabra app which allows you to play with the EQ settings and enhance the sound. All in all I'm very satisfied with these and would highly recommend them.

title: Best wireless workout buds for the money
content:
Some of the best Bluetooth headphones I have used. I work out almost daily, often running (4-5 miles at a time). Having secure, durable and good sounding headphones are a must. These don't shift in the ear, have solid sound and good connectivity. The included charging case is awesome and they work well making phone calls. I also have a pair of Jaybird X2s which were good, but the Jabras have better sound and connectivity.

A recommendation, install BOTH the jabra sound+ and Jabra utility for the headphones prior to pairing. You can do it either way but it helps to have that up and running first. The sound+ sometimes takes a bit of time to recongize the buds are connected so just don't get impatient. These are really strong workout and everyday headphones (great on planes too). Noise cancelling isn't amazing but they aren't dedicated for that so I didn't care (I have over ear headphones for that need).

If you need a strong, truly wireless set of ear phones you can work out in, this is the best I know of right now.

title: Excellent Quality Overall
content:
I got mine on sale for $130 and it was definitely worth the buy. The sound quality sounds fantastic and surprisingly bassy for how small they are. The microphone and overall call quality is good, too. I've never had someone complain about not being able to hear me and their voices come through loud and clear. The battery life is pretty good and the ergonomics are great (for me anyways, they might not be the best for people with really small ears). The earbuds sit in your ear canal and don't jut out too far past the side of your head (like the Bose Soundsport Free does). The overall package is pretty compact for what you get especially when compared to something like the Bose Soundsport Free.

My two complaints are:
a) The Charging Case: the charging case is hard to open at times, there aren't magnets to hold the earbuds in place when the case is opened, and the hinge feels kind of weak.
b) Dropouts: at times the audio stutters for a second or drops out for a second. This issue is kind of annoying but common for ALL true wireless earbuds.

title: True Wireless <<< Neck Loop
content:
I've had these for a little over a week and I'm not convinced that true wireless is  worth the premium over Bluetooth earbuds with a neck loop.

Pros:
- True wireless
- Nice design and materials
- Good sound quality and noise isolation

Cons:
- Left bud drops out constantly
- "Hear Through" mode is full of static and can only be enabled from the app
- Sound problems when wearing winter clothes
- Battery life
- Enabling all features requires 2 persistent notifications on Android

I'm never able to get a consistent, uninterrupted connection. The sound in the left earbud drops out for a moment at erratic intervals, which I find distracting. This never happened with my Samsung U Flex that cost less than half the price of the Jabras.

When wearing a beanie or hood, there's constant sound from the material rubbing on the earbuds, which I've never experienced with other headphones.

These support "Hear Through" mode, which (in theory) solves a major issue with true wireless earbuds. Taking them out to have a conversation is fiddly and annoying, so hearing through them would solve that. Except it can only be enabled from within the application and fills the audio with static. The end result is that keeping it enabled all the time makes the sound quality unbearable and enabling it on the fly is even more fiddly and awkward than taking out the earbuds. The neck loop form factor allows easy removal of one or both ear buds without having to worry about holding them or putting them back in a case.

For some reason, Jabra has 2 separate Android applications (Jabra Service and Jabra Sound+) that both have to be installed to use all features. Both applications have a persistent notification. The notification for Sound+ has the convenience factor of opening settings when tapped, but the Jabra Service notification does nothing. I find this to be cluttered.

title: Good but unreliable product; worse-than-useless customer service
content:
The headphones worked great at first. The only thing I didn't like about them was that there was a pounding noise when I walked (and especially when I ran). I got used to the pounding while walking, but not the pounding while running.

After about four months, they started behaving oddly. If I put them in the case after using them, they stayed connected to my phone. They also stopped turning on when I took them out of the case, so I had to hold down the power button to turn them on. Then the left one stopped working altogether.

I contacted customer support and told them about my problems. They asked me to try a few things, and but the problems persisted. They told me to fill out a warranty-request form, which I did. After a week, I didn't hear back from them. I sent them four follow-up emails, and they didn't respond to any of them. I was courteous and did everything they suggested.

As a last-ditch effort, I told them that I would write a critical review if they didn't respond to my messages. I hoped that this would get their attention, but it didn't.
