title: Secure fit, great sound and easy to operate
content:
I have tried so many wired and wireless earbuds hoping to get a good secure fit, an easy to use interface and quality sound for music and calls.  The Active 65t has come the closest fulfilling all of those requirements.

The fit is very secure and provides a great seal for noise isolation. The sound quality is very good for both music and calls and I love that I can wear only the right earbud when I just want to have it available for hands free calls and Siri. There is a several second delay when bringing up Siri and executing commands done through the earbud. I have found that to be the case with other Bluetooth connected earbuds as well.
The left earbud controls volume, when listening to music the only other control is skipping a track.

The charging case is very compact, 2 1/2” x 2” x 1”; with a tiny LED light that shows battery level of the case at a glance, and another inside the case to show the level of the earbud charge. Conveniently they automatically shut off when storing in the case and turn on when I take them out. Reconnecting with the phone is very quick.

The Jabra Sound app allows you to customize settings for including music equalizer for 4 different scenarios; music and calls, commuting, focusing for concentration and activity like running and walking.

title: Biggest Question How is the BASS? I'll try to answer that for you.
content: After a long search for a decent true wireless earbud setup I think these are by far the best sounding wireless earbuds I have ever used. I am an audiophile for bass, and I have used some of the best in ear monitors over the years. So this review is to clear some things up about how the bass quality is with these wireless earbuds. Personally my favorite in ear monitors are the Sony XB90ex Extra Bass, these by far hit the hardest. The bass would actually make my vision blurry at times because of how much vibrations were going through my head. I would also like to throw out there that I also own and use the Sony MDR-EX800ST In ear monitor. The XB90ex and the EX800ST both hit very hard when the bass drops and are by far the best for Bass heads like me. Now with that being said, the Jabra Elite 65t are nowhere comparable to the Sonys that I mentioned above when it comes to how hard they hit, but I can say that the Jabra is the closest wireless earbuds to them. If you are a bass head like me, I would highly suggest the Jabra Elite 65t. I also want to mention that it is best to pair your earbuds with the Jabra Sound+ App. The EQ is a nice feature, and good way to squeeze out a little more bass from these.  I have used these for about a few hours, I will update my review again after I get in a couple weeks of usage.

title: Not worth the price
content: I bought these largely because I was looking for a wireless earphone with good microphones for calls and this model has 4 mics. Unfortunately the setup doesn't work as advertised and the listener can barely hear my voice. In addition the headset is very prone to interference and the left earbud has a persistent static as some of the reviews below indicate. Some of the $25 earphones are better than this.

title: Careful that it’s not used
content: I had to get three replacements until I got one that wasn’t used. The first one had ear wax all over the tips and on the extra tips as well. The second ones we’re not as used but gross all the same. Be aware of the tape that seals the box and the cover for the extra tips once removed doesn’t stick as well so you can tell. Other than that these are the best headphones I’ve ever had. My only complaint is that I wish they could be louder. Just a tad.

title: Play through option is excellent
content: To hear music while go to Jogging

title: One stopped after 6 months
content: I use them daily during my daily walk. After 6 months the left one just stopped working.  I should have just stayed with apple ones.

title: Love these!
content:
My Plantronics I use for my office was dying, so I was going to buy Airpods, but everyone was out of stock after Christmas.  I came across the Jabra's.  I bought one of the originals 15 years ago when they were the first with Bluetooths.  These are awesome; I work from home, so I use it with the softphone on my laptop and then they double for headphones when I go out for a run and listen to Mark Levin ans Sean Hannity!

Awesome earbuds and you don't look like you have a Qtip sticking out your ear!  Thes

title: The Bose replacement.
content:
Ill be perfectly honest. I have struggled since Bose discontinued the Series 2 bluetooth ear piece. I have tried products from Sennheiser, lg, and Samsung. The comfort was the biggest issue I had. The Bose series 2 was comfortable, call quality was amazing, battery life excellent and overall my favorite headset.
I've struggled to find something to be my official Bose replacement. I wanted to give the Bose SoundSport a shot but they just appeared too freaking big. The struggle finally led me to the Jabra Elite 65t. They are excellent. I love them. I wish I hadn't been such a brand snob. I cant believe I waited so long to give these a shot. Buy them. You will not be disappointed.

title: Disconnect constantly
content: These things are terrible.  They randomly disconnect constantly. They do sound great when they are working , but for 100+ dollars they should work perfectly.  They aren't very comfortable either.  I stick to my 45 dollar knockoffs

title: Would recommend to anyone
content: If you do not mind spending a little bit extra , you will be overwhelmed by features and accessories from these. Easy to use and connect to your smartphone and will sure be hard to stop using. Had to get two pairs!

title: Great audio, well made device
content: Honestly I was hesitant about getting these since Jabra in the past was kind of a cheap brand, but these are actually great.  Can have these in throughout the day, battery lasts for hours, charging is quick and the battery case is small enough to fit in your pocket.  Love the hear through feature, and how much noise it can cancel out when the hear through feature is turned off.  I’m glad I got these during Black Friday and will be my daily headset for the next few years.

title: Don't Work
content: I bought a pair from jabra and they didn't work from day 1.  wouldn't stay connected.  Took days to get support to help me.  Did everything they said and they still didn't work.  Tried 5 different devices, same result, they would connect for about 2 minutes, then connect/disconnect over and over.  Couldn't get any help from jabra on a return so had to dispute the charge on my card to get them to respond to anything.  Will never buy a jabra product again, worst customer service I have ever dealt with.  I bought a 50 pair of bluetooth ear buds and they work perfectly.

title: Great fit and really wanted to live these but can’t
content:
Great fit and really wanted to live these but can’t.
Everyone complains about echo of there own voice when I am in call. Tried turning off and echo on same call goes away. Hook up a cheap pair of Bluetooth headphones on same call and echo goes away.
Really wanted to love these because of fit, case etc, but can’t because of terrible echo/sound quality.
Returning. Save your money!!!

title: Full sound listening to music.
content: Love the fit. Love the looks. Sound? Awful!! For the price, you should be able to hear some bass response. Bass boost does nothing. Using the equalizer does nothing. So, you looking for a nice full sound with your music, try the plantronics backbeat fit.

title: Great headphones one major flaw
content: These headphones are very good for working out or everyday use. The sound is crisp and clear. Only why I can’t give them 5 stars is I’m in New York City and their is a bad connection issue with these headphones and the subway, they’ll go in and out and become very staticky and for someone who takes the subway a lot it can be annoying.

title: Mediocre sound at a ridiculous price point
content:
These sound worse than Apple headphones or Airpods - in terms of audio quality, I would've classified Apple headphones as basic pair of acceptable-sounding in-ear headphones, and I've heard better-sounding but more expensive options as well. If Apple headphones don't sound at the very least decent to you, these absolutely will sound worse than that.

Although this likely won't matter for most purchasers, these also didn't fit the small ears of the intended recipient. Unfortunately they were otherwise worthless due to lack of basic-level audio quality. These have no business being priced anywhere near Apple Airpods.

title: These are Legit
content: I washed these in the washer for an hour and a half and they are still blessing me with beautiful audio. Love these things.

title: Solid Build Quality with some Minor Annoyances
content:
I really like these earbuds. I have a Pixel 2 XL and needed some wireless earbuds for work and the gym and decided to try the Jabra Elite 65t.

Pros:
Extremely well built and durable. They say they are just sweatproof, but man I unknowingly knocked on of the earbuds into a sink filled with water and final fished it our after searching the whole house after 12 hours. The earbud was floating face down. My stomach dropped because I just knew it was ruined. I dried it for and turned it back on after 30 mins and it worked perfectly without any loss of sound quality. I was blown away. Besides that the sound quality is very good. I'm no audiophile, but I like hiphop and rnb and these have nice rich bass and sounds very clear.

Cons:
My biggest issue from these earbuds is that right earbud is the only one that can be used independently. I like to leave just one earbud in my ear at work to be aware of my surroundings and I wish I could have the left earbud in and my right ear free. I get around this by putting the right earbud in my left ear. It's upside down, but still fits snug, albeit goofy looking. I fear this will lead to my right earbuds battery wearing out faster that the left. I wish the charging case was usb c and I wish the battery life of the case and earbuds were a little longer.  Also, when I play PUBG mobile there is a half second audio delay. Fortunately I don't experience and audio delays watch YouTube, Netflix, Instagram, etc.

Overall these are good earbuds. Jabra has left themselves some room to really improve these earbuds in the future, but I have no problem recommending this product. Hopefully some of my issues can be fixed in software updates.

title: You hear me?
content: Sounds great and easy to use.

title: Very Disappointed
content:
After months of reading reviews and researching quality wireless earbuds, I had finally settled on these after seeing how much praise they have received. So far I'm not impressed. The set-up process was fairly simple, and the sound quality is passable.
However, the companion app that goes with the headphones is utter garbage. The app is sluggish and has next to no practical uses besides updating the headphones every now and again. But Jabra can't even seem to install firmware updates properly on their headphones. I had used the headphones ONCE without any problems (right after I had taken them out of the box), and then I decided to install the Jabra app and install the latest firmware update to the earbuds.
To my surprise, the update made the audio in the right ear so quiet that it's practically inaudible. I've searched all across the internet and even contacted support about this issue and there seems to be no reliable fix to this annoying problem. So for now I am stuck with earbuds that pretty much only work in one ear. Thanks Jabra.

TLDR - Companion app and customer support sucks. Firmware updates only seem to break the earbuds. One earbud is constantly louder than the other. Would absolutely not recommend.

title: love it until it starts to hurt.... (maybe jut my ears)
content:
hit couple of bumpers when un-boxing the earbuds ....

1.  It took me at least 30 secs just to open the charging case.... no kidding, it's just soooo hard to open the first time... subsequent attempts are much easier though.

2. Connecting to bluetooth was smooth and easy, however, connecting to Jabra Sound+ is really a daunting task to say at least.... i am using Huawei Mate 9 and Jabra isn't built for that!  Always got error "Jabra service was not started, please configure your phone settings to allow it run in background"... fine, i am handy guy and able to solve this problem myself, two hours later.... while i am working on getting Jabra service to run at Huawei background, i keep earbuds in my ears and enjoyed music. I have to say that sound quality was great... though passing through feature is kind of over-advertized feature. Video playback is great, no visible delays. Overall, i love the sound quality. music  was great!

3. Then ... start feeling something wrong with my ear....Oh dear, it hurts... maybe it's just my ears.. but i can literally feel the swelling in my ear canal. i have changed the smallest earbuds but still hurts alot. it's a shame that i loved the sound quality , the build , the everything about this earbuds but it hurts... looks like this high-tech earbuds is on its way back to Amazon...

title: Wireless earbuds with great sound quality and battery life
content: Has a lovely design, very comfortable, an amazing battery life, and interesting features. Understanding the buttons on the earbuds can get a little complicated, but is easy to learn.

title: Great purchase
content: i love everything about these the best earphones yet. theres no static in my ear.

title: Fits great and has easy features to use.
content: I liked it all and bought another one.

title: Much better out there for the price
content: Defective out of the box. Unable to hear any sound out of right earbud. Reset over ten times, reinstalled app, and updated firmware to no avail. Better luck to everyone else!

title: Great quality, good connection, terrible customer service
content:
Sounds great and battery is awesome. Connections sometimes falters, but this is rare. Overall very happy.

UPDATE:

The left earbud randomly stopped working, and customer service has done nothing for weeks after repeated contact. I cannot recommend this product at all. Would be great if it worked properly and/or customer service actually fixed problems.

title: What AirPods wish they were
content: Just bought a set of these, and man do they rock. I kept looking at Apple AirPods, but their form factor fits so poorly in my ears that I'm afraid they would fall out. Plus they look consummately dorky. These things come in their own tiny charging case, like the AirPods, and they have sized flanges, which make them a perfect fit for me. The sound quality, both for calls and for listening to music, podcasts, etc. is outstanding...and adjustable through a graphic equalizer on the companion app, which also lets you set the level of "hear-through" of ambient sound for three separate use cases — working, commuting, and working out. If you're thinking about a new BlueTooth, I recommend these highly.

title: Water Resistant
content:
I like these headphones, as they have a nice long battery life, and a very quick recharge time when in the case.  The microphone isn't the best, though, and these aren't great headphones if you are listening to music.  I listen to a lot of talk radio or comedians, so this isn't a big issue for me.

One thing that did surprise me ... I accidentally put these through the washer.  I realized it when I was putting clothes in the dryer.  Both earphones had fallen out of the case during the wash.  But, there wasn't any damage and both earphones (and charging case) still work perfectly.

title: Sound quality is "ugh" when working out
content:
I want to like these, and they've been great when I'm not working out. For plains and trains, they're great. Love the sound, not tinny at all. However -- and it's a big however -- when I work out, sweat really impedes the sound quality. I've had them for about five months, I've tried each of the different-sized plastic tips, but with each one, sweat gets in between the tip and my ear and the music sounds like I'm underwater, or listening in the next room. These are my first true wireless earbuds, but I've never had this problem with wired buds.

The fit is great, they stay in fine. But I bought them specifically for running and I'm left with so-so results.

Anyone else having this problem?

-----------

UPDATE:
Jabra customer service was great. They had me try a few workarounds to fix the issue. Ultimately, nothing changed, so they sent me a replacement pair, which is great. I really appreciate the customer service.

However... The new earbuds will not pair with anything other than my iPod. Not my iPhone, not my iPad. So the only thing it works with is the product Apple has phased out. (The original earbuds worked with the phone and tablet.)

Prior to my original purchase, I had read that the Jabras were the best for running/working out, but the lack of flexibility is frustrating. I'm thinking that going with the Apple AirPods would have been the smart decision.

Bottom line - know what you're using these for and what you hope to use them for.

title: POOR QUALITY AND TERRIBLE CUSTOMER SUPPORT!!!
content:
BEWARE!...

The concept and idea of a “total free” headphones is fantastic, however, Jabra customer support has been the WORST that I have ever experience. Unfortunately my headphones are defective and it has been two weeks going back and forth with Jabra support team asking me to perform all sorts of troubleshooting with not solution. Yesterday I was finally given the option to return the item and get a replacement, however, since I purchased my headphones in Amazon, I need to go through a new customer support process now with Amazon and only God knows how much time and money I will need to waste to get a replacement.

DO NOT BUY! There are many other alternatives with much better customer support.

title: UPDATE - DO NOT BUY
content:
Newest update - this replacement set lasted four months...the same amount of time my last set lasted. I use these for work calls at my home office desk for 1-4 hours a day. Other than that, they are in their case on top of my desk. I would say they don't get used or abused. While on my first call this morning the right ear bud popped and then had a dramatic decrease in volume. I pretty much cannot hear out of it. Hoping Jabra will replace again and that it doesn't take them 40 days to do so, like last time. I had high hopes for these. My wife and kids have some $14 MPOW bluetooth headphones that get abused, left outside and all that and they work a million times better than these overpriced Jabra units. Maybe I need to make that switch if Jabra won't replace. Do yourself a favor and DO NOT BUY THESE!!!

UPDATE: almost 40 days after placing my warranty request with Jabra, I have a good, working headset. Jabra sent me a whole new set, instead of just replacing my right earbud. I had to send in my old earbuds and charging case before they sent me my new unit. I imagine this process would have taken less than 40 days but it seems Jabra forgot about me several times through the process. I had to call in several times to prod this request along. I was told that the person in charge of my ticket was "on vacation" one time. Another time I was told the person in charge of my ticket just forgot to get back to me. Either way, I am happy with my new earbuds. The first set, while new, never sounded good. I read all of these reviews and could not figure out why people rated these things so high. It seems my first set was a dud from the get go. This new set sounds completely different, powerful, smooth and even some bass. I am hoping they can last.

UPDATE: 4 months in and the right ear bud plays @ 10% volume. After trying all of their suggested fixes, nothing helped. I just contacted support to see about a resolution, hope they can do something about this. I have read that a ton of buyers experience this same issue. I use these very lightly so 4 months of use and $170 bucks really sucks. Missing my cheap Apple knockoff wired ear buds right now.

I bought these explicitly for phone calls. I have used wired and wireless headsets in the past. I dislike using single ear headsets because they tend to make me dizzy after a long day of calls. These ear buds are exactly what I have needed. I tried a lot of cheaper items en route to these ear buds and there is no comparison. If I rate these based on phone call quality, it's 5 stars. If I bought these for music, I would rate 1 star. I would prefer any of my other headsets for music, including $10 wired ear buds.

title: Initial impression-wow!
content:
I bought the elite active 65t earbuds from a big blue electronics box store in my town because when I initially browsed these on amazon last night, for some reason the Active model has a disclaimer that says ‘transportation regulations restrict this item to ground shipping’ . So,  I could get the regular Jabra elites by Monday because they don’t have that disclaimer, but these would take longer. I use my earbuds in the gym, and I sweat. A lot. So the Actives seemed like the way to go. If you aren’t crazy about the blue/copper finish of the buds listed on Amazon, just know the ones at the brick and mortar store are a more conservative matte black and brushed silver.

Pairing these could not have been any easier- I paired them with my iPhone 7 plus while I was waiting for my In n Out burger order- the hardest part was getting the packaging open. From there it took about 45 seconds to download the Jabra app, and as soon as I powered the buds on, they were connected. The sound is really good, and they’re comfortable. I’ve had them in for about three hours now and no issues. Bass won’t blow you away, but compared to my old Plantronics, it’s a huge step up. Overall sound is very clean and immersive.

The Active buds have a grippy matte finish and were easy to put in my ears. They don’t feel like there’s any chance of them falling out. For me, the medium gels that are installed on the buds out of the box was perfect, but they also pack large and small gels.

The Jabra Sound + app is fairly intuitive, with equalizer settings,  something called Hear Through that lets you decide if you want these to be noise cancelling or not, an option for step counting that another reviewer mentioned made the battery life slightly worse than the regular Actives, and one that I won’t use (that’s what my Apple Watch is for)- thankfully you can toggle it on or off via the app. A feature I think I’ll really get some use out of is a choice of several ‘soundscapes’, from white noise to waterfall, thunderstorm, diving, etc. also included is an option to integrate with Alexa, which I think I’ll pass on- not crazy about something constantly listening to me.

My only gripe so far is with the mini USB charging cord. This is old technology. Plus the supplied cord is maybe 6” long at best.

I can’t speak to battery life yet, but these are going strong 3 hours out of the box.

title: Overall Great experiance
content:
The sound is pretty good and they are quite comfortable.
They do suffer the occasional connection hiccup but nothing terrible.

Edit: Lowered to 2 stars because apparently people I call complain about awful quality and I always have to switch to phone to make a call

I have one side that cuts out since I opened it thought it was the motion censor.  It’s not, it cuts out every 10 sec and after downloaded the app I can see one ear piece constantly shutting off and they are fully charged. Waste of money.

I love the look and case of the earbuds but its lacking no magnetic to pull down the earbuds to keep them in the case and the case has a funky press flap to open with no magnetics also uses micro usb to charge instead of usbc.

title: Excellent Return Service
content: Thanks

title: Ease of use
content: The product works well for an entry level earbud. Suggest upgrading for better performance.

title: Kinda good. Kinda bad
content:
Let’s start with the good. They have really good sound for earbuds. Bass is solid and audio is clear. The “hear through” mode is pretty cool too. Good for working or running in busy areas. They connect easy and have good distance.

Now for the bad.
The headphones have some firmware issues that should be easily fixable but jabra refuses to do so. The audio is stronger in the left unit than the right.i suppose this can be fixed by altering the audio settings on your device but that makes the headphones that more annoying. There is also a noticeable hissing noise in the left earbud that can be very annoying at times. They tend to cut out at random times And in order for the headphones to work, they have to be within 8 inches of each other so forget about you and a friend sharing the buds unless you want to be very close to each other. You can however use just the right unit without the left but that’s only really good for phone calls. Also the button placement makes it so when you press any button on the devices, you’re shoving the earbuds into your ears and that makes them very uncomfortable.

All in all. Not horrible, but definitely not great. My advice is to stick with the connected wireless earbuds until true wireless gets a little better. Or maybe spend a little more money and get Galaxie buddies or wait for the new Powerbeats to come out.

title: Good quality earbuds

title: Really good wireless earphones

title: Perfect all around
content: The best wireless headphones around

title: Constant static and dropped audio in crowds
content: I really wanted these for the convenience, but it's very difficult to use these outside of sitting completely still at your desk with your phone on the desk. The headphones will drop audio and become choppy if you put your phone in your left pocket, turn your head to the right when the phone is in your right pocket, or while you're holding your phone but you're surrounded by other Bluetooth devices like in an office or in public. I'll keep them for running with an armband for my phone, but otherwise these are very expensive paperweights.

title: Pretty good
content: Sound is pretty good.  Not quite as good as my noise canceling Bose wired but good.  My problem is they don't stay in my ears very well but then my ear cancels are very small.  Even tried after market Xtra smalls.  My husband has a pair and they work well for him.

title: Paring is inadequate.
content:
I was surprised with the quality of sound from these little guys and the fact they fit in my crazy small ears without popping out a single time. I recently bought a pair of Bose and had to return them for inadequate sound and poor fit...so, why am I returning these? Well, let me tell you! The pairing is crap. Before I get into it too much let me give a few pros, because my con may not hinder some buyers.

PROS:
Sound quality is superb.
The app is awesome and offers some great added features and a lot of customization.
The hear through function is nice for the ladies who want to listen with both ears and take a walk. I really loved that function.

CONS (and the only reason I'm returning them):
The pairing is bizarre and poor.

To elaborate on the pairing issue that broke the deal for me--if you don't select the option in the app that allows for one earbud to be used at a time then when you take one ear bud out the other stops. Not too bad of a problem it would seem if you get to select it away, but the only one that works with this is the right ear bud. If you take the right one out the left one quits. I'm not kidding either. If you move the right one from your ear to the palm of your hand the left one stops. Completely annoying, because sometimes I want to give an ear a break, and sometimes that may be my right ear.

The other pairing issue that killed it was when I was in a 500 sqft. apartment where separation from room-to-room was barely anything and they kept dropping off and on. I couldn't even leave my phone in the middle of the apartment and go into other rooms with doors open without them doing it; I felt equally as tethered as having a corded pair.  Hence, they must be returned.

Sorry Jabra, but the whole point of having wireless is so you can actually BE wireless.  For at least a few feet in radius anyway. You nailed the sound, but failed the pairing.

title: Doesn't have staying power
content:
Initially, these were pretty close to a slam dunk. They fit me well and the audio is good enough. I loved the Hear Through feature so that when the noise isolation is not desired, I can hear things around me. The left and right sync is solid. The connection to the phone is solid. Call quality in both directions is solid. The initial impression had been that these were solid and they became my go-to earbuds.

Unfortunately, after less than a year of use, the audio on the right earbud has started to fail. With it being the master, it still connects up fine and I can hear through the left earbud, but the right audio is nearly dead. I've done a great deal of troubleshooting and came to the conclusion that I need to execute the warranty.

And this is where the next problem appears to come up. Because it's not an enterprise product, I can't seem to figure out how to execute the 1 year limited warranty plus 2 year dust and moisture warranty. I've opened a support request, but usually when one has to approach this through a nebulous support request system such as what Jabra runs, it takes a long time to execute a warranty, and the 1 year part of it almost up. We'll see how it goes, I just hope I didn't only get 11 months out of my expensive earbuds.

title: I can now talk and drive legally
content: I can now drive while talking on the phone, and the recipients of my calls hear me clearly.

The multi week process of getting through support, proving you have an issue, being told your issue is impossible, providing copious evidence you have the earbuds, then waiting for the replacements is over the top. The fact that the issue happened again is simply unacceptable. Will never buy a Jabra product again.

title: Awesome Fully Wireless Earbuds
content:
I purchased the Jabra Elite Active 65t primarily for use as my gym headphones, so that's the context in which I'll review them.

The size and appearance of the earbuds are the best I've seen of any fully wireless set. Most other people I've seen use either Apple Air Pods (which make you look a little like a dweeb) or the Bose Soundsport Free (which jut out of the ears extensively). I wouldn't say that either set necessarily looks bad, but the Elite Active 65t squeezes all the same specs in a smaller form. It's closer to the Bose in shape, but more compact and sits mostly in the outer ear opening with minimal protrusion. The buds themselves are very lightweight, and I rarely notice them when I'm working out. The earbuds also have a slightly grippy texture, which helps them stay in your ear when you get sweaty. Speaking of sweat, these buds are IP56 rated to resist dust and sweat, unlike the Air Pods (which were designed with hipster cafes in mind, not sweaty gyms). The charging case is another example of good design; it has the same grippy texture as the earbuds (unlike the slick Air Pod charging case), while maintaining a fairly compact size (similar to a thicker box of Tic Tacs, unlike the Bose case which is the approximate size of a police flashlight). The only thing that could be better are the buttons; the left bud is host to a volume up and down button (oriented horizontally for some reason), while the right bud has a multifunction button. While this is certainly better than the Air Pods' single touch button, the Bose buttons are better designed, situated on the outside edge of the buds which makes them easier to press. The cobalt and gold color scheme is sure to be polarizing, but I think it looks good. Besides, if you're that worried about your headphones matching your outfit in the gym, you need to rethink your priorities.

Battery life is equivalent to most other fully wireless sets (5 hours plus 2 full recharges from the case). Since I really only use them for 1-2 hours at a time, I can't attest to the accuracy of those numbers. They usually last about 10-12 workouts before I have to recharge the buds and the case. Overall, I'd say the battery life is plenty good for the intended purpose. If you're looking for wireless headphones for travel or business usage, I'd recommend travelers get a set of Bluetooth noise canceling headphones (like the offerings from Bose and Sony, which last around 20-30 hours) or a dedicated Bluetooth headset for the businesspeople.

The sound quality is another plus. This is a fully in-ear bud, which means that there isn't any sound leakage. This also provides a degree of passive noise-canceling, which is nice when the beanpole in the power rack next to you is screaming while pulling 135 with a back like a hissing black cat on Halloween. The HearThrough mode, which can be activated by double-pressing the button on the right bud, allows outside noise to filter in via the microphones. This is handy if you're running or doing another activity that requires you to be aware of your surroundings. Music playback quality is surprisingly good; it certainly won't win any awards, but the sound includes a decent amount of detail and doesn't feel compressed or airy. This is partially due to the in-ear nature of the buds (unlike the on-ear nature of Air Pods and Bose), but overall it's pretty good. The call quality is good as well. When I've taken calls with these the listener never had any complaints or had to repeat myself. Additionally, the Bluetooth connection is very strong. I haven't had either bud drop out while in use, even through walls. This is a bit better than what I've heard about the Soundsport Frees, which are still solid but tend to drop out every so often.

There are a few other interesting features. Music pauses automatically if you remove a bud, which allows you to talk to people trying to steal your bench while you're making a trip to the water fountain. Holding the right button brings up your phone's assistant, which is probably handy if you have an Android phone. I'm stuck with Siri, however, so I don't tend to use it. These buds also include 3 sizes of ear tips so that you can get a comfortable and secure fit. I was having mixed results with the default medium tips, but swapped them for the smalls and experienced a much more secure and comfortable fit (apparently, size DOES matter).

There are a few things that could be improved. You can use a single bud to listen to music and make calls, but only the right one. This is sure to annoy the lefties out there. Additionally, while the in-ear tips are fairly secure, they've come loose on a few occasions while performing intense activities (mostly barbell complexes and the rower). It would've been nice to have the ear clips like the Bose to prevent this. The Bluetooth connection, while rock solid, seems to have trouble switching between devices. I usually use them with my Apple watch, but I forgot it one day and had to connect them to my phone. Even in sync mode, these phones had trouble pairing. I had to forget the device on my phone and re-pair them to get a connection. This isn't the only pair of headphones to do that, though, so it might be an issue with my phone/watch.

Overall, these are perfect for use as gym headphones as well as being great headphones in general. While there are a couple of minor issues, they are vastly outweighed by the good desing, great sound, and battery life these buds provide. I wouldn't hesitate to recommend them to anyone.

title: AVOID
content:
I really wanted to like these. They are small and portable and there's a lot to love. Unfortunately, mine suffered the hiss on the left ear that a lot of other people mentioned. It's not terrible, but you know what is? Their customer service.

I called and was on hold for ~45 minutes. The guy who answered made me do a firmware update and told me to factory reset before I could do an RMA, then he hung up, saying that he sent me an email that I could use if I still wanted to return them. Still had the problem (because hardware problems aren't solved by resets). Sent him a few emails before I heard from Jabra. They had me fill out another form and about a week later told me to send them in for review before they'd do anything else. That was a week ago. They're still gone and I haven't heard anything from them. Apparently the Morale of the story is don't buy Jabra.

title: The Fit is the only Flaw
content:
Wanted to love these, but the protruding mics create a wedge between the earbud that cause some pain on the ear. I'm sure this would differ from person to person. My wife has the Samsung Iconx 2018.
I think both are great earbuds, and the fit was the only thing I was really choosing between. I would say for myself, I felt slightly more overall pressure from the Iconx frame (not in the ear canal, and not quite to the point of discomfort), but the Iconx also had a smaller profile while wearing, so kinda makes sense. The Jabra's didn't have as much pressure, but the "V" created by the external Mics pinched the area where it overlapped. For myself, this left the Iconx's more comfortable overall. IF it wasn't for the pain from mics squeezing the ear, I would have probably gone with these in terms of comfort. I think people would be happy with either choice. For myself, I'm still preferring the Iconx.

2. Accidentally dropping the right earbud on a concrete floor, about 4 ft high - had no problems after | water splashes from washing my face or sweat during workouts - still functions the same, no problems encountered
3. Specs-wise: 5hr battery life (Verified-if used non-stop); 10m bluetooth operating range (verified, I tried it to up to 2m more). I ahve adjusted the fitting of each bud on each ear so I can use the buttons easily.
>Functions I appreciate and use often: auto pause; passive noise cancellation; hear through; Soundscape; music equalizer.
>Things I can work around: prolonged use (6Hrs), start to feel the weight of the buds on my ear - learned to adjust the use time. The make of the charging case, I just have to be extra careful on opening and taking out the buds.

title: I really, really, wanted to like them
content:
I think that these are easily among the most elegant, good looking wireless ear pods avaialable. Everything about them screams quality and well thought out approach to quality. My problem is that they never worked properly. The audio, particularly when working out on my treadmill would cut in and out. They were fully updated, fully charged, and inserted properly. For this price point, this is completely unacceptable.

I purchased them elsewhere, which was a mixed blessing. I recently had the experience here of being unable to return something to a non Amazon vendor. The price here was the same. I went with the Bose Sound Sport, which is cheaper, and works. The design while not as sleek, seems to work more easily.

title: Good Sound but Uncomfortable
content:
I figured I would give these a try since they are highly recommended by most review sites. The sound quality is excellent for sure, and well balanced in all ranges. However, I thought that the EQ in the app gave it some distortion when I set it to anything but flat. They provide great noise isolation especially in a noisy place like the gym. The sound thru feature is a cool added bonus when you want it. The final positive for these earbuds is how small and discreet they look in your ears. They don't stick out at all and look great.

Now with the negatives. Like others have pointed out, the left earbud had an annoying static hiss which is a serious problem at low volumes and should not be an issue with earphones at this price range. I'm guessing it's a quality control issue because some people don't have this problem.  Additionally, these are VERY uncomfortable to wear. Some review sites mentioned that the fit is not for everyone, and that is truly the case for me. Inserting them in is actually painful and they become uncomfortable (rather than painful) as I wore them for long periods. But if you use the volume controls it again becomes painful since your pressing on your ear.

Overall I can't recommend these because of the static hiss issue and that they are uncomfortable for me despite the great sound and noise isolation.

title: Are they worth it for power users?
content:
Ive had these for almost a year now and I can attest that the sound quality is really great. I use them 8 hours a day, every single day. Their design and fit is perfect for my ears and I often time forget that I'm wearing them.

So why the 3 stars if I like them so much? While I find the quick charge on these incredibly convenient t given that I use them so intensively, after a year of use the battery holds about 3 hours of charge per charge. It's particularly annoying when you are really getting in the groove while working and you have to stop what you're doing to put them away in their case so they can recharge. Note, I'm getting 3 hours using just the right ear bud, when I use both I can count on getting maybe 2 and a half hours at most.

So, ok maybe I'm a bit of a power user when it comes to these things right? It would probably be fine for most users right? Wrong. The other main downfall of these is that after these latest updates (yes ladies and gentlemen you get software updates for your ear buds smh), if you stop the music or video playing you'll get really loud annoying alerts from the ear buds announcing that it's disconnected and reconnected to your phone about every 5 to 15 minutes. Sometimes I'll pause them while I attend to my customer or my coworker and it is incredibly jarring to have them suddenly announce their presense in your ear when you were in the middle of a conversation. I don't see why they had to make it such a jarring alert. I get it, you want to test the connection with the phone since the audio has stopped but I don't need you telling me that you're doing that every 5 minutes. I sincerely hope that they remove that function in future updates.

The case that comes with these ear buds can sure take a punch. I have accidently dropped this case I don't know how many times and it's only released my ear buds a few times at most. I can appreciate a secure fit. But that they had to use the flimsiest plastic latch to hold the ear buds in has already shown its weakness. Just last week, I opened the case carefully, as I always do and the little tab that holds the case closed broke on me. Allow me to emphasize, I have dropped this case quite a few times but the time that it chose to break was when I opened it carefully? That really set my day off to a poor start. Worst part is that the replacement case cost almost $70. I'm using a rubber band now but I'm severely disappointed.

Saving the worst for last, let talk about my biggest gripe with these. The Bluetooth connectivity range. My God, the range on these is God awful. Ill be working (I work a physically laborious job) and these puppies will cut out on me every once in a while. Soon as I step outside I might as well put them away. What's the point of having ear buds designed with athletes and physically active people in mind when you literally have to hold your phone up to your ears to get a stable connection. I didn't pay what paid for these for this much of an inconvenience in my work flow. I've had more than a few poor Bluetooth connective ear buds but these take the cake.

So after my little rant, what could you take away from this? Honestly if you want an excelent sounding truly wireless earbud, these are the ones yoh have been looking for. It's not fair to compare these to full headphones but they can sure hold their own. They dont fall out and they are incredibly comfortable. But if you are a power user like myself and use these for any more than 2 hours at a time, I have a hard time pushing you to buy these. They lose that premium feel to them once you experience my gripes up above and become a very expensive inconvenience. I'll be using these until they eventually die on me but I don't think I'll be buying any future installments from jabra.

title: Good Quality But Uncomfortable For Me
content:
Earbuds can be weirdly personal as far as comfort and quality. These fall short of perfection for a few reasons that are probably personal to me.

On the plus side:

The sound quality is great. I think they have a nice tone, with a good amount of bass. Music doesn't come through tinny.

They hold a charge for quite a long time.

The buttons are easy to access for phone calls, and the mic works well.

Even with music on, I'm able to hear enough to notice if someone is speaking to me or if there is something going on that I need to hear.

The flaws:

I find them uncomfortable. The longest I can wear them is about 30 minutes. By then, my ears are aching. This isn't solved by changing the rubber tips. They're just too bulky and heavy for my ear canal.

The range isn't great. I use earbuds a lot at home, streaming from my laptop. I get up to do something in another room, and I notice a weird static.

For some reason, these will not stay paired to my devices. I've tried my cellphone and two laptops. They stay paired fine as long as I want during a single use. But, when I turn them off, they lose the pairing. My device will still list them as paired, but the earbuds won't work. The voice will keep telling me to connect them. The only way to get them to work again is to remove them from the device and add them again. It only takes a few seconds, but it's annoying. I have no need for the app. It just seems like one more app that only takes up space, because I can do everything I need to do without it. I mean, seriously, I'm apped out. I don't know if this is why the earbuds won't stay paired. Maybe the app has to be installed on the device in order for it to work continuously.

title: Nigh invulnerable. I should know.
content:
My wife got me these wonderful earbuds as a particularly kind and thoughtful birthday gift. They sound wonderful, and while they don't _entirely_ fit my weirdly shaped ears -- the right one can start to hurt a bit after an hour or so, and occasionally falls out while I'm doing sit-ups, if I'm not careful -- overall they're very good in and of themselves, and immensely better than the janky wired headphones I previously had.

So, of course, having been given this wonderful and expensive gift by the woman I love, within a month I'd run them through the washer.

And the dryer.

Yep. Left them in my pocket after working out. Completely forgot about them. Wondered, idly, what that odd rattling sound was in the washer. Found out when I opened the dryer to find one of them sitting there, silently accusing me.

So, am I writing this review about my second pair? Nope. The only trauma the earbuds suffered from a full wash and dry cycle was running out of battery charge. I popped them into the charging case, prayed to the technology gods, and with a few hours' recharging, they were good as new. No drop in sound quality or connection ability, even.

Do I recommend that you, too, launder these very expensive earbuds, on purpose or by accident? Most emphatically not. But should you prove as forgetful as I was, rest assured that this _very_ well-made set of earbuds may well be able to survive your carelessness.
