title: Mic doesn't work. Not a great buy for money.
content: Mic doesn't work. Not a great buy for money. People I call fail to hear me, no noise cancellation.

title: These are GREAT! It will be money well spent!
content: I can't say enough about these wireless earphones. The design,fit,quality are all top notch. The different settings allowing ambient sound in whole listening to calls/music is a nice touch. I bought a pair of off brand to see if true wireless is worth it and it is. These are the brand to get. Music quality is superb also bass is usually where these struggle but sound was excellent.

title: Sound Quality goes away over time.
content: These worked awesome for 11 months. I used them for about 1.5 hours almost every morning. They worked great, sounded great, cancelled out all the noises. Then one day the right one sounded like it was under water. For the price I really expected them to last longer...

title: Are these used?!
content: Bought these for a gift so they haven't been used yet (by us). Off the bat, I noticed that the charging case was in the packaging upside down and had greasy fingerprints on it. As this product was advertised as new, I'm wondering why it had been handled. I will be very disappointed if it has any functionality issues, and will definitely demand a refund if so.

title: Nice features but not worth it
content:
These headphones have amazing features. The main one is the ambient noise feature. Although it is passive noise cancelling, the ambient noise features lets you hear your surroundings, so when your riding your bike you can still hear your surroundings and when you get to your destination you can easily turn it off.
The sound quality also is pretty good. Better than regular apple headphones, but no Bose.
The app has low reviews but I found it to be helpful. You can play background noise (ie river flowing or white noise) and change the bass and treble levels. However, I wish there was a better find my headphones feature. The headphones are not magnetically secure in the case, so they could fall out if you're not careful. Samsung and apple headphones have a feature that plays sounds from the headphones when you lose them so they can be easily found. I wish the Jabras had that instead of a general last location.
There are some small issues with the headphones that made me return them. It is not comfortable. My left ear was aching/turning numb from 2+ hours use. I have heard these are very comfortable but for my friend and I they hurt at least one of our ears. Also there is a static feedback in the headphones when you don't listen to music and when you start playing music.. The Airpods (no matter what anyone says about them) don't have a static noise when you are not listening to music and just have the headphones in.
Overall, I'm not sure if they are worth it. Even if they fit your ears comfortably and you don't mind the static noise, for the price there are other competitors. Samsung buds are almost half the price and have the same features (even has a better find my headphone feature). Although the Jabra has a better sound quality, it is not that noticeable and you shouldn't be looking at bluetooth headphones if sound quality is your main issue.

title: Left earbud buzz after certain volume
content: Like other reviewers state, there is a constant buzz in the left ear piece after a certain volume! Very disappointing since I thought I did my research and narrowed it down to these. I returned them the very next day after I received them.

title: Best on the market as of 12/29.
content: First off, I did A LOT of research. This is my third set of totally wireless buds I've tried. I read a review of an audiophile who dismissed almost all others, except for these. BUY THESE ear buds!! Amazing battery life (5 hrs. Then the charger pod gives you 2 more 5 hr. Charges). The sound is wonderful. Great highs and mids, but what the others lack is lows/bass. Perfectly well rounded sound. I could not be more thrilled with this purchase. Still waiting on the reviews of the new 1More totally wireless buds though.  I hope this helps you make the right decision, and BUY THESE NOW!

title: Love item

title: If you have non AirPod ears give these a try.
content: Just got these, tried them out in the parking lot and for the drive home. They came 60% charged. Downloaded the app, updated the firmware.  Done in a few mins. These are definitely not the best sounding headphones. BUT, THEY FIT PERFECT right out the box! And they sound decent. Maybe once the drivers bed in they’ll sound better. If the wind changes direction my left AirPod falls out. It never seals right so it sounds terrible. Zero problem with these so far. The noise canceling with sound pass through is a great feature and it works well. I can’t speak on the battery life yet. But initial overall reaction is 100% positive. I’m coming from Cambridge’s fully wireless earbuds and they are absolute garbage. These stop playing when the distance is too far from each other, it’s pretty seamless when you take one out and put it back in. The case lid latch needs a redesign.

title: Sounds great. Buggy connection, and boosted backround on calls
content: Music playback is excellent, so if all you want is that hoopty Uhura look and crisp audio you are good to go. If you want to take calls be sure to save up extra to build a portable sound booth to bring with you. The headphones re-balance the mic gain to provide "low-talkers" a high quality audio input. The result is if you aren't talking its confuses the person 20 feet away as a low talker and provides a super clear feed of that conversation to into your call.

title: High value for excellent quality!
content:
I had been looking for a set of wireless earbuds for some time primarily because I weight train 2-3 hours a day, almost 7 days a week and got tired of my wired earbuds getting caught on things. I also wanted wireless earbuds that did not have a wire that hangs around the neck. In the market today, there are average wireless "wired" earbuds (like the jaybird) and they all price around the same 70-90 value. I had previously owned jaybirds and they were great until I lost them. As mentioned, I was willing to pay a lot more for quality earbuds and ones that were completely wireless. Then I searched and heard about these Jabras. I was VERY skeptical at first because of the price. I mean I know for sure sound quality will be 200%, but will these last, will they fit in my ear without hurting, and will they be good for a frequent gym goer like myself. The answer to all those questions is yes.

In detail, the sound quality is amazing and I get a great suction and noise cancellation when using these. When I first popped in the earbuds, they hurt a little due to the size in both my ears. I kind of ignored it, but it became noticeable throughout the workout so I started reading up on people's opinions on the fit. It was a hit or miss; however, I found out that you can slightly rotate the earbuds up and down (once it's in your ear) and BAM, pain was gone, and fit was perfect. I assume the battery life is amazing, but I always pop my buds in my charger which is connected in my car. As for sweat resistance, I think these are doing good so far. Unless my doing an ultra long/tough workout, the sweat usually doesn't hit my ears/the buds and I always use towels so my buds stay dry for the most part. The buds stay in my ear perfectly for most of the workout, it's when I start doing HIIT exercises or running on the treadmill is when they start sliding out. I honestly believe this is expected of ALL earphones. The nature pressure on your head and ears during movements is gonna pop them out on their own. Distance is good for about 50 feet from wherever your buds are connected too, but beyond that you will start hearing stuttering and disconnecting sounds or whatever.

Just a few minor dislikes to note, but it is nothing game changer. Be careful where you put these because you can easily lose them. Also, I recommend taking them off when you are changing a shirt or sweater. I have had these pop out my of my ear doing so and had almost lost them. The other dislike is the case. Buds fit perfectly, looks sturdy, small to carry anywhere; however, I dislike how you open the case. It has a nice click/shut to it which is nice because it'll keep your buds secure and charging, but I have to press pretty hard on the case every time to open it I feel like I might crack the case at one point.

Overall, if you what high quality earbuds, earbuds that completely wireless, and a frequent gym goer, I HIGHLY recommend these. They pack a price punch but you definitely get what you pay for and it's worth it. Satisfied customer here.

title: Terrible battery life!

title: Save your money and time you do not want to deal with this products customer service team

A month has passed since I sent them in and after multiple calls to the support team still no replacements because they are "backed up". Completely incompetent customer service and broken product. The best earbuds I have ever tried , quality 10 from 10 ,sound 10 from 10 . I'm 100000% happy with it... 😍😍😍😍

title: i chose airpods over these
content: after using these and the airpods, i prefer the airpods. these do fit really nicely in my ear, i like how i can enable siri or alexa (you get to choose), and the sound quality was good. the accompanying app lets you adjust sound more precisely. if i didn’t have airpods, i would own these

title: OK, but they fall out too easily with no security options available.
content:
The size, weight, comfort and general operation are all very good. I am not an audiophile, but the sound quality is good for me. I listened to music, podcasts, and books as well as make conference calls.

The sidetone is weak making the headset generally unsuitable for long phone calls. The mics also pick up a lot of background noise, again, making them only good for an emergency backup for a better VoIP setup. This is disappointing. They also don't pair all that easily with laptops and do not automatically reconnect so, again, these are a poor option for VoIP.

The main reason I give a rating of only three is that, depending on your ears, the headset will not stay firmly seated enough and easily slips out. My right ear is OK. My left ear does not fit well and the earbud falls out. This is extremely frustrating on flights because the earbud is extremely difficult to find. I had a long trip and it fell out twice and I got lucky both times finding it. I had to use the flashlight on my phone and woke people up while I searched. Not good. These are too expensive to risk losing them like that. Plus, if you don't have a backup, then you are stuck with no sound for a 12 hours flight.

There is no tether or ear flap or hook option for these headsets. So, if the provided inserts do not fit well for you, then you are left only using these in environments where you are able to regularly reseat the earbuds and you can reasonably easily find them when they fall out. If you sleep on a flight, you can expect these to fall out.

If you want something you can trust to stay in, then you should probably look elsewhere. The sport option might work.

title: Refurbished items didn’t hold up
content: Sound isn’t working in left ear piece after two months of use. Not sure if this is jabra or just a bad refurbish

title: Not for the hearing impaired
content: I had a previous set that were awesome.  However, this new model isn’t as loud as previous models.  I will probably go back to using my older design with cable that connects both ear buds.

title: Second set and will be returning them
content: Both sets have the issue where the left bud doesn't work half the time. They also really hurt my ears after about 30 minutes and they don't breathe very well. Sound quality is good when they both actually work, but....

title: Awesome
content: Awesome

title: Not even close to worth the price
content:
My first impression (about a week of use) is that this is a 2 star product that deserves 1, or if possible, 0 stars due to the price.  For this price I would expect top of the line quality. So far all I have experienced are problems.

Pros:
- Look good
- Feel good
- Charging Case looks & Battery life

Cons:
- Bluetooth is terrible! Routinely disconnects / reconnects. Phone calls have a static and/or distorted noise while also constantly cutting in and out. This is with my phone literally inches away from me.
- Pressing buttons is a pain. You either jam the earpiece into your ear drum or you have to weirdly hold the earpiece in place while you push the button.
- Without looking at the app there is no good way to determine battery level or even if the devices are on/off
- Placing the earpieces in the charging case is easily done wrong and no way to tell if they aren't aligned correctly in the case which means they aren't charging.
- No way to tell how charged the device is
- The list goes on - just a number of little things that you'd expect to be figured out when you pay this kind of money for headphones. The terrible Bluetooth is the most frustrating as I've never had any problems with connection when using any other headphones (which have all been mostly under $35).

title: Call quality isn’t great
content: The battery life isn’t great and I use them for phone calls and have noticed the sound quality on calls isn’t very good. And every so often the person I’m talking to can’t hear me.

title: They are exactly what he wanted.
content: Christmas present for son who is very active. Loves them. He stopped using all other buds he has.  Says they stay in his ears without being annoying.  He is very happy and highly recommends them.

title: Great buy
content: Excellent sound quality, pairing is fast and consistent. It has yet to drop connection even with phone in opposite rooms of house. Battery life is outstanding.

title: They are great if they don't hurt you.
content: They work like advertised and after doing a lot of research I do believe that they are the best or one of the best earbuds for this price. The reason for the four stars is because they hurt my ears, they start hurting after half an hour and become numb after an hour of use. I wanted to get used to them and I read some reviewers with similar experiences that said they eventually got used to them and pain and discomfort was no longer an issue after 3-5 days. After a week and a half of use I can tell that I'm not getting used to them, in fact it's still just as painful to push the earbud buttons or to remove them after an hour of use. I can't use them and so I had to return them. I know that I'm probably the minority so chances are that most people won't have this experience.

title: Terrific Wireless Headphones!
content:
I absolutely love these headphones – and I completely didn’t expect to! In fact, before they had even arrived, I had told my husband that he could have them… He routinely loses headphones though (seriously, I think that he has lost at least five pairs of the headphones that the iPhones come with), and when they arrived they looked so small being all wireless and with a case looked miniscule in his big hand. So, I thought, well, I will just try them out first… and then he can have them.

But I never gave them over!! Instead, I fell in love with them. The headphones really retain their charge, which I love, and there is a little battery icon that shows up on your phone so that you can easily see their level. And the carrying case recharges them, and has a light on the bottom to indicate its level of charge. And it doesn’t take it long to recharge fully, either. I stop and start use them a lot at work, and then use them for longer stretches walking our dog or cleaning in our house and only one time have I actually run out of power! They are comfortable, too – and definitely noise-cancelling! Plus, I love the voice of the lady who assures me that they are in fact connected to my phone, and prompts you to respond if a call comes through while wearing them. They work great as a headset for your phone, too! They have a wider range from the phone as well than I expected, as I discovered while cleaning. I had managed to get quite far away from my phone before discovering that the problem was that I had left my phone on a dresser as I set off to put clothes away in another bedroom!

Because they are inner ear headphones, they are also easy to clean and are super portable – where I once listened to audiobooks only in the car, at home or walking the dog, now I find myself using these headphones as I shop, work and run other miscellaneous errands. I love them and would be heartbroken if my husband were to use them and lose one! So these are mine… all mine!!!

title: Poor sound quality.

title: Very happy with these earbuds
content: I have had these ear buds just over two weeks. So far, they have been great. I use them every day on my commute to work, at the gym, and sitting outside on my lunch break. They sound great, and volume control and track forward buttons work easily enough after a short learning curve. I love the hear-through function. It's especially good when trying to hear announcements on the subway, and keeps you safe on the street. I don't find it as useful when trying to have a conversation with someone. I frequently have to remove one to properly hear a person. When this function is off, it pretty much shuts out all the ambient sound. I was very impressed when I walked past a construction site and could hear my music without the background Jack hammers. The sync with BT works especially fast, although there were 2 occasions when it didn't reconnect. I popped them back in the case for a second and then they work perfectly again. The fit is great, and they stay in my ears when running and working out at the gym. I haven't used them yet on a phone call so can't comment on that. I do highly recommend them.

title: When call quality, and only call quality is important.
content:
I have (and have owned) several different wireless earbuds, including the Sony Xperia Duo,Bose SoundSport Free,Here One,Shure SE215,BeatsX, Apple AirPods, and Samsung Gear IconX. So, I'm not a stranger to what's possible with wireless earbuds in this price range.

And in saying this, for music, these are the worst earbuds I've ever heard. The sibilance is painful. Not "ugh, these aren't as fancy as I'd like." They're literally painful to listen to. That's really sad, because there's so much else to like about these.

For instance, Jabra has pretty much nailed Bluetooth headsets, and that carries over here. No, nobody's going to tell you they don't know you're using a headset, but you're not going to spend the entire call with someone going "WHAT?" every few seconds. (Well... at least not if that isn't normal for them to begin with.) Even in relatively noisy environments, call quality was better than acceptable.

The overall fit of these is awesome. Put them in your ears, give them a little twist, and they stay in place. Personally, I would have preferred foam eartips over silicone, but the fit and seal is great. And the way the materials feel conveys a premium nuance.

The buttons on either earbud are logical, and work well across multiple devices. The integrated voice prompt for pairing was a nice touch, too. I didn't notice any substantial delay with these (much unlike the Bose earbuds), and unlike the Here Now and Samsung IconX, I never had a problem with one of the two earbuds falling out of sync or dropping out.

The included charging case is... well, it's a mixed bag. The earbuds fit nicely in the case, no matter what size tips you're using, and it charges reasonably fast. On the other hand, the retaining tab that keeps the lid shut is kind of a pain to use, and feels cheap. Battery life on the earbuds wasn't anything notable one way or the other.

If I wanted these exclusively for handling phone calls while doing something active (e.g. at the gym, on a bike trail) they're really good. Again, the call quality is very good, and they stay put. But for listening to music, you don't want these. If this is within your budget and you mostly care about music and maybe the occasional phone call, you probably want to consider the Shure SE215's.

title: Not worth $200
content: I'm a little disappointed in these headphones considering the amount of money I spent. A couple problems I have noticed with these headphones is that the music cuts on and off repeatedly when you are not within a few feet of your phone. I'll walk into another room at the gym where I can still see my phone and I'll have to pause my headphones manually because it is constantly cutting the music if I'm not near my phone. I also do not find these sweat resistant. As I was stretching after my workout to cool down, my left earbud kept popping out regardless of how hard I twisted it into my ear. Overall, I am happy with the sound quality and noise cancellation, but I am not pleased with my earbuds falling out when I sweat and the music cutting off I'm not near 10 feet of my phone.

I provided proof of purchase, then received confirmation of an order... to be delivered ONE MONTH LATER. I figured "well, fine, not terrible but not particularly great." Yesterday, shy of when I was to receive the replacement gels I received a delay - FOR ANOTHER MONTH! This is ridiculous! all for the standard size ear gels?! I'm done with this brand.

title: If you don’t make phone calls, save your $$ and buy an off brand.
content:
Pros:  great noise isolation
  Good for phone calls
  Stay in well for me.
  Long battery life.
  Descent customer service. Good but
  Not great.

Cons:  these are significant to me, but not
  Everybody

  You can only use the right earbud by
  Itself.  I had a cheap $50 pair that I
  Could use either one solo. When I’m
  Working around the house I like to
  Wear only one and switch between
  Ears for comfort and battery.

  Another problem is that you can’t
  share w/somebody.  The earbuds
  have to be an exact distance apart
  For them to work.  On road
  trips I like to share w/my wife so the
  Kids don’t have to listen to our
  podcasts.

All in all they are good but not great. Compared to my cheap pair the only advantage is battery & phone call quality.  If you don’t plan on using them for phone calls, save your money.  For me the phone calls outweighed the other issues. Hopefully they improve this with newer models. I did have to return my first pair due to the battery not holding a charge. When you call expect to be on hold for a long time. For me it averaged 30 minutes.  Once I talked with somebody they were helpful, but it took way to long to get a replacement pair. After mine was returned it was 2 weeks and they didn’t even have the color I originally ordered so I had to take a color I didn’t want or wait another 2 weeks.

On my computer and phone I get atleast 35 feet of range thru walls and around the house.  Sometimes I forget to grab my phone and walk out the house and it works all the way to my car.  battery life is super long and the little charger box is nice to have so you can go all day.  you can't go wrong with these.  If you are a sound snob, you may not like these because the bass is not as strong, but everything else makes up for it.  Once paired, they auto pair which is nice

title: One Fatal Flaw
content:
So I ordered these to hopefully work as a substitute for AirPods since they don’t stay in my ear. So let’s start by the fit. Comes with different size tips and I did find the perfect fit for my ears. These things don’t move. No matter if it’s in the gym or laying down they fit great.
Now for the sound. I’m not an audiophile by any means. I just want something that sounds good and these do. I dod mess with the app that connects to these and make my own sound
Profile but there are set ones to choose from also. Bass is decent and the highs were also good. Overall sound is better then I expected.
Buttons are ok. You have to push on them in your ears so if your not careful it could become very uncomfortable if you push to hard.
The look in my ear is great. Most people don’t know they are in. I also use in the office and I will be on a call while people try to talk to me and I have to point to let them know I’m on the phone. Mic is great for calls. People on the other end say it sounds very good. Oh and here is one of my favorite features, I can just use the right one by itself which is another plus when in the office or car traveling.
Pass through hearing. You can turn this on in the app and still hear what’s going on around you while you listen to music or just have them in during the work day. Works decent. First time I’ve had a pair with this feature so can’t really compare.
The Charge. The earbuds have never died on me but I always put in the charging case which charges them Back up when I’m not using so I can’t confirm how long they really last. Charging case is ok. A little weird at first to open but then you get use to it. The earbuds sit in it nicely.

NOW here is my HUGE CON!!!!! So when I am at the gym the first pair I received would cut out in certain areas. Thought that’s weird and had them replaced. Well the second pair does the same thing around certain equipment. So I started googling and this is a common problem. As far as I can find something to do with the magnetic field of equipment but I’m not sure. I do know it always happens and in the same areas that I can’t avoid at the gym. So your listening to your favorite jam and boom it cuts out. Sometimes I have to power cycle to get to connect again. When I’m working out I don’t need this type of issue. If it wasn’t for that these things would be great. I wish I could return them now but I’m passed my time and will be purchasing the Powerbeats pro when they come out. It’s a bummer. I really wanted to like these but I guess I will try to sell them or just use as my office and car travel Bluetooth. People buying just beware of the gym fact, since these are active and people would probably be using these for that reason. I’m sure I forgot a couple things but I’m doing this review on my phone. Fingers are tired now

title: Updating review for the 3rd time - FINAL
content:
Someone said these have been a love hate relationship. Daily usage in this price arena will do that.
1. Jabra was nice enough to explain that the left bud doesn't have bluetooth capability so there's no possibility of L/R working independently. Ty for that.
2. Jabra also told me to wait for their next firmware update to address the left channel favoring audio.
  a. After adjusting the balance to the right for an even soundstage, I couldn't take the lack of volume. Jabra, please fix this issue somehow. 3 firmware updates ago you addressed this but the actives are still having the issue. What gives?
3. The charge is incredible. Haven't done tech tests, but they last around 4 hours during my 8 hour shift.
4. No one addressed this but they can withstand HOT temperatures. It's almost July in AZ and no problems in 115°F+ (105°F ambient).
5. Sound Problems and Strengths: Absolutely no bass control. Cranking the Sound+ app to max renders blah. Bass just isn't there. When listening to rock I was expecting to be tickled with the bass drum hit but Jabra falls completely flat on the low end. So basically if you want some decent bass, these aren't a good choice.
6. Ergonomically being a first time user, they stay put under activity like getting in and out of vehicles. I use the smallest size and it would be nice to have more than 3 options of tips like a S/M or a M/S or whatever. Aftermarket tips are no better.
7. Case is bull****.
8. On call background noise - Okay so, my gf is a telecomm engineer and her company [used to] contract with Jabra. After reading reviews I was confident I'd have a restrictive on call experience. That's a negative. Jabra will tell you to reposition your buds so they utilize their half-assed non-existent isolation algorithm. These speakers are so sensitive that your caller can hear a bird sqwahking 100 feet away. It goes both ways however, in a quiet room or one without birds-awesome mics.
9. Sum it up - Great sound quality with lack of bass. Noise canceling and sound through is really good. "HearThrough" is finicky with limited apps I've used but not the majors, youtube included. Main bud click is comfy for pause, answer, click-and-hold voice control, but volume control sensitivity on the left bud is harsh! To open the case, squeeze the sides then pick the tab. Idk, the case is cool but it got dirty my first day of ownership. Jabra, upgrade us Active users with a magnetic case for free! It's ridic having our buds fly out when we're in a hurry. No regard for case accessibility at $189.  Thanks for reading. Last time I'm re-writing this review.

title: Solid-sounding headphones with great battery life and some annoying quality control issues
content:
I'm now on my second pair of these headphones and apparently headed towards my third. Here are the hits and misses:

The good:
- They sound really good, and you can easily customize the sound profile in their app, which also functions well.
- They don't have noise cancellation, but the overall isolation quality is decent. The function that uses the microphones to bring in outside sounds is a nice feature too.
- Not a ton of bass (I mean, what do you really expect from headphones this size) but it's decent. Again, using the app's EQ really allowed me to tailor the sound to my liking.
- Fantastic battery life. I've never had to worry about these things running out of juice when I head to the gym and run errands.
- Jabra support (especially over Twitter) is pretty responsive and helpful.
- Comfortable. I have larger ears and have never found the headphones to be uncomfortable. They have a snug but not painful fit.

The bad:
- The headphones very loosely sit in the charging case when you put them in. It's way too easy for them to fall out when you open it, so do so carefully.
- The charging case itself has a smooth pebble-like shape, making it rather easy for it to slip out of large pockets.
- As others have said, the left headphone occasionally won't turn on when removed from the case. This is easily remedied by holding the down button on it, but it's still a bit annoying.
- The left headphone occasionally is susceptible to loud, very jarring interference that sounds like popping and cracking. It makes the headphones basically unusable when it happens, which thankfully is not that often.
- I'm replacing these headphones for the second time because the charging case isn't charging properly. It will sometimes show a full charge, then if I unplug and plug it back in, it shows a yellow or red light, indicating it's not fully charged.

The ugly:
- If your headphones need to be replaced, Jabra will NOT do advanced exchanges. In essence, in you're on the West Coast, be prepared to be without headphones for nearly two weeks while you wait for yours to reach Jabra and then for them to send you new ones. This, frankly, is unacceptable.

title: I really wanted to give this item 5 stars, but.......
content: Okay. Lets cut to the chase.  These are probably the best ear-buds I have ever owned.  The sound quality is AWSOME!! The only complaint I have is that I must have weird shaped ears because I keep having one of them come loose and fall out.  Right Ear.  Hard to keep fit......Also, (and this may have to be due to my antique 4.0 Bluetooth Phone) pairing is not very efficient. These things will probably really work fine with 5.0. I lose paring at least once every hour (more if I traverse heavily populated areas/stores/malls with lots of electronic stuff.) I suppose I should return them, but the sound quality is so darn good and I don't think a smaller ear-bud exists.  One last gripe - though several extra earpieces are provided, it would have been nice if two of each size would have been included.  Also, if you have sensitive ears (as I do), the earbud (s) can get uncomfortable after about one hour.  Don't get me wrong, folks. These are amazing earbuds.....Just need a little "tweaking"!!! Thank you, JABRA for some excellent earbuds. I'm gonna put up with some of the shortcomings and keep them!!!

title: They turn on REPEATEDLY by themselves!!!!!
content: I tried to (and, in fact would) like these earbuds.  The sound is actually really good, the battery life is very good. The carrying cases is the perfect size for me to put them in my pocket and carry around and can immediately listen to some of the videos that are sent to me on a moments notice.  I have two complaints though.  They really are not the most comfortable buds I have had.  I can only wear them for an hour or so, then have to give them a rest.  Overall however, this I can live with, and without any real problem.  The one thing that has turned these earbuds into an overall nightmare is that no matter what I do THEY KEEP TURNING ON BY THEMSELVES!!!!!  This is a real problem because during the day, I have important calls from work.  I will be talking to someone with the Bluetooth in my ear when all of a sudden, I no longer hear them.  When I look at my phone, I can see that it is connected to the Jabra earbuds (which are in my pocket).  I turn them off and I switch back to my Bluetooth earpiece.  Two minutes later, they have turned themselves back on (both buds) and have taken the call, playing the video, or whatever.  I have tried to find an answer for this to no avail.  There is no firmware to fix this, and no remedy.  This is completely unacceptable.

title: Will not disappoint.
content: Just unboxed. Packing was difficult to open. The earbuds fell to the floor when first opening package; not secured. It paired to iPhone X flawlessly...immediately. The fit is superb, comfy. They are inserted into the outer ear canal with a slight rotation, and are snugly secured like a cork in a bottle. My Apple AirPods fell out within seconds. content: I just got these at Best Buy. I did a lot of research on the best AirPod alternatives. My ears are small so AirPods always fell out. These always came up as the best in my research, often surpassing AirPods. I’ve only had them a couple of days but I’m very impressed. The fit is superb with the smaller ear fittings. I’m very happy with my purchase and highly recommend these.

title: Great investment!
content: Let me start by saying I did hours of research before finally deciding on the Jabra Elite 65t set. I looked into about every brand there was from knockoffs to Bose and Sony. I am beyond happy that I went with this set because I didn't want to sacrifice battery life for a lower price, or comfortability for better sound. This set landed right in the middle. The sound is incredible, hitting all the highs and lows flawlessly. The battery life is impressive considering how small the earbuds and case are. I use them for about 4.5 hours straight at work before they start giving me the low battery warning. They are more comfortable than I expected and stay in your ear really well, even though there is nothing that secures it to your ear.

I did a ton of research before purchasing. I kept having issues with the 40 dollar bluetooth earbuds you can buy on amazon. But these have none of the issues

title: On first impression, one of the finest products I’ve ever dealt with.

By miles...and I’ve gone through a few decent high-end headphones of various form factors over the past 8 years. More intuitive interface than an Apple products (taps, pull out to pause, single ear mode, easy to pair, charging case). It all truly Just Works. I have large ears and the Apple EarPods don’t fit me. If that sounds like you these head phones may be for you.

title: Best earbuds

title: No bass at all

title: Way better than I imagined...
content:
I was not a fan of truly wireless earbuds because of the low hour listening time. I had purchased a product from Apple and returned it so I ended up getting the Apple Airpods and the experience actually changed my mind about truly wireless buds. I don't like the way the Airpods fit but like the freedom the truly wireless give. I looked around for something that would fit better and decided on the Jabra Elite 65t and I have to say I'm very happy I did. I own a number of what could be considered high end over the ear headphones as well as too many earbuds and I like to rotate between 4 pair. I mention this to give some perspective. I listen to a wide variety of music and just went for a 7 mile run on Monday Nov. 5 2018 using the 65t and I'm really impressed. I first thought the 65t's would not be comfortable but they really are to me. When I ran on Monday I used some thin headband ear warmers because it's getting cool here in Connecticut. Anyway the 65t's never felt lose or like they would fall out. I used them today when I went out to take care of business. When I run I listen to music from my Apple Watch Series 4 and the 65t's stayed connected and didn't miss a beat, even with the Airpods I had a couple of drop outs so it really appears the bluetooth is rock solid. I have not had any issues with the left and right buds not connecting when I first put them in, right then left of left then right. Also for me the music sounds pretty dog gone good too. I mentioned my over ear headphones (I list them in some other reviews) as a point of reference and to me these are really musical, i.e. let all the stuff I listen to come through, I don't miss a thing, not one thing. I am so happy I got these the freedom of truly wireless is awesome. The battery is not an issue either. Even when I happen to listen at home using these while cleaning the house or doing other chores I can't see the battery being an issue. Like this morning I had business to take care of and walked around for an hour or so and when I checked the battery level they were up around 90%. I'm happy so far and hope these hold up. Really glad I chose Jabra. It's going to be hard to go back to regular earbuds with the wire connection, I do bring a pair when I go on my runs or use the 65t's while out and about. I always bring an extra pair no matter what I'm using. Anyway my experience with the 65t's are really good.

Update 11/8/2018: Just a follow up. I really like these buds but kind of disappointed with Amazon customer service. I purchased these on 11/1/18 and now 11/8/18 they are $50 cheaper. I pay my way as Prime member and even if I wasn’t I think that if I purchased these from the Amazon store and then the next day they are discounted then why not give some consideration to people that paid full price within a week or so. Come on, you lose more money having me send them back for a refund then you have spend time and money having to get them ready to resell at and even lower price. I guess that’s somebody else is a billionaire and I’m complaining about $50.

12/12/18 Update: Sorry about the rant above. After further use of these and trying the Elite Sports as well as the AirPods, the regular Elite 65t are by far the best as far as I'm concerned. Even making and receiving calls on the Elite 65t's are perfect. I've been looking at other truly wireless pods and actually ordered a couple then canceled the order after thinking about how well these perform, so I went ahead and ordered another pair of Elite 65t's. One for working out and the other for casual use.

title: Amazing sound, doesn’t fall out of my ears when running!
content:
I have to give these guys 5 stars. I wanted a pair of cordless headphones but as much as I’m an Apple fan, I couldn’t bring myself to purchase the AirPods because of the way they look (I know, I know). I’m so glad I got these Jabra 65t though and here’s why:

I am a 5’4 Asian female and I have relatively small ears. The fit of these (I used the med size caps) fit so snug, which I was surprised about because usually I have to use the super small ones. However, the minute I put these in they fit like a glove. The next test was the gym. Would they fall out when I started running or even when I was lifting weights? The answer is NO! They never felt loose when I was pounding away on the treadmill (relatively speaking...) and I felt confident that they were secure in my ears and were not going to fall out.

The sound quality works for me. I’m not super picky about sound quality, but I have to say the Jabras were great. I love the app as you can adjust the settings if you prefer more bass or more treble. I find it super handy. Also, outside noise. I didn’t hear a thing! (No annoying grunting from the dude next to me!).

Overall, I am so pleased with this purchase. It’s exactly what I was looking for and I would highly recommend these guys especially to the females with small ears, like myself. The price is also reasonable. The 2 year warranty is awesome, too.

Go get some!

title: Unbelievable!
content: These headphones are defective right out of the box. They keep losing volume in the left ear, so I'm left tilting my head in awkward directions to get them to work correctly. Also, the static issue in the left ear is very much real. Thankfully, I'm still within the Amazon 30 day return window so they are definitely going back. I don't even want a replacement from Jabra because of the less than glowing reviews of their customer service. I have owned $50 truly wireless headphones that worked better than this. I will be sure never to purchase another Jabra product.

title: It's all about the fit
content:
This product is very hit or miss. If the tips fit your ears then this could be great, but if they don't it is absolutely horrible. I called Jabra and they cannot provide any other tips than the 3 stock gels that come with it. At this price point that is ridiculous as I've gotten 6 or move with in ear headphones that cost half of this set. For me all sizes were either small so didn't hold or block sound, or uncomfortable so I couldn't use them for more than 30 mins at a time. I've had countless in ear headphones so am well aware of how to get these to fit correctly and have never run into this issue before. The issue here is that with only 3 options there isn't anything to work with. Either they fit or they don't, and if they don't all the other great features of this device doesn't matter. The loose tips make the sound muddled and the volume low, and the uncomfortable ones help the sound quality but it gets distracting if you're using for more than 30 mins. Also, since they are wireless the ear tips keep these in place so even if you're OK with losing sound quality with a looser fitting tip, they will fall out with movement so that isn't an option.
My advice, if the return policy will let you send them back after trying them for a few days then they are worth a shot.  They seem well built and the sound is good for wireless if you get a good fit. But without the return policy, don't risk it as those three gel tips aren't going to accomodate everyone. It just feels like a poor design flaw to make everything hinge on the fit of the ear tips but not provide options to make sure that fit is great for everyone. I might try some foam options that are out there but none of those are rated well and this adds to the cost of an already expensive set of headphones so even if they do work I could never recommend this product to everyone. As much as I hate the design, I get why Apple went with the air bud design. There flaws are obvious and you know what you're getting going in. It sucks to drop this type of money on something labelled "the best truly wireless headphones" only to have them ruined by little pieces of silicone.

title: Great Truly Wireless.
content: I purchased these "Used-Like New" via Amazon Warehouse to replace my Jaybird Freedoms because the wire kept pulling the buds loose from my ear. They came in great condition. Once I put them in my ears and turned them on they gave prompts for Bluetooth connection. The Jabra sound+ app is helpful and allows for tuning so I would download if you haven't. I'm not sure what some reviewers were complaining about regarding sound volume as I use Sony 950B over ears and find the Jabra Elites to be loud enough for my taste. title: These earphones exceeded my expectations
content:
I have an Android phone without a 3.5mm jack for headphones, and this makes it quite a bit of a pain to plug in headphones: I would have to get my headphone case, take out the USB-C to 3.5mm adapter, plug that in, then plug in my headphones and untangle the cables. On top of that, the headphones I owned didn't sound too great anyway so there wasn't much of a "payoff".

I've been meaning to buy a pair of wireless earphones but every time I went and looked they were either too expensive, had poor sound quality, or had poor battery life. The Jabra Elite 65t's seem to put a very good balance to all most of these by having both good sound quality and battery life, although many will find $160 to be a bit of a steep price to pay for any sort of earphones at all. I made the splurge and decided to go with these and so far have not been disappointed.

Two of my favorite features of these earphones are the ability to set passive sound so you can hear people around you through the built-in microphone, which works pretty well, and the ability to EQ your music. At first, listening to these earphones had me pretty let down considering I was enjoying the fit they had in my ears and the neat case they came in. After playing around with the EQ settings (which I recommend to use from my screenshot) it gave them a nice boost in sound clarity, much better sounding than the wired earbuds I have.

While I've only tested these earbuds for a few days, I've noticed that the battery life is pretty good, even after a few 5-15 minute phone calls while on my job I end up at around 80-85%. Mic quality seems to be okay as well, as I haven't heard any complaints about my voice sounding poor.

The charging case is also pretty slick and it's easy to drop the buds into their respective charging spots. I would have preferred for the charging case to be through USB-C as opposed to Micro-USB, but it does its job.

What I thought was going to be a $160 disappointment of a purchase ending in a return, actually evolved into a regret that I hadn't done it sooner. I really do recommend these earbuds, they're convenient, sound good, and last a good while.

title: Needs improvement
content: Will be returning these. The left slave cuts out and/or clicks when making phone calls. Seems not to have the same issues when listening to music which is odd.  Also, if using for traveling and looking for passive noise blocking, these are so-so. I have the large size ear buds in these and I could do with larger. Third party foam tips can be purchased for these which would most likely do a better job, but they also then need to be removed before using the charging case...not ideal.

title: They do NOT stay in during workouts
content:
The good:
They sound great. I haven't played with a some of the features like listening to ambient noise etc, but music sounds great to me.
The earphones stay charged fine for my use. I rarely use them for more than 1 hour at a time though, so placing them back in the case works perfect for me to keep them charged.
Connecting them to a device is super simple compared to other wireless headphones I've tried.

The bad:
They do NOT stay in my ears during hard workouts - running or lifting. That was my primary need. I have tried all 3 sizes of caps provided with the headphones, and that makes no discernible difference. They initially seat tightly and feel like they create a seal (there is a slight pressure inside the ear if you push on them). Once my body heats up and I start sweating though, they will not stay in at all. I have had them fall out while running indoors and out, and also while lifting weights  at the gym - all of which is extremely inconvenient (almost had someone step on one when it fell out and bounced around the weight room while I chased it around)! I find I can manage them at the gym now that I am used to them, but I'm hesitant to wear them running as they are more of a distraction than anything else.
They cut in and out often enough to be irritating. I haven't actually timed it or counted it, but I'd say about 1 use out of every 5, for 5 minutes of the hour I use them, they break up and sound like a bad cell phone connection. I haven't noticed any repeatable pattern for it either. It doesn't happen in the same place or under the same conditions (meaning it doesn't only happen when I'm standing next to something that is obviously interfering).
If you want to only use 1 earphone, you HAVE to use the right one. That's probably not a problem for most people, but I am deaf in my right ear.

Conclusion:
This is the best pair of wireless headphones I have used, and I've used several from $40 to $200. I would recommend these headphones, but with the caveat that you should manage your expectations if their primary purpose will be for running or other vigorous activities.

title: quality control issues, and unrefined buggy system. No sugar coat
content:
Before purchase I was very positive and excited to try these out. I couldn't understand how reviews were worse than airpods. Now I understand. A product like airpods may be missing some features and may have slightly worse sound quality, but what airpods have that these do not is the refinement, ease of use, and a polished feel to them. I didn't think that was a big issue but now I see it's a huge deal. If you have an iPhone, and maybe even android, definitely consider airpods.

I'll start with the ultimatum if you consider it so; airpods are more comfortable than rubber tips. May change from ear to ear, but I consider my ears average / slightly larger. No ear wax issues, and my ears don't get sore. I still use these, because I can handle this downside.
(First pair)
Before and after firmware update, left side is slightly louder. Tried them in both ears. Sound otherwise is ok. Comfort is the best rubber tips can be, which is mediocre. I'll order some memory foam tips. The thing that really disappoints me is lack of quality control, some guy probably marked these as fine but in actuality there was a slight problem with balance between sides. If this is a software thing it's even sadder because they shouldn't have that problem after so long since release. Ill probably return and exchange these for a pair that are balanced properly

UPDATE:
new pair arrived, they work fine. I wont give 5 stars because setup wasn't smooth and they aren't as refined and are more buggy and glitchy compared to airpods. And because of quality control being poor, there are lots of online stories about the same thing.

But rage aside, now that everything's setup and working, they are honestly good. Too bad a $190 dollar product feels so unrefined, but once they are setup, things go smoothly. I'd price them @120, and the cheaper ones @100. Or at least the same as airpods at 150... If bugs were gone and setup was smooth, I'd feel better about 190

Final update: software is buggy. Down to 3 stars. My settings consistently do not save. For example, I've turned off pause on removal multiple times, and it randomly reactivates. Very frustrating.

I know alot of this makes them sound bad, but in the end I haven't returned em, I'll use them. Everything I didn't mention works great, pretty much I recapped the bad things. I am disappointed with the lack of refinement at this price point, but eh I got the money to put toward the best available for Android in hopes improvements can be made. Excited to see new development in this technology.

title: They’re great... if/when they work
content:
I really want to love these headphones. They’re very sleek and have great sound quality WHEN they’re working. That’s the issue.

I got these headphones in November and they worked great. In February my R earbud stopped playing sound out of the blue (although I could still use it to control both headphones). I called customer service and they offered to send me a replacement for the R earubud. It just arrived today (5 weeks later).

Right out of the box I had issues syncing it with my existing L earbud. After 35 minutes on hold with customer service, I got instructions on how to sync them and I got off the call. After following the instructions, the earbuds paired but now they intermittently GMCLA out during audio.

I spent another 30 minutes on hold and spoke with a different customer service rep who walked me through a factory reset and a language update. Before getting off the phone she provided me instructions on obtaining a replacement set via the manufacturer warrantee if the reset should fail (which it did). The catch: they won’t send me my replacement until I send in the old pair, and then I’ll have to wait god-knows-how-long for the replacement pair to ship - let’s assume another month.

Let’s do the math.... out of 4 months of ownership, I’ve spent 1 of them waiting and I’ll likely spend another month waiting before I have a usable pair. And these headphones cost how much?!?!

title: Works
content:
Pre-face: the only "true wireless" headphones I've tried before were Apple's.

Upon initial impressions I wasn't wow'd when going through the contents.  The earpieces while solid don't appear to be much; the plastic is soft, the case was a toy and the box was 99% space.  Seriously they could of cut down on box size considerably seeing as the case + earbuds + small box of wire/ear gells and pamphlet aren't that big...

I don't usually judge a book by its cover and I already knew the public outcry over how terrible the carrying case is so I moved on.  Packaged everything up and charged over night, getting them to fit in the case isn't hard it is fairly idiot proof but getting the case open royally sucks.  I don't listen/workout with the case so I didn't equate it into my rating.

Case - It has a battery, its a bit bulky and opening it is stupid hard.  I found that if you squeeze as you try to pry the lid open its easier but I feel like I'm going to crack the case eventually.  More of a nuisance than anything but this seems like a terrible design to let through on a niche/expensive product.

Sound - They sound good, the Air Pods IMO sound better, but these are good enough.  For the price I don't feel like I'm missing out.

Connection - to the phone (iphone 6S+) they are perfect, auto connection is seamless, quick and usually done before I get them out of the case and into my ear.  They connect to my Surface Pro but it won't let me utilize them as a sound source, what ever as that's not what I bought them for.  Connecting together its a bit wonky, there are some hick-ups with the LEFT ear connecting.  In fact this originally led me to believe that I had a bad pair, but the left ear doesn't always sync up with the right and you won't get anything from it, it either isn't turned on or its "frozen." I haven't been able to determine what actually causes this yet but the fix is to put it in the case and take it out again, that fixes it.

Fit - These have yet to fall out and I run a 5k daily + I do circuit training.  They fit in your entire ear, for me they are super snug and at first I wasn't completely sold on them staying in there.  With that said I do have some ear strain after wearing them straight for 6 days, often for multiple hours.

Call quality - seems good, did some video calling and no one complained.  There is no active noise canceling, they physically block the sound from the other side.  They offer a hear through option that in my personal/unprofessional opinion .... sucks.  Turned it off, its staying off.

App - helpful bits of info, offers limited control of the earbuds but control nevertheless.  I want to say its gimmicky but with the help section, auto updater and ability to turn off *hear through* is a big plus.

Touch controls - sensitive enough to not have to jab your ear drum trying to get them to press, but stiff enough to not accidentally trip Siri when you are trying to scratch your ear either. Intuitive, easy to understand, its also laid out in the app if you forget what does what.

I wanted to like the Air pods but they don't fit my ears, these do, these are also "sweat proof" which is more important to me than better sound quality.  To me they are worth the price despite having some small hickups and a terrible battery case.

title: Almost perfect!
content: These are great! I read all the professional reviews and opted to buy these after I gave up on AirPods. I really wanted AirPods to work but they don’t sit securely nor do they have a good seal (more on that later). I owned them for 6 month and used after market silicone ear hooks to keep them in place when exercising. But in the end, because the AirPods didn’t crest a seal in my ear, I couldn’t hear my music when on the subway or while walking along a busy street. The Jabra Elite 65t solves most problems while only creating other minor ones. The “pause when you take it out” feature only works on the right earpiece so you can’t wear only the left. But this “problem” is mitigated by the listen through feature. The earbuds create a fantastic seal which blocks out a lot of ambient noise. By pressing the right earpiece twice, you can hear what is going on around you. The sound is a bit distorted, but you can still hear everything. This is actually a really great feature as you don’t have to take the earpiece out when a brief interaction is required. The only other complaint is that the left earpiece doesn’t connect when I take it out of the case. To connect the left, I have to press and hold the volume button on the left piece after the right has connected. I also with the earpieces were magnetic and held to the charging/carrying case like the AirPods. But these connect as reliably to my iPhone as the AirPods ever did. I have no battery issues and I do use them heavily. Love these and they never fall out.

title: Amazing Sound
content: The sound on these are amazing, and the hear through feature that is available is great. The Jabra app allows for finer tuning in how you prefer to listen to your music. But also creates various modes for specific settings such as Home vs Work and even Driving. The buttons feel like buttons and while at first wearing them tends to hurt, after about a week or two your ears will adjust and they will not hurt anymore. Overall great product just wish the price was more reasonable.

title: If you have smaller ears, pass these over.

title: Better than I anticpated
content:
I was concerned having read the reviews for these and the Bose bluetooth earbuds, and seeing so many folks just tearing them up as unreliable.  Left earbud drop out.  Won't stay connected with phone 2 ft away.. etc. etc. etc..

But(!) These things are great.  Paired them with my phone (iPhone 8) put the phone on my center island, and walk around my entire apartment with no issues at all.  Wear them on long walks (90 mins) and they truck along like no big deal.

The plastic housing is a little tough on the ears if I'm being 100% truthful.. but I haven't tried the other rubber earbuds yet, so maybe bigger or smaller would work.  and really I'm getting use to them.  They're secure in my ears and that's more of a concern for me.

 I also haven't tried the phone through these.  I didn't really buy them for that -- so no biggie.

Bought mine on sale for $119 which was about $50 less than the Bose.. so ... deal.

As far as sound quality is concerned, they seem fine to me.  Does it have the bass that a big woofer has?  no.  But, is it tinny or all treble?  No.  I hear little quiet elements in songs that I normally don't hear played in open air..  so I'm satisfied.

Good buy in my book.

title: Quality Issues
content:
The Good:
Sound is decent with good bass and treble
Build is perfect for workout, does not fall off ears (YMMV)
Feature/tech rich
Fast bluetooth (5.0) connection, instantly connects with device upon exit from case

The Bad:
Inconsistent bluetooth connectivity between earbuds. Left ear piece may not connect immediately and needs to be placed back in the case to reconnect
Hurts ears after 1 hour or so of usage
Wind noise is horribly managed
More below:

Comments:

I've had 3 pairs of the Elite Active 65t with no luck at all.  The first (purchased from a known retailer; Black Titanium) had the left piece remarkably uncomfortable than the other. It seems that it was slightly larger than the other earbud.  The 2nd and 3rd (purchased directly from Jabra; Copper Blue version)  had echoing/feedback issues.  Anyone on a phone call with me would hear a loopback of whatever sound they make, consistently. It's a major no go especially for mobile professionals that are always on conference/meeting calls.

TIP: If you already bought this product, ask the other person on the line if they hear themselves. There is no fix for this per Jabra, it's a defect apparently which requires replacement.

The tech support and customer service from Jabra were friendly but hardly impressive. Their replacement and/or return procedures takes around 2 weeks to processs (not counting 10 business days expectation for a refund).

I would not recommend this product.

title: Great sound, but the case is frustrating to open
content:
These earbuds maintain a clear connection--I can listen to audio books on walks now without the frustration of the sound sputtering and dropping.  Having my phone in my back pocket or in a running belt is no longer a problem: the connection remains strong and clear regardless of where the phone is on my person.  In that sense, this was a great purchase that appreciably reduced my general level of technology-related frustration. However, the charging case is weirdly hard to open.  The trick seems to be to squeeze the sides of the case firmly (just below the latch) while pushing up on the lid, but this is not at all explained in the brief picture-filled guide that comes with the device.  Are we now  assuming that most purchasers are functionally illiterate?  Why is it that every manual now includes as few words as possible and instead tries to convey information through stick-figure cryptograms?  Is this all supposed to be some sort of puzzle that will stave off mental decline in consumers at large?

The Jabra app was also not so clear about how to open the case.  Even my teen struggled to get it open--and once she did, could not reconstruct what exactly she had done to finally release the clasp.  We were both left with new-found sympathy for our poodle's struggle with treat-filled dog puzzles.

title: The included ear tips are bad, degrade performance.
content:
The ear tips make the good headphones sound bad. The are also the root cause of a number of problems I faced. I am going to give these a week and if I can't find a solution, these are going back.

1. The earbuds come with three sizes of ear tips. For me, none worked! They are silicone but just don't stay in the ear. These earbuds do not have fins and mostly rely on a good fit in your ear canal to stay in place. After really shoving (painfully) into my ear canals, none of the supplied tips  provided that secure fit in my case.
2. The ear tips absolutely degrade the audio quality. I could hardly get any bass even with the EQ bass frequency set on high. Again, this is because of the inferior fit and seal of the included silicone tips.
3. The charging case will NOT fit the earbuds if you use a different set of ear tips on them. I tried using ear tips from my older beats earphones and they provided an infinitely better fit and sound quality but I have to remove them before charging these earbuds.

Jabra needs to include better quality ear tips with these ear buds. The ones that come with it are bad in every way possible.

title: Best i've used but the price!
content:
I'm an active person. I workout 4-6 days a week, Run often, cycle when I can as well. Besides having the right shoes for the job (look at my prior reviews).

Tech is another crucial thing to me, in particular, headphones. I've gone through many headsets over the years from inexpensive over the ears sets, to top of the line wired earbuds to even Bone Conduction (which do not waste your money on).

What I've found though is there are tradeoffs when trying to find the right headset. One might do great that wraps around your ears--but gets in the way of sunglasses. The BT range is weak, but the battery life is excellent, they fit great, but the sound is horrid. The elite active 65t has all the strengths I look for in earbuds with the most minute weaknesses I've come across in a package.

Sound: They are spectacular nearly a 10/10, but the Bose counterpart is just a tad better. If the sound is a dealbreaker for purchase between the two, don't base it alone on sound.

Fit: Perfect. I generally tend to swap out the base buds for a bigger one that comes with them; I didn't here. They never move, they never feel like they are about to fall out. As earbuds with nothing around the ear or some obtrusive wire getting in the way, they never interact with sunglasses or a hat even in the sold with a skullcap on, they are not hindered by anything.

Bluetooth: Night and day between these and the Bose counterpart. I get NO dropoff whatsoever with the Jabra while the Bose gets lost in the woods all the bloody time to the point of disconnecting from the device I have it paired to. Jabra is solid the whole time.

Battery: Solid 5 hours of consistent use is what they claim. I haven't pushed it that far yet, but if every claim Jabra has made of these has come true, then I don't doubt this will be the same.

Usability: The left ear controls volume and tracks surfing the right is for calls/pauses music/Alexa commands if you use that. Both buds have a microphone for calls and voice commands. Easy to move through music tracks even when using bulky gloves (as I have been using at the time of this review. It's cold winter here).

The only weakness here would be the price as these retail at an eye-watering $189. I think Jabra has knocked them down to $159.99 (which is what I paid for them), but still way too high. If they were around $100-$120 I'd tell everyone to go out there and pick up a pair, but not at the price they currently sit at.

I would recommend at this point that consumers looking for reliability and product support look elsewhere.  I'll update if anything changes.

title: Excellent fit and function
content:
Biaural wireless earbuds with a nice docking case? Yes, please.

PROS
-Very comfortable and compact in the ear. The round shape fits snugly with minimal overhang. Lightweight enough that it doesn't feel like it will fall out. The included eartips work well for me. You can always swap the tips for something like the Comply Sport Pro Memory Foam Earphone Tips if you want an even more secure, noise-blocking fit.
-The dock works well. Earbuds fit in easily and securely. Undocking/docking automatically connects/disconnects from phone.
-Right side is the master and can be used without the left side (slave). Right side controls start/pause which works great for podcasts.
-Audio sync between left and right is flawless. No issues so far.

CONS
-None so far.

COMPARISON to the similarly designed Sony SP700N
-The Sony works well but I prefer the Jabras.
-The Jabra fits more comfortably and snugly in my ear. The Sony is elongated and hangs out of the ear a bit more.
-The Jabra master earbud button controls start/stop while the Sony master controls noise cancelling which is not useful to me. I prefer the Jabra here for the times I want to use only one earbud.
-The Jabra is much easier to dock than the Sony.

OVERALL
These Jabras are a great choice for wireless biaural earbuds.

title: Great headphones... OK charging case
content:
I've been a user of the Jabra 65t headphone for over a year now.  I use them multiple times every day for phone calls, listening to podcasts and listening to music.  I have been extremely happy with their performance, and would buy them again without hesitation.

They are easy to setup and pair -- I use them regularly with my Samsung phone, iPad and Windows 10 laptop. They can maintain a connection to two different devices at the same time.

I find them comfortable to wear, and I *hate* the fit of most earbuds.  For me, they either always seem to fall out when I move, or are painful after 10mins or so.  These stay put in my ears, even while walking and hiking. (I'm not really a gym guy, so I can't comment there.) I have also worn them before for >8hrs without any pain or discomfort.

Sound quality is really good.  Typical to most wireless headphones, the bass is a little light, but I find them comparable to my Bose set, and my other wireless headsets.  These have become my favorite pair.  They don't seem to block sound much (and aren't active with white noise), but perform well with phone calls and cutting down on background noises.

I use the Jabra app on my phone for equalizer and user settings, and have applied several firmware updates without any issue.

The ear pieces function well as a pair in stereo,  or the right ear piece (master) can be used alone with the left one in the charging case.

The case.  Conceptually, it is a great idea. Solid and durable,  they protect the headset well, and do a great job of quickly recharging the ear pieces.  Unfortunately the closure design could use some improvement. It relies in a plastic tab to keep the case closed and locked. When new, the tab is tight and the case hard to open. After use, the tab bends and eventually breaks off -- so the case will no longer stay shut on it's own. Over the past year I have gone through three cases -- and at $70 each on Jabra's site -- I have now spent more on replacement cases then the headset cost. As I write this today, Jabra is out of stock and my newest replacement is on backorder.  I assume that many others are having the same challenge.  I really hope this design is improved in the next iteration -- they rely on magnets to turn off the ear pieces, so I would think a magnetic closure wouldn't be too difficult to engineer. For now I am relying on tape to keep it closed so the ear pieces can charge.

5. Airpods are super easy to use within Apple ecosystem

There was one dealbreaker for me though, which is that none of the earbud sizes fit properly.  The medium was too uncomfortable, and the small fell out.

I ended up purchasing and keeping the Bose SoundSport Wireless headphones (not the true wireless ones).  Their open earbud design was much more comfortable for my ears, such that I can tolerate wearing them for at least an hour at a time.

title: They stay in my ears!
content:
I have been skeptical of wireless earbuds for a long time. Whenever I try to wear wired earbuds while running or just lifting weights, I sweat too much and they just fall out of my ears. I figured it would be the same with wireless buds. But I took a chance and I'm happy to report that these somehow stay in my ears! I use wired overear buds for indoor use and only use these while outside and/or exercising. Only occasionally does it move around, and only once in 2 months of active use has an earbud fallen out completely (compared to EVERY time with wired earbuds for me, this is a borderline miracle).

The "hear-through" feature is awesome, and it's great to be able to tone down loud traffic. I was concerned there would be issues with Bluetooth connectivity, since I've used cheap semi-wireless headphones in the past that would drop out even if my phone was in my pocket. I haven't had any issues with connectivity. Also NO weird static noise that other people have mentioned.

The case is very durable and I have had no issues with the connection in order to charge them up. Excellent battery life.
