title: Finally wireless earbuds that work for me
content:
As an Apple guy, I so wanted the AirPods to work for me, but unfortunately I wasn't born with AirPod ears. I even tried some aftermarket accessories that attach to them to try to make them stay put in my ears, but no dice.

Next up, Samsung's Galaxy Buds. The fit was better (still not great), but no iOS app and I'm convinced they make the sound quality worse for iPhone users. Not to mention, they look like you have cotton balls stuck in your ears.

So, in what felt like a last ditch effort, I went for the Jabras (Costco $149). THEY. ARE. INCREDIBLE. They stay put, block out outside noise, have a decent iPhone app and deliver better sound quality (for me, at least) than either the AirPods or Galaxy Buds. I haven't sweat a ton in them yet, so can't report on that, but I couldn't be happier with this purchase.

title: Intermittent buzzing in left ear bud - DO NOT BUY
content:
I oscillate between periods of loving these headphones, and then absolutely hating them. Overall the design is excellent: they are extremingly portable, easy to slip into my pocket, good at blocking external noises, the wireless is a BIG plus (and the reason I got them), and the charging case is fantastic. And the sound quality is generally pretty good too. BUT – and it's a huge but – there is intermittent buzzing in the left ear bud, that makes listening to music with them on most days an absolute nightmare. It's impossible to ignore, and it ruins the experience. I even complained after the first purchase because of this problem and had a replacement pair sent me in the mail, but the exact same thing happened.

Overall, I regret the purchase, and I would not recommend buying these to anyone.

title: Great earbuds!
content: Great fit in my ear and both the sound and battery quality are very good! Bluetooth connection is quick and easy.

title: Great Fit!
content:
One of my biggest pet peeves with earbuds is that they are usually all too big for my little ears. At first glance, the earbuds appear to be HUGE. However, they fit my little ears just fine! Especially when I use the smallest ear gels that come with them.

I love that you can go five hours in between charges and that with a short 15-minute rapid charge you can get one hour of talk time.

The Jabra Elite 65t does take a little getting used to when it comes to controlling them. The buttons are right on the face of the earbuds and sometimes when putting them in you turn them off or when adjusting the volume. Also, note that you can use they are meant to work together. The right one is the master and it “talks” to the left. You can use the right on its own, but the left will not work independently.

The sound is fantastic, and I love that the earbuds seem to cancel out all other sounds around you. You may be able to hear a little bit of what is going on, especially if it is a loud noise. However, for the most part, you only hear what is going through the earbuds.

title: Great product
content: Love them, great product, fits comfortably, great sound for music and calls and I like the noise pass through that doesn't muffle my environment. As much as I like these, if you have an issue with these types slipping out of your ear, that's gonna keep happening, you'll need some that go into the ear canal. Besides that, these are great for normal use.

title: Can't Trust them to Work.
content:
After a month the left unit no longer works.

I really hate the charging case.  I find I am required to vigorously fight with the latch to open it, each time.  And I suspect that the units sometimes independantly fail to make electrical contact with the charger often, leaving me to wonder if a failed charge will make for a day without the use of the earbuds.  Yes, I know about the green LED, but it lights up even if only one bud is charging in the crapy case. I don't trust the charging case LED.

title: Excellent wireless earbuds but good luck with support if you lose part of them.
content:
I bought these and fell in love with them, they're great headphones! The sound quality is excellent, the pairing is easy and the connection is great. I was amazed how long the batteries lasted too.

But then I lost my case on an airplane. They don't sell replacements on amazon in the same color as my headphones, so I placed an order through Jabra's website (they were backordered) and waited. They took my money but have yet to tell me when/if the case will ever arrive, and I've been waiting for 3-4 weeks now. I'm at the point of giving up and asking for a refund, but of course there's no way to cancel without calling in directly, and when I called their phone lines were down.
Great headphones, terrible support for replacing lost components.

title: They fall out of my ear or come displaced. (At least in my right ear mostly)
content: I really wanted to love these!! I loved the sound quality, the ability to hear without taking them out.... but they fall out of my ears, no matter what kind of earbud tip I have on them.

title: Great fit, amazing sound
content:
These earbuds sound incredible. The ability to tailor the sound to your needs with the equalizer in the app really helps. They came fully charged in the box, I paired them with my Google Pixel 2 in five seconds and was listening to music shortly thereafter. When I first put them in my ears, I was using the middle-sized buds, which sounded so-so (very little bass). But I tried the larger size and that made a world of difference - the bass punches. They fit snugly, but not uncomfortably. I don't think I could wear them all day, but that's not why I bought them - I bought them to listen to music while running & working out. If I'm working at my desk all day, I'll use my over-the-ear headphones. Bass response is full and mid/treble ranges are warm & beautiful. I tried metal, jazz & classical - all three sounded the way I think they should. No complaints whatsoever. I haven't tried them for voice calls yet, but I have no doubt they will be fine. I'd highly recommend.

Update - 8/2/18 - after wearing these a few times, they are even more comfortable. And I'll take back what I said previously about not wearing them for very long. I've had them in for nearly two hours and they are not uncomfortable at all. In fact, the bass response on them is as good as, of not better than, my Bose over-the-ear headphones.

title: Product has defect
content:
Sound disappears from one earphone.  For the price, this should NOT be an issue.
Disappointed.

title: These are slappers
content: These slap tbh

title: Simply put the left ear piece losses sound too often.
content:
If the left and right ear pieces are not (basically touching), they disconnect as I move my head or breath (as the left disconnects it pauses audio as well), so the pair is nearly worthless (not good at 200+ dollars with tax), for music or audio-book (normally what I listen to).  If I use it as only a single earpiece it works great (good range ...), it is the connection between the Left and Right that is the problem.
My head is not made of stone or metal (though I've been told it is hard), so I can not explain why it is so bad, but it is not worth buying if there is even a 1 in 10 chance of encountering such issues at the price.  I had a 40 dollar pair same issues (so try one of those first, and see if true wireless work with your head).
I would not buy again and I'm trying to get a refund as they do not work as described or at all if you desire stereo.
 I should mention the app is decent (not great, but decent) and the quality is very good, I like teh features and controls, but if they do not remain connected why by them!

title: Jabra Elite -
content: Jabra Elite...more like Jabra "Just Okay". I saw these on a YouTube review, and was convinced for the buck, these were 'all that'. Well, not so much. They are sleek, good batt live, do have good sound quality, if you keep them pressed up in your ear holes! They do not fall out, they just don't stay up in the ear far enough to get the kind of volume and bass that I was expecting. If you have small ear holes, and not big ass ear holes like me, you might be happy with them.....3 outta 5!  :D

title: No active noise cancellation
content: This particular product does not have active noise cancellation. I was a little upset to learn this when contacting the company direct. The volume control is pretty good the sound quality when listening to music or during a call is pretty good the noise cancellation when in a call is non existent. If you are looking for that particular feature this is not the product that you are wanting to purchase. Disappointment on the noise cancellation

title: Below average
content: Did not cancel any noise sounds was subpar

title: Almost there
content: Wish there was a function to turn on and off noise cancelling without the app. Other than that it is great.

title: Nice design for these Jabra Elite Active 65t
content: Nice design for these Jabra Elite Active 65t. Out of the box there was no Bass as compared to my other earbuds (Bose Sound Sport Wired) then I tried the larger of the earbud cushions that the product comes with. That fixed it. No issues. They are relatively light weight. Nice not having the wire between the earbuds. I haven't jogged, etc. with them but they seem not likely to fall out. The software update is easy to do - just use the App, it's free. Good on Phone Calls too. My music config - Samsung S9+, USB Audio Player Pro, .WAV files from CD quality to 96/24 bit. Not all that quality transmits over Bluetooth. Nice charging Jabra Elite Active 65t Alexa Enabled True Wireless Sports Earbuds with Charging Case  - Copper Bluecase too.

title: Great for the gym
content: Great for the gym, the audio setting where you can hear outside noise is strange when music is paused, almost acts like a hearing aid. Doesn't break from sweat, constant use, or being thrown around.

title: It is good enough for me.
content: good

title: Does not stay in ears while working out
content:
I understand it is impossible for companies to design a product that fits everyone, but the pure number of people who complain about this product not staying in your ears while working out holds merit.

I purchased the earbuds two months ago and have tried numerous types of fits for the earbuds to no avail. As a former owner of AirPods, I am severely disappointed in the functionality of this product.

title: Won't stay in my ears
content: I returned my order because they simply wouldn't lock in my ears while exercising. The main reason I bought them was to cut the cord for my workouts and I found myself constantly pushing them back into my ears instead of focusing on what I was doing. They sounded great and being able to filter in external noise was an awesome feature but if they don't stay in it's not worth it to me.

title: Don't believe the hype!
content: These are very overrated. The sound quality was good, but it was so low. I used multiple phones to make sure it wasn't a glitch. The app was okay, but the hype is just hype. I have a pair of $30 Dudios Air that sound better and with more bass.

title: Great buy

title: VOLUME NOT LOUD ENOUGH WHEN LISTENING TO MUSIC
content: This product is excellent in every way except for one.  The volume doesn't get loud enough.  Love the quality, great on conf calls, noise cancelling, just need the volume to crank louder for when listeneing to music. Did have the app as well and called support. title: Great sound
content: They work great all the time.

title: Best TWEs I’ve had
content: I’m an iPhone user and have used the airpods but these are just far better in terms of aesthetics, sound, and in terms of functionality.

title: Poor Fit
content: People love these and they are heralded in the press but I have small ears and even the tiniest buds left me with a poor fit - completely insecure in my ears. They are too expensive to lose, so... I returned for JLAB Epic Sport (real wireless) with ear hooks.

title: 10x better than AirPods
content: I love these wireless headphones.  I’m never going back to AirPods.  They don’t fall out of my ears and the sound is consistent and crisp.

title: "The Jabra Elite Alexa-Enabled Ear Buds," Nearly the Perfect Ear Buds
content:
I am not a big fan of ear buds for several reasons.

1 - Most are not very comfortable.
2 - I have trouble keeping them in my ears.
3 - I have heard that many people get ear infections.
4 - The sound quality isn't especially good.

Still, when I'm driving my car, my cigarette lighter no longer works, so I'm unable to keep my blue tooth speaker charged and listening to my Audible book library is not as nice as better speakers would be. My only choice is to wear headphones, but that is not very popular with law enforcement. So, I gave these ear buds a try.

These are the most comfortable, best sound quality ear buds I have ever tried. Their design includes a method to lock them into the ear that does provide a solution to my worries about them falling out. Spare ear bud covers are provided that helps with sanitation.

Another nice feature is the recharge on the fly case. You simply put them in the case and they recharge. I'm not sure how often this battery pack needs to be re-charged, but it does partially address the one shortcoming of the Jabra Elite, Alexa-enabled ear buds.

There is only one drawback: the promised charge life is only five hours. Usually, this is enough. But my wife and I frequently drive across country. On those days, I guess, I'll just have to work around this shortcoming.

BOTTOM LINE

i would rate them five stars except for the limited battery life.

title: Amazing sound, but download the app
content:
These headphones have a learning curve, but it's worth it.

- The gestures aren't typical for iPhone buds. The left earpiece has two buttons (or rather a rocker), and gets used to control volume, to skip tracks forward and back, and to check the battery status. The right earpiece has one button, and gets used to pause/play, to manage phone calls (including hold and decline), and to manage Bluetooth and turn the set on and off.

- If the buds are separated by much more than the width of a head they will go into pause mode (which is a huge feature if you want to take out one bud and talk to someone). But, if they are put back near each other (like, on a nightstand), they will unpause. If you want explicit pause you have to push the button on the right bud (I got burned by this a couple of times before I figured it out).

- The ergonomics can be annoying. If you press in the center of the right bud while trying to settle it in your ear, you can accidentally turn the set off. It is slightly hard to tell which is left and which is right on the first glance (the "L" and "R" are small, and black-on-black. But the left bud is the one with the rocker pips).

- The charging and pairing setup means you have to keep track of and understand three different sets of LEDs, two on the case plus the lights on the buds themselves. In five different colors.

- The quick start guide in the box is almost pointless, inasmuch as it skips all sorts of important information about how to use the buds, and is in annoying IKEA-esque graphics.

- The bass response is weak.

- There are only three sizes of eartips, and, if like me, you wear a small-and-a-half, this can be less than ideal.

Download the app!  It has an equalizer, a better and more comprehensive manual, and all sorts of other goodies, including an option to update the firmware on the buds themselves. Sometimes these kinds of apps are just nudgers to try to get you to post ads for the product to Facebook. This one is actually useful. (Except for the eartip problem). Download the app.

title: Easy pairing. Easy updates
content:
Easy pairing.  Easy updates. Excellent fit in my ears. Not the bassiest but a well balanced sound/ clear.

Way prefer form factor to competitor.

Absolutely NEED find earbuds in app.  CRITICAL

title: JUNK!
content: Used twice and the right earbud has no volume unless I hold pressure on it with my finger. Many such issues online. Bad product. DO NOT BUY THESE!

title: Great for Running!
content:
Just received these earbuds.  I have been using the VI headphones which have Harmon Kardon speakers.  Those have a very good sound, but you still have that albatross around your neck.  Also, those would cut out quite often so the Bluetooth wasn't very good.

Now, the Jabra Elite 65t's have an amazing sound!  I'm an audiophile and I want my music to sound the best that it can.  These earbuds really crank out the bass, but the mid and upper range are clear and crisp. I run with them and they feel secure the whole time (and I sweat profusely).  I ran 5 miles today and no problems with looseness.  I am using the medium ear tips.  Also, there was no dropping of the Bluetooth signal during my run, even though I run right past large high tension wires which is where my other headphones would drop the bluetooth signal.

Definitely glad I bought these!

title: As advertised
content: As advertised

title: Died After Two Months, Zero Customer Service
content: My right earbud died after about two months, rendering both earbuds useless. This seems to be a common problem from the multiple similar reviews I've read. I've made over 10 attempts to contact customer service, via phone, email and twice submitting a claim online. Weeks later, zero response. Don't waste your money on this garbage.

title: Great quality product!!
content: I read review after review between these and the Bose among other brands. I ultimately decided to give Jabra a shot and buy am I happy with my decision!! The app is great, sound quality is awesome and the fitment is superb (most important imo). I run like a guerilla on my treadmill and these have not fallen out of my ear! I do not have any syncing issues like others mentioned. Very pleased with my purchase. I think it's worth every penny for a gym junky like myself.

title: Definitly not Bose but pretty good
content: I was looking for a truly wireless set of earbuds that are comfortable to wear while I work out.  I have the Bose wireless buds and the sound is amazing but they are clunky.  These fit in the ear and are comfortable.  As other reviewers have noted, the base isn't great even when you fiddle with the equalizer - but hey - I'm not using these because my sole goal is to listen to music - I'm wearing them to work out and unlike the wireless Apple buds - these don't fall out regardless of what I am doing.

title: Best earbuds I've ever owned
content: I'll be brief. These are the best pods I've ever owned. Wireless or wired. They seal well enough in my ears to approach noise canceling, stay secure when I run, and the audio quality is very satisfying.

title: Amazing sound quality
content: Jabra elite 65t are awesome earbuds I can only give it 4 stars because the right one doesn't fit my ear correctly and it hurts so I can only wear for so long

title: Pretty awesome
content: Comfortable and feel like a nice quality. Better sound and fit then the original brands.  5/5 would buy again.

title: Loved these - the sound, the features, the look - except for one thing...
content: I wish I could give these five stars, I really do. They looks really good, they feel nice, the charging case is a nice size (albeit difficult to open most of the time), and the sound is really good! Walking through NYC, I could barely hear the traffic. The hear through feature is pretty nifty too, though I didn't use it much at all. But I actually returned these earbuds after a few days solely because I could hear my feet pounding the ground with every step I took. It gave me a headache! And given that I bought these to use on the treadmill, that just wouldn't do. Even walking casually from place to place it drove me nuts. So I had to return them. Perhaps the fit wasn't quite right (I did try the various sizes of earbud tips to no avail). I've seen no other reviews with this problem, so maybe it was just me -- but really everything else about these is great, down to the detail that calls come in through BOTH EARS!!! Which was a big reason I picked these in the first place.

title: Charging case is garbage
content: The earbuds sound great, good fit, no problems with the earbuds themselves. The problem is the charging case. It’s just complete garbage. It won’t close, so you can charge the earbuds and they keep falling out unless you strap the case closed with rubber bands or something. Horrible design on the charging case, which leads to more problems with Jabra support. The charging case barely closed from day one, and now 8 months later it doesn’t close at all.

title: Excellent
content: Very happy with these. I did my research before purchasing these. The fit is snug and good sound quality. Blocks out the surrounding noise well.

title: One setting made the difference
content: I mainly wanted to the earbuds as a bluetooth headset, and was happy that you can use the right earbud only for this purpose. When I first started using the earbuds it was a weird experience to have a complete noise-canceling listening experience without any outside noise. Walking around not being able to hear what's going on around me was different and I almost returned the earbuds. I then downloaded the app, and discovered the best setting that allows the microphone to pass through the sound around you to the earpiece, even slightly during a call or listening to music. This made a dramatic different for me. The sound quality is excellent.

title: I've Bought Two Pairs!

title: Great sound quality

Including a USB-C charging port and cable would also be better than the current mini-USB charge port and cable.

content: I was looking for a device that I could use mostly for conference calls and music secondary.  5 Stars for Music - these ROCK!...  1 Star for phone usage.  Here is the deal, the microphone is too close to the speaker.  The mic picks up the person on the call and they hear themselves echo on their side, so to fix, you have to turn the volume down to the point it is difficult to hear.  I had to return and buy AirPods - they don't have this problem as the mic is far enough from the ear piece.

title: overrated
content: Not worth the money

title: Jabra has a loooooong way to go before they start charging these prices
content:
I have had multiple Jabra products for personal and work products (my company buys Jabra and I do not know why).
Almost all of them have had "high-end prices" with "low to mid-end quality".
Before I go in the detailed review, look at Skullcandy, Soundpeats for same sound quality if not better at a much lower price or Bose for high-end headsets. But stay away from Jabra.

Jabra has consistently fallen short of greatness, with almost every product they make. They likely have smart Marketing (well there is some doubt about that too) who defines a good product and really bad engineers who do not know how to meet the requirements. In the end, almost every Jabra product has fallen short for the price I pay for them.
I should post a photo of my Jabra product graveyard (for some I could not return).

I picked these up from a local electronics chain store here, and once again, I returned it 3 days later.

When Jabra come up with a new product, they advertise and cover it well, and when it gets in the hands of the consumers,  reality hits. Let me cover few major requirements for a consumer.

COMFORT - as always, this is once again not a comfortable headset to wear. Look at Bose if you want hours of comfort or Skullcandy. Their rubber/ silicon quality if odd where it is harder than many others. So yes, after a while your ears will start to hurt. This was true to the three other headsets I have owned.

SOUND - Well they are OK in sound. very bass-y sound, I would say (Jabra, bass does not make a good quality headset). And then the left earplug had some odd flat sound response. I felt like I am having stereo effect of a stereo sound.

BATTERY LIFE - Yeah well, 5 hours under ideal conditions. For me they lasted a little over 3 hours. And that whole 15 hours claim with case is stupid ... Yes, I got the case too. 15 hours with case ? Well Marketing be damned. When it is charging in my case how am I listening to them? Just say that the case holds 3x the charge.

MATERIALS - yes, they look cheap to me. Jabra has always has had plastic-y headsets and they do this metallic satin finish to make them look great.

Stay away from this brand.
Save money and buy a Bose next month. Or buy a Skullcandy and put the remaining money in your savings account.

title: Worth the price
content: Best I’ve ever had, for phone calls, music..active

title: Needs a possible update
content: The reason I gave the product three stars is because the first pair I received had a hiss in the left ear piece that would come and go also signal would drop even while being within 20 feet of the device playing music. I asked for a replacement which arrived 3 days later and on that pair the earbuds was unbalanced. The left ear piece was loud and the right sounded mute. It was a clear distinction how unbalanced they were. So I sent the replacement back and kept the original and will just deal with them because even though they have a few problems I really don't want to have to not have them.

title: Love them!
content: The sound is good and it takes a long time wearing them before my ears hurt. I do wish they were smaller though.

title: Love these if they work.
content: I among many other customers am still dealing with getting my replacement pair of headphones from Jabra customer support. For me it was the right earbud that just stopped working after about 2 months of use. So I troubleshot on my own, updated firmware still nothing. Contacted customer support with their tight operating hours and after weeks of correspondence to include phone calls, waiting on hold and emails; I had to verify firmware version with Jabra, send screenshot of purchase from amazon, send photos of earbuds and case, wait for shipping label that did not work first time around. So then I had to submit claim again and got a new shipping label emailed to me, finally mailed earbuds and case back to Jabra only to get an email a week later that tells me "headphones ordered but out of stock to be expected to be back in stock in 2-3 weeks" then they will be finally mailed to me. Hey maybe they out of stock because they are deffective to all hell so they just trying to get it right with the 75t model. Do yourself a favor and look to other brands or wait to see reviews on Jabra products after customers have had them for a few months.

title: Greatest earbuds
content: These earbuds are great! It took me some time to get used to fitting them in my ears but otherwise the sound is great and I love that you can control outside noise

title: Unfortunately a little sweat allowed mine to slip around and fall out.
content: When I was out on my patio sunbathing, the EarPods began to slip out of place and when I stood up one fell out. Unfortunately I felt I had to return them. Purchased another earbud product with more prominent earwigs.

title: Definitely Recomend
content: These are fantastic headphones. Comfortable, great sound quality, won't slip out of your ears, even when running. I love the Hear Through feature, I can clean the house and listen to music and still hear my kid if he needs me. I love that it comes with an app, very handy. The charging case and headphones hold a charge for a lot longer than advertised, which is always a plus. I really have no complaints.

title: Fatal Design Flaw - Microphones pick up own speakers causing echo
content:
I bought these because of a trusted friend told me he loved them. For my work I am on the phone 10+ hours per day. I didn't get them for music and working out. They are comfortable.

However, people I am calling or have called me complain that they hear their voice echoing and is really annoying to them. I contacted Jabra support. They ran a couple of tests and determined more than likely it was a defective pair. They had me work with Amazon support to further diagnose problem, which I thought was very strange. Amazon support was excellent and determined they were going to ship me a new pair.

The new pair arrived and were fine for a day or two and then callers started complaining again. The next several days complaints increased. Then I had an epiphany. The buds are small and there are 2 microphones on each one. Was it possible that the microphones were picking up the sound from their own speakers thereby causing an echo / feedback? I turned down the volume and that did decrease the number of complaints substantially, however I had to turn it so low that if I had any background noise I couldn't hear them. This sounds like it is a fatal design flaw. Therefore I'm returning this second pair and going to start from scratch looking for another ear buds. This is too bad, I really wanted to like these.

title: Not a great product
content:
The product is well made but i had a few issues;
1. The case does not other size ear tip
2. I had a lot audio drop...not sure why when i am right next to my iphone 8
3. I also experience sync issue between the right and left

title: Great but weird issue with small engines.
content: Most of the time, these things are great. Whether I’m at my desk or getting some exercise, they do exactly what I want them to do. Why only three stars then? First, I can’t keep them in for long. The rubber tips that go in your ear are just uncomfortable. Easy and cheap to change but still disappointing. Second—this one is weird, they cut out intermittently around small engines. My lawn mower, string trimmers, hedge trimmers, etc all cause some kind of interference. I have no idea why but it gets annoying.

title: Nice
content: Nice , one of them suddenly pups up, i think every ear is different

title: This product is trash

When I'm driving down the high way, using the hands free microphone to talk with others through my cell phone, they randomly become unusable.  While driving there is a considerable amount of road noise, and typically they perform very well with canceling the road noise, until it doesn't.

The person on the other end of the phone call will say "Your voice is crystal clear, I can hear you perfectly. " and then 10 seconds later they will say "What did you change, I can barely hear you.  It sounds like you are in a wind tunnel."

This is very difficult to deal with because the problem doesn't increase linearly.  The noise is either fine or so terrible the other person has to turn down their volume because it is too loud.  Unfortunately I'm stuck using my $25 "cheap" headset to talk with people when I'm on the high way.

I've contacted tech support and they've been unable to fix the problem. It’s disappointing the noise cancellation works until it doesn’t.

title: Good buds. A couple of things to be aware of...
content:
I bought the Elite 65t during the Black Fri, getting a good deal (119$). They replaced the apple earbuds which I used until I got rid of my iphone. I'm using them on a Pixel3. Below my considerations:
1) Built - The buds' material is pretty good, and the design is pretty nice. They are not touch, but they have button controls which allow you to do basically everything (i.e. volume control, siri or google assistant, open/close calls...). Only downside of that, is that you have to push pretty firmely, and I found that not very comfortable, as pushing on the controls will also push the buds into your ears. This being said, I don't use the buds' controls a lot. So for me this was not a deal braker. The case looks pretty cheap. I don't like the closing mechanism at all. It seems that it's going to brake anytime (although I haven't heard of anybody saying that it broke up yet). It's not magnetic, so the buds will fall if you leave the case open, or if it opens accidentally (this was a small thing which could have improved the product a lot). Last but not least, charger is not USB-C.
2) Sound - Sound is great, very clean, and you can adjust the equalization from the app. They also have features such has hear through, which activates the mics to let you hear voices or sounds while you're listening to music (without activating this feature, they're pretty isolating). While you listen to music, you can distinguish all the instruments. I'm still very impressed from the sound. Same thing with the calls: the voice sounds great, and the other side hears you very well.
3) Connectivity - Not hugely impressed. They never lost connection from the phone. However, pretty often happens that one of the buds disconnect for a fraction of sec. Sometimes that happens 4 to 5 times in a raw, which becomes pretty annoying. I've noticed that it happens when I'm in the subway train, or close to the subway. This is one of the things which could be a deal braker. However, it's not happening very often, so for now, it's fine.

Overall, for the price I paid, I believe they're a good pair of buds. There are some downsides. However I'm a musician, and the sound quality for me is kind of a priority, so I'm fine if I have to be a bit more careful when I open/close the case, or if one of the buds disconnect for a millisec when I'm in the train, as long as the sound quality is great as it is (and as long as the disconnect issue is not something that starts happening more often). For 119$, it is def. a good deal. If you have to pay more than that, you should probably start thinking about what's really important for you. One thing I can say is that, I don't believe it exists a pair of true wireless buds which are perfect. So it's really choosing which one is the best for you (at least for now).

title: 1st time truly wireless user and am very pleased!
content:
Just received this product on 10/29/18 and am pleased with my purchase.

Here is my initial impressions and will give a further update later.

Background:
I'm travel weekly and have been looking to have good set of truly wireless earbuds to use while on a plane and in the airport. Having the ability to listen to music as well as take calls while traveling through the airport would be great.

The Jabra Elite 65t's have very good sound quality, great call clarity and battery life, although many might find $170 to be a bit pricy. I can say the price is worth it and so far have not been disappointed.

The sound quality is simply superb and rivals my Bose SoundSport® in-ear headphones.

Favorite features are “HearThrough” so you can hear people around you through the built-in microphone, which works pretty well, and customizable EQ for music.

While I've only tested these earbuds for a few days, I've noticed that the battery life is very good, haven’t run down battery yet, and haven’t had to charge the case either. Mic quality seems to be good as well, as I haven't heard any complaints about my voice sounding poor.

The charging case is small, taking up very littler room in your pocket. It is easy to drop the buds into their respective charging spots. I would have preferred for the charging case to be through USB-C as opposed to Micro-USB, but it does its job.

Pros:
Nice small compact earbuds that seem to last with a charge.
Use has been limited so far but the earbuds seem to stay well in the ear.
The controls on the earbuds. Seem to be easy to use.
HearThrough works pretty well when volume level is at 50%. I like the music mute option better.
Paring was seamless and painless. They connected to my iPhone X very quickly and haven’t had any issues as of yet.
Like the fact that the earbuds can connect up to 8 devices to the earbuds. I have two iPhone that I use daily (one personal and one for work). They connect to both as soon as I remove earbuds form charging case.
A voice command via Siri has worked fine. Have not tried with Alexa yet.
Sound quality is excellent. Smooth equalizer setting works perfect for my sound taste.
Voice communication is crystal clear as well. Other people on the call haven't had any issues hear me clear.
Noise reduction is great as well, even in loud areas.

Cons:
Earbuds seem to hurt my ears a little after wearing them for more than an hour.
Buttons could be a tap type instead of having to press. Sometime feels like I am jamming the buds into your ear. With that it sometimes causes the earbuds to become loose in the ear. I have to adjustment them again.

Final Comments:
I wish I had bought these sooner. I really do recommend these earbuds; they're convenient, superb sound quality, good quality, have nice added feature and a long lasting a battery life.

title: Update: worst fitting headphones ever
content:
Look. These aren’t bad headphones. In fact, the sound great, pair awesomely, and have a stupid long battery life. However, I HATE how these fit in my ear. I’ve had pairs of earbuds like these and they always squeeze out of my ear which is really annoying. I’m going to make myself a few foam eartips out of cheap earplugs in order to get the fit a little but better. Other than the horrible fit (for me, might be different for you), these are awesome true wireless earbuds. Let me slap in a few pros and cons.

Pros
- Awesome sound
- Helpful app with EQ and step tracker
- easy 1 time pairing
- Wonderful ability to stay connected (I actually forgot I didn’t have my phone on me and walked away from them only to realize that they were still working on the other side of the house)
- light and compact charging case
- Excellent build quality

Cons
- Doesn’t fit my ear and no (good) foam eartips on market
- Case attracts sweat oils (easy cleaned)
- Case can be easily lost as it is kinda small
- No magnets in case which allows earbuds to fall out if case is opened

Update:
Ok, so I wanted to give these things a chance, but the fit is just absolutely horrendous. They fall out of my ears no matter which eartip I use and I’m sick of it. I’ve gone out of my way to attempt to find a solution to fix the problem but there is seriously nothing. If your ear doesn’t fit any in-ear style headphones, DO NOT BUY THESE. THEY WILL NOT FIT YOU.

title: Ok At $30
content:
Wow, so many positive reviews in print and video in praise of these headphones makes me think I must have gotten a defective unit. I downloaded the app, updated the firmware and adjusted the EQ to maximize sound as much as possible. Then tried them with 3 different devices (PC, Android and Apple) and got the same results each time. I bought these primarily for media consumption so did not test call quality.

My first impression was that they are much smaller than I thought they would be. Build quality is ok, but they are primarily plastic and somewhat cheap feeling. Fit is ok, but I'd like to see some better tips, these are very thin and don't help with noise isolation. I'm no audiophile, but I know what I like and did not find it here. The sound is just ok. Volume level is pretty low at max and not loud enough to drown out noise from your surroundings. Bass is almost non-existent even when turned up all the way on the EQ. Mids and highs are clear if you can get the volume up loud enough to hear them. Honestly, I have $30 headphones that sound better than these at 6 times that price. If these were $30, I wouldn't be leaving such a negative review. You expect less for a lower price point and more for a higher one.

I purchased a set of Bose Soundsport Frees at the same time as these because there seems to be a lot of comparisons between the two. Let me just say that these aren't even in the same class as the Bose and no where near worthy of a comparison. I was very disappointed with these and will be sending them back in favor of the Bose.

title: Great Form Factor, Mediocre for the Price Otherwise
content:
I’ve had my Jabra Elites for about 3 weeks now, so I’ve had a good amount of time to give them a go as a replacement to use with my iPhoneX that I was previously using with AirPods.  Here’s the review:
The Good:
1. The form factor is great. I love how snuggly they fit in my ears, extremely low profile.
2. Battery life is okay as well.  They’re as good as any other truly wireless headset in it’s class.  They give me about 2.5+ hours per charge.
3. The Charging/Storage Case is well designed.
4. The “sound pass through mode” is a great idea, and works well often, but not always, as explained below.
The Medicore:
1. Button Functions Not Well Thought Out.  One thing I loved with my AirPods was that I could use either the left or the right, switch on the fly, and either could pause or play music.  With these buds, the right side has a play/pause feature, and outside sound pass through, and the left side has volume functions.  So you can’t really use the left only. You need to either use both or the right one alone as a practical matter.
2. Sound pass through buggy.  For some reason, when in the exterior sound pass through mode, often I hear buzzing in my ears. I think the buds are picking up some outside noise and converting it to buzzing.
3. Sound is very high in treble.  The sound is very tinny, not well balanced.
4. Often the left earbud doesn’t sync and I only hear sound from the left.  I have to put them back in the case and take them out to get them both to work.

The Bad:
1. They don’t work well with either Siri or dictation on my iPhone.  My AirPods worked flawlessly with Siri and dictation, but these don’t pick up much of what I’m saying well and the words are distorted.  This is a huge problem for me.

In sum, while they look much better than AirPods, they are still inferior in terms of sound quality and functionality.  I think the earbuds need work for iPhone use.

title: 3rd time's the charm - Great buds when you get ones that work!  - Jabra quality control is horrific
content:
It took three different pairs to get it right!

THE FIRST TWO PAIRS
In the first pair (which was in a sealed retail package), the sound was very slightly skewed to the left side (aka slightly louder in the left ear). It made it sound like the center of the sound was behind my left eye if that makes sense. It was a subtle thing, but maddening. RETURNED

The second pair, (which came in an unsealed box (no sealing tape on the retail packaging)), had a HUGE off-center bias to the left. The right headphone was barely audible at times, and full volume would cut in and out when I tried to adjust the fit. Also, the firmware update got stuck in what I'll call a boot loop. It would download, and then ask me to put the buds in the case to load it, which I would do. Then nothing would happen when they were in the case, so I'd take them out and it would tell me to put them back in the case again to do the update. I did the 10s reset of the right earbud, cleared the app cache and reinstalled, all to no avail. RETURNED

(I tried contacting Jabra customer service on the first issue, and days later I still hadn't heard anything, so I just started exchanging them.)

THE THIRD PAIR
Finally on the third pair, I got a sealed package again. Before even putting them in my ears I connected them to Bluetooth through the Sound+ app first, plugged the case in for a few minutes, then wiped (clearing cache) and reinstalled the apps (Sound+ and JabraService), then downloaded and installed the firmware update. These ones worked perfectly with balanced sound!

PROS
• Solid sound, fairly flat sound stage, maybe leaning a bit bass-y, and quite muddy for my taste. However, it's better than what I'd expect for true wireless buds. (My desk headphones are Audio-Technica ATH-M50x's for reference.)
• No cord to get snagged on things and to bounce around and pull them out of your ears when working out
• Tight fit - They really stick in your ears
• The app is well designed and pretty easy to navigate
• The HearThrough function to hear your surroundings is mediocre at best

CONS
• Micro-USB to charge the case (I hate everything that not USB-C at this point, so take that with a grain of salt)
• Tight fit - your ears definitely need time to get used to them
• Equalizer - doesn't seem all that effective

title: It's A Sad Day In Earbud-land When Reviewers Report These Sound "Good"
content:
How "professional" reviewers can say these sound "good" or "great" is beyond me. The SOUND QUALITY is one of the things these AREN'T GOOD for!  These were my 7th pair of totally wireless earbuds, & the most expensive. When you consider the cost, these are ludicrous. Cost aside:
BAD: 1. THE SOUND! The sound is bad. The frequency response is pretty flat, but they distort along the entire range, even at moderate volume.
2. They don't get very loud.
3. They fit well, but even the smallest ear-tips are too big and hurt like heck. Despite the ritual of screwing them into the side of my head to get them inserted, they would still come out if I talked a lot or ate something.
4. THE PRICE! For this kind of money, these things should rock. They don't. They whimper.
GOOD: 1. Ambient sound feature, where you can hear sounds around you, is super cool. A thoughtful touch is that it comes on slightly when you're on a call, allowing you to hear around you, but when you put on music, it automatically turns off, unless you turn it on. More manufacturers should do this.
2. A good set of controls via the push-buttons on the units.
3. They look comparatively good, not hanging out strangely, & the little microphone extension fits naturally in a certain part of your ear, angled like you see in the pictures, and isn't protrusive
4. Of all my earbuds, people I called liked how I sounded to them the best. I tested all the earbuds I have, one after another, pairing and then unpairing, & repeating the same phrase to people I called to get their opinion of these (& all the others). These won.
5. Paired easily & wouldn't drop/had good range.

Tired of being a test lab for earbuds, I bought a collection, including these, to try and find a pair that were "keepers." THESE WERE NOT THEM. I could begrudgingly put with the cost if they were good. I could even deal with the pain. To have bad sound quality, & pay a lot? That was the deal-breaker. I returned them.

title: Excellent for exercising!
content: I seriously cannot say enough good things about these headphones. I use them for my commute to work and exercising. Finding a pair of headphones that wouldn’t fall out of my ear was really important to me and I haven’t had that issue once with these. Sound canceling is phenomenal. I'm yet to use these buds for a call, but will update my post as needed.  I'm comparing these to my Galaxy Buds and my wife's PowerBeats 3.  These fall somewhere in the middle.  Pick'em up. title: Works for a few months, then forget it.
content:
I've had these for ~ 3 months & then things really started going south.  Call quality was always very poor.  I could hear OK (but never loud enough)  but every single person that I have called, complained that the ambient noise that they heard made the call unbearable, therefore, I had to disconnect my bluetooth and hold the phone up to my face to complete the call.  Yes, their 4 microphones pick up every little sound, which is a disadvantage.  Now 3 months in, they no longer turn off when placed back in the case.  My phone thinks that they are still connected so I have to manually turn off bluetooth on my phone to make a call.  The bottom line is the case is poorly designed.  The felt like plastic and the positioning prevents the earbuds from making a good contact with the contact points.  My wife has a pair of Apple Airbuds (for the last 7 months) and they drop in the case like a glove, and the sound for calls is far superior.

I already contacted Jabra customer support and after performing their troubleshooting steps (didn't work), they sent me link for a return (at first they just wanted to send a new case, but who knows what's wrong with these).  So they are going to send a label and I have to mail the whole set in and then wait (they said around 10 days but I have no faith in that) for a new (& it better not be refurbished) set.  I'm not a happy camper.  Biggest Cons are:  Poor Case Design & Poor Call quality.

title: No Wires Anymore
content:
If you are sick of earbud wires sticking to your body or getting tangled up in your pocket, Jabra Elite Active 65ts might be suitable for you. These true wireless earbuds get rid of the cords that are normally attached to the earbuds or headphones, which offers you a handsfree and cord-free experience. By securely fitting in your ears, these earbuds can shut down outside noise and help you enhance concentration while you are studying or working out. On the other hand, people around you cannot hear what you are listening to. This feature of Elite Active 65ts will also suit commuters.
Regardless of the benefits mentioned above, there are some downsides you might want to know before purchasing the Elite Active 65ts.
1. Sound quality. For those who like heavy bass, Elite Active 65ts might not be suited. However, leaving the bass sound aside, these earbuds still provide a high-quality, clear and rich sound. If you are not obsessed with the bass sound, you are likely to be satisfied by these earbuds.
2. Battery life. Elite Active 65ts have a long battery life, lasting up to 5 hours. The charging case, which is included in the product, delivers two extra charges and make the earbuds last 15 hours. In addition, featuring the quick charge, the earbuds can recharge their 1/3 of the battery in 15 minutes. You can store the earbuds in the charging case when you are not listening, and they are fully charged when you take them out later.
3. Design. Elite Active 65ts have a stylish and modern appearance, but some people might not like the earbuds’ earplug feature. Although this feature can isolate your ears from outside noise, this also can make you uncomfortable if you have never experienced earplug-type earbuds. Some people simply don’t like earplugs (my mother never gets used to them). One thing you can try is changing the size of the earbuds’ tips, as three different sizes are included. You might be able to find a comfortable size that suits your ears.
As long as you are used to the earplug feature, you will be satisfied by these completely wireless earbuds. Try the Elite Active 65ts and stay away from the stress of untangling the wires.

title: Great Sound and Features BUT Not Confident w/ Fit or Comfort
content:
I did my research before purchasing and after many reviews decided to purchase these over the AirPods due to them having more sound, fit, and other adjustments not available with most Apple products. I found the largest rubber pads worked the best and I used them for a couple hours sitting at my desk. Sound is great and “hear through” technology is also a nice-to-have feature and when turned off I feel they also had a pretty good noise cancellation effect. However, after the initial 1-2 hours of wearing them I struggled to get the left piece to stay in place and it fell out numerous times.

I was really wanting to like these but if they won’t stay in your ears and fall out just sitting still they unfortunately aren’t going to work for me. I also bought a pair of AirPods at same time and what they lack in features, adjustability, and overall uniqueness they totally make up for in fit and comfort – I don’t have any concerns with these falling out, even with rapid movements, and I feel no fatigue or pain after wearing them non-stop for hours. If you can get the Elite’s to fit your ear cannel then I would recommend but they just didn’t work for me.

Also, Jabra case is slightly larger than Apple and much harder to open. I do however like the more rubbery silicone feel over Apple’s slick plastic feel.

These are just what the Dr ordered. Sound is FANTASTIC for the size and considerable bass for rock/rap. Stay in my ears well and can use just the right one if need be. Only negative is the hear through doesnt lower the music volume so it's pretty useless. My Plantronic's Backbeats lowered the music considerably when it pumped the outside noise in however they are full size over ear headphones. Other than that I have no complaints

Hear-through mode is excellent if you’re using these for traveling or exercise - or any situation where you’ll want to hear what’s going on around you but also your music / podcasts / whatever you’re listening to.

It’s so convenient not to have to take them out of your ears every time someone speaks to you.

Also - my AirPods fell out my ears all the time. The Jabras have too - but not nearly as much.

Love these.

content:
I returned this item after a week of use.  I returned it due to the 1. fit, 2. sound, 3. I found a better headphone from my perspective.

The fit was either super snug or loose.  When it was snug, I had a weird sensation in my ear where I could hear my footsteps as I walked.  If it was loose, they felt like they were going to fall out any moment.  The fit was not comfortable at all.

The sound just seemed very hollow.  Nothing sounded particularly good.  The bass was weak and songs that have big hooks sounded small and didn't open up the way they do on other headphones.

title: Little Gems!
content:
I read, read and re-read reviews prior to ordering as to avoid a purchasing mistake.  I've used these little gems 48 hours now and can positively say that I didn't make a mistake.  I'm nearly 63, have only 15% hearing in my left ear, have two restaurants (lots of background noise) and go like crazy each and every day.  These earbuds have already made a positive difference, as I'm constantly on my cell phone.  These are nothing short of remarkable.  Clarity is vital when taking detailed information regarding catering for 250 guests or reservations for 25; these are performing flawlessly thus far.  It is early on, I realize, but I couldn't be happier at this point.

The only negative issue I've experienced is the left one falling out which was corrected by changing to a larger earpiece (three sizes come with your buds).  Instant fix.  They paired instantly, maintain the stated charge and recharge quickly.  Listening to music is a joy even though the bass is a bit on the low side for me.  Nothing to complain about, simply a personal observation.  I'm ordering a set for my son as a birthday gift, that's how pleased I am.

Love these.  Period.  Quality of life enhancement for me.
