title: Good but not for small ears!
content: I’m an adult and my ears seem to be small and it falls out of my left ear. Like using them an to be able to talk on phone is great.

title: Excellent but slightly over priced
content: Excellent but slightly over priced. Decent sound, hard plastic shell caused some painful spots in one ear, but I got used to it.  Pass-thru feature doesn't allow that much ambient sound to get thru, and noise reduction is mostly due to a snug fit in the ear canal. Pretty good but not quite there yet for the price.

title: Nice attempt at competing with Airpods, but falls short
content:
I was looking for something that delivered better sound quality than Airpods, but still had similar features. Unfortunately, these earbuds fall very short:

- didn't pair automatically with my phone/laptop. In fact, it was sometimes difficult/impossible to pair with my laptop.
- didn't fit well in my ear, in spite of having more customizable rubber eartips. Consequently, they fell out of my ears when walking.
- voice instructions are too loud and are not adjustable
- the case itself is difficult to open, and is poor quality. I feel like this was clearly not tested in user groups, as I'm a woman with medium-length nails, and I usually struggle with opening the case because there's no way to grip it without scratching the case.

Things Jabra does better than the Airpods:
- sound quality
- sound blocking (due to the rubber tips)
- having LEDs on both the earbuds and the container. It was nice knowing when the earbuds were fully charged and the case was not, and vice-versa.

Unfortunately, I'll be returning these due to the above reasons.

title: Great headphones. Not so great mic
content:
Oh, how badly I wanted to like these... Unfortunately, there were 2 big issues for me.

TL;DR: The mic didn't work as well as others have stated for me and the fit. Read on for details.

I purchased this locally, to get it that day instead of waiting for shipping, based on all the reviews saying how good they were including the mic. I didn't need headphones but a good headset. But according to all the reviews, I thought these would fulfill that need AND be a good set of headphones too. Unfortunately, that wasn't the case. I kept having to really raise my voice for anyone to hear me. Almost yelling. I was told that sometimes it sounded only ok and sometimes it was like I was way down a hallway. I do drive a truck and there is background noise from that, but people have mentioned how great they were even in windy/noisy places. Not from my experience.

As far as the fit, the medium didn't feel very good in my ear. I tried the small bud and thought "Yes! Perfect fit!". Until my first call... I guess the seal wasn't good enough because it was much quieter than the medium buds. Maybe I could get used to the mediums, but with the mic being an issue I won't find out. This is a personal thing that either will or won't be an issue for others. You just have to try them and find out.

I gave them 3 stars because as headphones they are really good. If they were just a headset, I would've given them 1 star. But that wouldn't be fair considering these are headphones first and foremost.

Also, they are a bit slick when trying to get them out or put them in the box they come with. Which is super nice by the way (not sure why they didn't go with magnets to hold the headphones in it though). From what I understand the active ones are a bit more grippy. I found that you can't really put them in wrong though. When you close the box, the headphones only fit one way in the top section and it should basically position them just right or not close. I saw some reviews mention how hard the box can be to open. And as someone who has a bad habit of biting my nails I can see that being a potential issue. Although I found it pretty easy to open by lightly pushing back on the top part instead of using the little "lip" to pop it open with my nails.

Overall, I really liked the headphones, and you can tell they went all out to make a great product with a couple small caveats (slickness and no magnets to hold them in the box). If only the mic was better, I would've kept them and maybe tried some other ear tips if I had to.

Sorry for the long review. Hopefully it helped someone though.

title: Not for runners, but good for the gym
content:
Great headphones for gym and controlled work out environments. NOT FOR OUTDOOR RUNNERS. Too pricey to take the chance of them fallling out of your ear for training or running outdoors. Had one fall out of my ear on a trail race and you can consider it gone after that with the size being so small, consider yourself lucky if you find it. I’ve tried a few different types of total Bluetooth earbuds and the sets that have the fitting around the outside back of the ear are much more secure and less I have to worry about losing them.
Last note, Jabra does have great sound and pairs well. Just wish the earbuds would stay in the ear better for running situations.

title: Great sound with Comply tips - but painfully uncomfortable for smaller ears!
content:
I have loved these ear buds for a lot of reasons:

I can't ever go back to wired ear buds. With comply memory foam tips (not cheap..), the sound quality and sound isolation are awesome, and not much worse than my Bose QC20s. I enjoy having the equalizer options and the automatic pause when one is removed. The battery life is also pretty good. Microphone quality is superb.

But I also slightly hate them, because:

THEY ARE SO UNCOMFORTABLE THEY BRUISED MY EARS. When I wore them with the tips they came with, I experienced actual bruising in my ears after a couple of hours. I tried EVERY position possible and was twisting and turning them for days to try and find the right spot. I have pretty normal size ears for a woman (do women have smaller ears than men?), and the bulk of these ear buds is just enormous and bumps against multiple parts of my ear painfully. Also they fell out very easily.

...BUT I found a solution. With the Comply memory foam tips, if I wear these in the opposite ear as intended, they are tolerably comfortable and I'm able to enjoy the great audio quality and noise isolation I wanted.

Sadly the tips that are comfortable do not fit in the case and I have to remove and store them separately every time, which is a pain in the ass a few times a day. The shorter Truly Wireless tips are as uncomfortable as the default ones, whether I have them in the right ears or opposite ears, but fit into the case.

Oh and the case looks & feels sleek, but the opening and closing action leaves a lot to be desired. It takes a bit of finangling every time to get the ear buds to sit correctly in them no matter which tips are used.

I wish I had gone with a different brand with smaller ear buds or a different shape because the sound quality isn't quite worth the cumbersome methods for making these not extremely painful to wear, and not-being-in-pain is a bit more important than superb sound quality.

title: Pretty much no customer service or help
content:
These earbuds honestly are aren’t bad, when they work. However, if anything goes wrong, good luck with their customer service.

Also if you think you are concerned you may lose one of these pieces, you might as well buy new earbuds because they won’t supply you with a replacement product even if you pay. I had the charging case drop out of my bag at the airport... yeah my fault I get it... but it’s been two months now with now update or response from their team. They are holding all their components for a total product sale and string you along when it comes to replacement parts. The Apple air pods are way easier to come by with replacement parts, sync muchbetter with your iPhone (if you have one), if you have an Apple Watch good luck with these it’s a nightmare, and air pods cost less

Battery life sucks too.

title: Fabulous!!!!
content: These are without a doubt the finest ear buds ever.  They charge to full strength quickly.  Pairing and connection is a synch.  I use them primarily for Team Speak and they function with excellence.

title: I Love these so far
content: I have had these for some months now and they are super comfortable and they do not fall out. I am a marathoner and I used these for a recent 18 mile race. The battery life is the best and the connection is strong. I ran out of phone battery before these did (they lasted the entire run). I do think It could have a bit more base, but there is an app that will allow you to change the EQ settings.

title: Great product
content: Fits snugly in your ears and will stay in even when  jumping rope and other high activity exercises. Also great noise cancellation with the option to allow outside noise in if desired

title: Best value?
content:
Purchased these when they were on sale for $139.99. Before buying anything like this I usually do extensive research, so scoured the web for competing products in the same price range or higher--read/watched as many reviews as I could (reddit, youtube, amazon, random tech sites, etc.)

Background: Bought these slightly apprehensively as I read about left earbud issues, static, connection, quality, etc. Though kept in mind that when reading reviews, they tend to be skewed as those with issues are more likely to review than those who are happy with their purchase. But compared to the competing products/brands (Bose, Sennheiser, etc.) these seemed like the best choice. I wouldn't consider myself an audiophile per se, but am knowledgeable and have a decent ear (play a few instruments, sing, listen to a lot of music). The audio quality on these is great, considering that they're true wireless earbuds. My over the ear daily drivers are Sennheiser 598s and Beyerdynamic 770s.

Length of ownership: Have only used these for about a week so far, so will update if I encounter any issues (some users with issues stated encountering problems a month or two in).

Pros:
- Battery length
- small/convenient case (no magnet..why? D: )
- audio quality (pretty detailed, also feel no need to EQ via app)
- ambient sounds are actually really cool (haven't used them extensively yet but rainy day and storm I would actually use)
- hear-through tech is pretty useful as well (better directional sound than I anticipated after reading reviews)
- look nice
- don't fall out (haven't exercised with them yet but gym is definitely no problem--will try playing a few sports with them in)
- comfortable enough and haven't felt the need to change the tips (silicone is fine though I did buy comply tips as well)
- Blocks out sound very well (this will vary for you depending on your ears--need a good fit and seal)
- Haven't had any issues with calls--seems to block out wind very well

Cons:
- Why no magnets? Would feel super premium and would make taking them out/putting them in so much easier
- Sometimes it'll think you're trying to go mono-bud (right earbud only) mode. Tip: take out the left earbud first and then the right quickly after.
- Bluetooth in random areas: I haven't had any normal skipping issues or audio lag for videos which is great! Though occasionally walking around places like stairwells or other areas with physical/digital interference causes the buds to go in and out. I'd assume this is simply the case for BT buds in general. No problems outside so far
- User/manual guide isn't very detailed or helpful but meh.

Bottom line: Am very very happy with these. Crossing my fingers that I don't encounter any issues in the next couple of months, though they come with a warranty so we'll see. Will update this review if I do encounter any problems

title: Worst purchase ever
content:
The sound is terrible, the fit is terrible, they fall out constantly.  They lose connection and the sound cuts out.  Worst headphones I have every purchased.

UPDATE 1 Aug 2019 - just under 3 months in they have failed completely.  The right earbud will not take a charge.  Jabra has the worst customer service and most complex return policy I have every seen.  Numerous phone calls, days of email exchanges, and they still will not send a return label, just more questions.  I asked Amazon to step in for assistance, but they will not take any responsibility saying it has been more then 30 days.  I do understand this policy, but ultimately Amazon is the one who took the money.  They do have share responsibility.  I have been forced to move on to file a dispute with my credit card company.  This has been a very frustrating experience.  I strongly discourage buying Jabra products.

title: Nope
content: Had to return them 2x

title: Three tips for a great experience
content:
Tip 1: Choose when to insert or remove. First time I put these in while walking I threw one right into a pachysandra garden. Fortunately found it. My daily commute involves crossing a river so I always wait until I’m across. Point is: these are small so if you’re moving from wired buds, handle them carefully.
Tip 2: Insert the left bud first. Inserting right first makes it think you’re going solo.
Tip 3: Occasionally the left bud doesn’t connect when inserting. Simply return both buds to the case then start again. If you look when removing these from the case, you’ll see a green light indicating that they’re powered up. If you don’t see it, put it back and remove again. This isn’t a frequent problem and easily resolved.
Other comments: The app feature of cutting out ambient noise or picking it up on the external mics is excellent. While commuting I allow external sound so I can hear when the conductor makes announcements and traffic when I cross streets, and on a recent flight I tuned out the noise while watching a movie.
The light indicators on the buds and on the case are intuitive. Watch the light when you close the case and if it’s yellow, recharge it soon. Easy.
I’ve tried many buds that don’t stay seated. Using the largest rubber insert, these stay put even if I run with them in.
Sound is very good.

title: Good sound quality/fit
content: Good product. Fit flush, does not fall.

title: Outstanding sound quality and microphone clarity
content: I'd been in the market for a truly wireless option for my iPhones, and the Jabra Elite 65t earbuds have met or exceeded my expectations for fit, comfort, reliability, and sound quality. They're not cheap, but still a good value given the high quality and convenience. Very pleased customer.

title: Love these.
content: Excellent product, occasionally the mic does not work as well as I wish it would.

title: Highly recommended
content:
I researched various true wireless sports earbuds and chose these.  I have been using these for at least three months. They look good, are light, are easy to pair, are comfortable and have a long battery life.  The app the earbuds is used with is easy to user friendly and provides more capabilities.

I ran approximately 50 miles total and used them in the gym numerous times from 20-60 minutes at a time.  The earbuds have not fallen out and fortunately have not hurt my ears.  The sound quality is impressive.  I even took a couple of phone calls and they sounded good.  I have not been disappointed.

The only thing I kinda don't like is the pass through ability.  If there is very loud noise or very loud music being played, the earbuds will go silent in order to allow the noise to be heard.  I guess that's not a bad thing in case of emergencies and I guess that what the pass through feature is supposed to do.

I have worn them on a run when there was light rain and  did not have any issues.  Since the weather has been cold I haven't drenched them in sweat.  However, on a particular day, I ran 8 miles and did get sweaty, but I did not have any issues with the earbuds.

Since I've had them I have not had to charge my earbuds or the earbud charger case.  I have simply placed them in the charger case and pulled them out when I wanted to use them.

Throughout, I did have a small pairing issue.  But I put the earbuds back in the case and pulled them out and earbuds were fixed.

The earbuds have a feature that I think is pretty cool.  While wearing the earbuds, if you pull an earbud out of your ear, the earbuds will go silent.  I think that's cool.

If you are willing to spend the money they are worth it.  You get what you pay for.  I highly recommend them.

title: Not Satisfied
content:
- Lack bass
- keeps falling off my ears
- unhappy with sound quality

title: Ear candy
content: Love em

title: Sound good, everything else is lousy
content:
The good: they're well-priced and they sound good (when they're working well).

Everything else is a mess. The bluetooth is really spotty when paired to my cellphone (Pixel 3 XL). To make it worse, when you're around a fair number of people also using bluetooth headphones (say, in a moderately busy gym), the audio crackles and cuts out.

The charging case is also pretty bad. It feels downright cheap when you handle it; every time I open the case, I fear the cover will snap right off. But that's nothing compared to the charging itself. The indicator light on the case is useless. It's green until the whole thing is dead. You never get a good indication that you should charge it. And, most infuriatingly, if you put the earbuds into the case while the battery is dead, the case drains the battery of your earbuds. If the case is out of batteries, it's literally better to manually power off the earbuds and leave them loose in your pocket or bag.

Finally, I just have to talk about the android app. Or, I should say more accurately, the apps. Any time your earbuds are paired, there are three different non-dismiss-able tray icons. One lets you know what "mode" your earbuds are in, one gives you a tray icon to find your earbuds if you misplace them (note: this tray icon appears _when the earbuds are paired to your phone_), and third tray icon that seems to serve literally no purpose. The only features these apps offer are an equalizer and the option to choose your voice assistant (alexa vs google).

These are truly a disappointment.

title: Great wireless headphones, coming from multiple generations of Jaybirds
content: I've used multiple generations of Jaybirds, from the X, X2 and X3. The latest X3's are still great headphones, are bulletproof (gone through the washing machine a few times even) and the battery lasts forever. However, after losing my X3's, I decided to try the 65t's and i'm not disappointed. The sound is not quite as good as the X3's (bass not quite as strong, but comparable highs and clarity) but they come very close and are completely wire free. I've tried the Samsung ICON X's and the Jaybird Sports, but the fit was just not real good for my ears, or they just stuck out too much from my ears. These 65t's however, are quite comfortable and they don't stick out like electrodes on Frankenstein. I've just had the 65t's for a few days, so the verdict is still out on the durability, but so far I'm impressed.

title: Better than expected
content: Had over 10 blue tooth ear piece over the years.  These are the best that I have used.  The sound quality is excellent.  Easy to pair with Apple iPhone.  Easy initial paring.  And auto pairing when you take the buds out of the box works seamlessly.  When I first put it in the ear feel a bit big.  Got use to it after a 5 minutes.  Surprisingly comfortable.

title: GREAT ear buds!!
content: Got these for my VERY difficult-to-buy-for husband for Christmas. He LOVES them!! Finally hit a home run with these ear buds after 29 frustrating years of trying!!😊

title: Reliable
content: Good

title: Good product if it doesn't break
content: I loved these when I first got them. It's been about 2 or 3 months, and now the right earbud won't charge. For some reason, you need right earbud on in order to listen with the left, so they are both useless. I'm pretty disappointed given I spent almost 200 bucks.

title: Be prepared for problem
content: Overall they are really good earphones, that's if you get through all the trouble first, before I bought them I read the bad reviews and they were about similar problems that I've experienced, first one was that the sound was horrible it sounded like cheap speaker system really distorted,so I called Jabra they showed me how to fix it, 2nd they wouldn't pair automatically with my phone I had to go to Bluetooth settings and manually sync them, that was a pain specially using them at work were no phone or earbuds are allowed. So I fixed that, and then the next day the earbuds would not charge, it's one problem after the next. And the hear through is not that great,it's sounds like if your on a call, the mics pic up sound, but it's useless when u listen to music you can't hear anything outside. After fixing audio issue they sound great, but I can't use mine they won't charge.

title: They look good, but they just don't come up to the bar.
content: I am not sure why these headsets are so highly rated by places like CNET.  The sound quality is mediocre. You can improve the sound by putting a bud on that fully seals your ear canal, but then they become very painful to wear. That being said, their controls are fairly good and they are ascetically pleasing when you look in the mirror! Their main competition (IMO) is Bose's fully wireless Soundsports. And, honestly, Jabra does not compare. Jabra's controls are slightly easier to use (you have to press 'hard' on Bose's) and the Jabra's look better in your ear. The Boses destroy Jabra in sound quality.

title: Breaks after a month
content: Defective product. As many other reviewers mentioned, the left earbud went out and stopped working after about a month. Before it stopped working, I was very satisfied with the sound and how far I could be from my phone with good quality music. Unfortunately, the buds would wiggle out while working out and ended up being defective so it didn’t matter.

title: Great true wireless headset:  Paired easily to my iPhone 6S easily and Apple watch
content:
I just bought these yesterday from another place.  I would have preferred to buy these from Amazon, but they weren't in stock.  They paired to my iPhone 6S easily and also my Apple watch.  Next was a quick firmware upgrade that only took about 5 minutes.  The firmware updates while the earbuds are in their case.  The medium ear gels seemed to fit me the best.  While it took a little while to get used to waring these they were pretty comfortable.  The feel solid and I don't believe I'll need to worry about them falling out at all.  I've tried a couple of calls and the people I spoke with said the call quality was great.  I thought the sound they produce was good and did take advantage of the app to adjust the EQ to my liking.  The "hear through" function basically uses the microphones to electronically push the outside sound into your ears.  I plan to use these for running and cycling and think the pass through will work just fine.  If the fit during my exercising stays solid (I think it will), I may even try these on my motorcycle.  It would be great to hear music and my GPS while I'm cruising.  I'll update this review once I put some hours on these.

Update 5/29/18:

Ok, so now I've used these on a run, a bicycle ride and on my motorcycle.  They have worked really well.

During my run they were comfortable and secure.  Being able to turn the hear through feature on or off while running using the button on the headset is very useful. While listening to music, it can be difficult to tell if the hear through feature is on or off.  I recommend Jabra add a tone or message to confirm if the hear through is on or off.

On my bicycle ride, the ear pieces stayed put and never shifted.  I put "hear through" on and it worked well.  There was some wind noise which I expected, but  I didn't mind as I was also able to hear cars and outside noise.  I did try turning hear through off while riding on a trail and the wind noise stopped instantly.  These worked better than I would have thought.  I did end up leaving the hear through on most of the ride as I felt safer and was able to speak with people I passed.

Next was a ride on my Harley. With Vance & Hines pipes my bike is a little loud. I turned the "hear through" off and the volume up a little and these worked great.  I wear a half helmet and these fit well under the side straps.  I even made a call while at a traffic light and riding at slow speed. Over 50 mph I turned the volume up a little to find a good balance between hearing music and my exhaust.  I also tested these using my GPS.  Actually hearing "turn by turn" directions while riding was a big plus for me.

Over all, I'm very pleased with these.  While I've only had these for a short while, they do everything I need them to and more.
Good work Jabra!

title: Lost a significant amount of sound volume and quality.
content: I bought these about 6 months ago and they gradually lost sound quality. They went from being pretty good to the worse headphones I have owned. They have gotten to the point where I can barely hear the music and can hear all surrounding sounds.

title: The quality of the sound is amazing!
content: I've actually heard new sounds and previously unheard lyrics to songs I thought I knew.  Plus the find your Jabra feature was helpful when one of the earbuds fell out of my pocket and the app pointed me in the right direction.  You can customize the equalizer too.

title: Great sound
content: Great sound. easy to connect. App works hood too. Alot better than the other pair I had 3 days ago that kept disconnecting. These Jabra are tops

title: WTF Jabra...Sounding good..!?!?!
content: Thought folks were high AF saying these sound great.... Nope, well, maybe they could have been, but I'm not and they sound frickin' awesome. Screw Bose and all those other "Crapple" companies that over charge you for their name.  These are great for working out (i like the "hear through" option can be turned on and off) or just paired firestick, PS4, etc... Battery tech only allows for them to be so small and last as long as they do but I do believe the battery in the case can be upgraded to allow for more charges for the buds.  I am impressed and quite happy with them.

title: Great, Clear Sound
content: Excellent Product. My husband uses these every day, all day long. He talks to people for a living and walks while he talks. Great and clear sound. He has told me. - repeatedly how much he loves this new generation.

title: Jabra Ear Buds
content: Excellent!

title: Painful
content:
Painful. Seriously did the product development guys try these on? These are extremely painful after keeping them on for more than 30 minutes.

They feel a little better buyingthe comply earbuds but it is such a serious design flaw you CANNOT buy these. Trust me people move on.

Sound quality really good. Voice control actually is very nice. But I cant keep them on for more than 30 minutes which defeats the very purpose of earbuds!

title: one doesnt work
content: Purchased for a Christmas gift.  The right ear bud does not work.  I am asking for a replacement to be sent.

title: Fits your ears great no discomfort for me
content: Great product ! Best way to listen to music !

title: kept cutting out when moving
content: i would move over to the Jabra, works great and doesnt cut out

title: Tech not quite there yet.
content:
Just not quite as advertised. Skippy connection, lag on videos makes watching videos very frustrating. Also the microphones pick up a ton of noise from external environment. Returned these after a few days.

Two stars because they play music well and seem to stay in my ears but that’s a very low bar.

I wish they were better because the concept is great and fit was good.

title: Don't be afraid to purchase.
content: I bought them for great sound and was not disappointed.  I also bought them to keep out unnecessary noise, again not disappointed!

title: Meh.  They are absolutely 'ok' ear buds, but there are better alternatives
content:
I returned this after 3 weeks of use.  Overall: mediocre sound, not comfortable, finicky to connect and painful to control.
Details:
* Sound was terrible until I changed the ear cup size, then it became ok.  Still tinny.
* The medium cup was too small and the large too big - I felt them in my ears continually.  I never had this problem with my old JLab earbuds
* Changing volume or controlling anything required pressing the ear unit and it was painful
* If I was not super careful removing them from my ears, I'd lose an ear cup sometimes requiring tweezers to get them out
* Refused to pair with my older MacBook.  Several times had to 'forget' and reconnect with various devices, a major pain switching between phone, (newer) computer and exercise equipment.
* Often refused to connect and had to put them back in the case or power cycle them
* Not very good a blocking outside sounds
* The 'hear through' feature meant to allow in outside sound didn't really do much other than add a faint 'hiss' (You can already hear conversations, it's not needed.)
Overall an average experience. If these were all that existed in the world, I"d probably use them as better than nothing, but there are better choices.

For alternatives, AirPods would be much better experience though lacking in any noise isolation.
I'm planning to try the new Power Beats next.  More expensive but presumably they will deliver where Jabra falls short.

title: Easy to use
content: Easy to use, good sound and stays in your ear. I did a lot of research prior to buying and I’m glad I choose these.

title: Needs APTX
content:
These headphones don't get a good enough seal or connection to keep up with the audio experience of my $20 Aukey B40s. Amazon sent product without tips, so required extra effort to even make useable. Comply tips didn't help with seal. Very pretty product but unusable in real world scenarios imo.

Hopefully next generation will ship with Aptx to improve connectivity in cities.

title: Almost perfect
content: Great device for the money, It does lack a little more base, but very easy to pair, it comes on automatically when I put them in and near my phone. Phone calls are also very easy and very very clear on both ends :-) Very satisfied with this purchase.

title: Esr buds good, case terrible.
content:
The earbuds are good, coo km colors and good build quality.
The case however is terrible. The closing latch is a plastic tab that us hard to open even with 2 hands. The buds do not sit with a magnetic hold.  They just sit in the case lose. If the case was better they would be very good and worth the price. But the ease of use is not there.
If you want them for the gym only they are good but if you want to put them in and out of the case more than once every few days no way you should get these

title: Used product exceeds expectations
content: Like new, sound great.

title: Solid Purchase, with caveats !!
content:
Overall, these Earbuds are a stellar when it comes to sound quality, Microphones, and fit, so ill list the pros and cons to make it easier :
Pros :
1- Great sound quality (very heavy bass, helps a lot in the gym).
2- Good fit for the Gym.
3- Bluetooth Multipoint (its a con too.)
4- battery lasts long.
5- Microphones are no joke, hands down you won't regret making phone calls using these buds.
6- No Latency whatsoever.
Cons :
1- Case is bulky, won't fit in pocket, feels cheap, not magnetized, and very hard to open the first couple of times.
2- No USB-C.
3- No Wireless Charging.
4- Bluetooth Multipoint can only pair two devices at a time, and there is noway to turn it off (why would you want to turn it off ? because if you're moving around the house and getting out of range from the second device, the earbuds will keep connecting and disconnecting from such device and keep disrupting your activity, trust me I specifically chose these earbuds because they had Multipoint, but now I'm regretting that I was too focused on that part).
5- only the Right earbud connects to the device.
6- They became defective after 5 months of usage, and Jabra's Tech Support was very frustrating to deal with, they took over two weeks to complete my return, and kept asking silly questions.
I would still buy these again.

title: Really Wanted to Like These
content:
From all of the reviews I thought that finally, there was a pair of BT earbuds which would work and sound good.  The problem is that when they work the sound is only so-so.  Issue was using with a Samsung S9+ in my pocket.  Each time my arm swung in front of my leg, the sound cut.  Since it is hard to keep your arms from swaying, these were a no-go.

Really wanted to like them!

title: Jabra Elite 65t review after 1 mo of usage
content:
Overall good wireless earbuds.
Sound quality is good with an equalizer feature that you can customize your sound settings with.
Hear through feature enables you to hear outside noise (when turned on) so you don't have to pull the earbuds out for quick conversations.

Only thing that would've made these headphones great is if you could use the left earbud independently of the master right earbud. The left earbud cannot be used unless the right earbud is pointing directly at left earbud (eliminating the ability to share earbuds with another; and/or, use only the left earbud as the right one charges).

title: Best bluetooth wireless ear buds
content:
NOTE - I did NOT download the Jabra app onto my phone after reading less than favorable reviews. I'm good with keeping them working just the way they have been. Please continue reading!

I've owned these for 5 months, so I've had a chance to really use them in all situations - listening to music while working out, running, while riding in the car or on a plane, or at my desk as well. I've also used it to take calls. I am really impressed. I love the low profile as they don't look outrageous when I'm wearing them (I got the copper black color, like it better than any other released colors). Water resistance was what really steered me towards these when I was comparing against others (I was about to purchase the Sennheiser Momentum bluetooth earbuds, but they are not rated as highly against dust ingress and water resistance; for those interested, the Jabra Elite Actives are rated as IP56 while the Sennheiser Momentums are rated at IPX4). They don't fall out, they connect almost instantly, they do not drop connection to my phone or each other, and the controls are easy (forward/back, volume up/down, answer call/hang up). My music sounds good; note that you will not get bass like you do for over ear headphones. I was aware of that during my research for bluetooth earbuds, you should be too. When I have the volume up (as much as is considered safe), I am not hearing too much outside noise, so noise cancelling is good enough for me (used them on my business flights). Battery length is pretty good, and the extra charge you get from the case is good too (a 20 min charge from empty will give you about an hour's worth of operation).

As for the HearThrough option, while I can notice it a little bit, I don't really see it as anything special. However, that was not a deal breaker for me. You need to decide whether that's something really important.

A tip I saw on a different review that I followed myself after reading is when you are putting them into the charging case, ensure that you line them up on the cap and then close. Works every time.

title: After several months of usage
content: The product stopped charging after many months of usage and sounds deterioration. At this point, I am in the market to replace this no good product. Have tried calling for a warranty or replacement and no luck.

title: Use them everyday... No issues whatsoever!!
content: Work perfectly for me... Once they're locked in your ear, they don't pop out while running... Charge lasts a good long time, and the sound is excellent!!

title: These headphones are some of the best on the market
content: These headphones are some of the best on the market. Really like how small they are. Battery life lasts as advertised.

title: Great if They Were Reliable
content:
I've owned a set of these for about nine months, and initially was very pleased with them.  I offer the following:

Pros:
1.  Audio quality is very good.  While the set I have does not include noise cancelling technology, the noise isolation feature works very well, resulting in close to the same results as the Bose wireless earbuds I have for a much lower price.
2.  For my ears, they fit very well, and are comfortable.  Your experience may differ.
3.  Sturdiness - They hold up well when you are sweating.  I've not seen any moisture-related issues, and I have given the set plenty of time to prove itself in that regard.
4.  Battery life - Considering the size of these earbuds, the battery life is excellent.  I routinely get two to three hours of full-time listening without need to charge.  When I am on long duration conference calls, the battery life is shorter, but not significantly so.  Pop them in the case for a half hour and you get another 3 hours or so of full time listening.  When the use is intermittent, I get all day use without recharge.
5. Bluetooth range - the range is very good, much better than the Bose set I mentioned earlier.  I go out of the room my phone is in (20-25') without loss of signal.

Cons:
1.  I have recently noticed a tendency for the left ear bud to come unpaired with the right.  The right earbud is the one that communicates with your phone, and the left simply receives its signal from the right.  I will be rocking along enjoying some music when the left ear bud will come unpaired.  I have to put them in the case, turn off my Bluetooth on my phone, and then take the right one and start it to pairing.  Then I have to press both sides of the control buttons on the left earbud for a slow count of five to get it to pair with the right.  This started showing up after a recent firmware update (the firmware updates automatically to the buds from the app), so the problem may be software rather than hardware-related.

Considering the star rating I've given the product, this one con is a deal-killer for me.  I don't know the cause of it, nor am I interested in finding out why.  I just want them to work reliably.  They don't, so my message to the prospective buyer is: buyer beware.  I expect a minimum of two years of trouble-free service from electronics of this nature.  This one doesn't pass that test.

title: crap
content: on my second pair and having same problem with connectivity and left headphone static...when it works at all.

title: SOUND
content: Great sound and great battery life way better then the galaxy buds.

title: Not worth the price.  Expected more.
content: Finally gave up on these; purchased in Feb.  Silicone ear tips that come with the 65t do not fit well.  Third party tips like Comply, which I have had good luck with on other earbuds, do not fit either.  The sound quality is only so-so.  Without good fitting tips the bass is lacking.

title: Very good pairing and sound quality, but run very HOT
content:
I really liked them from a sound quality perspective and they paired very well with my Galaxy S9+, however they (at least the pair I got) run extremely hot, and get very uncomfortable after a couple hours of use.  I have very standard sized ears (Apple Earpods fit me perfectly, for reference), and the fit was just okay.  Comes with 3 different sized ear tips, but I didn't find one that could give me a good seal.  There are of course other solutions to this that can be found on Amazon, but that requires a separate purchase.

In the end, I chose to return them because of the uncomfortable temperatures they kicked out.

title: Great product
content: Amazing product, exceeded my expectations and for the sound quality “top class” is what i call it

title: Left earbud experiences poor connectivity
content: Seemed like a good choice however the feedback/crackling I experience in the left ear bud makes them unusable. For well over $100 this should not be an issue however it is, save yourself the headache.

title: Probably going to return
content: The charging case is really hard to open. I was most dissapointed with the sound quality. I read a lot of reviews saying it has a natural sound to it but maybe I got a faulty pair because the sound is really poor. Sound quality aside these are really convenient and I would totally keep them if they had an acceptable sound for their price range

title: Good quality, bad - buds dont work further apart than about 10"
content: We were super excited to try these headphones from all the other glowing reviews. The overall sound quality was very good. However these are impossible to use more than about 10" apart. If they get any further the left bud disconnects. This is super disappointing if you want to share music or an audio book with a friend.

title: Rad
content: Rad

title: worst outgoing call quality of all time
content:
I bought this as it boasted an excellent call quality due to its 2 mic/ headpiece design. I just received it and did the firmware update and then tried to have a voice call while having a brief walk around the block. The person on the other side was constantly complaining because of the outrageously loud sounds coming in from the cars (although they aren't that loud but only magnified) and the smallest car honk and bike passing by.
I wanted to check for myself so I started the voice recorder on my phone and was standing around 50 feet away from the main road. I kept talking for around a minute and cars were passing by on the road. After I stopped to listen, my voice was barely heard while I could hear the sounds of every car very loudly. I could even hear a slightly loud pick up truck which i saw around 70 feet away. Its sound was annoyingly high in my ear knowing that the volume was on half.

These earbuds are falsely advertising great call quality, this is THE worst experience i have had through all the earbuds, earphones, headphones or even phones itself. I emailed jabra about this and will be updating this review with the result whether it was positive or negative.

title: Awesome choose for heavy metallicssss
content: I just didn't liked the next and backward buttons kind of complicated but overall omg best earbuds I ever tried. U dont even feel them much. GREAT FOR HARD METAL and gym

title: Solid product
content:
I got these for my gym workouts. You kinda twist them into your ears and they stay put. They are not obtrusive and you don’t know they are there.  They sound great, though my ears are 68 years old.
They hold a charge well. Once you pair them with your phone they are always ready to go with instant on. They recharge easily in their little case. They feel solid and sound good so I hope they last.

title: Great! When I leave anywhere they are in my pocket.
content: Love this earbuds! The only thing I can nag about is it just feels like they could add just a little more volume. Other then that I love them.

title: Works for all assistant apps, alexa, Google, etc...not a good ear fit
content:
So, I thought they were good, but for the price I would think they would have better sound or fit. I'm returning mine because the hard plastic against my ear gives me headaches after twenty minutes.

If your ear is Cinderella and these are the glass slipper then congratulations, I did really like the voice activated assistant. It says Alexa, but it will activate for any assistant app your phone has, including Google. I wish they advertised that. That was the main draw in the purchase and wow was that convenient.

title: Feels great. Sound quality is great. Cancels out sound.
content: Sound is great. Changed the ear fittings and don't have to worry about dropping out while exercising.  They are better than Samsungs newest model. I bouth both but 100% better with comtrols.

title: Great Value
content: I had the Bose Soundsport Free for a week and switched to the Jabra Elite 65T. The Bose connection kept dropping. The Jabra Elite 65T has a much more stable connection. The sound is good. Phone calls are clear and you're able to hear on both head set.

title: Dead after two months/ terrible claim process
content: Worked great til one of the earbuds stopped working after two months. It's been 41 days since I submitted my claim and the replacement still hasn't shipped. What a terrible experience that's been. I regret buying these earbuds. Avoid these because of the possibility of this happening to you both product and support side.

title: Perfect for the gym
content: I have been using these for a few months now and I have to say I've had zero issues. I use these pretty much exclusively for the gym and they are amazing. Never drops connection, plenty loud enough, the ambient noise option actually comes in handy, and they have never come loose in my ears. I've always been skeptical of true wireless ear buds but these made me worry no more.

title: Hands down the best wireless headphone I have ever bought
content: I frankly have nothing negative to say about these headphones, they are small, have a great battery lift and a ton of features, so no complaints from me.

title: Don't fit!
content: These keep falling out of my ears if I am eating, drinking, walking, sitting or just breathing!! I have tried the different tips included but none fix the problem.  I don't use it as often as it was intended to, which is a pity because the sound quality is pretty good.

title: Left earbud died after 12 days of use
content:
Purchased at Best Buy. Used it regularly for under two weeks before the left earbud died while it was in the charging case. Tried to get it to work but it won't even charge anymore. The volume is pretty loud since you can adjust the volume from the earbud and your phone independently, others will only adjust your phone's volume. However, it lacks deep sound while listening to music, even with the equalizer from the Jabra app. The hearthru option is a nice idea but all the noise sounds much further than it is so it's a challeng making out words. Also all noise it picks up sounds as if it's at equal distance. Someone speaking to me 5 ft away is the same volume as someone speaking 30 ft away. As far as volume other hear while on calls, the mic seems to be too sensitive. Doing normal things around the room would hurt the ears of the person I'm on the phone with (closing the door, footsteps, throwing garbage in the trash.)

Things I like:
secure fit if inserted as in the instructions.
Very loud potential for volume
Good battery life
Charging case
Jabra app helps locate earbuds

Things I dislike:
Lack of deep sound
Poor quality mic
Hearthrough option needs improvements
Buttons require too much pressure to register command
It's a gamble if your earbud will die early
Can only use right earbud independently
Range feels too short. Starts cutting out around 20 ft.

title: Great BUDS, just hope that you don't need warranty service  !!
content: I have had my earbuds for just over three months, and they have been great. I just love them. Recently however the battery will not charge fully, and after a few weeks would not charge at all. I have spent nearly two hours on four separate phone calls, sitting on hold, it's nearly it is impossible to reach Jabra for warranty service. I will update this review if and when I ever get warranty service.........

title: Best truly wireless headphones on the market
content: These headphones are perfect for just about everything: the gym, work, class, you name it. I have had no connection or latency problems! The sound quality is great. Probably my most favorite thing is very little ear fatigue after hours of wearing. Super long battery life with convienient pocket size charger. HearThrough is pretty cool but can be weird to adjust to.

title: Not worth your money STAY AWAY
content:
I bought this product about 3 months ago and was surprised by the low build quality of the product, the headphones fool you by making you think it has a long battery life but that just because its constantly charging in its case. the headphones themselves are also extremely buggy the software used to run them seem to be held by band aids.
 I was willing to look over all of these issues until the left headphone stooped working correctly after 3 months. the worst part is i know its due to their sub-par software. ill turn them on and the left headphone will work for 5 min and 20 secs (yes i have times it) and then the left headphone will static out not making any audio. STAY AWAY FROM THIS TRASH PRODUCT

title: Great headphones with just a couple minor shortcomings
content:
These headphones are all around great. Great fit, great sound, no connection issues, and the hear-through function is extremely cool and useful.

The only reason I took a star off is because the charging port is Micro-USB instead of USB-C and the lid of the case opens and closes using a plastic notch instead of a magnet or something like that. It makes opening a closing the case much less easy and smooth than it should be.

title: If you can escape the pain & challenging charging, the sound quality is great!
content: Overall, very displeased. Made a mistake replacing my Bose Soundsport with these. Charge very slowly, if the buds and the case is dead, they don't charge in the case while the case is charging, leaving you with at least an hour of charging time. Soundsport you can plug in for about 15 minutes and get at least an hour out of. I never found a comfortable fit, they either plug your ears so you get a very closed sound, or they're about to fall out. If you shower or clean your ears before wearing them, it is near impossible to get them to stay in. Additionally, the noise cancelling aspect is very dangerous in sports headphones. You cannot hear cars or atmospheric noises until they are right next to you. There are buttons on the buds that allow you to advance the song, adjust the volume, or turn the buds on. In order to push these buttons you have to leverage the bud against your war. Turning the music up comes at the expense of jamming then into your ear. Also, they constantly autoplay music if they're in your pocket and not in the case, running down the battery of both your phone and the headphones. The charge amount given fresh off of the charger is never accurate, it will say "50%" and then 10 minutes later they'll be at 10%. Sound quality is good, that is if you can actually get the headphones to stay in your ear or stay charged. The worst purchase I've made in recent memory. Maybe wait until an updated model is released.

title: Top notch build quality
content:
I ran over the left bud with my car. I found it the next day in the grass next to my driveway with a few scratches but otherwise no major damage. It still sounds great.

For those of you thinking of replicating my durability test, I drive a Mazda 3. Results may vary if you drive something like an M1 Abrams.

title: Jabra did not stand behind their product and it quit working after less than 3 months.
content: I purchased this product in April 2018 (shortly after it was released)  I started having some issues with losing signal early on but then it would work fine at other times.  Then one ear quit working altogether unless I held it tight to my ear. (no idea why that would be).  Anyway, when I tried to return the item they said they would not honor guarantee since I bought in Amazon marketplace seller who was selling it as a return item. (It was in an unopened package and in orignal new condition).  Irritated with this product and company.

title: Excellent for calls, good for music while riding, amazing durability
content:
I have had these earbuds for 6 months now and have used them everyday for work calls (7 days a week).  While I can't say much for the control app as it never quite works, the buttons have all the functionality you need.  I'm am constantly concerned with the quality of the microphones I am using as I pretty much talk on the phone all day for work and I have received nothing but positive feedback for sound quality.

I also use these for listening to music on my mountain bike rides.  While they don't have a nice full response for music, they sound fine for listening while riding and the Hear Through function lets the ambient noise in if you want to hear other the surroundings - for me other riders/hikers/horses.

The battery life is great if you keep the little charge case charged and bring it with you.  They really do give you around 5 hours talk time and they charge quite fast in the case.  This is still the case after 6 months.

Although they have never fallen out of my ears, I have accidentally dropped them in the dirt a dozen times without any damage.  They have also been through 2 FULL WASHING MACHINE CYCLES!  Yes, I accidentally left them in my bike jersey and washed them... twice.  They still sound the same... including the microphone.  If that doesn't say something about durability, I don't know what does.

I love the functionality for calls.  My phone rings.  I put the earbuds in and it answers the call immediately so I don't miss the call.  I also love how easy it is to adjust the volume.  Do not expect amazing sound quality.  These earbuds have 2 purposes - music while exercising and phone calls - and they are great for those 2 things.  I was hesitant because of the price but after 6 months, I am completely satisfied.  If I want sound quality for music or even movies, I'll use my over the ear headphones.

title: Amazing
content: Very nice ear buds love them

title: Beware faulty left earbud!!  I am not alone!
content:
I wish I could recommend these headphones, but I can't.  BEWARE left earbud no-sound issues.  Got them brand new from Amazon, opened and set them up as per Jabra instructions (the included instructions in box are horrible, make sure to go to Jabra.com to get the full manual so you can see what the lights mean and buttons as it's not that user friendly).  Right earbud works fine but no matter what I did the left one will not play any sound.  I contacted Jabra support and none of their super obvious "solutions" worked.  Factory reset (I did this like 4 times already, no change), update firmware (again, no change), fill out warranty and wait to get replacements (hell no!).  I looked online and this is far from a unique problem.  There are posts all over the web with the same issue.  Even one YouTube video from some random person titled "left earbud no sound" with over 11,000(!!) views.  That is not an isolated problem and Jabra should be recalling and doing better QA.  So I am returning to Amazon and looking for a more reliable brand.  It's too bad because from what I heard through the right earbud, the sound was very solid.  I tried Cambridge Audio's true wireless and they just did not sound good and apparently they have a terrible mic for taking calls.

Other feedback about the buds in general:
1. The fit is pretty decent and I have small ears which often makes it tough.
2. The buttons are super annoying and put quite a bit of pressure on your inner ear to press them to increase volume, pause etc.  Not sure how to fix that given the buds are the only place to put buttons.
3.  Pairing is kind of a clunky process and all the different flashing LED colors on each bud are only obvious after you read the full user manual which is not part of the package but online.
4.  Charging case is a really nice compact size, but super tough to open.  Feels like I'm going to break it every time I open it.

Again, I was ready to love these earbuds, but not having both buds play sound is kind of a big problem.  Do your research and know that you might get ones that work perfectly and you'll love them. Or you'll be unlucky like me and seemingly thousands of other people and have this issue.

title: Very good quality just wish they buttons weren't so hard to push
content: These headphones are working pretty good so far. The only issue I have is with one of my ears. That your phone does start to hurt the inside of my ear after an hour or so. The other issue is that the buttons on the earphones are a little hard to push because they are physical buttons so you end up jamming the earphone into your ear harder when you want to use the buttons. Not ideal. Sound quality is great. Noise reduction is fantastic. I use them on a plane and they were great. For phone calls people cannot tell I have a headset on.

title: airpods = bad
content: airpods are for people who care more about aluminum and logos than product quality. These bad bois right here will do you good i promise

title: Best truly wireless experience Ive had - worth ecery penny!
content:
I was almost turned away by the 3.5 stars and $200 price point. But having owned thrse for about a week now, I feel that this headset is hands down the best overall wireless experience Ive ever had. Ive run through 4-5 pairs of wireless earphomes now with sound quality being a top criteria (including bose, audio technica, optima nuforce, etc), but I've fallen in love with these Jabras. Sound quality is excellent, the connectivity is nearly seamless, and the app is perfect.

I believe a lot of the issues pointed out by previous reviews (left ear bud not working, low volume) are fixed by the sound+ app! They fit/seal fine in my ears. Worth every penny!

title: Left earbud has a constant hiss sound at upper volumes
content: Be warned: There is a flaw in these earbuds. if you attempt to turn the volume up above a certain limit - say greater than 70%, the left earbud has a constant hiss sound. I searched online and found out this this is not an isolated thing. There are a few work arounds that didn't work for me. I find it unacceptable that you immediately need to troubleshoot bugs  after opening a new pair of $170 earbuds. I promptly shipped them back for a refund.

title: Great earbuds
content: These are my first truly wireless earbuds and they are great. I've had them for a few months with no problems. The sound is clear and crisp and the bass is great. Sometimes there is a small interruption in sound, but I don't know if that's from the headphone connectivity or the network. I would recommend if you have money to blow on some nice earbuds.

title: Great workout headphones (with the right tips)
content:
When I first tried these on I got so frustrated I almost put them back in the box and returned them.
My initial impression of sound quality was that it was sub-par compared to the jaybird x3 headphones I had been using.  I need large tips, the "vacuum" the seal created in my eardrums was annoying, and after a short amount of time became very uncomfortable in my ears.  I did not get the noise isolation and deep bass that I was used to getting with the jaybird foam tips and I felt that I was constantly adjusting them trying to get a better sound out of them.  Played around with EQ settings and the sound didn't get any better. I tried this setup for a couple days and could not get used to it.
I had some extra pairs of comply T-500 isolation tips laying around from a previous set of jaybirds.  At first, they fell right off the jabras.  Using a razor, I carefully cut the clear silicone part off the original jabra small tips, leaving only the red inner sleeve, and put the red sleeve back on the jabras. Then put the Comply tips on over the red sleeve.  Guess what, now my Comply tips fit the Jabras perfectly. WOW.  What a difference!  After tweaking the bass up using the EQ in the Jabra app, the sound was way better.
The earbuds fit snugly in the case with the Comply tips but they do fit.  Occasionally one tip gets stuck in the case when I take the buds out but it can be easily pried out.  Minor issue considering these tips weren't designed for these earbuds.
The jabras are perfect for lifting weights and have made me forget how annoying corded headphones can be!  With the X3's, I've pulled an earphone out of my ear many times and would need to move the cord from back to front so as not to get caught in between a barbell and my neck or catch on the bench.
I have had them in my ears all day and they're still comfortable now. Often I wear them all day both at they gym and making calls from my home office.  Battery getting low?  15 minutes in the case and they're good for another conference call.
Noise isolation is good but not great.  Significantly better call quality than the X3's.  Now I can talk on the phone with the windows down in my 3/4 ton diesel and my wife says she cant even tell I'm driving.  On the X3's, call quality was atrocious with background noise present so its definitely better there.  But it still seems to pick up some outside noise, particularly higher pitched noises, so I wouldn't put the noise isolation up against a trucker's headset like the blueparrot series (which i have also used in the past)  In the office they work fine, although sometimes I need to adjust them to make sure the mics are pointing in the right direction.
Bottom Line, get the right tips and you won't be disappointed.

title: Excellent sound, clever battery-charger design.
content: I LOVE these earbuds.  The sound is stellar - WAAAY better than that of the Apple Airpods (which is mediocre at best).  They fit securely, more so than any wired or semi-wireless earbuds I've owned ( a bunch, from Shure to Beats to Bose).  Pairing is bulletproof, but the icing on the cake is the charging case which, when fully charged, gives you three full charges for the earbuds themselves, allowing them to recharge every time you put them back in the case.  Solid.

title: Extremely Happy with these headphones
content:
Extremely Happy with these headphones.
These are my first pair of wireless headphones and they couldn't be more perfect.
- Excellent Sound Quality
- Quick and easy Bluetooth pairing
- Great Noise Cancellation
- Perfect Fit
I haven't had a single issue with them.
They charge quickly and last long, with the Sound Quality being superb.
Highly recommended!

title: Great headsets
content: These were great and when paired with the app it was perfect. Unfortunately the fit for my ear was uncomfortable after about an hour and I tried the different options and still didn't work for me. If you have a larger ear canal these will be great however if a smaller canal you could potentially have a similar issue

title: Do not purchase these ear buds
content: I purchased these in late November. They have very low volume, they have zero low frequency representation and they sound like a 1973 landline handset as far as dynamic range...and that's with music. I bought a 49.00 pair of Ankers that embarass these ear buds. Save your money and buy something else, they are absolutely not worth the price of admission. Comfortable, absolutely. Light, absolutely..dont even feel them in your ear. Problem is, you dont hear them either. I'm a 30 year sound engineer and am well qualified to tell you these are absolute garbage.  All the equalization and adjustments in the app made little to no difference. They just simply shouldn't be purchased.

title: Quit working after 6 months
content: Had this product for about 6 months before the charging case just stopped working completely. This caused the headphones to be completely useless, as I can no longer charge them at all. I have been attempting to contact jabra’s customer service for weeks now (multiple emails and calls) with zero response. I did enjoy the headphones prior to the case stopping working (good sound, good noise cancellation, and only ever had them fall out with heavy sweating), but the price is way too high to pay for just 6 months of use plus being unable to get ahold of customer service. There are plenty of other good wireless headphones out there, spend your money on some that have a company that will stand by them. If by some miracle jabra decides to finally respond to me then I will adjust my review accordingly.

title: Save yourself the trouble and just buy AirPods
content: Was looking for a replacement for my Bose over the ear headphones and I was torn between these and the apple AirPods. I wound up ordering both to try them head to head. Long story short, the AirPods have way better sound quality and are far more comfortable to wear for extended periods. These will be given to one of my kids. Sad that I wasted money on these.

title: Traveler needing good airport headphones
content: These do NOT cancel background noise for people on the other end of a phone call. They seal your ear off somewhat painfully so you hear less outside noice but they are NOT good for phone calls.

title: Great buds
content: Nothing love them

title: Not really sweatproof for excessive perspiration.
content:
Overall very good sound for wireless.  However for heavy sweat workouts these jabra elite active 65t lasted two months. The two stars are because you can’t advertise sweatproof and still fail like cheaper headsets.  Over time sweat will eventually have a corrosive impact on the hardware.

Of note I run marathons and primary use is for running and weights.  I do sweat a significant amount compared to my fellow runners.  I use occasionally for streaming movies when traveling.

I have used Jabra, Jaybird, JBL, Sanso and others but I won’t compare them.

Negative:
1.  After two months the right headset volume output decreased suddenly.  While I was running on treadmill there was a pop noise and output went to half the volume.  This has happened on cheaper headsets and always on right side which is usually the master side.

2.  The hear through feature is designed to hear sounds while working out for safety, etc...  I used it during runs and found you could hear traffic but sound quality is significantly impaired.  You are better off getting bone conduction headphones.

3.  Volume controls harder to use when running but fine for low impact activities.

4.  Lasts longer than 4 hours so it is good for long runs.  The charging case works quickly and easily but caution as it can fall out of case because not magnetized.

Positive:
1.  Very good sound quality if not working out or running.  Quality decreases with hear through feature.
2.  Initial fit was uncomfortable but ear canals adjusted so very comfortable.  It did not fall out during long runs.
3.  Earbuds may fall out of charging case as it is not magnetized.

Overall this review is meant for people that sweat profusely.  This product is advertised specifically for active use.  After trying expensive and cheap headsets they all have a corrosive impact over time.  If you can deal with the headset warranty periodically then you will be fine.  It has good sound but you are probably better of getting cheaper headsets and replacing every six months with updated technology.  The sound quality difference is more noticeable with less strenuous activities.

title: Uncomfortable and unstable, with short battery life
content:
I bought this product because Wirecutter chose it as their top pick for workout earbuds. I'm glad they work for them, but they sure don't work for me--I am definitely having buyer's remorse. The ONLY thing I like about these is the sound quality of calls. People can hear me fine and I can hear them.

Cons:
-the buds have to "screw" into my ear canals for a snug fit--I've tried both the small and medium plug coverings and they are both uncomfortable bordering on slightly painful.
-even after inserted they are prone to falling back out. I have to re-do the insertion several times.
-the aggressive insertion means I am pressing the buttons on the outside of the headphone.
-they only hold a charge for 5 hours, which means if you are on calls all day you'd better have a backup pair.
-the charging case is almost impossible to open. Honestly it's like adding insult to injury that I have to wrestle to get these uncomfortable headphones out of their damn charging case.

The idea of wearing these for a workout makes me laugh. I'm ordering a different pair right now for that purpose. If you've ever been told you have narrow ear canals these are not the wireless headphones you're looking for.

title: Great ear buds!!!
content: Bought these after reading all the reviews and wanting another option to my Apple Air Pods.  The sound is good and the battery life it similar to the Air Pods, though the case doesn’t hold as much charge as the Air Pods case.  I like that I can control my music with these ear buds on my Apple Watch, just like the Air Pods.  Highly recommend these, especially for the price I paid before Christmas.

title: They don’t last
content:
I am amazed at these earbuds. I run in them, work out in them and listen at the office. The sound quality is good. I prefer more bass. But I am VERY satisfied with these.

Update 7/10/19
Almost a year since I bought these. I actually have two sets. I use one at work and one to run. Went through an issue where the sound was off balance. The left ear was quieter than the right. One pair barely has sound now and has a high pitch sound to them. I did the hardware update. Seemed to work fine for one pair. But the second pair would never update. I tried and tried with support and they always came back with something for me to try. It’s been 4 months and I wasted $380 on these two sets. These are crap and not worth the money. They start off great. They don’t last and support is awful! Don’t waste your money on Jabra.

title: Good sound. Bad quality and warranty.
content:
I bought this ear buds like new condition from amazon market place.
Pros: Better sound quality than AirPod, it maybe caused by the tighter fit. Active noise cancellation. Personally like the low-key style. Not noticeable at work place.

Cons: quality is not good. Although it is like new condition and passed amazon inspection. Left ear bud volume became significantly lower than right ear bud after 3-month moderately use. Searched online, it is known issue. Jabara does not cover the earbuds from amazon market place because it is used no matter if it is still under 1-year from first usage.

title: Do not buy these headphones
content: I bought these headphones after much consideration and research. I bought them because of their many features like the “hear through” capability because I run on roads and ride motorcycles with them and like to hear my surroundings. But unfortunately I dismissed the reviews that stated they had issues with the left earbud dropping out because there didn’t seem to be a lot of them. Alas I had mine for 4 months and they worked great, then I started getting random dead moments and clicking noises in the left ear bud. Jabra has very good customer service and agreed to replace mine under warranty (maybe good customer service? Maybe it’s because they’ve been seeing this issue? Idk). The reason I put sound quality at a 3 star is because my first pair didn’t seam to have the volume or bass I was expecting (wrote it off because they were water proof)and after I received my second pair the issue was confirmed because my second pair had much better volume and bass. But I was sorely disappointed when not even 2 days after recieving the replacement they started doing the same thing my first pair did. Called jabra and their sending me a third pair (hopefully this helps?). I suspect it might be something screwy with the headphones proximity system but I cannot confirm it.

title: Sounds Great

title: Disappointed on quality vs price
content:
I decided to give Jabra a try because of all the fancy advertisements and claims.
For the above $150 price range these earbuds look good but disappoint.
Bass range is inferior.  At times there can be subtle clicks in the audio.  Ear canal comfort is a bit below comfortable.
The design of the storage case is not that great.  The case is rounded which makes it easy to slip out of ones hands.  The flip top lid is a challenge to open every time, requiring two focused hands to peel that open.  I tried several methods to open, it is always a task to do.  I'm not sure why designers cannot make that happen well.  Pushing the earbuds into the case holder bays is also a focused task.  If you open the case the wrong way one or both of the earbuds can flip out onto the floor with a nice cracking sound.
Ran into issues where in a moderately industrial environment the person called gets all the background noise and also has a hard time understanding what is said because of cut off and ambient sound.  Using other brand earbuds or wired buds did not encounter this in same environment.
I can say, Sony puts out a better earbud for sound quality and Bose earbuds, while bigger, those do meet the challenges of being earbuds that work well for handling and delivery top end sound.  For the $150 range and up, better off going with those brands.

title: Nice but...
content: These are very nice, with good sound and features. The only thing I tend to hate with most of this style of isolation headphone is that I will never get used to hearing my own heartbeat and breathing and feeling like I have been walled off in a sound proof chamber. I think it actually messes with my equilibrium. Maybe I am only cut out for old school headphones or in ears like the sport models where much more of the ear is open. Still going to use them as I have found none that solve this issue for me. yet.

Not the best sound either, I found the bass to almost be non-existent, and the volume leaves you wanting more.  All in all, I would say that these earbuds are overpriced by $150 bucks.  Save your money and look elsewhere.

title: Spendy but worth it.
content: Probably some of the best sounding headphones I've use, definitely the best sounding true wireless I've used. Super comfy, I wear them for 7-8 hours a day, no problems with them falling out, little to no ear fatigue. They charge in the case really quickly (30ish mins), have no issues with connections. Only thing I don't like is you can only use the right one by itself, and the left one can only be used about a foot away from the right. If you like using the earbuds independently, or sharing music, maybe go with the Samsung galaxy buds. You'll get USB c and wireless charging on top of that. But if you want good comfortable headphones with a good ip rating and better button functionality, definitely can't go wrong picking these up. Also if youre looking at these and trying to justify the price over some of the more affordable options out there, trust me just get the better headphones, they'll last way longer and sound way better.

title: Functional for office calls - needs improvement otherwise
content: The headphones work fine (sound quality is just ok buy a little static-y at times if taking calls over WiFi).  I like the fact that you can have two devices connected at the same time (but only using one device at a time). BUT a major design FLAW is the charging case.  In order for the ear buds to recharge properly, the case must be upright; however, there’s no way to sit the case upright unless it’s wedged between something; the bottom of the charging case isn’t flat and the earbuds don’t remain connected for charging if the case is on it’s side.  Also, there’s no way to fully charge the case AND the earbuds simultaneously with the earbuds inside because the charging connector for the case is on the bottom so the plug and charging cord on the bottom of the case even prevents you from wedging the case in between something to make it sit upright.

title: Great when they work, but unreliable
content:
I've had these for two months and the first couple of weeks they worked great.  But they are at this point completely unreliable.  The left earbud only turns on half the time, and you have to keep re-closing and opening the case over and over until it lights up and turns on.  There is no manual way that I'm aware of to turn the left earpiece on, which is a bad decision when it doesn't reliably turn on when it's supposed to.  Also, they will sometimes turn on while still in the case which gets extremely annoying when I'm in the car listening via a headphone jack and the sound suddenly switches to my earbuds in my backpack.  Additionally when they turn on while I'm not using them, they run the battery down and start chirping and giving weird feedback, which is normally how I find out they've been sitting there turned on.

When they work correctly, the sound is good and they are mostly comfortable.  The battery life is very good.  For this price though, they're far too unreliable and I wish I hadn't purchased them.

title: Apple AirPods and Bose Killer
content:
This is my latest review after initially rating this product as a 2 star.

I have used these earbuds for about 12 hours daily for 2 weeks and have come up with a different opinion.
They are worth every penny and they out class my apple Airpods by far.
If you do not own a defective unit, you have paid for a very good quality piece of equipment.
I will recommend the Jabra Elite 65t any day to anyone looking for a quality product.
My reasons are listed as follows.

Pros:
1. They easily connect to two phones at the same time
2. Bluetooth 5.0, meaning better and clearer connectivity and better range
3. Phone app has various settings, including a high quality equaliser, to suit your taste of music and sound.
4. One charge gives me about 6hrs on the right earpiece. Well tested and proven.
5. Charging case provides an extra 10 hrs of charge.
6. Clear and crisp sound quality for voice, though not too loud.
7.Volume control plus track fwd on left earpeace
8. Caller identifier, plus can receive or ignore calls with the Voice prompt without reaching for your phone by saying "Answer or Ignore". My phones can remain permanently on silent mode.
9. Noise cancelling can completely seal out outside sound or noice. Perfect for airplane travel.
10. Good quality microphones, 2 per earpiece. I can speak quietly and the receiver can hear me clearly. Well tested and proven.
11. Music stops when you remove an earpiece, just like the Airpods
12. Very good connectivity between the two earpieces. No delay in both connections like the Apple AirPods.
13. When using both earpieces, the sound quality outclasses the sound on the AirPods due to the reduction in outside noise.
14. Never falls off your ear ,unlike the Apple Airpods. This is due to the earpiece fit design. You can jog and  workout comfortably with them on.
15. Best of all, They look GOOD !!!

Cons
1.You can only use the right side as a single earpiece . Unlike the AirPods where you can use either. If you remove the right earpiece the left goes off. But you can still use the right side alone and still get good quality sound. I believe this is because the right earpiece is designed to be the Master.
2. Because of the high quality of the equaliser, you have to set the frequencies right, inorder to get very high quality sound for the music.

The Pros far outweighs the Cons.
I own the Jabra Elite 65t, a pair of Apple AirPods and the Bose QC30 Noise cancelling earphones.
Even though the Bose packs more punch on Bass frequencies, the Jabra is a lot more functional and an overall winner of the three.
Good job Jabra.!!

title: Great set off headphones!

title: Make sure you're using the right ear cups

title: Update the FIRMWARE!
