title: Great for the gym!
content:
These are my first set of true wireless headphones I’ve owned. The sound is A+ considering they’re true wireless and the Bluetooth connection is almost seamless. You simply take them out and they connect immediately and store them away when done. I workout at the gym quite often and these do a wonderful job at blocking out noise and staying in my ears. My only complaint is my ears will get slightly sore after long hours of listening but it’s nothing major. Some others may not have this issue.

The app is quite interesting as it has ambient sounds which is good for studying. If you’re looking to get the most for your money in terms of true wireless performance for the gym or anytime, buy these. If you want to look like you have deep pockets, buy air pods.

title: Fantastic
content: It is a bit of premature review as I have been using them for an hour. Compared to my previous pair of ear buds, this is leaps and bounds superior: ease of pairing, sound quality, features and above all, fitting.

title: Jabra got it right...
content: I've had these earbuds for almost a month now, and I have been very impressed and pleased with the performance. If I had to downgrade anything, it would be that the Hearthrough function is not always detectable while listening to music. I would just stop what I'm playing to hear whatever ambient or external sounds I need to hear. Otherwise, volume, ear fit, connectivity, battery life, phone reception, and portability are above grade. I prefer the look of these than the Airpods. These are more unassuming and not prone to falling out of the ear. I plan to use these as much as possible. Jabra did an excellent job!

content: So far pleased with sound quality, noise cancellation, and connectivity. Much better than the Bose Sound Sport, which I had to return due to connectivity issues. Also, sound quality and noise cancellation far exceed AirPods.

Have this for a month now, used it several times and I am delighted.
Using in Gym, and for music and phone calls. They fit perfectly: insert twist and lock into my ears.

title: ... the sound would be a bit louder cause I like to really crank my music up but I grew ...
content: In my first listen I had hoped the sound would be  a bit louder cause I like to really crank my music up but I grew to like how high it goes as far as sound( plus I researched it's not good for your ear drums if you have too loud any ways). Connectivity wasn't hard during the time I had them I didn't experience any drop during calls or anything. The only issue that I had  was size, I have small ears and they tend to hurt after awhile in my ears so I would have to take them out for a minute. For the most part they stayed in while doing any activity that requires constant motion and sometimes they would get loose. That's the only thing that's kept me from giving it 5 stars. I actually hate that I had to return them but I have to consider comfort. So if you have small ears these may not be comfortable to you but overall they are great earbuds.

title: Overall great product.
content: No issues so far, get at least 5 to 8 hrs of use a week still. Range is less than 30ft maybe 20. Quality great, volume is ok. I only wish it got louder.

title: Good, if they fit
content:
I was impressed with the quality and ease of use of these earbuds. The controls and charging/carrying case worked well.

I had to return them eventually because they didn’t fit. These come with several different sized silicone earpieces. The standard size was too big for my ears. They sealed against my ear canal so tightly that I could hear a rumbling with every step I took. The next size down eliminated that problem but at the cost of sound quality— the bass disappeared to such an extent that I couldn’t hear instruments I knew were in my music.

I’ve been dissatisfied with many of the silicone earbud headphones I’ve tried. So my guess is that if you generally don’t like silicone in-ear headphones you won’t like these.

title: Updated: After a while, they stopped being uncomfortable.
content:
Day... I don't know, its been 2 months now, ish. I've been meaning to update my review for a couple weeks when I noticed that they are no longer causing me discomfort. that could be a good thing or a bad thing so far as my ears are concerned??? Maybe they're misshapen or something now.
But the earbuds no longer cause me pain. so 4 stars instead of 2.
Day 8: Still having issues with connectivity. Spoke to Customer Service, I think my pair might be defective. going to try exchanging them tomorrow. As for comfort, They are becoming less painful. My ears must be, for better or worse, adapting to them.
Day 2: I see people rating them as the most comfortable earbuds... I want to see their ears.  I have large ears, and these things hurt. If I use the smallest foam piece that comes with it, then the cartilage in my ear hurts. aches is probably a better word. If I use one of the 2 larger sizes, my ear doesn't ache as much, so it is more bearable in that regard. But those two sizes irritate the skin around my ear canal. so wearing them make the skin around the ear canal feel like it's sunburned, or just brushburned like the skin under your nose can become during a bad cold if you're not careful.

I'm not an audiophile, but the sound quality is at least as good as any other pair of earbuds that I have ever owned.

The left bud is a bit fickle in whether it connects or not. Sometimes it connects immediately. sometimes I have to hold down buttons on it to get it to connect. sometimes I have to put it in the case and close the case. the light on the case will flash yellow or purple, and then I take it out and it works. This could be a minor inconvenience, but I got these to wear at work. I can't be sitting around playing with them trying to get them to connect.

the noise canceling works pretty well. The only problem here is that the sound pass-through, when turned on, is a bit fickle. every few seconds it will stutter and not pass outside noise through. this can be distracting.

Other reviewers have wrote about the earbuds breaking after a few months, and the left one especially goes out pretty quickly... between this, my own experience with the fickleness of the left bud, and the discomfort I experience while wearing them, I will probably be returning them before I have to deal with customer service. I really wanted to like these because they have controls on them, and I can't find others with controls on them.

title: Be weary of the left earbud
content:
These are great. The sound is perfect, the battery lasts a long time, and they never fall out of your ears (unless wet).
However, there’s somehow no guard to keep dirt/earwax out of the headphones (which is disgusting) and YOU CANT USE THE LEFT EARPHONE ALONE. How? Why? This is arguable the most annoying part about these. The left earphone only works when the right is inserted in your ear. Even then, it has trouble maintaining its connection, and will periodically cut out while playing music. Fingers crossed that a future update can fix this annoyance.

content:
I bought my pair over the Christmas season while they were on sale (just over a $120) - setup was easy and I wear them 6 -8 a day without having to charge them.  I have my work phone forwarded to my mobile phone so I take all my calls by Jabra Elite 65t.  Alexa isn't very useful at this time - maybe I should try it more.

Simple use - once paired with phone and playing Pandora.  Removing right ear bud - pause the music.  A single tap will also pause the music or restart after pausing.  A double tap allows for hear through listening and if the music is stopped they actually provide some amplification of the surrounding environment (like a hearing aid).

Keeping my eyes on Jabra for future releases.

title: Pretty good for listening - not so great for talking.
content:
I really like these headphones... as headphones.

PROS

They connect flawlessly with my Essential PH-1, my Nintendo Switch (with HomeSpot transmitter), and my work laptop, a Lenovo ThinkPad Carbon X1.

Sound quality is pretty good - not as good as cans, but come on, these things are packing communication, battery, and sound production into a package the size of a marble.  They don't fizzle on extreme highs or lows like cheap earbuds.  They isolate sound pretty well if you don't have HearThrough on, which is a software feature that will intentionally let an adjustable amount of outside noise in - I don't want to get smooshed in a crosswalk by a siren I can't hear, so it's a nice feature to be able to toggle on and off.

Battery life is great.  I haven't flatlined the earbuds themselves because I usually use them for an hour to an hour and a half at a time.  I charge the case once or twice a week.

The charging case is sleek and secure.  No satisfying magnetic POP like Airpods, but the buds settle in without a lot of fuss with little notches where the microphone portion settles in.  The buds will blink red when they've made contact with the charging prongs, an LED between the buds shows their battery level, and an LED on the bottom shows approximate case battery level (green/yellow/red).  Pretty informative little package!

CONS

I am disappointed with their performance as a phone headset, especially coming from Jabra.  People on the other side often complain about every noise in the background getting picked up - a car horn a block away sounds as if it's two feet away.  If you're in a relatively quiet environment, they work great.  If you're not, though, they will amplify everything.

The buttons are not easily triggered.  Best thing to do is anchor the bud with your thumb and middle finger and navigate with your pointer... or just give up and change it on your phone like we had to in the good ol' days.

Sometimes the left one won't connect at first, so I'll drop them back in the case and put them back in.

Comfort is so-so.  I have small ears.  Someone bought me Airpods as a gift and the hard plastic killed my ears after just 15 minutes.  The soft tips on these are infinitely better, though after two hours my ears could still use a break.  They hurt more when I first got them, so there is some getting used to them.

OVERALL

If Airpods aren't your thing, these are a viable contender.  The case is slightly larger than the Airpod case and much less floss-like.  They're amazing for what they are - a pocket-sized set of headphones with a good battery life.  I like that the whole case + buds fit in my tiny girl jean pockets and I don't have to wear them around my neck.  If you're looking for a solid pair of headphones to add to your everyday carry list, these would be a great contender.  However, if you're looking for comfort and solid quality sound, I'd recommend a nice pair of over-ears instead.

title: VERY Pleased
content:
This is my first review which, considering the number of items I've purchased from Amazon, says something. I can compare these with the Zolo Liberty+. I was an early backer of the Liberty+ and have to say that I've been very impressed with the sound quality of those buds. The problem is that the Liberty+ HURT my ears after a few hours of wear.

I was hesitant about pulling the trigger on the Elite 65t mainly because I've never known Jabra for anything music-related. Boy am I glad I took the chance. The sound quality is on par with the Liberty+ but different. The Liberty+ goes slightly deeper but the detail and clarity of the 65t is MUCH better.

Phone call quality is much better on the 65t; the call comes through in both ears and there are many more options for answering (or not) calls. The controls on the headset are much more expansive than on the Zolo's. Taking one of the earbuds out of the ear pauses the music, re-inserting the bud restarts the music. This is a neat feature.

Fit: I'm able to get a good seal with the supplied silicone tips but I have ordered a set of Comply foam tips to test comfort. My left ear develops a little bit of soreness, seemingly emanating from the tragus area, after several hours of listening but these are MUCH more comfortable than the Liberty+.

I think these deserve the high marks; for me they're the best option available right now for truly wireless earbuds. I've not tried an extensive range of sets so take that in the spirit it's intended.

title: Lost Sound in Right Earbud After 5 Months
content:
I bought these in April of 2019, and they lasted until August of 2019.  I was out on the trail running, and the right earbud sounded a little scratchy, then died.  I thought maybe I hadn't charged them properly, so I recharged.  The left earbud puts out normal sound, the right is nearly inaudible.  You can hear it inside when it's quiet, but it is too faint to hear outside.  For nearly $200, I would hope that these would, at least, last 6 months, but they did not.

After some research, I found a couple of "workarounds" to remedy this relatively common situation.  However, after trying all of the online fixes, I have nothing.  One good earbud, one with barely any sound.

Other than this most obvious issue, these were pretty good earbuds.  They occasionally lose audio, if you crank your head to one side running, which is not often (hopefully!).  They stick in place dry, but will work themselves free when you are sweaty.  It is not a huge deal, but they start jarring free, and I was constantly adjusting them.  A slight twist every mile or so is not a gamechanger, but it is annoying.  Granted, I wore these mainly for marathon training, so they were in my ears for hours at a time.

The battery life is good, and the sound quality is pretty good too.  You won't get a great sound experience, but they are not bad for small wireless buds.

If it weren't for the loss of sound in my right earbud, this would have been a 4 star review.

title: Great sound/design - Left earbud louder & has more bass?
content:
I bought these at Best Buy before they were available on Amazon. I love them, but there are some quirks they need to work out.

PROS:
- Sounds quality is excellent with a nice balanced profile
- The EQ feature is exactly what I wanted and let me get the sound just right
- Fit is secure (a little uncomfortable at first but you can get used to them
- Battery life is excellent
- Controls are tactile and solid
- Calls just work. They are great.

CONS:
- Sound seems to be louder on the left side? Or the stereo image is shifted to the left ear slightly? (if anyone else has this issue please comment below)
  - I noticed this right away and had the same issue with a replacement pair
  - There also seems to be more bass in the left ear
- There is a half second delay for Youtube, less prevalent with Netflix but hopefully will be fixed with a firmware update on Jabras side, or software updates from Youtube etc

yep, they're expensive. Buy them anyway.

title: Great earbuds, but light on bass
content: These are really some of the best headphones I've used. Despite having some issues with pairing 2 devices at once at first, my PC and phone connect every day without any problems. The audio hand-off is sometimes a little funky, but that could be because of a USB bluetooth adapter on my PC rather than the headphones themselves. The HearThrough feature is great for keeping them in at the office or out and being active. Battery life is solid, too. I've been able to wear them for almost an entire workday, only having to take a break to charge them while I make lunch. Battery life is better without HearThrough as well, and the case is good for about a day and a half to 2 days before needing a charge. The only complaint I have is the bass is kinda disappointing, even with the equalizer. I really have to jam them into my ears for better bass and, while they don't fall out of my ears, they do shift a little bit and cause the bass to diminish. Honestly not a dealbreaker though. Would definitely recommend.

title: Excellent voice quality.
content:
Very good voice quality - on par with my wired sennheiser buds. The app is also easy to use, comes with an equalizer that actually does the job. The little usability features really make a difference. It also works pretty well as mic-headphone when making calls!
Only minus is that BT connection on most phones isn't perfect. I think that's generally the problem with all wireless buds. I have experienced some short cuts in the voice when BT connection is unstable. Too far from phone, or in an environment with a lot of radio noise. Most of it goes away if I put the phone in my right pocket instead of left one.

title: Buyer Beware!
content: My right earbud stopped working after 2 months. Controls on the bud worked and it would power on but very faint sound out of the bud rendered it useless. Contacted customer support by email and phone. They usually do not respond. Finally spoke to a rep. Was offered to fill out the warranty and submit proof of purchase. I did. It's been a few weeks and no response. No emails saying a replacement bud is on the way, nothing. Tried calling. Was tired of being kept on hold with no answer. Awful product and awful customer service.

title: Not a reliable daily exercise earbud, Jabra support is slow and not customer-oriented
content: Initially I loved the product. It worked well out of the box. I liked how compact they are and the battery life. Sound quality was decent - not as good as Bose but the had a better fit and less bulk. However, after a few months I ran into intermittent issues with the left earbud not working. The fix is to put the buds back in the case and try again, and this usually got the left bud to "wake up". This happened enough times that I contacted tech support at Jabra. It is best to call by the way. If you communicate by email the average turnaround time from them to respond is 2-4 days (but they do respond). Their response is always the same - reinstall the firmware. Despite doing this, the left bud still sometimes did not work. I decided to just live with this issue as it was infrequent but annoying. But recently the right earbud stopped working. When I contacted Jabra, not surprisingly, they asked me to reinstall firmware and even do seemingly strange things like change the default language of the buds. None of this worked. Eventually I got the bud to come back to life by just tapping on the housing of the bud. When it did come back, its output was below that of the left. After multiple rounds of Jabra asking me to play with the firmware, they finally had me ship them back to them at their cost. They then told me they are going to replace them under warranty, but then immediately told me they are on backorder and gave no firm date on when they would be available. So now I have no earbuds and no date for a replacement. Whatever initial excitement I had about these earbuds is lost. I'm not happy with their durability and think their responsiveness to address this issue could be far better. I am regretting abandoning Bose for Jabra and considering I have no earbuds now and no date for replacement, I will be shopping for a new pair and I will not be buying Jabra again. I would have given them a one star but I'm reminded that for a time they worked well and I was happy with them.

title: A couple of things I wish I'd known beforehand...
content:
the Jabra elite 65t are high quality wireless ear pieces with very good sound quality and flawless bluetooth connection to smart phone.
2 issues prevent me from giving it a 5 star rating.
1. the case is not easy to open, once closed.  I actually have to use 2 thumbs, apply fair amount of pressure to pop open the lid.  I've seen a co-worker's apple air pods and the case easily pops open without much effort at all since it is magnetic.
2.  I've tried every ear bud provided from the smallest to the largest.  these ear buds are not the easiest to stay in the ear.  I can actually feel them sometimes working themselves loose to where they have fallen out and I've had to catch them before they hit the ground.  Jabra should have included an over the ear attachment as an accessory for folks like me when their is a fit issue.  One of my colleagues has a Bose with an over the ear attachment and he loves it even though his is wired.  C'mon Jabra - you can do better!

Hopefully their product development will contact me if they have an over the ear attachment because I waited too long and can no longer return these.  I guess I just have to grind these into my ear until they stay in place.

title: Seems like a quality product, but color is not accurate and they look like hearing aids
content:
I agree with the other reviewer who said they look like hearing aids (before anyone jumps down my throat, nothing wrong with hearing aids, except that's not the look I'm going for, especially at this price point). I expected a much more light gold/pearl color earbud, and instead received an ugly flat ivory/gold pair and also look much larger in my ear than I had anticipated. As soon as I put them in, I thought to myself that they look like hearing aids, and when I saw the other person's Amazon review indicating the same, knew I wasn't crazy.

I tested them out for a bit and they were super easy to pair, sound quality seemed very good (compared to much less expensive wireless earbuds I have purchased on Amazon), and the button press controls seemed intuitive. However, I could tell they would become quite uncomfortable after extended periods of time. Not only are they large, but you have to press the buttons (especially on the left bud which controls volume and song skipping) pretty hard to get them to work, which presses them in to your ear even more, and that ends up hurting after a while. However, I will say that when I first put them in, they fit very snugly and I would not hesitate to use them for working out.

I am going to go with my first pick and try out the Samsung Galaxy Buds instead as they are supposed to have a sleeker profile than these. If I didn't already have the Galaxy Buds in mind, I would stick with the Jabras but go for the black color.

**EDIT 7/21/19**: I ended up buying the Samsung Galaxy Bud and enjoy them significantly more. Rather than buttons, they function by gestures (ie, tap once for play/pause, tap twice for next song/answer call, etc.), and you can customize  what you want a long hold to do in the app that connects to the buds. In addition, they are smaller and have a much sleeker profile as I had expected!

title: Great earbuds that don’t fall out
content: They fit very well in my ears, the only ear buds that I’ve been able to find that do so. I use them for running and they work great.

title: Good idea, Poor execution.
content:
Put simply, these headphones were a phenomenal idea that wasn't tested enough before going to market. They look nice, fit comfortably (unless you want to use them for working out, in which case you'll be chasing them across the gym!), charge easily and sound decent. I thought they were the whole package, and they were, for a few weeks. Then everything started to go downhill.

Major drawbacks:
- Left ear buzzes constantly, and for no apparent reason. This started about 5 days after the return period expired and hasn't stopped. Occasionally i can get it to go away for a song or two if i reset the earbuds multiple times, but there isn't a consistent fix.
- You can use the right earbud by itself, but not the left one. This is a design flaw, and often leads to inadvertent automatic pausing.
- Connection drops all the time, even when i am sitting at my desk mere feet from my phone. I don't have this problem with other products connecting to my phone via bluetooth. This was a real problem, as my phone would play my music for the whole office to hear when the earbuds cut in/out every couple of minutes.
- Interference is a huge problem with this model for some reason. They are almost worthless in airports/stadiums/malls/gyms/anywhere there are multiple connected devices operating. I've tested other wireless headsets in the exact same areas, and they worked just fine.
- Don't even bother trying to get Jabra to honor their product warranty. That's just a waste of everyone's time and patience. They are well aware of the connection/interference/static issue, and don't seem to care/know how to fix it. This was my first and last Jabra purchase.

title: Great Wireless Earbud
content:
This is for the regular Elite 65T after using it for like 5 days.  I debated and did bunch of research between Active and Elite.  The main concern was battery life due to the step in Active and Elite falling out.  Well, it never fall out for me so I'm satisfy.

Pro
- Wireless and can connect to multiple device.  I use it for my PC and cell phone.
- Rapid charging and last ~5 hours.
- Wireless charging in the case is one of the main reason why I bought it.  Didn't like my previous wireless needing to plug into the earbud to charge
- Charging the case is fast.  I'm not sure if the case have rapid charging capability but within 1 hours, my case is full.
- Regular Elite 65T does not drop out of the ear.  Make sure you rotate it after you put it in.  I ran on the treadmill for hours multiple days and no sign of it falling at all.  Even the sweat didn't affect it much (except making it a bit more slippery when I took it off)
- No voice out of sync at all when watching movies
- Hear-through is great.  I haven't try too much in public places but I can definitely hear sound from further away if my slider is up high.  It would also amplify my key press while typing this review.  Only recommend if you want awareness.
- There is an equalizer in the apps, but almost every music apps have them too.  I don't play around with those, just standard guy who listen to music as is.
- The Sound apps also have background music if you want to go sleep like Oceans wave or Rainy background.  Not sure if that the purpose of it though,  Have 3 profile, Regular, Commute and Focus (study mode)

Con
- Randomly drop signal for 1 sec like once every 3-5 hours?  I'm ok with it but many like it to be perfect.  I also notice, if the device you connecting to have crappy bluetooth, you can expect some signal loss.  With my S8 phone, no signal drop at all.
- I prefer that my Right Earbud, pressing it once would automatically activate my voice assistant like Ok Google or Alexa.  I have to press the button then say those command.  Just a personally preference.
- Don't really like pressing buttons into my ear, but something I can get use too.

So I sacrifice my body for some numbers.  I would not listen for 5 hours straight next time.  Stopwatch and battery level based on the Sound apps at 50-75% volume.  This is for my Earbud.  Yours may be different but it should give you a picture somewhat.

1hr 03min 92%
1hr 12min 88%
2hr 03min  62%
2hr 45min  50%
3hr 13min  43%
4hr 10min 23%
4hr 39min 9%  Battery low announcement
4hr 49min 4%
4hr 53min 2% Dead

Now, here the thing with Rapid Charging using a fully charged case.  It blew my mind compare to what was advertised:  10-15min charging for addition 1.5hr music.
I did exactly 10min charge = 52% so based on my stats, that about 2hr

Overall, it was a hefty price to pay but was worth it since I really needed wireless earbud to PC usage.  I first did Large left and Medium right but the left side got really uncomfortable after 30min.  End up doing Med/Med but keep noticing that my right ear felt loose/strange.  I just swab to left Med and right Large and it feel better now.  Trial and error.  I really hope it last for 1-2 years.

title: They seem to be designed for larger ears. If you have smaller ears they may be uncomfortable.
content: Very well designed earbuds. A little snug in my ears. Appeared to be designed for larger ears. Battery life excellent. Sound quality is excellent. Overall, very impressive.

title: These are much smaller than my Bose Soundsport Free Headphones, and sound just as good
content:
I have a pair of Bose Soundsport Free headphones that have been alright, but not great.  I wanted to give these a try to see if they would might be better.  So far, the one area that they are definitely better is their fit and comfort.  They fit almost completely in my ears, where the Bose hang way out and are very large.

I'll update this review as I have more time with these, but so far, I am very happy with them.  They are at least as good as the Bose in sound quality, comfort, and usability, and are far better in weight, size, and fit.

See the attached photo for a comparison of the size of these compared to the Bose.

// Update //

I've been using these for a week now, and although I didn't have any complaints about the Bose Soundsport Free Headphones, I definitely prefer these Jabra Elite Active 65t Earbuds.  They work very consistently, sound great, and are much smaller and lighter in my ears.  They get the full five hours of promised battery life.  I'm really happy with them.

One thing that these Jabra headphones definitely do better than the Bose ones is YouTube on an iPad.  With the Bose there is a huge delay that makes them largely unusable for video.  With these Jabra buds there is no noticeable delay.  That is a huge advantage for me.

title: ... available on Amazon so I picked it up from Best Buy the other day
content:
This wasn't' available on Amazon so I picked it up from Best Buy the other day. Since I'm an android user, I've been looking for something comparable to the airpods that will work as well for android. This is as close as I've been able to find so far.

The Good:
1) I've only heard the two earpieces get out of sync once in the three days I've owned this...surprisingly while I was writing this review.  Most true wireless earbuds I've used, the left ear piece would randomly lose sound and come back in again.
2) To turn them on, you just remove them from the case. To turn them back off, just put them in the case. With cheaper earbuds I've tried, you had to hold both buttons down on both earpieces to turn them on and off, so this is much nicer.
3) When you pull one earbud out of your ear, it pauses whatever music you are playing.
4) Much more comfortable than the air pods.These actually tightly seal in your ear, so I find that I can actually play the music much more quietly, as it is not competing with other noise.

The Bad:
1) This is small, but I believe the air pods have a feature when you reinsert the pods into your ears, the music beings to play again. The Jabra earbuds do not have that feature. You have to push the button on the right earbud to start the music when it is paused, which is followed by a loud beep.

Update 03/20/2018: It looks like these earbuds do have the feature where the music does begin to play again once re-inserted in to your ears. It does not work on the Pixel XL, but I was able to get that feature to work on the One Plus 5.

title: My favorite wireless buds
content: These are fantastic and the design keeps them locked in your ears, maybe a bit too sealed to be honest.  Great quality, about 20ft range before sound starts getting garbled.

title: Great sound in a small form with no audio lag
content:
I use these literally everyday for hours. I've had these for four months now and can confidently say these are 100% worth it. At work (server admin), grocery store, etc. The feel is great, they will not fall out of my ear even though I try.

The look is compact and trendy. Most don't even notice them. The touch buttons on them to pause music/videos work flawlessly. Netflix, YouTube, Google Music, even downloaded movies. Pause and play with one touch. Even when my phone screen is off.

Bass quality can be good for truly wireless earbuds. The app that lets you configure (equalizer) the ear buds on the fly works great. The app itself I've not run into any problem at all. If you aren't confident using the equalizer, there are a few preset modes that work great too. I can even use these with my switch with Genki Switch Bluetooth Adapter (humanthings.co).

+Holy crap! The call quality on these babies is nothing short of revolutionary! Crystal crystal clear voice going both ways. Taking a call and talking to someone is seem less.

+ Noise cancellation is good but not the best. There is a passthrough option that turns on and let's all sound pass through if enabled that is an amazing feat.

+ Battery life is by far the best on the market (still!) And four months later is still holding strong. Maybe 4ish hours of constant use, and I have the equalizer to emphasize the bass to that no doubt t uses more power.

+ Range is maybe 20 feet If in direct line of the device. Through a wall and 10-11 feet away I can still hear perfectly fine.

+ I have not seen ANY audio delay at all when watching Netflix, YouTube or Google Movies

- The carrying case is a rubberized matte that charges the earbuds. The ear buds just lay inside there and the top clicks shut. If you drop it, the ear buds will go tumbling about.  But overall it generally won't open on it's own in your pocket.

+ Tested with Google Pixel 2 XL, Google Pixel 3 XL, Motorolla G6, Asus Maximus Formula X Motherboard (built in Bluetooth), Genki Nintendo Switch Bluetooth Adapter. I cannot recommend these enough. I tried my significant others Air Buds from Apple and these blow them away. I cannot stress how great these are. If you are a huge audiophile and want the best sound you can get but don't care about more than 2 hours of battery life get the Sennheiser. If you want the best overall experience for audio, calls, movies, battery life, durability, get these now.

title: Good product but has issues
content:
Was very excited for these earbuds and had high expectations but they fall short. First, the sound is great and they stay in my ears well. Especially like the ability to block sound (great for airplanes) or to let outside sound in (great when outdoors near traffic).

What I don’t like is the connectivity. I have to clear all previous connections even if I am using the same device.  It connects but takes several extra steps.  My other wireless earbuds connect quickly so this is an issue with the Jabra product.

My other issue is dropped signal. Thes work well with a phone but only if it is in my right pocket or if I’m not moving. I wear my iWatch on my left hand and it is a joke trying to walk or run and listen to music from the watch. The earbud receiver is on the right ear and when your arm swings behind your body the signal drops.  Doesn’t happen with every stride but I have yet to make it through one song without multiple drops. A product at this price shouldn’t have this issue.

Works OK for phone calls but I prefer my $20 headset instead. I give this 3.5 stars

title: Dont Buy!! Poor Quality!
content: Very uncomfortable pair of earbuds. Very hard to hear songs. I would not recommend buying this product.

title: Good earbuds, a few qurks. This listener is satisfied.
content:
Dealing with earbuds is a finicky thing. So much revolves around how they fit your ears, size of ear canal, etc. I have oddly shaped ears, in a way that usually i end up with different size silicone for each one to get a solid fit. This set of buds is no different, and initially I was hesitant to purchase after reading reviews. But I went ahead anyways. Overall i give it 4 stars. good set, surprised me in some ways (fit was better then i expected), and disappointing in some ways (reception). Sorry for the long review, lots of little things about this set (plus a few tips on fit and use). So I provided a summary. you can read the rest below.

PRO:
Good fit, even with my finicky ears.
Nice sound
App has nice features
No cord.

CONS:
Fit is all or nothing. very dependent on the earbud shape fitting into your earlobes.
App is cumbersome and non intuitive.
No Cord (seriously, it's too easy to drop one of these and have it bounce under the table. never happens with my corded buds. Having a cord comes in handy at times like these).
Reception is bad, left side is finicky with connecting at times (connection is solid once it does connect). songs hiccup too often.
:
1) Fit
I was actually surprised at how well they fit my ears. I still had to go with 2 different sized silicone...medium for my left, large for my right. But the nature of these buds (they use the lower inner earlobe to stay in place), seems to afford them a nice fit with good external exclusion. the pass though feature allows some sound in, and is adjustable. I keep it around 20% and it seems to give me enough to hear if anythings happening around me, but still enjoy the full sound of the music at the same time.
I would recommend for a solid fit is to initially put them in with the mic extension a bit high, and then twist it down as you pull a bit on your lower earlobe. picture pulling the lobe down and around the lower side of the earbud, and you'll probably get a nice fit. after doing it a few times it gets easier and I don't feel these are any more difficult then a traditional earbud at this point. Took a few times to get it down...i kept pushing on them directly into the ear and it was painful and didn't work. the pull/twist method was much more successful.
The downside to this is the fit is all in the shape of the earbud. If it doesn't fit your ear, your not going to get good exclusion, and this affects sound quality. That being said, even with finicky ears, I still got a comfortable fit with no discomfort (usually wear time is 1-3 hours max).
Overall, these are slower to set up then my wired ones. pulling them both out of the case, setting them in each ear, often having to reconnect the left side, adds some time to it. But once they're set up, they're great. I don't have any issues with them slipping out of my ears at all, and I tend to be a heavy sweater in my workouts. My Jaybirds will usually require regular adjustments halfway through the workout. With these, I almost forgot they were there. Not having a cord bop you in the mouth every time you lay back for a bench press is a solid win as well.

2) Sound
Sound isn't bad. Decent lows and highs, and having the equalizer in the app helps, even if it is a bit basic, it's something. Fit impacts the sound quite a bit. the sound on my left side was bad until i swapped for the medium silicone, and now it works quite well. The downside to this is there are limited silicone sizes...if they don't' work for you, these earbuds suck. you can't just push them a little deeper or twist them a bit this way or that...they only have one fit, and they depend on the silicone outside of that for exclusion and sound quality. But again, even with finicky ears, the combination of the earbud and silicone worked fine.

3) Reception
This is where these earbuds missed the mark for me. multiple drops during a song on average. they are usually no more then a fraction of a second...the song hiccups, then back on track. But it is definitely an immersion breaker, and too often it distracts me...I keep waiting for a call or a text ping thinking it was interrupted due to that, but then the song kicks back in and i either have to assume it was bad reception, or run over to the phone to make sure I'm not missing an important text. Very irritating. My Jaybird v2's have a drop about once every 2-3 songs. These drop 2-3x per song sometimes. Again, small, and as I get used to it I just sigh and get back into my workout. But it's bad enough to affect the rating IMO.
Plus the left earbud seems to be very intermittent with it's connection. About 50-60% of the time when I pull them directly from the case and plug them in, the left earbud is silent. I have to power down the set (hold down button on right bud) with them in my ears, and power back up again for the left side to connect. The whole master/slave setup for the two earbuds is logical, but the left earbud needs to have better response to the right one on activation.

4) App
Having an app is nice. equalizer, adjustable settings...but the app could use some love. the main page isn't intuitive...I feel like there should be a simply set of toggles for the most used features (much like the Bluetooth and airplane modes on my phone). But instead you have to go to a sub menu and select features there, which open a third window...allot to worry about when you just want to reduce the sound that gets through. A simple control panel for the most used features (exclusion settings, equalizer, etc). would make the app actually enjoyable to use. As it is, you fiddle with initial settings and then pretty much leave it alone. It's too much of a pain to tinker with while your in the middle of a workout.

5) Other Features
the buttons on the side are very easy to use and get used to, and they're functions are probably the most intuitive I've had in an earbud setup. I had to refer to the manual a few times to get used to the full options, but I don't even think about it any more. Very nice. I have yet to really use the mikes, but on the few calls I've used them they seem to work well, no negative feedback from the people on the other side.

Quick note on the case: as others have stated, it IS slippery, and it's round shapes make it easy to drop. I found the best way to hold it is to grab it on the sides where it's flat. Same with opening the lid: I don't try to squeeze a fingernail under the silly little divet they offer on front: I grab each side of the lid with my fingers, apply a bit of pressure, and pull. It pops open easy this way, with very little chance of slipping out of your hands.

title: Battery life deserves at least six stars
content:
I was not really sold on the idea of wireless earbuds, and I largely ignored them when the Airpods came out. I bought these primarily because I wanted a smaller option than my over-ears (Samsung Level Over) that I can keep in my work bag all the time. These exceeded every expectation.

1) Fit and noise insulation. I am not taking these for an air flight until later this week, so I will have to hold off on commenting, I think they're probably going to be usable but nowhere near as nice as over ears. For day-to-day, they provide a very nice fit for me (they have three earbud options, they are a little flimsy and the replacements are obnoxiously priced, one of the few downsides), they're comfortable, and they're very immersive. Sound quality is not perfect, but for earbuds I think it's very satisfactory, and many reviewers rate this among the better option from a sound perspective.

2) The tech - the microphones seem to work well. These are my go to for making phone calls. The Bluetooth will simultaneously connect to two devices, e.g., phone and laptop, without dropping either one, and this works really well most of the time. This is a game changer - we have Bluetooth speakers, over ears, etc., these are the only thing I have that does this and does it well.

3) The battery and case. As others have pointed out, in 2018 the case should have a USB-c connector so I can just carry the same cable I charge my phone with. Other than this, the battery life is amazing - I'm not a heavy user, but I barely think about it, I have never run them down, and even if I did, the case would be there as a backup. With relatively sporadic use, I honestly charge the case maybe once a week or less. Aside from the micro USB port, everything is perfect about this aspect of it.

title: LEFT EARBUD NOT WORKING AFTER ONLY 12 MONTHS
content: After 1 year left earbud quickly cuts out or doesn't work at all. Worked fine for 12 months. Nothing I do solves the problem. NOT HAPPY

title: Jabra 65t is a good product
content:
I have enjoyed using this product.  The sound is very clear and people can hear me when on the phone.  The sound quality is good and you can hear movies/music quite nicely.  They aren't quite as good as the Bose QC35s, but they aren't intended to compete with that level of product so it isn't a fair comparison.

There are a couple of things to keep in mind.  These are "place in your ear" type ear buds...not hang over your ear, etc.  You may find they just pop out for whatever the reason.  They have comfortable silicon seals that keep it in place, but I have found they will just pop out for what seems like no reason.  They will land where ever they like and you need to keep your eyes open and make sure you don't step on the bud if it happens to be in front of you.

The microphone for when talking to someone on the phone is very sensitive and not noise cancelling.  If you are in a noisy place, the person on the other end will hear these noises as well as your voice.  Even someone just talking who might be near you will be picked up.  You need to be aware of the noises around you when using these ear buds on the phone.

I bought them with one intent to use them while sleeping on a plane (instead of my Bose over the ear headphones).  I have a sleeping collar and the headphones are in the way a bit.  I have found that they really aren't very reliable for that because they do pop out as mentioned above.  I have resorted back to using the headphones so that I don't lose the ear bud on the floor, seat, or wherever it might land if it should pop out while sleeping.

title: Sweat causes sounds to cut out
content:
When these are working properly they produce a great, well-balanced sound. They play louder than some other wireless headphone (Powerbeats 3 for comparison). The issue is, if you run with them and sweat alot, the stems will clog with sweat and you'll lose sound in one or both buds. After a workout, you'll need to leave them sitting out of the case to 'dry out' for a few days, which means you can't use them to run again. In some cases, they'll dry out overnight, or after a few days, but sometimes I've had to leave them out for 7 days before sound is audible in both buds.

Also, for my ears, the stems seem to be short, which means if you do sweat, the seal will break and they could fall out, so you'll be shoving them back in your ears frequently.

I purchased these because I thought the 'active' moniker would provide more resistance to sweat/water, but that is not the case. If you don't need these for exercising, I would highly recommend them, otherwise, I'd steer clear of them. It's unfortunate, because I love the sound and functionality of these, but they simply don't work for the primary purchase I purchased them which is to run with. If it were're for the sweat issued, they'd get a 4-5 start, but obviously, since they don't work half the time, it drops to one star.

title: Best Bluetooth earbuds.

title: If they fit they're great...
content:
The Good: The sound is good. The controls are surprisingly intuitive, I do wish the volume was flipped though. It works seamlessly with Google Assistant and pairing. They are low profile and nice looking.

The Bad: The shape is the worst aspect of these buds.  They determine what size ear can wear them. My ears did not fit their mold and caused discomfort when they were pushed in all the way. Speaking of... when running I noticed one bud would keep coming loose (the one that hurts my ear). I finally got it to fit but there was a trade off: not fit in/let ambient noise in/comfortable or fit in/great sound/uncomfortable. Lastly, the hearthrough is helpful in theory but if you have music playing that can be so distracting that you cannot focus on the ambient noise. They are more of a "I don't want to take these out but I still need to pause them."

title: Best wireless earbuds I’ve found so far
content:
Good sound, good battery life, quick to recharge, reliable connection over good distance. These are the best wireless earbuds I’ve found, and I’ve tried many.

I use them to help focus while working or studying. Whenever I take a break, I recharge them in their case. Because they quick-charge, by the time I’m back from break they’re completely charged again. When used this way they last all day.

I especially like being able to choose whether to clearly hear ambient sound when I want (so I can hear when someone speaks to me), or block ambient noise I find distracting.

They’re also great for watching movies without disturbing my significant other, so I can still hear her when she says something to me.

title: Nice.

title: Won't Buy Jabra Again...
content:
These are decent; not great.  Jabra support is frustrating.  (Reversed because I think the second issue is more important.)

My second support incident occurred when the left earbud stopped pairing.  Just wouldn't connect.  I opened the support case 12 days ago.  I'm waiting on RMA instructions.  But it's been almost two weeks.  I'm sure I'll have to ship mine in before they'll either ship refurbs (gross) or deny this warranty claim.  That'll make this three weeks, at least.  Probably a month.  I would absolutely not buy these again.

My first support question: "The medium eargels are too small and the large are too big. Is there another option? Either from Jabra or another source?"  Their response: Update my firmware.  Are you !@#$% kidding me?  Okay.  "Um - I think there was a miscommunication or some tickets got mixed up.  I'm pretty sure reinstalling the firmware won't change the size of the tips."  Their response: "With what you've described, it sounds like something like the Elite Sport may be a better solution. While the Elite Active 65t only has the three ear gel sizes, the Elite Sport uses a wider selection of model-specific inserts that do work to provide an increased snug fit."  Yeah.  The earbuds I just paid $200 for?  The manufacturer says I should have bought something else.

Note: I tried the Comply True Wireless tips, and they were okay.  Still a little small for me.  The Comply Audio Pro are better, but they don't fit in the Jabra charging case.

title: Jabra customer service is a problem - know before you buy!
content: I purchased 3 pairs of Jabra Elite Active 65t earphones in November as Christmas gifts (for me, my son, my daughter). The sound quality and ease of use was fine, but no better than I have had in Bose previously for example. The earphones hurt my 23 year old daughter's ears. She is not small, 6' tall, so they should have been ok I would think. Anyway, I contacted Jabra to see about a refund or exchange for her set. She only wore them twice and tried the smallest ear adapter to no avail. The customer service rep, if you want to call her that, was rude, curt and had no sympathy for our situation. She said they have a strict policy of only refunding and only if defective (not f they don't fit apparently) for 30 days after purchase. So they were past 30 days when my daughter opened her Christmas present. I bought directly from Jabra to get better service than Amazon (I had read several reviews on Amazon that people had issues and Jabra would not support their products when purchased through 3rd parties - it makes no difference! - this is basically an "as is" purchase). No Christmas consideration or spirit at Jabra. Well I have a strict policy now. I will NEVER purchase another product from Jabra and will never recommend or support them. There are too many options out there. I hope their customer business model works for them. My guess is it won't for long. I hope future expert reviews include some customer service support aspects to their reviews of Jabra in the future so other consumers know what they are getting into whey they purchase these expensive earphones.

title: Liberating!
content:
I have had bluetooth headphones for years, and I'm probably into double digit units of various brands. To compare I have Bose QC 35II, Jaybird Bluebud X Sport, Phaiser 760, Plantronics Backbeat Pro, etc. Most comfortable would have to be the Bose, and they have the best noise cancelling and sound. Those are over the ear headphones however. These Jabra Elite Active 65T earbuds are almost as good for noise cancelling and sound quality and are earbuds. Comfort wise the Jabra are probably better since you don't have bulky headphones on your head. For the size, comfort, lack of wires, these buds are amazing. The calling capability is also really good. I've used them for a few calls and I have had no complaints. These also stay in the ear really well. I have tested with Youtube and they are right in sync with the video, another point these win over Bose.

Pros:
* Great sound
* Good active noise cancelling
* Pass through function works and is useful
* Sound and video in sync
* Comfortable, stay in place

 Cons
* Micro USB charging port. Come on, its 2019, USB-C please.
* Not fully waterproof (rain/sweat ok).
* May be to big for those with very small ears

Suggested improvements:
* Waterproof/float
* USB-C charging port
* QI charging
* longer battery life (>8 hours)

TL:DR:
If you are in the market for truely wireless headphones, you won't be disappointed.

title: These are really great true wireless ear buds!
content: I love these headphones! I read about the audio lag happening with video playback in other true wireless headphones, so that was a concern. I watch a lot of video while working out and have NEVER had that issue. The sound is great, and they automatically connect as soon as you put them close to your ears, as long as you have just taken them from their case. I seem to have to charge the case every 9 days or so. I have dropped one or the other of them repeatedly, and they are no worse for wear. No signs of damage at all. Oh and they are quite comfortable too.

I use these while lifting/jogging and only very rarely have experienced any problems with them.  Definitely worth the investment if you listen to music often.

title: Very nice quality
content:
I love these bluetooth ear pieces.

I used to test a lot of them for a company I worked for. Largely to test in noisy rooms, nights with long talk times, comfort, batterlife etc.

This was for a personal set, and I've enjoyed the Jabra line in the past. I figured, why not?

It did not disappoint. I picked up the gold set preferring to have something a little more subtle than the black earpiece in my ear with my gray/white hair and fair skin. It was a good choice.

The only drawback right off is the ear piece itself is a bit large, it took some getting used to.

there are 3 sizes of plug adapters which go into the ear canal, soon as I got one that wasn't too small, or too big, it helped keep the ear  piece in place.

Once the ear pieces are paired with each other, I could still use one alone (RIGHT ONE ONLY).
I have a large German Shepherd that loves to pick up small things, so I have to be very careful to put it back in the charger when I'm not wearing it. When wearing both the left and right earpiece a lot of the noises around me are barely noticeable though I would not consider this a noise cancellation earplug.  The application that you use on your phone (optional) allows you to upload updates to the earpieces. It also allows you to chose various settings of white noise like woods, waves, beach, static etc. You can also select your own balance, be it sports, talking, high base or treble notes etc.

I've used them for a few days now and I love them. The charging case Is plugged in every night, though I've yet to have used it till it was dead. I take it off the charger in the morning and drop it into my satchel.

title: Surprising quality earbuds
content:
Wow, the Jabra Elite earbuds were so easy to connect to my iphone I was amazed.  The set comes with 3 sizes of earbuds, which is fab because my ears are small and the larger ones hurt my ears, so that was a plus.  I simply put the buds in my ears and turned them on.  They voice prompted me to install the iphone app and once I did that, they easily connected to my Jabra music.  I use Pandora a lot so that come up and began playing immediately.  Awesome.  The earbud has a control for volume and for skipping tracks  They also hook up to my iphone for calls.  There is a setting through the app for customizing the sound..add bass or treble.  And, you can set the sound so that ambient sounds come through, so if you're listening for your commuter train station call out, you won't miss it.  The little carrying/charging case  easily fits in my pocket.  Too bad it doesn't have a space for the little charging cord too.  The charging cord could have been a bit longer, because at 8" it has to be fairly close to the USB plug to use it.
  The sound is pretty decent.

title: Best truly wireless headphones right now...Bose should start taking notes
content:
I bought these on Sunday since I was able to take advantage of a discount from work.  They have quickly replaced my Bose Soundsport Free headphones as my go-to headphones around the house and certainly when out.  The first attraction for me was the design. They are MUCH smaller than the Soundsport Free. I can wear them while laying on a pillow without them digging into my head.  I can change my shirt without it ripping them out.  They also don’t look anywhere near as weird since they don’t stick out from my ears like the Soundsport Free.  Plus, the Jabra headphones are far more comfortable in my ears.  I have worn them at pretty much every opportunity, for hours each day since purchase, and for every phone call I have taken.  I have yet to want to remove them to give my ears a rest like I have with other headphones.

The Jabra Elite 65t sound pretty good, yet the Bose headphones still have the advantage for sound quality.  The Jabras simply cannot match the low bass or the clear highs but they sound really good.  While comparatively not offering the sound quality of the Bose the Jabras sound good enough that their comfort and size advantages easily outweigh this.

The hear-through feature is a big deal as well.  If headphones are going to be so comfortable that I will want to have them in all the time, it is nice for them to have a feature that can allow me to engage in a conversation without it being a necessity that I remove them.  By double-tapping on the right earbud I can hear everything going on around me. Another double-tap and I’m back to the passive noise reduction.  Passive, not active.

Lastly, these are excellent on phone calls.  Call audio is routed to both earbuds.  Incoming sound quality is excellent.  Not a single person has noticed that I was using headphones, with two people telling me I sounded better than I do when holding the phone.

title: Amazon Used Can Sell Defective Items...
content:
This I'd a review of Amazon's used product. I was excited to get my wireless earbuds and immediately used them for work and conference calls. It required better ear foams to get the noise cancellation to work, but it was worth the extra cost. Months later I took up working out and started to notice a connection loss when I had the phone in my pocket. Turning my head could completely sever the music and it became more of an annoyance than the solid product I thought I had.

After dealing with Jabra support I came to found out I was sold a defective pair of buds. They wouldn't honor fixing it because they were bought Amazon Used. The window for returning it on Amazon was so short that I never had an opportunity. So my only recourse is to use them when my phone is in the table or in my hand (in which they work fine). Saving a few dollars for a used Amazon product is a risk that is not worth it for higher priced items.

title: Too Many Issues to be Worth It
content:
I have had these earbuds for a few months now, and I regret buying them. While the sound quality and fit are quite good, the persistent issues I've had make it not worth the money.

The main issue is that the charging case doesn't work often, and since dead wireless earbuds are useless, I've been using my cord headphones more often than not. I've seen some "fixes" for this on Reddit, but a good product shouldn't require you to fix the hardware problems yourself. Also, if you don't place the earbuds exactly right in the charging case (which is more tedious than it should be, since you have to make a light on each earbud light up), then you will end up with only one earbud that plays sound. (Meanwhile, AirPods fit into their case automatically due to the case's shape & magnetism.)

Also, the user experience could be better. It's annoying to have to reconnect them through the settings app so often (knowing that AirPods connect automatically). These also struggle to connect sometimes, so I have to turn them off and on a couple times until they finally connect. Furthermore, it's just annoying to hear the headphones announce "DEVICE DISCONNECTED" and "TWO DEVICES CONNECTED" whenever you walk within a certain radius of one of your bluetooth devices.

I know some of these sound minor, but when the product is so close to being good, but falls short in a number of ways, it's simply not worth buying. Maybe in a couple years Jabra will figure it out. Just buy the AirPods and save yourself the frustration.

title: Bad for phone calls in public & Broke in 3 months
content:
I bought these because I read all sorts of reviews on how great they were at taking calls. I think I even saw a claim of “I was skiing with these under my helmet at the person in the other end had no idea.” Which is so weird because if I’m in a call with these headphones I constantly get complaints on how extremely loud the background noise is. I went as far as recording a call while I was in an airport and Jesus, man, these things made it sound (to the other person in the call) like I was in a warzone. It picked up noises I didn’t even hear and blared them over the call.

Overall, if you’re buying these with the expectations of making calls in public areas, don’t bother.

UPDATE: So, now the right headphone just stopped working intermittently. Only had them for about 3 months, mostly used on flights and such. So, I can’t use them with just one headphone in since you can’t use the left one alone. I contacted support but they needed the original receipt and unfortunately I already returned the ones I bought from amazon originally because they came in the wrong color and the box looked opened, the pair I currently have I bought from another store and didn’t keep it. Bad call on my part, but I guess I didn’t expect them to break so soon. Won’t be buying anymore jabra products. These things are far more expensive than they’re worth. They don’t do anything better than the dozens of other wireless headphones.

title: Audio passthrough is amazing
content:
These headphones are excellent. Great sound. Noise cancellation is perfect even when something quiet is playing (as long as you pick the correct tips). The call quality is clear and the app is well made. It even has a feature (Soundscape) which will play relaxing sounds of nature to help you relax (like rain for example).

Even better than the noise cancellation is the audio passthrough which allows sound to bypass the noise cancellation through the four mics. It's accessed by a double press on the right ear. It's one of those things that sounds like a gimmick at first but is becomes a requirement on all future purchases. It balances the incoming sound perfectly with whatever's playing so you won't miss your song when someone talks to you or vice versa.

The base could be slightly deeper but I'm comparing to my $250 over-ear Sony headphones. The fact that the Jabras even come close enough to compare is a testament to how great these are.

title: Pleased with the Jabra Elite Active 65t's
content:
I purchased the Elite Active 65t from BB since they have the exclusive on the black ones I wanted (and Amazon apparently has the exclusive on the copper blue).

I have been using the JLab Audio Epic2's the past 18 months.  They have not been staying in my ears all that well, and sweat was getting in my ears.  When they sealed well they had excellent bass (which I like for workouts).  I have been looking for something else. Totally unrelated I happened to lose them somewhere on a short hike where I had them around my neck (really!!!).

Based on reviews I had narrowed it down between the Jabra Elite Active 65t and the Bose Soundsport Free.

In 2014 I compared the Creative Sound Blaster Roar vs Bose SoundLink Mini side by side and the Roar was the obvious winner.  That said, I do have Bose FreeSpace 51's I purchased in 2004, and still using them.  In general the boominess of the Bose sounds good, but as soon as you compare it with something else you feel that a lot is missing.

From the many reviews I read, the bass on the Bose was better. Bass on the 65t's seemed like a mix bag, some people think its great and some people think it is tinny. The Bose did zero sound isolation whereas the 65t had the same mixed bag.  Sound isolation is important to me for the gym.

As I mentioned, bass is very important to me. Knowing that a good seal is the key to bass, I figured it was all about getting the buds to seal and I was correct.  The small and medium tips did not seal and left me with a tinny sound and no sound isolation.  Using the large tips got a good seal, which meant good sound isolation and good bass response.  I wear earplugs every night so I do not mind the feel of a good seal, but some people might not find it comfortable.  I have worn them for an hour with no comfort issues at all.

I use the 65t's with several phones, but for my power walk/runs I use it with my Jelly Pro strapped on my left arm. Unfortunately there was a huge problem with sound cut out, so I had to switch the Jelly Pro to my right arm and have had zero issues since.  I blame the Jelly Pro but I should mention I never had the issue with the Epic2's (but of course the bluetooth transmitter was on my neck as opposed to in my right ear).

The Elite Active 65t's sound is much better than the Epic2's. The Epic2 might have had a titch better deep bass, but even that was muddier than the 65t's.  The 65t sound is excellent, far surpassing what I was used to.  That said, I have not used wired earbuds in years, so I cannot compare sound to wired earbuds. That said, I will never go back to wired, period!

The first time I tried to open the 65t's case I could not! I did a quick google to find that you should hold the sides to open the top (take note of which side the hinge is on). Do not try and use your fingernail or some other object to open the case where the slit is. Sometimes I still have an issue opening it when my hands are sweaty. Not a big deal but something I had to mention.

I have not used the phone features, other than I did try it, and it works. I hardly ever do voice ;)

For workouts,they stay put, they do not loosen up, and they do not fall out. That said, when I start working up a sweat, it sort of feels like they are coming lose, but they are not.  Also, big plus, no sweat ends up in my ears like it did with the Epic2's!

The HearThrough feature is a cool feature but not perfect. The HearThrough volume is set in the app and that is where it stays.  I have it set to max volume. If you have the music at a low level, you can hear others conversations near by.  However, turning up the music does not turn up the ambient sound, and you can't hear much.  That said, I did hear a car go by, so it's not terrible. There is an option to have the music pause or keep playing when you activate HearThrough, if you are going to use HearThrough mostly to talk to others, you might want to have it pause the music (or else you are going to have to turn the music volume down). The HearThrough volume is controlled only in the app, it does not go up with the music volume which I wish it did.

The Android app equalizer works pretty well. I am not sure why some people have said it's not.

As I really only use these for working out I have not gone beyond an hour, so cannot comment on battery life.

Overall I am pleased with the Jabra Elite Active 65t's.

title: Great headset if you want a premium android experience.
content:
I picked these up to pair with my Samsung S8+. I love them and use them all the time. The required apps to install a little funky at first but after your initial setup they never really require any interaction. The case that acts as a charging station is very sturdy and well built. I've carried it in bags and pockets and it shows no signs of wear.

The headsets themselves are comfortable and sound amazing. I've experienced zero lag when watching movies and love the on ear buttons. The sound cancellation works well and the pass through is useful. Microphone quality is top tier so much so that I can switch between my handset and this earbuds without the other caller having any clue.

My only real complaint is the battery life is a bit lower then expected. Typically with a fully charged case and headsets I can only make about 9-10 total hours. This isn't a deal breaker for me since I typically only use them in small bursts throughout a day, but heavy users should expect to charge these at minimum every night.

title: Great Wireless Earbuds
content: Overall one of the best for the money. They are more expensive then a few pair I have bought before but the range, battery life, and sound are the best. The buttons work great also, to skip or adjust the volume I dont have to go to my phone simply just use the buttons on the ear buds. These are my choice over my over the ear head phones.

title: Overall a decent pair without wires
content:
So I don't normally write reviews. But I figured since these are pretty expensive headphones and a investment I would.
The pros are there wireless, they stay in your ears and they somewhat cancel noise.
As far as noise cancelling goes it's almost as if you're sticking your pinky fingers in your ears while listening to music it's good if someone's talking to you in the room or round you in the room you can drown them out with your music. But if you're in the gym and you're lifting you can still make out the klink's and clanks of people around you.
The music quality and sound isn't exactly ideal if you're a big music junkie and if you like to listen to music really loud that needs headphones aren't for you,but the overall sound quality is decent. They do stay in your ears, but every now and again you can feel them start to come loose and have to push them back in... not a make-or-break. When you order these headphones it comes with a two-year warranty you can sign up for so people saying that the batteries don't last or this or that the two year warranty should cover it.
as far as Bluetooth and dropping calls or music I haven't had any bad experiences I've been able to walk across the gym 60 + feet and still come back and my music's playing just fine.

title: Probably worth the money.
content: The sound is not bad. Comfort is good. They have never fallen out and really need to be adjusted. Still getting used to the functions and controls. But it doesn’t seem difficult.

title: Didn't last 60 days.
content: I purchased the 65t in late November 2018. In late December 2018 I started having issues with the right pod volume getting lower during calls. Until it finally stopped letting me hear on it at all. I called Amazon customer service, and another unit was sent to me. Today is January 25th. I have had 3 instances with the second units right ear pod mic going mute to the other party on the call. I have had Jabra products in the past, with much success. This product I do not recommend.

title: Worked great for first 3 months of use...
content:
Worked great for the first 3 months of use. Left earbud audio suddenly died and wouldn't work. Tried reaching out to customer service for replacement but up to this day, I'm still waiting for the replacement to be shipped to me. 1/10 customer service satisfaction :(

I do think the case is really flimsy as well and easily prone to possible internal damage. Definitely not worth $179

title: Better for music listening and not for talking
content: I was so disappointed when I received my 65t's that I returned the first pair thinking they where defected. After receiving my second pair, I realized they were better sounding with music and not for cell phone use. The cell phone use sounded like a hollow tunnel and no one could hear or understand what I was saying clearly. With both in ear, the stereo sound of music was great. If your going to use them for music, they're still a little pricey but worth the sound. For cell phone use I would probably try a different type.

title: Wouldn’t stay in my ears
content: I really wanted these to pair with my TV while on my treadmill, so my husband can sleep through my workout. Unfortunately, even with the smallest sized earbud, I only got them to stay in successfully one time, so I had to send them back.  Otherwise they were great and I’m sorry they didn’t work for me.  I’m still on a mission to find something with this quality that will stay in my ears.

title: Simply awesome
content: These sound great, feel great, and are great quality.

title: Active 65t is a outstanding product
content:
I bought these because of the reviews by Flossy Carter and other online reviews. They look discreet and don't stand out. They are comfortable to wear for a long time and they are excellently balanced for not having aptx.

Music is not heavy bass but sound quality is very good. Call quality is top notch and noise canceling features are superb. The Bluetooth 5.0 keeps them attached to my Note 9 at all times.

Music play back, youtube and Netflix play back with out any dropping of words or phrases. It synchronizes with my Note 9 as soon as I take it out of the charging case. The left side is synchronize as soon as I install it in my ear with no loss of synch or dropping.

The earbuds are noise canceling and the hear through feature allows me to hear things going on around me and to talk to people as well.

They quick charge to 1.5 hours of use in 15 minutes. The charge case gives you 10 hours of listening...... Buy these they are the real deal

I used these to replace my plantronics bluetooth headset

title: They are pretty good.
content: Pretty good quality but do occasionally fall out of ears with some exercises.

title: Sound is not great
content: for the price i paid i expected better sound quality. I had to download the jabra app to see if it was my phone that was making the quality so shitty and to make matters worse i have abnormally small ears. i thought using the smallest silicon ear buds would make these the perfect fit but unfortunately not. they always fall out. definitely returning

title: Known issue with one earbud playing at low level
content: There is a problem with one of the earbuds always playing at a low level. It is very noticeable and based on what others wrote, this has been an issue for a long time. Also, when pressing on left earbud buttons, you get a stabbing feeling in your ear. All other things that were nice about it were trumped by the right earbud playing at low volume, I mean earbuds essentially have one job to do, one job and they fail at it. Only good thing that came out of this is a proof that you can't buy a good quality product anymore even if you spend extra money.

title: Battery life sucks!!!!!
content: Great headphones, but the charging case doesn't even last 4 hours!! I took them to the beach fully charged in the morning and was pissed by the afternoon because I had nothing to listen to my music with!!! AND that was after having had to recharge them twice!!!

title: Just okay...
content: It is at the margins a fair product, and the second day of wearing them one fell out and fell on the NYC subway tracks.  They didn't have a warning that it was about to fall.

title: These fall out
content: Fall out, don't stay in.

title: Don’t fit well and are too quiet. Nice features, though.
content: Difficult to keep in my right ear with the supplied tips, for this price some additional tips, some a lot longer, should be supplied. They fit semi well with third party tips.  Sound is somewhat quiet compared to wired buds.

title: Pleasantly surprised
content: I have been racking my brain which earbud to buy...settled on these and am really impressed. Comfortable in ear and really stays put. Unobtrusive look on ear and noise cancellation is very strong.  Good value for money.

title: DEFECTIVE/ FRADULENT PRODUCT!!! DONT BUY!!!
content: DEFECTIVE!!! Garbage, pure garbage. The left ear bud is louder than the right ear bud. The left one also dies first. They also do not stay in my ears. I contacted the seller about this and they offered me $20!!! They are selling defective versions of the original product. I bought a pair of the same headphones from Best Buy and they were far superior!!! This is unacceptable for a pair of $190 ear buds. Give me my money back please or send me a brand new pair of WORKING ear buds.

title: Terrible reception/and trying to pair with my iP:hone was a joke
content: Couldn't get to pair with my iPhone and was so disappointed for the money I paid for them wasn't even close to bein g worth it!!

title: Good!
content: Though my ears are a little bit painful when I use it for a long time, the price is great!

title: Glitchy straight out of the box
content: I've had these earbuds less than 24h and they are going back. Extremely disappointed in the quality of this product. The left earbud drops in and out during usage. Pandora will not play for more than 60s before crashing. I don't have either of these issues with wired earbuds. I don't think this was from bluetooth interference, as these problems occurred while I was at home and I don't live or work in a large city.  As for sound quality, when they did work, the sound was clear and balanced, not bass heavy. In fact, the bass was kinda of weak across R&B, hip hop, pop, and rock genres. But as far as truly wireless goes, the sound wasn't bad. However, these earbuds are definitely not worth the exorbitant price and not at all recommended.

title: If wireless earbuds stay in your ears they would be great.
content: I wish they fit my ears better.  I tried all the included different tips and none would stay seated when I move around.

title: The best buds
content: I own two pairs of jabra ear buds. My absolute favorite buds.

title: Pretty good!
content: Got ther most part, these have been great for work and even listening to something for when I go to sleep, but sometimes wont stay in long.  I have tried all rubber earpiece sizes and the smallest fit best, but when cleaning the house or exercising, after about 30 minutes or so they will slip out or I have to uncomfortably place them to stay in. If I move up to the next size, they are too big and wont stay in at all.

title: Defective
content: Worked fine till bout 2 months when left earbud does not work and now case won't charge

title: Stopped sleeping in case, returned for warranty replacement
content:
Really liked these.  Solid build quality, good sound, easy to operate.  Battery life was great. My only negative is that I thought the mic quality was oversold.  On phone call, nobody could hear me clearly.  Which is totally understandable since the mic is so far away from your mouth.

But after about 6 weeks, the right ear bud stopped turning off/going to sleep when it was returned to case.  One of the main attractions to these wireless earbuds is that they automatically connect when they are removed from the case.  If you have to completely turn them off before you return to the case, well, that defeats the point.

First tried to return via Amazon, but they (without telling me, I only saw it when I received the refund notice) wanted to only refund 80% since I was outside the 30 day window.  So I cancelled the Amazon return and initiated a warranty replacement through Jabra.

title: Easy to use
content: Good hold/sound
