The best almost $200 i've ever spent on headphones. A lot of reviews showed some kind of disconnection issue with the earbuds but the only issue i've had is with my phone connecting to them.

Ok, wow. Not even a year into having these and of course, the left earbud has just started to go out. It's connecting just fine, but is barely producing ANY sound. I can crank the volume up to the max and hear that the speaker is failing. Waste of money.

title: good gift
content: got these as a holiday gift for my husband, he loves them and uses them several times per day.  easy to use, great sound, comfortable.

title: Good sound quality. Terrible durability. Literally, the worst customer service.
content:
These headphones work well. For the price, it’s hard to beat the sound quality. I looked at many different options (Momentum Wireless were the main completion for these) but these sounded great and I loved them.... until...

The volume started lowering rapidly once they turned on....

I bought them in April, and they a 2 year warranty. So I had them 5 months and had a failure. Not great, but hey... there’s no such thing as a perfect product, and Incontaced their support. Here’s the problem:

I contacted them about the problem. You are lucky if you get a response within 24 hours. Ok, maybe I’m the exception to their customer service. After a 1 week back and forth, they say if I send the headphones in, they will ship me out a replacement as soon as they receive them without delay. Great!

It’s been over two weeks since they received them and they keep telling me the item is on back order (even though they offer free overnight shipping for the headphones as a new purchase). I asked them if there’s a way to expedite the order. Their response was “No”.

In summary, of all the headphones I’ve spent $150+ on, Jabra has been, by far, the worst. This was my first foray into Jabra quality headphones, and while they sound great, the durability combined with the customer service has made it an easy decision to never buy them again.

title: Not useful for sharing
content: These disconnect if they are more than a foot or so away from one another, which makes them impossible to share with a friend. Airpods can be used 20 feet from one another.

title: One Year
content:
One year. That's how long you can expect the battery to hold out on this set of wireless earbuds and its charger with regular use.

Is it worth the price of admission for a year of usability? I would say no, but wireless earbuds as a whole are not really items built with longevity in mind. I would like to see that trend reversed.

Pluses: great sound, great fit, ambient noise passthrough

Minuses: call quality is AWFUL, bluetooth connectivity is tenuous at best when multiple devices are connected, battery life, build quality is iffy

title: Very good sound, pairs easily with iPhone and iPad, secure in my ears
content: When I first tried these I was going to return them as I thought the sound was poor.  But after trying a larger ear bud size the sound came alive!  What a difference getting a good seal in your ear makes.  They also feel very secure in my ear and do not feel like they will fall out.  I bought these to replace my Apple EarPods which I think have very good sound but they do not stay in my ears without attaching some ear hooks which I have to put on and the off each time I want to put them back in the charging case.  These are my new go to earbuds!
Really good sound, bass maybe 4/5 but great fit, i use it to run outside and daily work as well as gym. It stays in my ear qnd theres an app to adjust to ur kind of vibe.

title: After 3 weeks, left earphone stopped working
content:
My real rating is zero stars. It worked great at the beginning. All the features were easy to learn. The battery life is amazing. Then, after 3 weeks the left earphone stopped working. If I press the plastic lightly, it works intermittently, like if there is some loss contacts.

I wish there was a way to search in the reviews for Quality products specifically. I searched for the best reviewed products and the "Value" ones get prioritized by the system. Lots of people buy the cheapest ones and of course they are good..... for the price. But reading in detail, all of them last short. Still trying to identify the best wireless earphones for Android phone. Not the best "value"

title: Good but uncomfortable
content: I wanted to go full wireless and after a decent amount of research decided on these for Black Friday. After a few months I can finally give a decent review. The earbuds themselves feel high quality and the sound quality is also great. However the fit out of the box is abyssmal. I am constantly on guard of either them falling out or the discomfort of having them in for extended periods of time. That being said they pair extremely easy, very rarely drop signal, sound great, have a good enough battery life to where it’s only been an issue once, and and small and compact. I bough a pair of comply foam tips to fit on the earbuds that would also fit in the case. Hopefully this solves the problem but for headphones this expensive no one should be uncomfortable in them.

title: Great sound quality. Buy THESE!!!
content:
It has become very impractical to wear my wireless over-ears into the grocery store while on phone calls, so I decided to give the Jabra Elite 65t wireless earbuds a try. Here are the things I like and dislike about these buds.

Look: They are very discrete and perfect for the office. their neutral color scheme does not draw much attention. I'd say these go really well with business attire, or any attire for that matter.

Comfort: This is the only area that could be better in my opinion. Instantly, I feel the pressure from them resting on my cartiladge. After about 30-45 minutes of wear, my ears begin to hurt. Mine aren't exceptionally small either, as I've tried on earbuds by other brands. It's almost as if theres very little give or rubber-like material there except for the tip. It may be something to consider for the next version.

UPDATE: I switched from the medium tips to the large ones and it made all the difference in the world! Not only are they more comfortable, but the bass is deeper than before.  Changed to five stars!!!

Controls/Noise Cancelling: the Jabra Sound+ app is great! There's an equalizer, a hearthrough option to control whether you can or cannot hear your surroundings, and Soundscape sounds for times when you need to block out the world and focus. I cannot hear people talking or making regular noises at all when I have these on, music playing, and hearthrough off.

Sound Quality: Honestly, these earbuds remind me of my Bose QC35's! The bass is tight and punchy, the mids are not too recessed, and the highs are crystal clear! I love to let others experience this sound and watch their faces change from meh to WOW!

Again, if only they were a little more comfortable. If different tips make a difference, I will come back and update you all.

title: Great!
content: It was one of the best headphones you could get. I wish you can use the left side by itself , but it good over all.

title: Works great. Convenient charging case.
content: Sound great. Cancel a lot of noise but you can allow it if you wish. Great product.

title: Fast shipping
content: Good quality

title: Ambient Noise pickup is awful - almost unusable
content: Best use of these headphones is only for listening to music, doing calls on it is impossible in loud environments because the microphone is too sensitive and there is no way to fix it.  Was hoping after owning them for a while they would finally come out with a firmware update but they seem to be advertising the heck out them but no plans to update firmware.

title: Great true wireless earbuds
content:
I purchased these on a whim from a local Best buy, thinking that I would end up returning them. Overall, they're great for my needs.
I use these mostly in class and while driving, as they have a feature allowing noise from your surroundings through. It isn't perfect, but it works in most cases for me.

I recently purchased comply memory foam ear tips for these, and while they sound much better, the tips are too big for the charging case, especially at certain angles, and I find that they get stuck in the case and don't come out with the earbuds.
They sound pretty good normally, and with the comply foam ear tips they sound even better. The eq can be adjusted from within the jabra app to your liking.
The app is ok, it works and I haven't experienced any major bugs as of yet.
The buds are relatively easy to lose, but I haven't had much of an issue with that as the case is small enough to keep in my pocket.

My only real gripes with these are that the memory foam tips don't fit well in the case, and that you cannot use the left earbud separately from the right. Neither problem is that big of an issue for me though.

Overall, these are great truly wireless earbuds that just seem to work. They connect quickly, theyre easy to control and use once you get used to the controls, and most importantly they sound good. I also haven't had any major issues with stuttering.

Update: I returned the Elite 65t and purchased the active version as it cost less, and they are nearly identical. They have a different finish, which I prefer, but they function exactly the same in my usage so far

title: Someday will be a pair of these that are great for now not so great
content: The controls to invoke Siri are confusing and I can't get it to work consistently. I haven't figured out a combination of soft foam inserts  that are comfortable, have good sound and stay in. If you use sufficiently large ones then you can't put the earbuds in the case to charge because they didn't leave enough space for anything but the small foam inserts. So you have to remove the foam inserts and then of course you will lose them because they're tiny and black.  I'm using this with an iPhone X and constantly have to mess around with the Bluetooth settings to connect to these.  I think this got good reviews by wire cutter and elsewhere because so many of them are so bad.

title: Overpriced Headset-
content: not worth $200. you can get as good or better quality for $50. Would return but missed my 30 day window.

I sent several e-mails for jabra help center but there was any responce

title: Didn't last
content: Sound started out great.  Everything was good.  Fast forward 3 months.  The right ear bud sound volume would deteriorate after 3 minutes.  Within a week, the right ear bud has no sound.  I contacted Customer Service, (via email, couldn't find a live human to speak with on the phone) and the email said to update the software and re-pair the device.  I did.  Same result.  Another email, another week... They said send them back, they'll inspect them for defects and possibly ship me replacements within 5-7 business days.  3 months of use, 2 weeks of back and forth with Customer Service and send them in and wait is the response.  Seems expensive for 3 months of use.  I'll spend my $$ on a different company and I'll tell everyone I know to never buy a Jabra anything.

title: Awesome headphones - cuts out occasionally

These headphones comes with three sets of rubber gels, so you're pretty much guaranteed they will fit well. I always have problems with earphones being too big, but these are perfect! Sound is great too! I use these at the gym and they don't block out the music in there completely, but about 95%. My only complaint is that they will drop the connection when I listen to music for no apparent reason; I am right next to my phone and both devices are charged. It's only for a few seconds, but I have no idea why it's happening. Overall, great purchase!

title: Not sure they are worth the money

title: Good quality ear buds

title: happier now .. be sure to test in different areas if  crackling sound in left earbud
content:
UPDATE: returned and received a replacement .. and experienced exact same crackling sound in the left.  So, of course, at that point I had to change another variable..  Turns out I have some strange interference in that part of my house.  Outside that area no crackling.  It is strange b/c I have a couple of Plantronics BackBeat FIT headphones that have no problem in that same area at all.  It seems that Jabra BT is more sensitive to your environment.  Hope this can be adjusted with firmware update.

A couple of more observations:
- i get minor dropouts while walking or running (like running to catch a bus, not treadmill running).  I never get that with any of my BackBeat FIT headsets.
- the case usability can be greatly improved with the use of magnets helping guide the earbud into its slot.  right, if you're accurate, the earbud will drop into its spot.. if not .. it can bounce right out.

These two are the reasons for 4 stars so far.

Fit is good (but may vary for you).  I appreciate the ability to use silicone eargels to achieve a tighter noise isolating fit.  that was one reason i looked at these rather than getting the airpods.  I like the ability to enable the pass-through feature - allows me to keep the earbuds when people interrupt with a quick question.

FIRST REVIEW
on the very first day, i'm hearing crackling in the left earbud just like a few other reviewers have reported.  when i play music on my phone, crackling sound starts right away and even starts to cause the music playback to stop probably b/c the earbuds are disconnecting.  I have galaxy S8 and use it successfully with a number of bluethooth devices without any problems.  Synthesizer on default setting - not really pushing the sound to new heights here.  updated firmware - no effect on this problem.  and of course, I charged them overnight before setting up and testing.

sure sounds like it is defective.  will be returning

title: Left earbud went dead after 5 months; still waiting for replacement
content: After a little over 5 months the left earbud stopped working; I did all the "basics", reinstalled sw, re-paired, hard reset, etc.  After talking to Jabra customer support they had me do same thing.  One week later they also concluded that left ear was defective.  However, before they would send me a replacement, I needed to send back my defective pair...the entire process should only take "a few weeks"!  A few weeks?  Why am I getting punished for their poor product.  I even offered to give them a credit card so they would send me a working set ASAP.  They declined that offer.  Will never buy Jabra again!

title: Microphones are bad
content:
For this price, and with such quality claims, the product better be essentially perfect.  It isn't close.

Sound isolation and speaker quality -- what I hear when I wear these -- are good. The battery life is good, and they fit well in my ear, staying in place while moving.
So if these were only for listening to music while working out, and not advertised as "we are great at audio calls with so many microphones and fancy tech", and not priced as the best things for music and calls, this would be a positive review.

But they are sold as the best thing for calls, and they are priced accordingly. And the microphone quality -- how people hear me when I talk through these -- is awful.

Lesser but still major problem: the activation force for the buttons is way too high. You either have to drive the earbuds deep into your head to get the buttons to click, or half-pull the earbud out to hold it with your fingers while pressing the button.
And a nasty sw bug that should be fixable: every time bluetooth connects, a random few seconds later the headphones change to near-maximum volume. Usually after starting music, while trying to lower the volume. Ouch. Ouch ouch ouch.

title: Great set of buds

title: Great sounds

title: Great earbuds
content:
I bought these for my husband for our anniversary in February. He has a tendency to be rough on things like this so I was reluctant to spend the money, but they are rated as the best so I went for it. He LOVES them.
PROS: The sound quality is great, range is excellent, and they cancel noise almost too well- especially if you plan on running outside. My husband is able to go to other rooms without interrupting his music or phone calls. They have even gone through the wash and dryer with no apparent damage. The app allows users to change sound settings or search for misplaced earbuds, as well as offer support.
CONS: if you take one earbud out, you can't listen to music because the connection is lost, but if you plan to run safely outside, the noise cancellation makes it difficult to listen for hazards on the road. This is irritating where we live since there are no sidewalks near us.

title: Great fit and noise isolation!
content: Volume is lacking compared to significantly cheaper ‘wired’ earbuds. I really like the seal I get - which is what noise isolation is all about. Voice prompts work well for answering calls without physically touching either earbud. Hear through seems ok....haven’t really use it much. Charge life seems - as advertised for both the earbuds and the case. I highly recommend buying a case to house the charging case....worth the investment. Seems to be a very good product....durability will be determined over time. Already like them more than the 3 pair of Beatsx that I’ve gone though....needless to say Beats are not on any future shopping lists.....

title: Decent for music but bad for bluetooth calls.
content: I use these earphones to take calls and listen to music.  Music sound is ok, but everyone complains that my voice is very faint when using for calls.  I complained and received a replacement pair from Jabra but the second pair has the same issue.

title: It works

title: Good earbuds, usability issues...
content:
Overall, a good choice for sound quality, but I have a few issues with them now that I'm using them every day.  Purchased them a few months ago after trying a number of others, both name brands and generics.  Didn't compare them to the $200+ competition (like Bose, etc.).

POSITIVES:
Sound quality is definitely better than earbuds in the $50 or less range.  I tried a few, even from "brand names" and these have better sound quality.
Nice app from Jabra that serves as a manual, software updater, etc.
Charging case is reasonably small and can recharge the buds when I'm out and about.  I charge the case every few days.
Several equalizer settings in the app to help you get sound that's appealing and accurate for you and your surroundings.
Work with my iPhone surprisingly well!  People can't tell I'm using wireless buds.  I can touch the right bud to answer or hang up, etc.
Stay in place without hooks.  Surprisingly, these buds don't attach to any part of the ear, and don't stick into the ear canal  a long way, but nonetheless, they remain in place, even when I'm in the gym on an elliptical or doing weight training.  I attribute that to the nature of the rubber fittings that come standard with the buds.  (See below for comments on replacing these.)
Seem durable.  I've dropped them a few times and they continue to work well.
Stylish look, both the buds themselves, and while on me.  (Some earbuds look garish when people wear them.  IMO, these don't look bad in place.)

NEGATIVES:
The case and the buds are very rounded, and can slip out of your fingers really easily.  I've read other reviews of them being dropped and being damaged.
Occasionally, I put the buds in the case to charge and one of them didn't charge.  Now, I'm careful to make sure they are in contact with the charging pins in the case and haven't had this happen.
Occasionally, the case shows that it is adequately charged to charge up the buds, but when I have used the buds, they run out of power pretty quickly.
When I wear them for more than than an hour, I have a little ear canal soreness.  Goes away when I take them out.  Probably shouldn't have them in for that long anyway.

COMMENTS:
These are not "noise cancelling".  If they fit well in your ear canal, they attenuate surrounding sound, but don't actively cancel noise.  I don't find that effect very powerful, but noticeably better than the Apple pods that just hang on your ears and don't seal the canal.
The amount of bass depends on the fit (like most earbuds).  My left ear fits better than the right, so there's a little difference in bass between the two.
I thought I would replace the rubber fittings to get a better seal, both for better noise attenuation and better sound.  Tried getting memory foam replacements specifically made for these Jabras.  Found that the rubber fittings that came with the Jabras had better sound quality and a more comfortable fit.  Stay with what comes with these buds!

OVERALL:
I recommend them for sound quality, etc.  Make sure you place them in the charging case so you see that they are in contact with the charging pins, and be careful when you're handling them so you don't drop them.

title: Comfortable fit
content: Very comfortable fit, sounds amazing once you download the Jabra app and utilize all the features. If you use them daily they are definitely worth the money in my opinion.

title: Was Great....Then They Weren't
content: Received these as a gift last December.  I really enjoyed them.  Sound was good and they were comfortable to wear, even while running.  About a month ago however the right earbud experienced a noticeable loss of volume causing an unpleasant listening experience.  After going through about a week's worth of trouble-shooting, the problem persisted.  This is apparently a known issue for this earbuds.  After submitting paperwork Jabra authorized a warranty return.  That was over two weeks ago.  The replacement earbuds are on "back order" with no estimate on when they will be available.  So no earbuds and no idea when they might arrive.  Be wary of purchasing this item!

title: Too bulky for me.
content: Not good for people with small ear, the headphones are big and bulky. I didn’t even turn them on so I don’t know how the sound is etc.

title: Works really well so far...
content: I'm very happy with these so far.  I was a little leery based on the negative reviews, but I'd just returned a pair of $35 knock-offs with horrible sound, and wanted something for workouts.  I've used the earbuds on a couple of walk/runs and once at the gym for a strength training workout, and so far, they're fantastic.  Great sound, and they stay put and are comfortable for 70 minutes.  I haven't used them yet for a phone call.  I'll update the review if something else comes up.

title: Great buy
content: Great

Hello person reading,
I have been looking into these headphones for sometime and after purchasing and using rigorously working out and everything in between. I proud to say Jabra well done. This isn't perfect but you will be happy. Before purchasing I found that some users had issues with the left earbud (it's not turned on) also the comfort level. It took time for me to get use to the fit and feel coming from Bose soundsport (super comfy.) Overall its made very well. Apple take notes really not bank notes regular notes.

title: Decent, but expensive and somewhat cheap feeling - and no USB-C!
content:
These aren't bad headphones at all. They fit comfortably, and the advertised battery life is more or less faithful to reality (4-5 hours). The sound quality is pretty good - all the music I listened to sound nice. The app is fine as well - though there's no iPad version which always irks me. Unfortunately, there are a few things I just couldn't get past.

First, they feel cheap - plastic everywhere. The case is plastic, slippery, and very lightweight, so I found myself dropping it quite often. It's a huge step down from my Zolo Liberty+ headphones which has a metal case.  The case is also microUSB, which I just despise *so* much. The case needs to be USB-C.

There's a bit of latency when watching videos; everyone has different levels of sensitivity to this. My wife is far more sensitive to seeing audio/video latency than I am, but it was just enough for me to notice. I may have talked myself into thinking it was OK the first week, but over time I bet I'd find it more irritating.

These are expensive compared to the many options available from other lesser-known brands; if they had USB-C I might have kept them, but I just can't justify buying a new device using microUSB in 2019. I returned these to Amazon.

Jabra needs to update this product with USB-C, tighten up the latency, and drop the price the $129 or less to be competitive.

title: Fits comfortably and sounds great.
content: Fits comfortably and sounds great.

title: Great sound quality (for earbuds)
content:
Pros:

These little earbuds sound better than my klipsch wired earbuds. I am no audiophile but they do have different sound signatures and these have more clarity and positioning of the audio sources in the tracks and the vocals sound more clear and less muffled and mixed together in these compared to my klipsch. Bass has more impact too.

They are extremely convenient without the need to worry about wires and they sit securely in my ears. I do need to twist them in as described in the manual.

They look much better and low profile than certain competitors on the market.

Cons:

Charging can take a loooooooong time.

Can get uncomfortable after sitting in my ears for a few hours.

Sometimes there is interference when using in a crowded metro, not sure if it comes from the electric trains/railway tracks or wireless devices other people use.

Neutral:

Decent sound isolation but still allows you to hear outside noise, regardless of which mode you set to in the app.

I have been using these in months and overall I am pretty satisfied.

title: was great until the right earbud stopped working

Less than 6 months for the right/main earbud to stop working.
contacted warranty support, but no help
******
UPDATE
Finally, after much consternation, I got customer service to respond. I had to ship both earbuds back to Jabra before they will send replacements.
I'll update again if/when they arrive.

Overall sound quality is okay. Going back to my Sony bluetooth headset....been 2 years and still works perfect till date.

title: Great product
content: Great sound

title: Best true BT headset I've ever had
content: The sound quality is great, even if it's not the active, with a good head band they stay in and the sound is great, there's some interference when around solid iron, but goes away once you're out from in between the weights. But for gym use, never had an issue of them falling out. Not really good for full face helmets -- not ones that fit tight. Half Helmets is ok, again, wearing a fitted head band will help keep them from flying off for sure. But for everyday use, at work, with the noise cancellation it's great. The mics that allow for outside sound to get in while using them is good. Takes some time to get use to them because it amplifies everything with the mics. Also make sure you use the right ear gels to fit your ear to seat better. Overall, best true BT I'll ever own and I don't need another model to compare. Just best bar none

title: Don't expect the plastic to last
content: I like most things about these (I don't get static issues like others have reported) BUT they do not cancel sound and everything feels cheap with the plastic and breaks. I don't see that these are marketed as great for noise canceling so I'm not taking points off for that. I'm taking tons off for the plastic. I have gone through two charging cases in a year because the small plastic latch breaks really easily and the headphones are useless without the case

title: Don't expect warranty to be honored.
content:
As long as the headphones work, they are good. (1) The sound is good, (2) the headphones stay in your ears while moving, and (3) the battery life is satisfying.

However, if you receive a faulty product, Jabra appears not willing to resolve the issue. My headphones stopped working properly after a short while. I have been trying to contact Jabra and get a replacement for the last 2.5 months. I filed multiple cases and sent many mails. Sometimes, I received an answer after weeks; but this answer would not resolve the issue.

Buyers should take this behavior into account when buying the product. Products on the frontier of tech, like this one, frequently have problems. If then, the manufacturer ignores warranty claims, the buyer is stuck with the faulty product.

title: Great sound, with a few issues.
content:
I've purchased the Bragi's The Headphone, Anker/Zolo's Liberty+, and now the Jabra's Elite Active 65t. The Elite Active 65t overcome issues i have experience with both the Bragi and Zolo earbuds. They come close to having my full wish list of features, but don't have everything.

Pros:
1. Great sound quality.
2. Great battery life.
3. Comfortable. Took me about a week to get used to getting them seated perfectly when putting them in my ears, but no problems after that.

Cons:
1. Micro usb instead of usb-c for the charging case.
2. The charging case is not magnetic. Sometimes the earbuds fall out when I open it.
3. I use the earbuds to connect to my phone and laptop. When connected to both devices simultaneously, the audio focus has been an issue. When i listen on the laptop and a call comes in, or the phone makes an audible notification sound, the audio focus will switch to the phone without issue. However, it will not switch back. In order to switch back to the laptop sounds, i have to go into the computer settings then disable and re-enable the bluetooth connection.
4. Only the right earbud can be used independently. If i'm listening while at work, and the battery is getting low, i would appreciate being able to put one earbud back in the case to charge while listening to the other.
5. Color. I desire the earbuds to be all black; therefore, i purchased at Best Buy to get the exclusive Titanium Black edition. However, even then the buttons are a silver color. I would appreciate this area being black too.

title: Fantastic
content: Great product. Very happy

title: Eh...Returned.
content:
Bought these because I talk on the phone a lot.  Read many reviews on various products and tried these out.  First thing I noticed is that the sound for music is very tin-like.  Even adjusting the app equalizer did not change that.
Second issue was that they did not stay in my ears.  I know that's something the manufacture can't fit to every individual, but there's no way I could workout with these, let along just walk around without them dropping.
I really WANTED to like these, but returned them.

title: They're good, if you can get a cheaper price
content:
Overall very positive. These buds have two features which were most important to me.

1. Multi-point.  Seamless transition between two devices.  Stop music on one, play on the other, without having to re-connect.

2. Microphone.  The quality of the mic is very good, so I can use it at work during zoom calls.

Some pretty horrible design flaws IMO.

1. No magnet on the bud. So they'll just slip right out of the charger. Yay.
2. The left bud is useless without the right.  Better would be the option to use them separately to extend battery life.
3. Plastic is slippery, so it's easy to fumble them.

Battery life therefore is good, if you consider 5 hours good. I've heard that you get a very solid 5 hours though, usually a little more.

The app is pretty cool but no matter what eq setting I use, it doesn't sound all that different to me :)

Comfortable, very secure fit.

title: Brilliant

Even though it may say connected but when I start playing Spotify it does not play any sounds.  I have to turn my bluetooth connection off and then turn it back on to reconnect then sounds would start to play.  A lot of times it disconnects for no real reason.  When I'm on Youtube sometimes it just looses the sound during the middle of a video.  Noise cancellation is also below average.  I don't use this every day so gonna stick with it for another while then switch to another brand.  Definitely regret buying this.

title: Customer Service from Hell
content:
These headphones have good sound quality, so I was disappointed when the left one began sounding much louder than the right. This rendered the unit pretty much unusable. Some googling revealed that this is a common firmware problem; I tried the solutions, but they were temporary, and the problem returned.

I wrote customer support; they responded with a list of suggestions I had already tried. Wrote again: no response. Wrote more times, still no response. So I had to call. After a twenty minute wait, I had something else come up and had to hang up. Tried to call again; another twenty minute wait and got through. The gentleman promised to send a replacement right ear bud if I filled out a form. Filled it out, and they said they would be in contact soon.

A week and a half went by, then I got an "order summary" for a right ear bud. That was three weeks ago. It still hasn't shipped. With a new baby and a new job, I haven't had time to spend another twenty minutes on the phone just to be told to wait another week.

So in sum, it's been a month since my nearly $200 earbuds went on the fritz, and the customer service seems designed by the actual devil to force every claimant to give up in frustration.

title: Great except volume control defect with iOS - great for Android devices
content:
These are well made, comfortable, and sound great.  However on an iPhone (7s with iOS 11 and 12) the headset volume defaults to a very loud minimum volume.  The headset volume can't be operated independent from the device so lowering the volume on notch on either from minimum mutes it.  You only have choices of mute, loud, or even louder.

By contrast on an Android device minimum volume is very low and you have a lot of control over the various levels between headset and device volume.

I wanted to like them, but not being able to turn the volume down on my main device is a deal breaker.

Lol). But of all the in-ear buds I’ve bought, these easily have the best fit, sound, water resistance, and overall “enjoyment factor.”  I like them more (for fit) than my new Powerbeat Pros (which actually hurt a bit after awhile because of the plastic hook). Jabra has been at this for a long time and it shows. These sports-oriented earbuds are worth every penny. Mine come with me to the gym all the time. They sync flawlessly with all of my iOS and Mac devices too. The software’s good. The iOS app on the iPhone has quite a few adjustments available and I especially enjoy being able to tweak the sound via the built-in equalizer. Can’t say enough good things about these—one of my all-time favorites (wearing them now, in fact, as I type this review).

title: Jabra Elite vs. Bose QuietComfort 20
content:
I've only had these for a couple of weeks and have only used them to workout and mow the lawn.
I also have owned a pair of wired Bose Quietcomfort 20's for several years so I'll try to compare.

Connectivity:
Jabra 5, Bose 4(wired)
The Jabra connected instantly and connects every time I turn on Bluetooth on my phone.  Bose is wired so the obvious here.

Audio:
Jabra 4, Bose 5
Just about on par with Bose but you'll need to use the Sound+ app to get to a place that you like.  I like the richness of the Bose but the Jabra come very close.

Noise Cancelling:
Jabra 3.8, Bose 4.5
I don't think the Jabra's have noise cancelling but they are very close to the Bose especially when the volume is turned up.  I haven't used these on a flight yet and I'm expecting the same experience as the Bose (ie let's in some background noise).  Mowing the lawn is pretty damn close for both.

Comfort:
Jabra 5, Bose 5
I typically use medium ear buds but put the larger ones on the Jabra which helped blocked out more noise.  Jabra are very comfortable and I forget they are in my ear.  Bose is very comfortable as well and have that little ear hook that keeps them in place.  They both stay in while working out and I don't have any issues feeling like the Jabra will fall out.

Controls:
Jabra 5, Bose 4
I really like being able to press a button on Jabra for volume, pause, skip a song etc.  Since the Bose is wired, I typically run the wire under my shirt and have the phone in my pocket and control it with the in-wire controller which sits near my chest.  I wouldn't say the Bose is bad here but tapping on the ear is much more convenient and being able to do so without pulling the phone out is great.  That's the other thing, I can leave my phone out of pocket near me which is awesome.

Chewing gum:
Jabra 2.5, Bose 4.5
I like to chew gum when working out and its natural for the ear to move which affects the Jabra more with sort of a thumping sound vs. Bose which I never thought much of when chewing gum until using the Jabra where it's pretty evident.  So, I try no to chew as much.

Charging:
Jabra 5, Bose 2
I love the charging case and the fact that it continues to charge the earbuds in the case which is so much better than the Bose where you need to connect the cable in advance to make sure you have enough juice to have noise cancelling work for the amount of time you'll use them. I don't have any information on how long it takes to charge each, how long it lasts etc because I frequently charge them both and they both seem to charge up rather quickly.  However, I've forgotten to charge my Bose a few times and have to use my car connection to charge them on the way to the gym.  I don't feel like this would be the case for Jabra.

Value:
Jabra 5, Bose 3
I picked up the Jabra for 1/3 off during prime day in addition to 20% back on my prime awards card. Bose runs around $250 so for something that performs almost as well for around half the price is great value.

Other:
I can walk pretty far away from my phone to the water fountain at the gym and still have connectivity.  It does start to break up a little.  Sorry, I don't have the distance.  Maybe 75-100 feet.

I haven't worn my Bose since I've had these so that's probably saying something.

title: Not so great
content:
I really did want to love these earbuds but there are couple of drawbacks that I just can’t accept considering the premium price tag. There are times only one earbud provides sound and the only way you can get them both working again is to put them back into the charger then remove them again. That’s not convenient while on the go.

The other very big issue for me was toggling to the transparent mode. You’re supposed to be able to push the button on the side of the earbud to stop the music and hear people attempting to speak with you but I often found it very inconsistent and was forced to completely remove one earbud to have a conversation. I had other minor glitches with the app and for that reason I returned them.

I now have my fingers crossed waiting on the arrival of the Sony WF-SP700n true wireless ANC earbuds. The problems with these don’t justify the price tag.

title: Great Quality. But comes with pain, and connectivity issues.
content:
These are great true-wireless earbuds; they really are. I would agree with people when they say that these are probably the best on the market. But I have some qualms with their design that I just cannot get past.

1. They hurt my ears.
In over 2 decades, I've never worn headphones or earbuds that actually physically hurt when I wore them. But these do. The form of the casing presses against the cartilage around my ear (anti helix, anti tragus, and tragus) that ends up hurting like hell after an hour or so. It's fine if I don't adjust or move them (or press the buttons). And, yes, I'm sure that I actually have them in correctly.

2. Connectivity.
This seems hit or miss. Some people say they have great range and connectivity, others don't. I was one of the ones that don't. Paired with a Samsung S8 (so both the phone and headphones have BT 5.0), they can't really go that far. In addition to that, when "switching states" (i.e. loading a new YT video, turning off music, etc.) the audio in the right bud just cuts with a click for about a second (this includes the audio pass-through). Even then, sometimes they'll just both go in and out even with my phone two feet in-front of me.

But, hey, the audio quality is fantastic and they feel super stable in your ear. Plus, audio pass-through is a wonderful thing. If they weren't $160 I would take some sandpaper and grind down parts of the casing to make them feel better in my ear, but I really don't/shouldn't have to do that.

title: Too good to be "True"
content:
They're comfortable, even after hours of constant wear. I don't listen to metal, but if I did, I'd feel confident head banging without losing them. The battery is said to last five hours, but I've never ran them past yellow. They pop into a conveniently sized case, with insanely fast charging speed. Their sound is nice and balanced. I'd say it's on par, or even superior to comparable buds with a wire. Which brings me to the most important thing, the freedom of wireless earbud technology. From yoga, to snowboarding, hiking, to cooking, cleaning, to writing, I've found the lack of wire on my Jabra Elite Active 65t's to be absolutely liberating.

Not only does music sound great, but podcasts come through clear as day. And in true Jabra fashion, the former headset company has produced another conversation capable earpiece. When a call comes through, all have to do is say “yes” to accept it. You can track them if they’re lost or stolen. And they’re dust and water resistant! The features are endless.

After three weeks of ownership, I love them, there's just one problem. They don’t work half the time! Okay, maybe it isn’t half the time, probably more like a quarter, but all too often, when I pop my Jabra Elite earbuds in, they get stuck on “connecting…”. I’ve noticed that the issue is more prevalent in congested areas. Trying to connect in the lift line? Forget about it.

I keep expecting there to be some software update to offer a fix, but I haven't been able to check, because the "Jabra sound+" app is completely useless. It connected the first day and hasn't recognized my earbuds since. It’s hard to call these things Elite, when at times, they’re nothing more than jewelry. Oh yeah, they're also discreet. But that doesn’t matter when they won’t produce sound! I have no doubt that these things will one day be awesome, but it seems to me that their current software just isn't quite ready yet.

So, if you're on the fence about wireless earbuds, I'm not quite sure what to say. On the one hand, my Jabra Elite Active 65t's are amazing, they're liberating, so much so that I can't see myself ever going back to the wire. But on the other hand, they're frustrating, less than reliable, and far from cheap. My guess is that these first-generation buds were rushed to compete with the likes of Apple's Pods, and that both their price and consistency will improve with time. I want to advise you to wait, it's the wise thing to do, but the freedom of these things (when working) is almost too good to be true. I could return them, but I'd rather listen while I wait. If only (slightly more than) half the time.
MORE at tryingandwriting.com

title: A+ for these Elites
content:
The best Bluetooth earbuds have in my household. Trust me, I've gone though many, many kinds. No name cheapies, big brands, different styles, price points, ect. But my search has ended! Enter the Jabra Elite 65t

Audio quality is excellent! Crank up the volume and enjoy the bliss of, dare I say, perfect quality? Yes I do. They have nice range, and everything sounds amazing. No distorted audio at all. Volume is plentyy loud enough and will definitely kick.

Build quality is as I'd expect in this price range. They don't feel like they'd break if I dropped one. They have a nice size to protect from a regular drop I suspect. With the nice build quality, comes the comfort. These elites don't hurt my ears after hour long sessions. One of the biggest gripes I've had with past buds.

Another plus is the perfect Bluetooth connection.  No signal cutting out, and songs going choppy here. I've had that before with cheapies. Big win there.

The case itself is sleek and seems to be durable as well. I am confident it will protect my buds from normal daily travel. The case may scratch up, but it's doing it's job. The case closes nicely and should also stay closed until you open it. No weak lock here. So your buds won't go missing

Price point is iffy. These are the most expensive I've ever bought. I am happy with them though, and you do get what you pay for though. I doubt price is much an issue these days, with all the Airpods I see in people's ears. I'd bet my money on the Jabras over Airpods anyday. You won't regret it.

title: I don't regret pulling the trigger for these true wireless earbuds
content:
Pros:
-Small size of the earbuds give a low profile.
-Sound quality is above average, and having a built-in equalizer helps emphasize certain audio ranges. Although, it admittedly lacks a satisfying bass.
-Battery life is amazing, where I usually get ~4-5 hours at 50% to 70% volume.
-Charging case allows the earbuds to charge relatively fast.
-Background noise feature allows me to be aware of my surroundings.
-The design of the earbuds and its ear tips allow them to be stable inside of the ear and not require earbud wings in order to prevent them from falling out.
-Earbuds are light-weight and don't cause ear fatigue when wearing them for a few hours.
-Bluetooth 5 allows for quick pairing and extended range (they pair up before I even get them into my ears).

Cons:
-Biggest problem I have with these earbuds are the battery drain it appears to have every so often. After taking them out of the case, it would drain to ~70% in less than an hour. This issue has happened a few times. After it hits the ~70% mark the battery drain returns to normal/expected time, where it then reaches the advertised 5 hours of battery life.
-The charging case itself is not exactly small, but also not exactly large. If placed in a pocket, it will definitely make a noticeable bulge.
-Often makes a high-pitched hissing sounds when taking them out of the case. Not too bad considering the hiss is short lived.
-Noise distortion happens occasionally as a result of environmental factors (happens at certain locations at my uni).
 -MicroUSB charging. I don't want to carry around an extra cable to charge the case. Jabra should utilize USB-C next time.

Notes:
-Common issues seem to be the left earbud not working after a certain period of time. So far, both of my earbuds work perfectly fine (~2 months after purchase).

I would definitely recommend these earbuds to anyone who's looking for true wireless earbuds. They are comfortable and provide great sound. The issues it does have are minor and usually aren't isolated to this specific brand. Overall, they are a 4.5/5.

title: L/R audio balance issue Jabra can't or doesn't want to fix.
content:
I want to rate these 4 or 5 stars, but...

I bought a set of the Jabra 65t Elite at a local big box store.  They worked great for about a week or so - great fit, great battery life, good sound, ability to use just right earpiece, loved the Alexa/Siri activation feature.  I then installed the iOS app and performed a firmware upgrade.  After the upgrade, almost all the audio now only comes through the left earpiece.  Have tried resetting the set.  Searched message boards and found this to be a known problem that Jabra only give Tier 1 support type answers to, barely acknowledging that the problem exists.  Have since tried recommended fixes and hacks to resolve the issue, including uninstalling/reinstalling the iOS app, changing the language and installing two more firmware upgrades that have come out since.  Still no resolution after many months.  If I has known that is issue existed before looking for something to buy, I probably would have avoided these.

title: A disappointment
content: Garbage, then need to go back in the lab with these,take off market

title: Shout out to JABRA Support!
content: I ordered these several months ago and they worked fine until a month ago something went awry. The headphones would no longer play 3rd party app sound for more than a few seconds. I went through all the customers support suggestions. No dice. They finally asked me to send them in. I did, shipping was free, and 10 days latter they sent me a new set that work perfectly! Also, I love these headphones. Anyway, Jabra has a customer for life now. Well done!

The pods don't sit well in the case and mine stopped charging after about a month of light use because of some tiny broken thing.  Jabra support told me to reset the software to fix the broken part.  Not helpful.

title: Quality Product
content: The earbuds are very well made. They pair very easily. The sound quality is great. The only issue is that they are a little big for the inside my ears.

title: Easy and Functional
content: A great quality pair of ear buds that works just like any other pair of earbuds minus the cord. Pair effortlessly with my iphone, and the "hear-through" feature is nice when I'd like to still semi be aware of my surroundings while listening. I can pause at the press of a button on the right ear bud and have conversations without taking the ear buds out, acting as a semi hearing aid. They fit great and on my runs never worried about them falling out (I use the small sized ear cushions that came with it. They come with small, medium, and large sized cushions)

title: Best truly wireless earbuds out!!!! PERIOD!!!!
content: These are amazing best on the market I have had them all. Apple's Sony Bose. These are the best and with the hear through feature which uses the speaker to hear the outside sound so you dont have to take them out to hear anything I love that feature and if you dont want to hear it turn it off. The app is awesome can customize anyway you want. Dont know why these idiots on here dont like it probably because they are to stupid to use them right. title: The best

title: great use but shoddy case hinge quality. breaks easily (two in 1 year)
content:
I've had two pairs since August 2018. i love using them, the tight ear-fit to block out other noise. I got it because Wirecutter recommended it.

Two issues which are dealbreakers

1. The case is poorly designed. I've broken the clasp that clips it open/closed on two bases with daily usage for the past 14 months but I am not hard on it at all. The Airpods are magnetic to prevent this kind of issue. now the case stays open and the buds fall out or won't charge. have to use a rubberband to keep it shut and works *most* of the time. airpods by design dont have these issues.
2. Can't call switch - when call switching from iPhone, sometimes the audio becomes completely messed up. to fix it, you have to hang up the call and call back. (not as much of a dealbreaker)

airpods sit in the ear without a proper seal so really bad to listen to with lots of ambient noise (unusable in propeller planes)

title: Awesome
content: Best true wireless earbuds I've ever used.

title: Best Alternative to AirPods!
content:
** This review is written after 7 Months of usage**

One of the issues with writing reviews is that you really need to test out a product before you can review. I can say with honesty I have tested these headphones in almost every condition: Winter in the snow, Spring Rain, while exercising in the summer heat, and even in NYC Subway with all the noise!

These headphones are great and comfortable.  I was looking for an alternative to AirPods as they hurt to wear them.  These have the Bud style in-ear which is the same as the wired headphones. Great Sound and quality, the noise cancellation works very well and dulls out the loudest noise, connects to my iPhone in seconds.

Here are a few notes to decide and take away:

- Test the headphones: You may need to swap out the ear buds for the correct size.  I found myself stopping during my  work outs as they had dropped out of my ears a few times.  Swapping them to bigger earbuds helped hold them in, you may need to use the bigger size. (I do high impact workouts like boxing so bear in mind I really move around) You also don't want to lose them so be sure to test them in a controlled environment before you start running thru the woods and have an ear bud slip out.

- Adjust the system: Downloading App to adjust your headphones is a must (Snap shot included), it helps to adjust them to your surroundings and the main activities you do. I found some settings better than others in the subway and other settings better at the gym etc.

- Clean them often: Especially if you sweat for workouts like me, sometimes the salt builds up and I forgot to clean the charging case (Pic Included)  But it helps to use an alcohol based electronic wipe.

- Charge time is fast and holds power for a long time. Plus just like the AirPods it also charges in the case.

Negative Points:

-Charging case is a snap shut case vs the AirPods Magnetic closure. Im always afraid I am going to break the darn thing or open it too hard and have the Buds come flying out. (happened a few times when I first started using them) The case is ok, but could use some engineering adjustments.

- Hearthrough mode option just doesn't work right.  (Option found in the App, pic attached). You hear everything and it makes it difficult to use especially on a phone call. I just keep it on noise cancelling and call it a day.

- Need to take both buds out quickly or only one will turn on. Some times I need to put them back and take them out to turn on both. Not sure if this is a syncing issue but the individual buds do work just like AirPods if you need them to. But when using both, you need to take them out right away or it will only activate just one Bud.

-If you are in an area where a lot of people are using wireless devices you may start to hear static interference. I had to put my earbuds back in the charging case and take them out again. It helps re-sync to the phone and clear up the static issue.

Final Thoughts: Great Purchase and buy, I have had them for 7 months (as of this review posting) with little to no issues and even the ones I mentioned are more minor annoyances.  There is an option between the regular earbuds and the athletic water resistant model. I purchased the the Active model knowing how I would use them, they cost a few dollars more (approx. $20) So I cannot state this great review would be for the regular Elite model.

title: Great, just not for me.
content: I picked these up on a whim. The functions and integrated app are both phenomenal, the battery life and sound quality is very good, above my expectations. However, the width of the earbud itself is too big for my ears and has nothing to do with simply swapping out the ear gels. The pain of wearing these for any extended period, I can only compare to sleeping on your ear wayyyy too long compressing your cartilage. Also, I have a tragus piercing therefore I can't see myself ever comfortably wearing these. Boo.

title: Not a great fit for smaller ears
content: Good sound quality. However don’t stay in my ears as well as I would like, which is annoying

title: Great headphones, wanted to give 4.9 stars.
content: Only reason for not giving 5 stars is that I can’t use either headphone individually. I’m limited to using the right one if I only want to use one of the headphones at a time. Not a big deal whatsoever, everything else about the headphones is great.

title: Jabra 65t are the best product in this space
content: While reading the reviews I see a lot of complaints about lost connectivity or overall issues with the technology.  The reality is that this technology is in its infancy.  All truly wireless headphones are having similar issues.  I would say even in this regard Jabra is the best.  If you want truly wireless headphones that never have any type of tech glitch than wait a few years to buy them.  Knowing this I place the warranty terms at the top of my priority list.  I have had two issues with my Jabra 65t over the last year and have very simply returned them for a brand new pair both times without any fuss.  I keep a pair of MPOW headphones that are 15 dollars as backups.  When I have had issues and have had to ship my Jabra's back I simply switch over to those.  Within 5-7 days I have my brand new pair of Jabra's ready to go.  Nothing in the truly wireless space compares to Jabra's quality or warranty point blank periot.

title: Beware if you get a defective product Jabra’s customer service is horrible!!!!
content: I bought this product as a Christmas gift to myself. After 2.5 months the left earbud stopped working. It has been a horrible experience getting Jabra customer service to resolve this defective product. I have had several email exchanges with jabra’s customer service giving me directions such as firmware update or rebooting the device but no real solution to replace the product. And it takes them 2-3 weeks to respond to an email. This has been the worst customer service experience ever.

title: Hurt my ears (not the sound, like they physically hurt my ears.)
content: These hurt my ears SO BAD. I had to return them. I know everyone’s ears are different so I don’t want to give a horrible review. They just were not for me.

title: Good when they worked (one day)
content:
They arrived on Thurday.  I wore them on Friday and they worked well.  Though whoever designed the case should be taken out behind the barn and horsewhipped!!  It is amateurish and stupid!!!  Once you figure out how to get the case open, the buds pop right up in the air since there is nothing to hold them in the case.  Why are there no magnets to retain them, I don't know.  If magnets are a problem, they coudl have least used some plastic grips.  It is plain amateur!

Today, Monday I used them again.  I discovered that the Left bud stopped working.  It was paired and I could see the connection flickering on and off in the app.  I did a complete reset and started over.  Still no change.  Called Jabra support and after a 45 minute wait (never a good sign), she recommended that I reset them.  When I told her I already had, she said there was nothing to do but return them for a replacement.  Actually, I am seeking a refund.
The case design and poor quality control makes this a non-starter.  If your product is not ready for market, don't sell it.  I am not your tester!!!!!!!

title: Great build quality and very good for physical activities
content: These are a game changer for me.  My biggest concern and requirement is that the earbuds physically fits into my ear and stays in my ear.  I can't use apple earphones or air buds as the design isn't conducive with my ears.  These Jabra Elite Active 65t earbuds are a phenomenal, secure, conforming fit.  They are equally well on a treadmill, elliptical, stairclimber, bike or rower.  I also lift heavy weights and there hasn't been an exercise that has caused issues with the earbuds staying in  place.  The sound quality is excellent as well as the volume control.  Battery life is fine for my usage profile...I find I need to recharge every several days with several hours of use/day.  The quality of the build is also robust....no fears of anything wearing out or breaking apart.  If I had to complain, the controls are a little tricky to use as my fingers are a little big but it hasn't proven to be an issue..  To net: the Jabra Elite active 65t works great for the application it was designed (active usage, like exercise), build quality looks great, sound is excellent (pass through is a nice feature if you need to hear your surroundings), battery life is more than adequate for moderate usage.

Returning as I write this review...

title: The latency (audio lag) of streaming video can be bad.
content: I usually would not have bought a pair of headphones for this much money.  To be able to reconsile this purchase, I thought I would be able to use them at work as well as at home.  I am in customer service and take care of customer accounts so I talk on the phone alot, multitask and also work outside in the elemets so these sounded perfect for all of that. Rain/sweatproof, 4 microphones for calls, google assitant or alexa. I would keep my phone in the back pocket at work and take calls with one earbud (right earbud only supports mono mode) and in the fist few days people said I was cutting out at times which was disappointing. The audio quality is good but not stellar and it has alot of upside and can be updated much like youre phone, tablet or computer. THE ONLY REALLY BAD THING IS I BOUGHT A BLUETOOTH RECEIVER FOR MY TV SO I COULD LISTEN THROUGH MY EARBUDS AND THE LATENCY ON THESE ARE NOT GOOD. The delay in audio is signifcant. I looked at even higher priced earbuds and it seems they all have this problem. Overall I would give these 8 out of 10. Would be 10 oit of 10 if calls didnt drop and audio lag or latency was better and now I cant use the earbuds for everything I wanted to.

title: They sound good, fit well and look good. In my opinion.
content: I love these freakin’ things. I got them about a month ago, and initially decided I wasn’t going to write a review, but MAN, these buds have earned my 5 stars. They sound great, they look great and they seem to be built well (I’ve dropped them a couple times.) I haven’t had any issues with connectivity, though I really only use it with my phone in my pocket while I’m exercising, or casual listening with my phone on-hand. title: Love these ear buds , just need more ear jel sizes
content: I've only had these Jabra elite 65t active for only a couple of weeks and so far i am really happy with their performance, the battery life is as stated around 5 hours on the ear buds and 2 more charges in the case , the sound is great once you have a good seal with the ear jels , good bass and good highs not extreme on either but very nicely tuned and you can make adjustments through the app , these wireless buds meet or exceed all that they advertise. My only con's are they don't have more ear sizes with the ear jels my ears fall in between the sizes they do send with the device, I've had other brands that send many more sizes that aren't as expensive and quality as these buds , and the other con would be that jabra should put magnets in the case to keep the buds from falling out of the charging case accidentally,  other than that i highly recommend these wireless buds Jabra have made a great set of true wireless earbuds ,I would have given them a 5 out of 5 if they had included more ear jels for the device.

title: No sound out of left earbud unless the earbuds are next to each other.
content:
These earbuds worked for about a day. Now, there's no sound out of the left earbud unless the right earbud is about two inches away from it. The volume controls on the left earbud do work. I did a firmware update and a reset and there was still no sound out of the left earbud unless the two earbuds were right next to each other. Since my ears are more than two inches apart I think these will be going back.
They did fit my ears very well and the sound was fine. Just wished they worked.

title: Very nice piece of earbuds
content: Great sound, wont fall off and prefect for gym and just office

title: Not great
content: There are several downsides to this product. The most noticeable is the rattling sound in the earbud. Compared to the Apple AirPods the bass and clarity just isn’t there. Same can be said for the Bluetooth connection. When doing talk-to-text when driving it is very few and far between that the earbuds translate what I’m saying correctly. Never had an issue with Apple AirPods. I wish I had saved the money I poured into this product and just bought a new pair of AirPods instead.

title: Can't go wrong!!
content:
OMG!!
These things are GREAT!!  Sorry Mama for ever doubting you-I'll never leave Kansas again!  These have always been reliable, and dependable, they became my go to! At half the price of my Sennheiser Momentum. (Which has been a tremendous disappointment).
Great job. Jabra!!

title: Excellent and highly portable option for music, podcasts, gym, video conferencing
content:
These are really excellent headphones... I bought them to replace my Bose Quiet Comfort 35 noise-cancelling headphones, because I was tired of carrying them around when travelling and they weren't useful for the gym.

These earbuds are extremely comfortable (as long as you can get used to the pressure fit in your ear canal), lightweight, good at blocking ambient sound and great at picking up your voice during calls. I have used them on long flights to block ambient noise and listen to podcasts and watch movies on my ipad. (One disadvantage is you can't connect them to in-flight entertainment systems, unless you spend ~$40 on a bluetooth transmitter that will plug into a standard headphone port.) They stay in fine when I'm running, and there's no cable to bounce around or snag on things.

Audio quality is acceptable, but not exceptional. If you're ok with iPhone earbuds, these are better than those, but not as good as headphones like the Bose QC35 or even high quality wired in-ear buds. But that's to be expected given their tiny size. So they're not audiophile, but in most case they do a totally acceptable job.

The size is where these really win. I can leave them in the outer pocket of my backpack and they take up essentially no room, and they're always recharging when I put them back in their case. I do wish they made the case a brighter color, however - I can see a real risk of dropping it on a airplane floor during a flight and not noticing, since it's black. I've tried to prevent that by wrapping some yellow tape on the case.

I purchased these from another retailer because they were out of stock here at the time.

title: Just don't.
content:
I bought these primarly based on reviews from reputable tech sites.. not sure I trust their reviews as much now..

I use these with a iPhone SE, which might be an issues since it does not support BT 5.0, but if your device doesn't support BT 5.0 either I advise against dishing out the cash for a mediocre product.

I had previously bought a pair of cheaper earbuds, ENCAFIRE 18 earbuds (less than half $ of these). Were they all I had hoped for, no, but they played music reasonably well. However after about 3 weeks, I ended up ditching them for the jabras for one primary reason. If my phone was in the pocket of the "slave" side, the audio would drop out quite a bit when walking around.

Same thing happened with these.

title: Works great
content: These headphones are great, I've used them every day for the past 5 months. The sound will sometimes crackle but I think that is mostly the Bluetooth connection's fault. Very good overall, and comfortable.

title: Doesn’t fit
content: Thèse headphones come with three sizes of earbuds but none of them work and they are constantly falling out of my ears. Basically unusable.

title: Great...but broke...and support is terrible
content: Works great! Easy to pair. But, left earbud stopped working. I contacted customer support via email (couldn't fine a phone number or easy way to talk to a real person). Someone emailed me back and gave me generic "reset and reconnect" instructions. So, I spent an hour doing that and didn't fix a thing.

title: Good Seller - product leaves a little to be desired
content: Seller delivered in 2 days and as promised condition (new) The disappointment came with the phone call quality on my end and the receivers end. They can't hear me unless I have both earbuds in and I have to speak at a higher volume. and hearing the person I am talking to is not very good either- very hollow sounding, even when i use the sound app equalizer to adjust the sound quality. Lots of websites rated these high, but not for me. Amazon Prime rocks as always and I am returning these to Kohl's and think I might try the AirPods

title: Great secure and comfortable alternative to Apple’s AirPods.
content: I was looking for an alternative to Apple’s AirPods, which didn’t feel at all secure in my ears. These are great. No drop outs, comfortable and secure, good sound quality (similar to my beats x) and excellent battery life & call quality, all in a truly wireless product. Highly recommend.

title: Great Sound, VERY Poor Design
content:
Like others have written, I really wanted to like these earbuds.  They sound amazing and do a good job of blocking outside noise---IF you can get them in your ears just right AND IF they decide to stay in your ears.

These kept sliding out of my ears little by little as I worked out, so I had to keep adjusting them (pushing them back in) every 10 mins.  At one point without adjustment for 30 mins, one fell right out.  Returned.

title: Not for multi-device calling
content: The item pairs with multiple devices fine. However, phone calls are fully interrupted if notifications are received. Those you are talking to cannot hear you and you cannot hear them. This is a big miss. Ideally, notifications would be heard over-top of the ongoing call audio without interrupting the conversation.

title: Awesome.
content: LOVE these. They stay in well even during intense jumping workouts. Great noise isolation and sound. 10/10 would recommend.

title: Perfect!

These have the best sound quality for earbuds I ever seen. Make your own research before but this kind of thing.
There's the Jabra active app. You need to have it to take advantage of all the features.

title: The best by far
content: I rarely write reviews, but it took a lot of research and one dud purchase of the Samsung product before purchasing this set. They are awesome. Easy to use, great sound quality and common sense features.

title: They're alright

Jabra replaced the Elite 65t, but it took 5 weeks to get them replaced. I have been on the phone waiting for support to answer for over an hour. Submitted a  online ticket no response. Now I am out of 160.00 for a pair of earbuds that don't work. I will need research other alternatives  for webex/Microsoft teams conferencing calls

title: Warranty and support are sketchy
content: Purchased in November 2018 and left earbud died a few weeks ago. Not getting much support from their warranty team - buyer be ware!

title: Best pair of wireless earphones on the market today!
content: Exceptional pair of wireless earphones.  Ive tried other pairs of true wireless earphones such as the B&O E8s and each pair would cut out and loose signal or sync between the two headsets.  Very inconsistent playback and just riddled with problems.  The Jabra did not do this and has performed exceptionally well.  Sound quality is extremely good in all conditions and while they are not noise cancelling perse they do block out a lot of the ambient noise around you.  The Jabra app that accompanies the earphones provides you with enough capability to customize your experience and sound with an equalizer.  The battery storage unit is small enough to fit in your pocket and provides 10 hours of additional charging.  My favorite feature of the earphones is that they auto connect to my phone when I pull them out of the storage case and I dnever have to fumble around connecting them.  They just work! Also if you are listening to something and want to pause to speak to someone, simply pull one of the earphones from your ear and it pauses the audio until you put it back in your ear. Cool feature. Would definitely buy these again and will be getting a pair for a few family members as gifts.

Now they do not turn on or off when being placed inside the case every time I put them in I have to turn them off or turn them on when I pull them out. I have had them for less just over 3 months!!
