title: Not terrible but no where near as good as the now defunct Dash Pro
content:
I have a pair of Elite Active 65t's.  Overall I strongly prefer the dash and feel like I wasted my money on the 65t's.

They're not on the same level as a Dash Pro or even a Dash. If Bragi hadn't dumped the hardware business, I'd just buy another Dash Pro.

Cons vs. the Dash/Dash Pro:
Audio on the 65t is very tinny.  Laughably so.
Device feels flimsy/delicate.
They fall out easily when talking or chewing or on their own after a bit
They protrude further from your ears (earmuffs/industrial ear protection won't fit over them)

Pros of the 65t vs the Dash/Dash Pro:
Much faster connecting to the phone each time.
Smaller/better charging package.
I prefer the buttons to the touch.  Bragi's touch has always required multiple gestures from me.
It's an actual company that didn't lie about warranty support.  Repeatedly.  Over the course of months.  Seriously - the owners at Bragi should be ashamed.  The  company lied and stole from people.

Going to use my Dash Pros until they die and then see what's on the market at that time.  I use my 65t's as a backup only.

title: Great pair of wireless earbuds.
content: I have been wanting a good pair of wireless earbuds and I did not like the Apple EarPods. I found many reviews stating these were one of the best pairs available for the features and sound quality. They sound great, fit great, look great, and have great features as well. So far I’m very happy with my purchase.

title: Great purchase
content: My husband is totally pleased and loves how the cancel out back ground noise.

title: 'Active" headphones not compatible with smart watches
content: Just spoke with both Garmin and Jabra customer support.  Should have done so before purchasing.  Jabra headphones are meant for computers, tablets and phones.  They are not compatible with Garmin products nor are they meant to be used with Smart watches.  At best these worked if I kept my watch close to the headphones.  They would cut out if my hand dropped down by my side.  Now they will not even connect to my watch and when they do connect they disconnect almost immediately.  Returning these now.

title: Awesome until the crackling starts
content:
This product is awesome, until you start hearing crackling noises in the left earbud.

Apparently this is a common problem; my first one had this issue immediately but I figured it was a fluke. The replacement worked flawlessly, so I bought the Active version (this one) and it was great for two months. Today it started with the crackling noise in the left piece, and it's not going away.

Read other reviews; the problem isn't just me. The product is great but the quality control is absolutely awful.

title: Love It
content: It is just as I expected and more. Wil be using for my workouts.

title: Not the best workout headphones
content: I love the sound quality but these headphone won’t stay in my ears to save my life. ESPECIALLY when I’m working out which I start thinking what’s the point ??!!

title: Wont last more than a couple of months
content:
Summary: Dont buy them

These earbuds worked amazing for first few months of use. At first they hurt my ears to wear for large lengths of time but my ears got used to them. After that more and more problems such as connectivity issues and balance started to appear. To elaborate, when i took the earbuds out of the case to use for a minute or two they would not play at all or the audio would skip A LOT. I would have to manually disconnect the earbuds and reconnect them in the Bluetooth menu. This sounds like a minuscule problem but after awhile it gets annoying not being able to right out use them when you take them out of the case. The balance issue came after, and that entailed the right earbud slowly losing volume in comparison to the left until it was at a VERY noticeable 10% of the left earbuds power. Looking it up it seems to be a common problem that Jabra knows about and have "attempted" to fix in an update but it hasn't worked. Various remedies to this problem i have found online haven't worked either so i'm stuck listening to all my media focused to the left. Very disappointing in the longevity of the product as apart from these big problems i like them very much.

title: Better than any others I've used
content:
Pro: True wireless, good fit, Sound is great, Battery life
Con: Connectivity can be difficult with different devices, volume controls take getting used to

title: Great fit for ears
content: Great product. Easy fit for ears. Great for running.

title: Not recommended if you sweat a lot ( weightlifting)
content: I had to return the headphones: if you sweat a lot in the gym not recommended. Sweat kept making them slip off my ear. All I used them was for weightlifting and they wouldn’t stay in.

title: Purchased these as a compliment to Apple Airpods
content:
These new earbuds have exceeded expectations. I purchased these as something I would use during my commutes on the loud train, but now use these everywhere as the sound and noise cancelling is so much better than the Airpods.

I would recommend to anyone needing to invest in new audio equipment.

title: Best ear buds.
content: Product works great!

title: My husband LOVES these. A+++
content: I bought these for my husband for Christmas after doing a lot of research and reading so many reviews. I could not be happier with my purchase. He uses these every single day. He loves the sound quality and the fact that they charge in the case. He actually uses one at a time while he is working to listen to audiobooks and podcasts. This allows him to work and be available to sounds around him and it also lets him listen all day long. When one earbud needs to be recharged he simply switches them out. He uses them for phone calls as well and said the sound quality is great. Try these, the reviews do not lie. You will not be disappointed.

title: Hurt my ears
content: Hurt my ears

title: Single eabbud use is limited
content: These are great ear buds. My only and main issue is that I like to use a single ear bud in my left ear. These only allow single right ear use.

title: Buy these!
content: Great sound.  They connect every time.  Good amount of battery life.  I wear these everywhere:  In the car, office and outdoor runs.  They never fallout and are super comfortable.  Best ones I’ve found for the price.  Sweat doesn’t seem to bother them, but I wouldn’t run with them in the rain.

title: Virtually no static.
content: This is my fourth truly wireless earbud and my search stopped with this one. These are amazing, specifically for their insanely low noise floor. If you hate how much static the JayBird’s have, these are probably your solution too.

title: Finally found truly wireless headphones without compromises
content:
I've gone through many (and I mean many) headphones that work 1) in the gym without falling out on things like bench press 2) work without falling out when running 3) have good audio call quality.

Prefacing the review by saying I previously had the Zolo Liverty+ and sent them back, mostly due to the case and not good fit in the ear. Aside from that, I've used many other headphones like the BeatsX, Jaybirds etc.

My review specifically looks at these three use cases and hopefully, it's helpful to people in similar situations.

1. Gym work
These are the first headphones that actually stay in place using the bench. Even without the comply tips (only available in small size), the little tips stay in place really well. I don't sweat a lot so haven't tested that 'issue', but I've used them for different types of workouts and they have stayed in well.

Sound quality is in the 'good enough' category. As they get a decent fit on my ears (your mileage may vary), the sound and bass come across quite well.

2. Running
Running with earphones is usually where most fail. The 65t's worked surprisingly well and I barely had to touch them on a 5 mile run. The tips may start to move if they got more sweaty, but the angle of the microphone helps to secure them to the ear lope and aids the fit.

One downside - as the fit is quite good, I do get the 'boom boom' when I run. As each foot hits the ground you can 'hear' it in the earphone. It's not a deal breaker but definitely a negative.

3. Audio calling
I mostly use my cellphone at work, and so far they've been working great. I keep them in front of me and when I get a call in I attach just the right and answer it. Callers say they have no issues hearing me. Experience on iPhone and Android seems similar.

I've not commented on the battery life, case, etc as others have done a good job there. Overall, for my use they are working great.

title: My ear buds of choice over Sony and Bose. Here's why:
content: I've been using these Jabra Elite 65t earbuds for two weeks now to give them a fair run before expressing an opinion. In my mind, the best measure of a product is to ask, if you own several competing products, which one do you find you consistently reach for, use and leave the house with. I've appreciated my Bose Quiet Comfort noise cancelling headphones especially during noisy airplane flights. Enjoyed the surprisingly premium sound of the Sony WF100x/BM1 wireless bluetooth buds and the light, waterproof utility of the lower cost Sony WI-SP500 bluetooth buds. But these Jabra Elite 65t buds have become my new favorites that I use every day now to the exclusion of the others.  Here's why. First is their lasting power. They can be used constantly for a full 5 hours without a recharge which raises the bar for wireless ear buds. Then after the charge is finally depleted they can be recharged in their case, twice, for a full 15 hours of listening before needing to recharge the case that night. Second big plus is the fit. Many ear buds I've tried or owned feel like they're always about to fall out of your ear so you modulate your movements accordingly. These come with several inserts to try, but the ones initially attached fit my ears perfectly. Everyone's ear anatomy is unique, of course, so your impression might vary. But the body of these seem like they were custom molded to my outer ear shape. You insert them and give them a quarter twist so they seat effortlessly and so comfortably I can easily forget they're even there. Fitting so well into the ear canal, they naturally eliminate most ambient noise and require less power to push them since the sound is routed directly into the ear canal. There's an app you can download that also allows you to slightly vary the amount of ambient noise allowed in so if you're on public transportation or say a flight, you won't miss an announcement or PA. There's a rudimentary equalizer in the app that actually does work to tailor your sound somewhat. At the moment, I'm streaming from an Amazon Prime Music play list and the base, depth and soundscape, at least to my non audiophile ears is incredible. Music can be paused by pressing the center of the right bud. Adjust the volume by pushing the left or right side of the left bud which is made more tactile by two small bumps, one on each side. The app let me know there was an update to the buds available, which I downloaded to the case and then the buds updated once inserted in the case. A purple light on the case flashed until the update was complete  and then a green light was displayed. As for the case, it's almost half the size of the Sony WF100's and has more ergonomic  curved edges so is even skinny jeans pocket friendly. The case is smooth and feels both protective and very sturdy. The one negative of that case is it's a little difficult to open but I suppose that should eliminate ill timed openings that might release the buds into your pocket or bag. It's recharged via the included USB cable. A full charge is said to take about 2 hours. To sum it up then. Likes: great battery life, exceptional moulded fit in the outer ear and ear canal, excellent sound reproduction and volume...I never need to go above 50%, a functional phone app with usable though basic equalizer, connection is very solid rarely having any hiccup, operation for voice calls has also been clear on both ends and solid, sturdy and very compact storage and charging case, . The music also automatically pauses when you remove a bud from your ears. Dislikes: It might actually tune out too much ambient noise, so I don't wear them if I'm doing something that requires being aware of your surroundings for safety sake. Sound reproduction is an individual preference and these aren't audiophile experiences obviously, as high end Sennheiser or Sony over ear earphones. But for their intended use, these are the buds I carry with me and use every day now. Highly recommended.

title: Awesome for music, awful for calls
content:
On my 2nd pair of these, hoping the call quality issue would have been resolved but nope.  Anyone on the other end of the line can hear literally every little noise over my voice.  I've tried adjusting every setting in the sound+ app but nothing seems to work.  I can hear the person I'm talking to great but they can't hear my voice at all if there's any background noise

I have these paired to a Pixel 3.  On the flip side, listening to music is pretty much flawless with noise cancelling enabled.

title: Good sound quality. Poor Bluetooth connection. Needlessly complex
content:
I was told review after review that these earbuds are the promised land of true wireless Bluetooth headphones. We're not there yet. The android Jabra apps, which are supposedly both required to operate the headphones are needlessly complicated, and somehow inhibit basic functionality (when my headphones are synced as a media device is expect them to play media playing in my device). They allow setting up numerous profiles, for differen0t atmospheric sounds conditions. How these actually equate to usage totally escapes me, and obfuscates the features of the earbuds (I can never tell when I can and cannot enable 'passthrough' mode).

As far as Bluetooth goes, I get frequent sound gaps/clips due to interference, or because these basically require line of sight to work effectively. God forbid I want to keep my phone in my pocket while listening to music.

Physical construction and sounds quality is good, though. Microphone clarity is impressive, and the battery life in the charging case is extensive.

When these earbuds work, they work well. Unfortunately, that is only ~60% of the time and the Bluetooth, and app configuration leaves such a terrible impression that their use is overall frustrating.

Update: I've updated my score to a 3 because I was able to improve the bluetooth issues with settings, but the score remains lower due to the very poor experience I've had with customer support. Customer support took on average 5 days to respond over email, never attempted to assist in debugging issues (didn't even ask what device I was connecting them to..) and only answered my questions about the return process after I badgered them on email and twitter. Fortunately I was able to improve the bluetooth connection after digging through forums and was able to fix the media playback issues, and at least improve the bluetooth connection (see my reply to this comment).

title: Finally!!!!!
content:
So I've been using these about 3 months now and so far they have been wonderful!!!  I'm really shocked to see only 3.5 stars for these so felt the need to put in a good word for a good company.  I use my earbuds for exercise and I am a notorious earbud killer.  Most of them are manufactured very cheaply and designed to fail or become outdated in a short period of time.  I've had B&O (nice sound awesome customer service but continually break), Jaybird, Powerbeats, and the most recent Samsung IconX version 2; which failed after 2 months and warranty never sent me a replacement.  Samsung also has HORRIBLE to non-existent customer care.  They will help you but it takes 10 calls and repeating yourself over and over.

Enter Jabra Elite, Sounds great with right earpiece, stays in my ear, pairs quickly and easily with my phone.  Easy skip tracks and adjust volume.  Like having access to Google Assistant and for me most importantly BUILD QUALITY.  No fail so far and I've been running in the Hot Texas sun for 3 or 4 months.  Also, don't tell Jabra but I dropped the earbuds from a 3 story floor hearing them crash to the hard concrete.  I knew I was going to be buying a new headset.  Well I found them all in one piece!!! Nearly zero damage.  My next thought was that the sound would be off.  Put them in my ear and would never know this happened.  I can't say how happy I was.

In the past I've owned cellular phones stores and can say that back then and even today Jabra's customer service is excellent.  If you believe in supporting companies that truly back their products Jabra is hands down the winner for the price point.  (B&O does very well too)  They get the issue fixed promptly as they recognize your loss of use of the product.  Very good job and thank you Jabra.

title: Sound quality is good. Volume is horrible.
content: Sound quality is nice and clear and Bluetooth pairing is smooth. I personally don’t think the bass is impressive, especially for the price. However, the most disappointing quality of the headphones is the volume limit. I know this a safety feature but these are by far the quietest earbuds I have ever owned. This feature alone has led to me regretting buying the product. Also, there’s a white noise that I can hear out of the left earbud at low volumes which makes listening to podcasts unbearable.

title: Left Ear Bud Fails
content:
Received the Jabra Elite 65T ear buds as a  present last December. For several months they were awesome, great fit and sound. Stayed in my ears perfectly while walking, finally a product that met all my needs. Now, the left ear bud quit working. Support team while slow to respond, did and offered steps to correct the issue. Unfortunately these steps did not work.

Back to square one.

title: Long play time
content: One ear or two great everthing.

title: I was skeptical, but they're awesome!
content:
Really, how are these things going to actually stick in my ear and not fall out?  Well, they do.
the sound quality is WONDERFUL!
the engineering to pause your music or podcast when you take one out is pretty cool (and it restarts it if you put in back in within 60 seconds)

Also, I'm a small person, so many times the "fits most" stuff is too big for me, and these are very comfortable in my ears

size
feel
totally wireless
Case has several charges in it
The case has a closing lid

CON
The case can be a little difficult to open the first few times
no audible warning that the battery is getting low, or is critically low

They are definitely worth the money

title: Great product hampered by high price and questionable quality (disldoged magnets issue)
content: Great product hampered by high price and questionable quality.  Like many others,the auto on/off feature when removing and returning to the case was not working.  This stopped working after owning these for about 8 months.  After researching the issue, I came across a comprehensive thread online that described the problem and the fix with pictures and a lot of detail.  Rather than try to deal with a warranty return/repair, I made a self-repair.  The issue is that the magnets in the case that trigger the auto on/off when the earbuds are placed in the case become dislodged and no longer function properly.  To repair, I removed the base that holds the earbuds from the rest of the case, and reinserted the magnets using adhesives to keep them in place. The fix worked, but the base tore a bit when removing from the case due to the adhesives that were used. It took a lot of force to separate one from the other.  It sounds like this is a common problem and, hence, my comment about questionable quality.

title: Fantastic. First wireless earbuds that just plain work
content: Fantastic.  First wireless earbuds that just plain work.

title: The first pair of earbuds that come very close to perfection
content:
I wish I was capable of doing a better review of these really intriguing earbuds, but I've been disappointed to learn that none of the wireless devices that I own are capable of allowing me to hear what these sound like really pushed. In each device that I tried I had the sensation of their not being properly pushed. Even at maximum volume I felt like they were quieter than I preferred. There are a couple of reasons for this. One is that with truly excellent earphones, the sound is often so clean as to allow higher volumes without stressing the ear. That was certainly the case with these earphones. I felt like they were better than my devices. I have a Toshiba Satellite gaming laptop, an Amazon Fire tablet (latest version), and a Samsung cell phone that is so old that it is crying to be replaced (I feel, however, that I've been permanently pushed out of the smart cell phone market - the prices have gotten so absurdly out of hand that I simply refuse to buy another - seriously people, we've reached the point where you either have to sign a long term contract that you can't get out of or you have to pay nearly a thousand dollars for a phone, which is further than I'm willing to go any longer - we are essentially being asked to buy and keep current either a laptop or desktop computer [or both!], a tablet, and a smart phone, and of the three, I've found the smartphone to be the one I can most easily do without). None of these have quite the sound card that I would like. That said, these earbuds provide a remarkably clear sound. While I didn't get a deep bass sound listening to several of my favorite alt rock bands, I found that listening to several classical recordings on provided a wonderful clarity. While I spent most of my life on the cutting edge of rock music, I am just old enough that I was never able to enjoy or appreciate most rap artists. I even wanted to, especially after reading Jeff Chang's essential CAN'T STOP, WON'T STOP: A HISTORY OF THE HIP-HOP GENERATION, but even after listening repeatedly to the Danger Mouse mash up album THE GRAY ALBUM, I have failed to find what is compelling about rap. I don't doubt that it can be great (just as I also do not doubt that there is little good in all those booty rap numbers). But the reason I bring up rap is the fact that there is so much inner detailing in the music that I think I could listen to rap and get all the lyrics, something that I don't even manage to do in rock. The clarity in these earbuds is striking. I listen to things constantly with these, nearly all on my Kindle Fire. I listen to a bunch of Youtube videos, catch up on TV episodes on the CW online, watch various things on Netflix and Amazon Prime, watch a few shows on FOX, ABC, NBC, and CBS online, and listen to a ton of things on Spotify. The great thing about these earbuds is that I simply forget I am wearing them. I fall asleep wearing them and wake up seven hours later, with them still nicely in place with no fatigue or discomfort.

Let me put it this way: these are both the best sounding earbuds I've ever had, but just as importantly they are the most comfortable.

I also want to praise the case that these come in. I've had a number of pairs of wireless earbuds and a major problem I've had is having the two become separated or having one of them sustain damage. The case for these earbuds is the most protective that I've seen. But it is also the most convenient that I've seen. You can easily put the case in your pocket and carry them around for hours without really noticing that they are there. The literature that comes with the earbuds claims that they last 5 hours, but I've easily gone 8 hours. Now, there is a chance that as they age it will drop to 5 hours, but this one of the few times when the product has outperformed what the manufacturer has claimed for them. The case also is a recharger, so that when you store them as you go from one location to another, the case recharges the earbuds. I love that when you put the earbuds in the case and hook the unit up to a USB cable, it charges both the case and the earbuds.

I have for some time now been a pretty severe critic of wireless earbuds, but these are the ones that have changed my mind. As a reviewer for Amazon I often get earphones or headphones or earbuds that I simply don't need, so I'll give them to my daughter or my brother or another relative. But no one is getting these earbuds but me. Each night when I go to bed I take care to hook up to my USB 3.0 hub that I keep on top of my night stand. I put only a few crucial items on them hub, but now these earbuds have earned a permanent place on top of my night stand. In short, if you need a pair of wireless earbuds, I can't think of a single pair that I recommend more strongly. A huge thumb's up.

title: Over priced poorly engineered.
content: My main issue was the earphones fall out if you sweat while running or cycling. Secondly the max volume is not loud enough when cycling due to wind noise. Poor product for a steep price. Would not recommend. Contacted company via email was told no solutions to earphones falling out.

title: Headphones failed
content: I bought this for a friend of mine and gifted him on his birthday. He lives in India and for some reason the headphones stopped turning On- I don’t knkw what to do

title: Very good earbuds
content: I've tried a bunch of headphones and these have been by far the best workout and wireless headphones I've had. I consistently have issues with earbuds falling out of my ears but these have not had that problem. The battery case is also great.

title: Stunning voice quality
content: What an amazing product. Absolutely stunning quality

title: Left louder than Right
content:
So I had heard good things about these earbuds from various review sites and decided to give them a try. After one day of use, literally one day, the left earbud became noticeably louder than the right. I tried to see if there was a firmware update. There was not. I tried resetting them. It did nothing. So I took to Google and found out that this is a common issue that occurs in these earbuds and Jabra has yet to address it. So sad.

I want to love these so much because of the design and the quality of music. But if they can't perform properly then why pay as much for them? Very disappointed.

title: These are amazing, support AAC and great sound quality
content:
I am surprised by the reviews! For me these are a perfect 5 stars. The sound quality is great (I appreciate good quality sound although I am not an audiophile) - I have had a variety of headphones and earbuds through the years and these rank exceptionally. I originally got these over the airpods because the airpods keep falling out of my ears and my right airpod has broken twice now, the second time was out of warranty.

These sound better than the airpods, are more comfortable, and if you have bigger ears like me - they stay in your ears! I also like that I can have multiple devices connected to it and I do not have to reconnect/disconnect.

The only slight downside is that the case is not magnetic. Also note, if you're using a Mac - mac doesn't default these to AAC. You have to download bluetooth explorer (Additional Tools.dmg from mac developer tool website) and enable AAC. This is true for every non-airpod device I've connected to mac over the years  - Macs dont seem to do a great job at figuring out codecs other than the airpods.

But I cannot recommend this enough! Get them! And they feel premium quality. I love the copper & gold.

title: Left earbud Dead upon arrival!!
content:
Ordered these on May 31st and waited for 4 weeks for this order to arrive!  Apparently the “real” release date is on July 3rd 18’. Excited to open this puppy up after the looong wait and got a Big surprise upon unboxing. Left earbud had no power when I tried to pair them. Right earbud powered on and easily was paired. Thought I just needed to charge L earbud to give it some juice but when placed in the charging case no flash of LED what so ever (Thought bubble...strange), place right earbud in charging case and a flash of LED. Left both earbud charging for a good 30 min. Proceeded to update earbuds thinking it may need the current software update to fix the problem but with NO LUCK. Continued to repeat to charge left bud but there was still no reaction or led that flashed when place inside charging case. Finally gave up and called amazon customer rep for a replacement order. Jabra needs to look into these complaints and STEP UP their current QC Procedures. I am not the FIRST  to rant about the flaws of these earbuds here on Amazon. Thank you Amazon for hassle free replacements!

AC from Cali

title: Broke after a few months, Jabra support useless
content: They were great when they worked. The right earbud became quiet and muffled after a couple months of use. I reached out to Jabra and aside from a canned email with steps to reset the firmware and repair they have been useless. I have tried email and calling and they do not answer. Don't buy if you expect the warranty to be honored.

title: Solid music and call performance, decent background sound cancellation on calls
content:
This is a review for the Jabra Elite 65t true wireless headset.

Unlike most reviewers here, my primary interest is not in the sound quality while playing music, although that’s certainly important as well.  Rather, I’m looking for a moderately priced Bluetooth headset for making and receiving calls, both in the office and while outside and in a moving vehicle.  Important factors, to me, are my ability to hear the caller on the other end, the ability for the caller to clearly hear me, and the ability of the headset to block out background noise so that the person on the other end can hear me clearly.

For the past year I’ve been using the Taotronics TT-BH026.  It’s a decent headset, with nice sound quality on my end.  However, in recent months I’m finding that I need to take more calls outside and in the car, and that’s where the Taotronics falls short.  It does a good job of cancelling background noise, but also cancels my voice in the process.  The end result is that the person on the other end of the call can’t hear me.  So, after some research, I decided to try the Jabra Elite 65t.  After a day of real-world use, here are my initial observations:

The Jabra is a clear improvement over the Taotronics. On my commute this morning I made a series of calls to my voicemail, using a) the Taotronics, b) the Jabra, and c) just the phone (Google Pixel 2XL) by itself.  When I reached the office I made a call to my voicemail using the headset on my desk phone.

End result is that the Pixel, by itself, has the best call clarity. Of course it has $1000 worth of fancy noise canceling microphones and 1.5GHz of CPU power behind it, so I'd expect that. The Jabra, and desk phone headset, were nearly equal in a quiet environment. The Taotronics had volume issues unless I yell.  And it sounds very muffled in all circumstances. When I speak fast, or not at full volume, the words blur together.  The Jabra doesn’t have that limitation.

In terms of noise cancelling, the old and new headsets are not hugely different. Background noise still comes through, but in different ways. The Taotronics kind of blurs the background noise, but slightly blurs the speech at the same time. On the Jabra the background noise comes through, but with less overall distortion of everything.  I had no trouble hearing and understanding speech on the Jabra.  Retesting in a quiet environment confirmed those results across the board.

Other things that I like:
1) The sound pass-through functionality is nice.  Some reviewers like it, and some hate it.  I like it.
2) The companion app has a number of equalizer and white noise functions that I like quite a bit.
3) I had no trouble pairing.  It was paired, and up and running, in seconds.
4) Sound quality for music is solid.  The equalizer works very well.
5) People on calls are no longer asking me to repeat myself!
6) Love the fact that they turn on, and pair to your phone, when you take them out of their charging case.  By the time you get them into your ears, they are ready to go.  Of course I only figured this out after I repeatedly turned them off while trying to turn them on after putting them in my ears.  More on documentation later…
7) Love the fact that they can be configured to pause sound/mute call when you take one out of your ear, and resume when you put it back in.
8) The earbuds are comfortable in the ear, after you experiment with the different size silicone tips.  They come pre-installed with the small tips.  I tried the largest tips, which fit better, but were a bit painful after a while.  Now on to the medium tips, which are just right.
9) LOVE that I can have them connected to multiple devices simultaneously.  As I type this, they are connected to both my phone and my computer.  I can take a call on the phone, hang up, and place a Slack or Teams or WebEx call on the computer without having to touch or switch anything.  It just happens.  Love that.

Things I’m not as excited about:

1) These little suckers are slippery!  Trying to get hold of them to pull them out of their charging case, and trying to hold onto them to put them in your ears, is a challenge until you get used to it.
2) Some reviewers have noted that you have to push hard enough on the volume buttons that you push the earbud into your ear canal.  I found the same to be true at first.  But after a bit of familiarity, I found that you don’t have to push nearly as hard if you push in just the right spot at the right angle.  It just takes some practice.
3) Ok, here’s the weird one.  Getting the charging case open takes some practice.  It’s nearly impossible to get open until you discover that you have to squeeze the sides of the main part of the case, and press upward on the lid at the same time.  I guess it’s supposed to prevent the lid from popping open accidentally.  But the documentation should tell me the secret.  Oh, the documentation.  Again, more on that later…
4) There are 4 Jabra apps in the Google Play store.  Which one works with this headset?  Hey, install them all, and try them all, until you find the one that lists the Jabra Elite 65t.  Seriously?  The documentation should give some guidance.  Or give me a QR code on the package that I can scan.
5) About that documentation… that’s the biggest issue here.  There is none.  At least none that is usable.  This is very much a “figure it out your own damned self” situation.  I’m extremely tech savvy.  I never read the documentation unless I need to.  But come on, guys, at least give me a head start here.  The booklet that comes with these things has 3 relatively meaningless pictures, and no accompanying text.  After you find the appropriate application, and dig through it far enough, you find another 3-4 cryptic pictures, and again no text.  I’m starting to figure this thing out, but it really shouldn’t be this hard.

Overall, the Jabra Elite 65t is a solid product, but with lacking informational infrastructure around it.  It’s a clear step up, has nice music sound quality, and does a decent job handling calls in both quiet and noisy environments.  I’ll be sticking with it.

title: High hopes.... low score
content: I had hoped for the best but had to return. The fit just isn't there and the only adjustment is increasingly uncomfortable silicone cups that make a loose fit an ear-canal plug that turns into a bass drum when running with them. Almost lost the right in in a sewer when it fell I get it, universal fit is not an option but the design gives zero room to dial in and the ultra slick surfaces make it worse when using for the intended purpose of being "active".  I didn't expect great sound from a b-tooth earbud so no issue there, it was as expected regardless of the hype. Voice calls were fine (I use buds as an office hands-free) but the ambient noise filtered through and I got complaints when outdoors and in the car. The advertising benefits are far better than the execution but I don't wear the advertising on a run.

title: Great sound - Do not stay put, cant wear under motorcycle helmet - inconsistent connection for me
content: I couldn't get one of them to connect consistently, so ultimately I went for a refund, but had they worked and fit my ears, sound quality was killer.  If you're already this far, consider going to ultimate ears and just biting the bullet for some custom molds. If music is important, its an investment that will reap dividends for years to come.

title: Works flawlessly and seamlessly
content: I love everything about these!

title: Great product, awesome price
content: Best wireless earphone ever!

title: Not bad, but wired products are much better.
content: I can't compare these to other wireless Bluetooth earbuds because I haven't used any. I relied on the review at the  Wirecutter website which  said these were the best they tested, so they are probably pretty good. But the sound quality is much worse than you get with wired earbuds, even the cheap ones that came with the phone. I also have some Sennheiser headphones and these are far, far better than the Jabra. But for listening while running or doing work with your hands, wireless ear buds are much less hassle. For listening while sitting down, the wired products are much, much better.

title: Pretty easy for signal to get interrupted
content:
Love that it's wireless, pairs really easily with my phone, sounds good, easy to use, love the Alexa integration.

Seems to have no buffer for the data. When listening to a podcast, if I turn my head or hold my phone under my armpit, the signal gets interrupted and the sound briefly hiccups. If I walk out of range of my phone the signal dies almost immediately. Just seems kind of weird that there's not like even a little buffer in anticipation for the signal getting interrupted like that.

title: Great sound - fit varies
content:
There are a lot of reviews out there painting the Jaba Elite 65t in a great light, and for the most part, it deserves it. I decided to return these earbuds not because of their overall quality, but because they did not fit my ears. Read on:

SOUND: 8/10
The sound is generally excellent. The earbuds have a great range - I like to test mine by playing "Limit to Your Love" by James Blake. I've found that when speakers are truly inferior you won't even be able to hear the bass at all. It deals with treble well, making something bright like Irish folk music sound almost live. As other reviewers have mentioned, in a quiet environment I noticed there was a low white-noise static particularly in the right earbud, but it didn't annoy me too much.

STYLE & FIT: 6/10
The earbuds are quite large and even though I wouldn't say my ears are small, I had a very hard time getting them to fit. It didn't make a difference which earbud tips I used, the earbud was too large to sit in my ear. I was able to get it to stay in place for about an hour if I fit them so that the microphone portion was angled basically straight downwards, which is not how they are supposed to seat and would likely have led to poor mic quality. They would work their way out of my ear in about an hour as my ear formed around them and then I would have to adjust them every few minutes or they would simply fall out. It didn't make a difference whether I was sitting still, moving my jaw, or tilting - it was really based on the initial fit vs. the ear relaxing after time. Stylistically, they do have a medium-large profile - not as much as some of the more expensive, large earbuds (Bose, Master & Dynamic), and overall didn't feel distracting. They are not particularly fashion-forward, but are on par with most of the decent ones out there.

VOICE QUALITY: x/10
I did not attempt any phone calls with these, so I can't rate the call quality.

FEATURES: 7/10
One of the best features ought to be the HearThrough, which will use the mics to pick up and amplify environmental sounds. Everything sounds a bit tinny this way, but you can still carry a conversation and feel like you're aware of your surroundings. Some noises it seems like the earbuds are fighting, actively cancelling some things out, and favoring more sudden noises or things that would sound like conversation. It's not particularly distracting, but it's obvious that they're not trying to pick up and amplify *all* the sounds around you. The controls make sense for the most part, although many of the controls are on the left earbud (volume, forward, back) and so you have to count seconds you press until you get used to it, because you can do 4 things by changing how long you press, including turning it off or putting it into pairing mode. The case is a good size, but Jabra is steering clear of the USB-C train, which is not flattering. We have a new standard, so there's not a good excuse to keep putting out microUSB products.

BATTERY LIFE: 10/10
I never drained the battery, but if you're using them typically there's no reason you should run out of battery unless you are intent on running them through a whole work day. Every time you put them in the case they charge, and the case has a great battery.

title: TERRIBLE quality control, received defects twice
content: Quality control is terrible, first time i recieved these the right earbud only worked 25% of the time and cut out, warrantied them and now i suspect (or hope) i received a refurbished pair and the left earbud has a pronounced hissing sound that nearly overpowers my music and podcasts. The earbuds are great but the quality control is completely rubbish. At least of they didn't require me to return the first pair i could have kept the working ones from each pair and combined them for a fully functional pair and sent back the defective ones. I only hope the ones i bought my mom dont end up being defective as well, otherwise that'd make jabra 0/3. Probably wont be buying Jabra's again in the future.

title: Horrible tech support
content: Good product but horrible tech support and customer service

title: Would buy again
content: Only reason sound quality gets 4 stars is I wish they where a little louder at max volume...easily fixed with sound booster app on phone...other than that, great product

title: The Left Earpiece Cuts Out After 48 Hours Use and the Warranty is Worthless
content: For the two days I could use this product it worked wonderfully. Then, the left earpiece simply stopped working.  I tried resetting multiple times to no avail. Then, I tried to contact the warranty company to get reimbursed or replace the product but was then told that they "did not cover items that were shipped broken." I've been cheated out of $200. If I can get Jabra to replace or fix the issue themselves I will change my review, but until then do not purchase this product.

title: Buy these now. Don't listen to the bad reviews.
content:
YEEEESSSS. I love them in every way. I was very skeptical because of some people's bad reviews, so I spent days wondering if I should buy these or go with some competitor. But highly trusted tech reviews kept telling me these are the best. And, well... THEY ARE.

I have asked several people on the other side of a phone call how my voice sounds and they said it sounds even better than normally. Sound quality is CRISP and connection is instantaneous whenever I take them out of their case and put them in my ear. The bud recognizes if they are in an ear or not, so when you take them out it automatically pauses. There is also the awesome ability to have "hear-through" sound so you can hear the sounds around you (even amplify them) if someone start to talk to you while they are in. This is nice in an office space because you don't need to take them out. You just pause the song (single click) and then turn on the "hear-through" mode (double-click) and you can hear perfectly while they are still in your ears. I highly recommend these to anyone looking for awesome, true wireless, high-quality earbuds.

title: I'm sold on wireless earbuds.
content: I wasn't sure if I was going to really like true wireless ear buds, but my wireless "connected" set was showing it's age and needed an upgrade. I'm pleasantly surprised at how much I like these! Great battery life and excellent sound quality. Took a few days to get used to the feeling of them in my ears, but now I can't tell at all. Plus, the sound pass through feature is amazing at the office. Great buds, I highly recommend them.

title: Exllent.. finally found a headset that works!
content: greatest headphones ever... great quality, work with my pc / phone and switch seamlessly

title: Amazing
content: So far this product is perfect. Fits perfect in the ears and the sound is super clean and crisp. I have had this product for 4 days. If something happens I will update review. So far a solid 5!

title: Great fit and sound.
content:
These headphones are great. They connect to my iPhone almost immediately and work flawlessly every time. They come with the medium ear pieces installed but I recommend you try all three sizes, I was surprised how the smaller size fit better because of there they are placed in the ear. I had trouble in the past with wireless headphones falling out, but this are rock solid and never move during multiple mile runs.

Great purchase and I can see myself going back to any other headphones.

title: Very good
content: Perfect

title: Comfortable but maybe large for some people
content: Some connection issues from time to time, but you'll get that with any bluetooth

title: Left earbud cuts out when running.
content: I’ve had these headphones for not that long at all(A week or two) and the left ear cuts out when I’m running. It’s a shame because everything else about these earbuds are great, just not good build quality I’m assuming.

title: Great buy.
content: Husband has a freight job. Used to use Beats. Loves these 1000x more. The option to use 1 headphone at a time was a nice bonus. Would buy these over and over.

title: Be careful when handling case. It’s slippery 😞.
content: The fit. Amazing. The sound = 😊 the case, too slippery. For such an expensive item, the case should be soft and or rubber coated. I see these falling out of my hand and I’m terrified. I’ve only had them one week, no complaints. Well it’s been 3&1/2 weeks. The mike picks up everything except my voice ( that’s why I really purchased it for phone covo ) the left ear has static from time to time. That’s tells me of problems to come ( it’s new ) I am returning mine and that makes me sad. I liked the look and fit of these but I don’t want headaches for such a pricey new item. I’ll just keep looking. My buying points are stereo phone chat and noise cancellation.

title: Excellent Bluetooth Earbuds
content:
I've been using these earbuds for a few weeks now and I love them more and more every day. They are well made and have a quality feel to them. I thought the fit was going to be an issue at first, but I just learned how to rotate them slightly so that they fit more comfortably in the ear. The fit is snug and I have no issues wearing these during physical activity. The sound is above average, but will likely disappoint audiophiles. The battery life is amazing and the mic works extremely well. Everybody I've talked to say that I sound very clear and loud. The features through the app are very nice and I do like the hear-through feature a lot. The touch controls are easy to use and logically placed. The bluetooth connection is excellent.

In summary, I love these earbuds and don't regret spending the extra money. I've tried cheaper earbuds which did not deliver.

title: Great sound
content: Earbuds work great, a little bulky for smaller sized ears but sound is great, works well

title: These earbuds are great in every aspect
content:
These earbuds are great in every aspect. I have yet to encounter a single issue/annoyance.

I've used Bragi's The Headphone before, and the Jabra Elite is way better than it.

- The buttons are very easy to press.
- The design is top notch (it has an expensive look)
- The fit is good.
- The UX is good (for example, earbuds automatically turn off / on when put in / taken out of the case).
- The battery life is great.
- No issues in connectivity/charging. It takes less than 2 hours to fully charge the earbuds and the case as advertised.

There is one small "con": At first, I thought there was a bug because there was no sound from the left bud whenever I power on the buds, and I had to repair the buds to my phone or put them into the charging case and take them out again. After checking out the manual, I now know that the left bud needs be turned on separately (by holding the volume down button for 1 sec).

tl;dr: Great overall wireless earbuds. Be sure to read the manual.

title: All and all great ear buds
content: The sound quality wasn’t what I was expecting but the noise canceling is very good they stay  comfortably in my ear through intense workouts and while running also the battery life was better than anticipated

title: Good Fit, Good Sound
content: I have been using Bragi for a few years now, and I still will for my swims.  While I like Bragi, the unit did not hold a charge well.  These are as advertised with the amount of time they work, and the number of charges that can be gained from the charging case.  They fit extremely well during runs and exercises like burpees and sprints.  The sound is good quality and what you would expect from a smaller earbud that fits in the canal.  What I like is that they are snug, and do not stick out like Bose.  They naturally align with the ear.

title: Love them
content: Great little ear buds. Work perfectly. Only once in a while I have to catch them if they fall out of my ears. I have little ears.

title: Yes... everything arrived as described. However:
content: Arrived in a timely manner, everything looked "factory fresh" ... The serial number for the unit had been removed from the packaging.  Because I got a such a sweet deal, I really can't complain. But... I don't have a warranty.

title: Great but for two things

1. Did not fit in left ear well; fell out when eating or talking!
2. Would not pair with Power Mac laptop; deal breaker!!!!!

However, good overall sound with a little EQ!

I'll keep them as backup for Power Beats Pro; \long battery life, never fall out, and they pair with laptop and iPhone!!!!

Ed
DJ Hack

title: Love how easily they connect to my phone
content: I’ve purchased several earbuds and these are the best

title: Poor sound quality
content: You cannot hear anything out of these. Very poor sound quality. They were more expensive than air pods I purchased for my daughter but did not compare to the sound that the air pods produce.

title: Just ok
content: Not worth the $$ it’s priced at. Average phones.

title: Terrible audio quality.
content:
I bought these elsewhere because Amazon couldn't get them to me fast enough. Overall, they are okay in fit and finish. The problem is the quality of sound can best be described as barely intelligible on the receive side, and everyone, without exception, has asked me to switch off these when on a conference call or web conference. The recorded sound from these sounds like a metallic robot voice -- and the signal breaks up constantly. I must keep any device I'm using these with, within about 12 inches, to keep them working at all.

Maybe I received a "dud set," but these things are not nearly worth the money I spent on them.

title: So far so good.
content:
I bought these to use as well as my AirPods because I thought these would be more waterproof. They're also good because they block out more noise and I can listen on the bus without turning the volume up all the way.

Heck, I have a hard time hearing when a bus goes by with my AirPods. These work much better.

title: How long do they last
content: If you get this earbuds, my suggestion is to get the added warranty protection. After purchasing this product seven months ago the volume on the right side is considerably lower than the left side. In addition, the replacement buds given with this product doesn't even fit after needing to replace them because the original were torn.

title: I would buy these again
content: I did my research before deciding on these headphones. I am very happy I chose these ones. I work out in a gym frequently (run on a treadmill, lift weights) haven’t had any issue with them. They haven’t fallen out and they stay charged for a long time.

title: Not what I expected
content:
Again I travel a lot and wanted something I could use without the cables. These were made well and I wanted to like them, but I had issues. They wouldn't stay paired and I didn't like the charger case. I don't even remember how long the battery lasted because I didn't use them enough. They just didn't work for me.

They get a lot of great reviews, but I am a detail-oriented person and I work around electronics everyday. These just didn't do it for me. Sorry Jabra lovers.

title: Not happy with these
content:
I liked the fit very nice👍🏻 But that is all I liked about them the sound was not great they didn’t get loud enough and my biggest complaint was that they cut out if I didn’t have my phone within 1 foot of them!!
Very disappointed!!!!

title: Bonus Item Included: someone else's ear wax!
content: Providing a one star rating based on the condition of my Jabra upon delivery. My Jabra Elite 65t's were packaged in original box, case/charger, instructions, charging cable, and additional sized ear tips all inside a sealed plastic bag that indicated it was "inspected by Amazon" well Unfortunately, the tips attached to the ear buds contained a extra bonus of someone's ear (crud, debris) wax, see attached photos. However after a through cleaning of all included ear tips, charging case and ear buds. I'll add a performance review after a few weeks of regular use.

title: I really wanted to like these (but couldn't)
content:
First, the good:
• Battery life is great. With pretty consistent usage, I got 2-3 days usage out of the headphones/case battery before having to recharge.
• Connection strength with phone was great. I could walk several rooms away and still have an uninterrupted signal
• Fit for me was ideal. They never felt loose, but I could wear them for hours and not feel sore like some other earbuds. Your mileage may vary, but this was great for me.
• Sound isolation / sound cancelling was a good setup. When I wanted to be isolated, they did a great job of blocking out outside noise, but when I was running or in the office, I could leave the pass-through audio on. This is a killer feature.

The OK:
• Call quality on my end was good/clear. I definitely got a few complaints of sounding distant from the other end.
• Jabra service has to run fulltime in the background on your phone.

The really bad:
• Connection to the left earbud was beyond flakey. I would leriodically get a static type noise on the left earbud that actually started to hurt my ear after the 2nd or 3rd time. This happened consistently 10-15 times per hour of wearing the headphones. No matter how many times I reset, updated the firmware, charged everything up, or whatever else, this problem was constant. This is true across several phones too (iPhone and android, both with Bluetooth 5.0 capable hardware).
• Very fiddly if the right earbud connects while the left is still in the case. You'll often have to reset them both to get them to connect to each other.

If I could have fixed the static issues, I would have loved these headphones. The form factor, battery, audio quality and other features were ideal. That painful static and shakey connection between earbuds was just too much to handle.

title: They stopped working after a week. -WORST EXPERIENCE EVER.
content:
I got my Jabra elite 65t on Black Friday,

a week after I got them the right earbud stopped working no matter what I tried.
yes, they were good for a few days but now I have no use in them anymore.
I'm frustrated and don't know what to do, I use my headphones at work, gym, car etc...
I feel like its a product you cannot trust, which is such a shame because it is an expensive product.

after buying them I feel that I got cheated, scammed, and now I need to find a new solution from the beginning.

WORST EXPERIENCE EVER.

title: Not adequate for gym. That's a no-no! Pass on them.
content: Not too bad of a product overall, however if You're planning to use these for the gym, DON'T DO IT!  Had them for a little over 2 weeks and the left ear bud started acting up. Jabra support said it's due to the metal objects around. (Hmmm Lol!)They didn't replace my product because I called after the 30days, which I understand. They offered 40%OFF on my next purchase of another Jabra product, and recommended the SPORT version for $199.99 for gym use. So like I said, the 65t model is for light duty only and definitely not for the gym. They sounded good though (when they worked) for the first 2 weeks. Bummer.... I'm rocking with the Momentums now, pricey but Jabra can't compete.

title: Get what you pay for....
content: Love these..very comfortable, sound quality is great! Very easy to use...

title: Multi device connection is great! Connects to devices almost instantly Very very solid ...
content:
Used about 3 weeks. Had to resell them.

Pros:
Multi device connection is great!
Connects to devices almost instantly
Very very solid connection
Fit is good, doesnt feel like theyll fall out
Battery life is good

Cons:

Uncomfortable after wearing it for <2hrs
Mic is not as advertised, using indoors is fine, outdoors forget about it...

* This is the main reason I had to get rid of it

title: Almost perfect wireless earbuds for sports
content: I originally started with Apple AirPods and would have probably  kept using those since they worked pretty well. I'm so glad I lost them and that gave me a reason to buy these, which I'm so much happier with them. I thought from the pictures here that the 65t would be a bit too bulky in the case to fit nice in the pocket. It's not, the case is VERY small, almost as small as the AirPod case really. Cycling with AirPods worked pretty well but running was a real struggle since the AirPods were just so hard to keep snug in the ear and I was constantly pushing them back in. These Jabra 65t DON'T COME OUT or even get loose while I'm running. They stay put perfectly and stay real snug without a doubt. I couldn't be happier with my purchase. I can't really comment on sound quality or the amount bass or whatever since I rarely listen to music on them, mostly podcasts and those sound fine. I said "almost perfect" in my subject line. These work VERY poorly when I'm inside my house. They're basically unusable in my house and the sound is pretty much constant static and audio dropouts as I move around my house. If I find a good spot and sit still, I can get good sound in my house but If I'm doing chores or something like that, forget it... they just have too much static. I still gave them 5 stars because I didn't buy them to wear around the house. They work just fine outdoors.

title: Really Impressed With These, Compared to AirPods
content:
I'm am an Apple user and spend a ton of time on the phone/conference calls, running, and listening to music.  I found the AirPods to be decent and easy to integrate, but they didn't fit snugly in my ears (no way I could exercise with them) and wasn't very impressed with the sound.  Saw these on sale over Xmas and decided to give them a shot...

- Much better fit than AirPods. Could shake my head until I'm dizzy and they wouldn't budge. (they also come with s,m,l silicone tips for the "perfect fit").
- IMO the sound is better than AirPods, and I really like the "Hear Through" feature so you can hear your surroundings with them snugly in your ear.
- Battery life is pretty amazing.  I've been on 4 hr conference calls and never had the battery die.
- The range is amazing... I roam my office and other rooms with my phone on my desk.  Only dropped signal once and I must have been 50 ft. away with 5 walls between me and the phone.
- The case charges them 3x full capacity, and they fit easily and snugly in it.
- The App is actually pretty decent and presents several modes and features which can be customized, including EQ.

In my opinion, these beat the AirPods in every category.  Battery level is displayed in the app, and they're super easy to pair.

Really, the only "downside" is you don't get that "cool" pop-up on your iPhone when you open the case... but they do automatically re-pair, so who cares.  Also, they look better, and I'm told my audio sounds better than with the AirPods.

These aren't audiophile-level earbuds.  The sound is good, but they're just great wireless earbuds.  If you want audiophile-grade sound, get something with a cord.

TL;DR

I have a set of AirPods that I haven't used once since I bought these about a month ago.  Would recommend in a second.  Can't say anything bad about the Jabra 65t's.

title: AirPods Killer!
content:
Best wireless solution in the market.  I’m glad I lost my AirPods as these are a significant upgrade on numerous levels (I’m a huge Apple fan boy so don’t usually hate on their products).

1.  Sound quality is phenomenal, fully isolating without artificial noise cancelling.  These sound almost as good as my $1k wired earbuds
2. Features are great, everything can be customized from EQ to the function of the buttons.
3. Range is better than anything I’ve used.

title: PERFECT!!
content: for me, PERFECT !!

title: After 2 months the right ear bud has a shortage in it,goes in & out ,so low u can't hear
content: Good for about 2 months, so ppl complained that my voice was going in & out during phone calls

title: Terrible syncing
content: I am incredibly disappointed in these headphones. While the sound quality was satisfactory, literally 2 weeks after the 30 day return window (via Amazon), the left earbud continuously disconnected for no reason. We tried all of the "remedies" suggested online and none of them worked reliably. They also do not rest comfortably and securely in your ears.  Perhaps if you were just lifting at the gym they would work, but if you are jogging or doing anything with a bit more movement, they aren't optimal. I miss my Bose Soundsport headset.  I would not recommend these headphones.

title: Professional design and feel...:)
content: Professional design and look and feel. fits your ears perfectly and comfortable. Depending on the sensitivity of your ears.

title: Need a little wort
content: Just don’t exspect top sound but for the price they are ok

title: WARNING
content:
Yes they are cool, yes they sound great for wireless earbuds, yes the battery is great.
BUT all that worthless because the quality is in the toilet. Left earbud on day 2 started hissing. Tried to take off the ear piece rubber and it broke. None of the others fit me so unusable. My brother has had these for over a year and gone through 2 left ear replacements. ALL FAILED. He gave up. Returned mine since its failing on day 2. Yes hissing means the speaker is going.

title: Great Headphones but poor charging platform
content:
I picked these headphones after having them recommended by a very happy customer. I have been using them for a little over a year and have been extremely satisfied until now. I had the charging case tab snap on me from normal wear and tear. I expected a premium product to have premium service, and since the product hasnt been abused, a replacement charging case to be provided. I am still working with their customer service, but so far, no luck. This experience has this overall great product sitting at 3 stars. I will upgrade/downgrade the rating based on how they handle this issue.
I truly believe that the manner in which a company handles issues is the best reflection of a product. The sound quality and features as shown below are wonderful:

Pros & Cons:
Look 5/5
Fit 4/5 - Fit perfectly in my ear, only comment is that the fit might be a hair to snug, I struggle to hear outside noise, even with the hear through active.
Sound 4/5 - Excellent sound
Charging Case 1/5 - This case is flimsy, and the tab broke on me. Since it is the only method of charging and not covered under a warranty, then you have to pay to replace the case if you want to use your headphones. I believe that a case is, honestly, part of the headphones and should be treated with the same warranty protections as the headphones themselves.
Controls 5/5 - These controls work fine for what I need. I agree that it would be nice to be able to do more with the controls but it does everything I need.
Pairing 5/5 - Honestly, I haven't had any issues. Occasional, after a couple of months, i have to re-pair the headphones but it is very infrequent.
Usability - 5/5 - I have been using these headphones consistently for a year and love them. I would estimate 4-6 hours a day of use.

I believe this is a 5 star product with a company that will do the right thing, but, until the case is included in warranty, I will not evaluate the product over 3 stars.

title: Perfect for workouts.
content: The fit is tight and snug. It isolates ambient sound really well. The battery lasts as adverstised. The build is also premium. I wished it has a usb c input. The sound is okay, the highs and mids are clear but a little bass punch is wouldn't hurt. Overall, it's an outsanding true wireless earbud.

title: Great product
content:
Overview
I have been using the earbuds both in the gym, around the house and  cutting the grass.  The earbuds work great.  They fit snugly and stay in during workouts or grass  cutting.  They connect as soon as they are in my ears.  Every once and a while there is a glitch in the audio, when my phone is in my cargo pants pockets and moving about briskly.  It is not often enough to be annoying, but I want to try to give a very accurate review.

Details:
When I first started using them, they were not  comfortable. Then I realized I did not have them positioned correctly in my ear.  The short bar needs to point downward for me to have optimal comfort.  Once I did this, then they are nearly unnoticeable.  I have used them for the entire battery charge.

Not sure they hold a charge as long as advertised, but they work for a good amount of time close to advertised.  I haven't measured it.

I really wanted to write this review mainly to help others.  I had used quality wired earbuds for years.  Recently I found I was  getting tangled up at the gym.  I decided to go wireless.  Aside from reading the reviews on Amazon, I also research in the technical forums. I found a few pair on Amazon that were in the $50 range with 5000 reviews of 5 stars.  I thought this must be the ones to buy.  However, none of them were verified users.  Seemed a little odd. These  earbuds are clearly not $50.  They are pricey.  Are they worth the money?  Well I feel they  are a  good starting point  to get into wireless.

Something the company may consider is creating a "no frills" package for them.  They come in an elegant, multi box, sleeved system that is beautiful. It is now working its way through the recycling process.

The buttons to raise/lower the volume requires a bit of a push, but  works fine.

I really like how it automatically connects when I remove them from the charging box and they tell me they are connected once they are in my ear.  I like how they automatically shut off when you put them in the charging box.  No  fiddling with  them.  Just remove from charging and put in the ears.

The microphone works much better than expected. Callers cannot tell any difference when I am using them vs. being on the phone normally.  I haven't used them in a high noise environment though.

The pass  through function works pretty good.  When you turn it on you  can hear people talking very easily. It is not perfect; in other words, it picks up  some of  the other ambient noise.  Not a big deal. You are not going to be listening to high quality sound when it is on, however.

I  doubt I could sleep with  them on a plane. A little bulky for that,  IMO.

They block out a lot of ambient noise when the pass through is turned off.  In fact, you cannot really hear someone talking to you unless it is quiet and you turn off the music.

I hope this is helpful.

Enjoy.

title: Elite 65t vs. $9 corded Panasonic's - If I'm being honest...
content:
Elite 65t sound is good once you download phone app and make equalizer adjustments.  And the fit was good right out of the box.  Securely fits in ears during light workout (sit ups, push ups, rowing machine & treadmill jogging).  In all honesty, they're not as comfortable and don't sound as nice as my $9.00 corded pair of Panasonic ErgoFit In-Ear Earbud Headphones RP-HJE120-K's (I've bought several pairs from Amazon).  If you don't mind a cord, I suggest you try these Panasonic's.  But there is a "cool" factor with these 65t wireless earbuds, especially when working out.  I'll probably use the 65t's for gym only, and continue to use the Panasonic's for my daily commute.

I was having difficulty updating the headset firmware via the Jabra app on my iPhone.  I kept getting a failure message.  The solution was to reset and re-pair the earbuds.  Here are the steps.
1.  Press and hold (10 seconds) the Multi-function button on the right earbud until the LED flashes purple.
2.  Go to bluetooth settings and delete (or forget) the previous Jabra earbuds.
3.  Then re-pair the earbuds with your smartphone. Important!  You need to delete (or forget) the previous Jabra earbuds before you re-pair.
4.  Then go into Jabra sound+ app to update headset.

title: Great Headphones - Until They Break
content: These headphones worked great for about a month.  I sweat a lot at the gym and have had issues with other earbuds staying in (don't even get me started on Apple's head phones and how often they fall out of my ears), however these stay put and I never have to adjust them mid-workout.  The controls are a bit backward (volume up/skip forward is the back button which is counter intuitive), but once you get used to them, they're fine.  Having them in for a couple of hours got uncomfortable, but I've got over the ear headphones for long listening sessions and my workouts are never more than 1 hour.  A month after I purchased these headphones, the sound driver in the left earbud died.  Literally all functions of the left earbud work EXCEPT for its ability to play music.  No amount of troubleshooting was able to fix this which was frustrating, however Amazon did come to the rescue and overnighted me a new pair.  I would not recommend you purchase these headphones due to their breaking in 1 month; 2/5 stars for the QC issues, otherwise 4 stars.  Props to Amazon for sending me a new pair, but when (not if) those break I'm 100% buying a different product.

title: Fantastic product that hurts to use!
content:
Off the bat I do have to say, I am a HUGE fan of the product here... but I do have issues.

First and foremost, the sound quality is fantastic for something so compactly packaged.  I like to think of myself as somewhat of an audiophile, though I don’t have quite the refined ear of some of my colleagues who work as sound engineers. Nevertheless, even they were overwhelmed by the audio delivery of such a tiny device.

The pass through audio takes some getting used to - it provides an effective background soundscape that is of a far less quality than the audio files stored on my phone (obviously!), so you end up with a weird mix of high quality, heavily produced music playing in your ear, over a fervently high range and tinny version of the outside world.  It’s jarring for the initial few minutes, but something I have grown to greatly appreciate.  It can be turned on and off at the double tap of a button on your right ear, and is probably the function I use the most.  I feel much safer walking to a busy NYC subway knowing I can hear the traffic around me, but when I arrive on the platform it becomes a simple button press to remove the outside world and focus in on the song I want to listen to.  The difference is enormous, and shouldn’t be understated.

It also works well in an office environment, where I can now listen to music and readily hear when someone wants to talk to me.  Removing a single earpiece works wonders to cut the audio so I can properly engage, but it’s not impossible to hold a conversation even with both earpieces in (kinda makes it sound like the other person is talking to you with a handkerchief over their mouth, but for passing exchanges there’s little need to remove an earpiece... unless they’re softly spoken)!  More often than not, it gives me enough of an indication that I can whip one (or both) of the earpieces out of my ear when someone is approaching, and a proper conversation can take place (the auto shut off of the music when you remove one earpiece is instantaneous and incredibly helpful).

That being said, the microphones do pick up a area of sound far wider than your actual ears can, but then can’t do a great job of translating that into a surround scape (I think it’s still stereo, but feels largely mono).  So I have found myself in situations where someone is talking from behind my back or off to one side, and I could hear them as well as the person in front of me.  It’s occasionally confusing, and you lose a sense of which direction the sound is coming from.  I was at a cashier recently with the earpieces in, and didn’t realise the person in front of me was asking if I wanted a bag or not... I thought it was the cashier one station down, and just came across a little rude and inattentive!

Lastly, the comfort of these things feels largely hit or miss based on your ears.  The earpiece fits my right ear perfectly, and I could listen to it all day.  But the left earpiece hurts like hell after an hour+ of wearing.  The default padding is clearly too big, but the provided “small” padding is SO much smaller as to prove utterly ineffective.  I lose all ability for the piece to stay firmly in my ear at motion, and the outside world bleeds into my audio to a degree as if I wasn’t wearing the earpiece at all.  I would gladly fork over extra cash if I could get an ear cup that is sized between small and regular, but the difference between the small, standard and large earcups is so enormous as to negate any kind of fine selection.  It’s still early days though, and some other reviewers have stated that their ears managed to “get used” to the feeling of having these devices in there.  I hope that’s the case, because I love the sound and convenience so much.  I just don’t want to spend $200 to sit with an ear ache all day should I want to have an extended listening period.  I’m going to look into potential third party replacement earcups, and will circle back if I find something that works.

In summary - SUCH an incredible product, but it’s unbelievably frustrating that at this price level they weren’t able to provide 5 subtly different rubber earcup sizes instead of the 3 incredibly disperate ones.  Would that really have killed their overheads?  It’s certainly killing my left ear!

content:
I bought these 3 months ago and immediately fell in love with them. They worked so easily...put 'em in your ear and they turn on...take 'em out they turn off. They connected to my phone flawlessly everytime with no effort.

Recently I started noticing that the left earbud was considerably quieter than the right. I looked it up online and the are MANY, MANY people who have experienced the same thing. There are suggestions of updating the firmware, which I did and it didn't help. Some people had to send them back to Jabra for replacements and the new ones did the same thing.

I'm super bummed because I loved these SO MUCH. They were th perfect earbud in my opinion...until they stopped working right.

title: The best!

title: Good product, audio delay is annoying
content:
It's good for calls, but I use it mostly for working out in the gym and watching videos on my phone in noisy environments. The noise cancellation is good.
My one complaint is the noticeable delay when watching videos. It's not in sync with the speakers lips. My other bluetooth headphones (with a wired connection between the ears) doesn't have the problem. I've learned that all wireless earbuds have this issue because there's a bluetooth connection in only 1 and they use an NFMI chip to send data to the other one. That adds extra lag. I'm going to keep these, but I wish they could do something about the lag in a newer version.

title: Magnetic tech could cause problems in specific situations
content:
When it's working, they are great.
I have frequent short disconnections w/ the left earpiece, which can be distracting or when they get frequent, they get annoying.
When I work near some equipment in my shop, I have to turn off the feature that pauses the headphones when one is removed, and the left still won't work.
The few responses I did get from customer service explained it was due to the magnetic connection between the two headphones, and that's just how it is. Luckily for me, I don't use the equipment often.
Again, I like them, but if I was trying to use these for reasonable periods of time near magnetic equipment (it can be more than you'd think! Running a microwave while listening in the kitchen can cause occasional disconnections from the left bud!), I might have stuck with my wired-wireless earbuds I had before.

title: best wireless headphones I have ever owned
content: Far better for sound, fit and comfort than Apple Airpods - great battery life - quick charge in case and case charges quickly as well.  The hear-through feature is particularly helpful for running/outdoor use so that you can hear your surroundings (cars, people) when necessary for safety.  After using these for a month, I gave my airpods away to one of my kids!

title: Meh - certainly not worth the price.
content:
The sound is "okay" but often times "clips" when the source (in this case my phone) is as close as a back pocket.  That was very disappointing.

Even modest exercise, a brisk walk and the headphones need to be constantly adjusted so they don't fall out.  I can't imagine doing real exercise.  I vigorous bicycle ride and you almost certainly be stopping every few hundred yards to search for these on the ground or jamming them back in your ears.

Maybe I have odd shaped ears, I don;t know but these "hurt" to wear no matter how many different way to insert them.  I tried all three sizes of the ear buds but it did not seem to make a difference.

It turns out my dog liked them more than me.  I accidentally left them within his reach one day and he chewed one in to submission.  The only reason I was sad is because I felt like I had wasted the purchase price on something I wouldn't have used and could not longer return.

I hear some people love these things but for me, they were a complete and total bust.  The falling out while "just" walking was by far the most annoying trait.
