title: These ear buds are just ok
content:
I use these for music, working out, and making calls.  Sound quality is a little tin-y, but decent.  On a long, sweaty run, eventually my ears are full of sweat and I need to keep removing them and soaking up the sweat with my t-shirt, so they're not great for moisture wicking.  Noise cancellation is pretty good without it needing to be super-loud.  The charging/carrying case is great.  I can always find them in my purse.  They do the trick and are generally good.
The only issue I've had with them is that periodically the left bud just doesn't work.  If I put them back in the case and close it, making sure the charging prongs inside the case make contact, it usually gets it to work.  But it is annoying when I'm needing to make a call and I don't have the time to go through that rigamarole.
Overall, I am satisfied, for now.  I've had them for about 3 months.  We'll see how they function over time.  At this point, the jury is out as to whether I'd buy this model again.

title: Almost flawless
content: The Jabra Elite Active 65t have excellent sound quality, they're comfortable to wear (in *my* ears, at least), and easy to use. So why only 3 stars? Well -- They fall out of my ears when I run. These are billed as being waterproof and for active folks. I have worn these on several runs and they have fallen out of at least one ear each time. On one occasion, one earbud ended up in some grass and it took me a while to find it. I thought it was gone forever. I've tried the other ear tips to get a tighter fit but the larger ones make my ears hurt. Mowing the grass, vacuuming the house, etc... these are great. But for running or cycling, forget about it. You're going to lose one. I guess I'll have to go back to the "wireless" earbuds that have the wire that connects the left and right earbuds... such a pain... and a pity. These Jabras would be better if they looped over the ear or something to hold them in place better.

title: Good: Fit, Google Assistant support, mic performance. Poor: music quality
content:
I think these are fine for taking and making voice calls.
They do fit well in my small ear holes, the first such buds to not only fit well, but they don't fall out, nor do they bother you with this feeling that they are going to fall out.
The pairing was immediate, the Google Assistant support is quite good.
Very few dropouts.
My major complaint is the music quality.  Reading these reviews I was led to believe to the bass quality of music was impressive. Not only is it poor, but overall frequency response is poor, making the music sound like an AM radio.
I know they are much bigger, and over the ear, but compared to the Bose QC's, these are way way off.
That being said, maybe for ear buds of this form factor, maybe they are really good, I don't know, this is my first such pair.

Can you still enjoy music wearing these ? Yes I think so... just come in with low expectations that's all.
Again these may better than the rest... if that's the case, wow, this concept has a long way to go.

title: Beware color mislabeled (3 times)
content: I bought a set of the Jabra elite active 65t in COPPER BLACK. I was sent a set of COPPER BLUE. This is an AMAZON mistake, NOT JABRA (see first pic). I was sent a replacement set and I ordered a 2nd set as an experiment. I now have 3x COPPER BLUE and 0x COPPER BLACK. Not the end of the world, but pretty upset I can't get the color I want. Customer Service tried to help I guess. Didnt do anything except offer to send another pair, which I would fully expect to have the same problem. Can't even guarantee I will get the same price if I waited for them to finish their "investigation ". Not inspiring a lot of confidence with this one guys.....

title: Great Buy, Worth the price - great app features and multi-BT
content:
Very happy with purchase.  I was very hesitant to purchase because of price... but glad I did.
1. connects to phone and computer (HP laptop Windows 10) at the same time! Phone calls will trump any browser or spotify from phone.  this is a great feature.  the headphones say "2 devices connected"
2. its convienient that there are no magnets holding buds in case.  Open lid and spill buds into hand- easy. Some reviews complained about opening case lid- this is not an issue... you won't accidentally open case and lose buds.
3. Noise cancelling due to fit (not actively noise cancelling) and able to play ambient white noise sound through app. very nice.
4. App has great features!  easy to update firmware. easily create preferences for "music","commute", "focus", "active".  The HearThrough feature is awesome! I use often in the office and can have conversations without removing buds.
5. Battery:  best I've had for buds.  the case and buds have green yellow red LEDs, my phone has battery life on homepage.

title: Great truly wireless earbuds.
content:
I'm super happy with these.

They charge up super fast (and the charger itself acts as a portable battery pack, so you can recharge the earbuds on the go). Instruction manual says they have a 5-hour battery life, and so far that's been my experience (although I've only run them down once so far). Pairing these earbuds with my phone and computer was a snap.

I popped 'em in and went out to mow the lawn. It's not super active, but the constant plodding along while I'm sweating in the sun usually bounces other earbuds out of my ears -- these ones stayed put. I just used the default ear-cone things (although they give you a couple others in different sizes, in case your ear-holes are bigger or smaller than average). The seated snugly in my ear and made a good seal without feeling like they were suctioned to my eardrum. And after an hour of wearing them, my ear was still feeling fine.

Music quality was great, at least as far as earbuds are concerned. Crisp, clear, good range (although bass wasn't any better than you'd expect from a set of small earbuds). Perfect for listening while you're out for a walk/run/mowing the lawn.

My one complaint (which I didn't take off a star for, because this isn't why most people will buy these) is that phone call quality is pretty mediocre. It's on par with every other Jabra bluetooth phone headset, but that's basically the result of bluetooth comms being pretty bad in general. My friend said I sounded like I was on a bluetooth headset, but he didn't have any trouble hearing or understanding me.

Wore them to the gym and was so frustrated but the constant cutting out that I tossed them back in the bag. The charging case is not magnetic, very difficult to open and when it does finally pop open the ear pieces end up falling out and onto the ground. I thought this might be an airpod replacement, but it does not appear so.

title: perfect for commuting
content: Good fit and the logistics are great.

title: Great sound and they stay put!
content: The sound on these buds is excellent: crisp, true sound without bass enhancement and other modifications which can muddy the listening experience. They are easy to carry with you in the charging case which will charge the earbuds 2 or 3 times without needing a wall socket. Most importantly, they stay put when you put them in your ear. They take a little bit of a twist to lock them into your ear canal but the tighter you make them, the better the sound. I had these in while on my motorcycle at 75mph and no helmet (don't judge...), didn't mean to but there you go - rode with them like that for an hour and they didn't budge.

title: Sound quality and blue tooth connection is great!
content: The wireless sound buds are excellent for sound and blue tooth.  However for noise cancellation and moisture wicking is just okay.  I've used it in planes before and you can still hear the background noise.  Also, I use the ear buds for working out at the gym, and it is great for sound quality but sweat can get in the way.  Overall, it is a great product and would recommend.

title: Would Recommend
content: Very good earphones. Never had any dropouts. Sound quality is above average. Would recommend to anyone.

title: Good buy
content: Battery usually lasts my husband's full work day and is constantly yelled at for not hearing them when so the noise canceling is pretty good. The left ear piece glitches occasionally but overall its a pretty good buy.

title: Right side died. No support response. 4 attempts w/ Jabra. SAD!
content:
After 3 months of use, the right side died completely. No sound. But, to make the left side work, I still have to put the soundless right side in my ear.

Reached out to Jabra support. They sent me a to-do list of restarting, disconnecting, anti-blutoothing, turning-oning, etc. I did all of that. No change. Now, I have sent them 3 emails over the course of a week... no response.

Buy these if you want crappy support and only one ear bud to work!

title: Theses are great!
content: I loved these. Unfortunately they were stolen a week after I got tgem. But they stay in your ear very well and sound great.

title: Terrific sounding earbuds
content: Really appreciate the sound quality compared to my apple wired earbuds.  Once secured in the ears they are comfortable and secure. I had to use the smallest insert  but then it was fit well.  Pairing took several attempts and was a bit frustrating, but once it finally paired I haven't had a problem.  Battery is as advertised

title: Good for most gym exercises, hear through function works well
content:
I have a job that requires me to be able to listen for radio calls while I work out and the hear through function on these works great. I also love the true wireless and the autoplay features. Sadly, I have only had these for one day before the one of the eargels separated into two pieces. For that, and the fact that they immediately began to fall out of my ears on the treadmill, I docked a star. I really liked using them today for other exercises though but don’t understand why the eargels fell apart so easily.

Edit - Jabra replaced the eargels after I contacted them.

title: I'm a Bose Guy Almost Exclusively, But These Are Great!
content:
So I have owned pretty much every Bose product there is. My last pair of SoundSport Wireless, which I think are great, started to have battery problems after about a year plus. So I decided to try something different since I read several complaints about batteries concerning Bose.

Although these are very comfortable, they aren't as comfortable as the Bose SoundSport Wireless. I think the biggest difference is that Bose's headphones doesn't create a seal inside your ear where you feel the pressure difference, they just sit inside your ear comfortably. These create a seal, but that is necessary so that they can stay in. Bose uses the winglets which may get uncomfortable on extremely long runs.

Sound is great, the hear-through is also great. I have gone on very long runs and they are comfortable throughout. I have never experienced any dropped audio like some of the reviews I have read. I haven't tested the battery life to ensure it meets the advertised capacity, but I like that the case recharges them. So after a few runs, I'll plug in the case for recharging, whereas with the Bose SoundSports, I would have to recharge every night, and if I unplugged them at night, the morning of they would be at 50% (this was not the case when they were new, just the last few months of owning them).

Overall, I was skeptical that I would like these, but I am a big fan now. Again, if you asked me which ones I would recommend, Bose SoundSport Wireless or these Jabra Elite Active, I would recommend the Bose first, as long as you were good with them possibly only lasting a little over a year. But if you wanted absolutely no chord, then these are great. No idea if in a year I'll have the same battery problems, but we'll see.

title: A decent earbuds especially for SPORTS
content:
[Update] Sept 2019: having used it for over half years, I think the product is excellent. I love the sound quality. It weighs light and no burden for my ears at all. Five stars.

[Update]: The bass is farily good when I use a small gel.

I would think the sound quality should be better as a $150 earbuds. The tremble and middle are very good but the bass is insufficient even though I enhanced the Bass on the APP. You know, it won't work as physically it is not built to provide a better bass.

Overall, it is a great earbuds. Fast connection. When I placed it in my ear, it got connected already. It stayed in my ear firmly even when running. It is light and I don't feel any burden. But I would feel tried when wearing it for over 2 hours after a moving. I just think my ears need fresh air. I don't see any water resistence issue.

I am not so care about the noise cancellation when listening. I do care more about microphone cancellation as having a lot of conference call. I want to have a clear voice passed to others. I haven't tested it in a noisy environment (will do it later). But at home the microphone works quite well.

It does have one main earbuds and one slave. Slave one cannot work without the main. Battery is not a problem. I never ran out of battery as the charging case will give you a whole day power.

title: Too big, other than that its amazing headphones but not for me
content: i loved the sound quality and noise cancellation, the long battery life and compact size of the package. but after using it for a while it hurt my ears after wearing it for a while, i realized it isn't for me. its a bit heavy and you will notice the weight on your ears.. other than these two flaws, its a great product

title: Wow! Better than expected sound and great comfort.
content:
After having the Bose SoundSport Free truely wireless buds for more than a year and putting up with their uncomfortable fit and being laughed at because they made me look like I have Shrek ears... It was time for a change.
These Jabra's are so comfortable! Noise cancelling is great and the pass through feature... Cool!
The sound quality was better than I thought it would be. Because to the fit of the Jabra I would argue that these sound better than the Bose.
One complaint... I don't like the charging case. Difficult to open and the buds seem to float in them a bit. Good size case though. Not too big for my pocket.

title: Fall out
content:
They fell out during normal walking, yawning, and life. I called Jabra and her answer was they don’t fit all ears. Great!

I had one roll into traffic lane yesterday and earlier one bounced to the edge of the sea wall at the Academy. fAt $150, falling out and getting crushed or lost will be a big deal.

title: Awful connectivity
content:
I am very disappointed right now.  Just bought these last week and was excited.  Figuring out some of the  nuances isn't that difficult; the app seems serviceable.  They sound great, albeit I wish they would produce a little more volume.  When functioning properly, people on other end of my phone calls say that it sounds great (as long as there isn't too much background noise.).  The problem lies in the connectivity.  I cannot move move my phone (Samsung Galaxy Edge S8+) more five to six feet from the headphones without quality and connection significantly deteriorating.  For example, last night I simply slipped my phone into the pocket of my pants and the connection crackled and the other party on my call could not hear me. This phenomenon seems to be inconsistent as about 50% of the time I have been able to put the phone in my pocket without issues.  Same thing when I am stationary -- if I put my phone on my desk and walk away, then the connection pretty much immediately starts to crackle and becomes completely inaudible anywhere between five feet and 10 feet.  For what it is worth, I have had my phone for over a year and it has maintained bluetooth connections with dozens of products and never has had any connectivity problems.  What good is having wireless headphones if you literally have to hold the phone around your upper body for the headphones to work?  These will definitely be going back today.  Maybe I will give them one more chance in hopes that I just got a faulty pair.  Would love to hear from anyone else that has ever had a similar problem.

Post Script: I've now spent time reading other reviews and have run across other mentions of the connectivity being weak inside of 10 feet.  I've also noticed that Jabra comments on many of these reviews that the the experience the reviewer is having is "not typical".  When 20%+ of the reviews are already 1-star and 2-stars with many of the same issues, I think I would consider a different approach than telling everyone that their experience is 'not typical'.  It appears very 'typical'.

title: Great but not perfect
content:
Very good headphones.
Opening the case is way too hard and uncomfortable but all in all a small price to pay

title: Left ear piece is defective out of the box.
content: Left ear piece didn’t work out of the box. I’m coming from an AirPod 1 that was low on battery already.  I was able to use this 3x with left working but now it’s losing connection from a full charge in just 15 mins. I wish it would work as it sounds great together.

title: Jabra 65t
content: Comfortable. Compact case that charges the earbuds. Easy to travel with and simple phone call answering, volume control, and stop/start audio playback.

title: Price VS. What's most important for you and your Buds?
content:
Good buds, sound quality is lacking for music but not the worse.  For business or active people very good design and works good with other devices.
Just no comparison to 'Beats' or Others known for their sound.

title: Best headphones I've ever had
content:
Buy these. Do it now. If the money isn't a problem, just buy them.

The sound quality is great.  The mic quality for calls is pretty mediocre.  It works fine, but you sound like you're talking on a mic from 2007.

The form factor is what makes them so great (along with the quality).  Do you ever go 5 hours listening to headphone straight?  I don't.  I get up to do something, I talk to someone, I take them out from fatigue. Every time you take them out, what do you do?  You pop them in the case, and what does that do? It charges them.  So, for most people, they'll literally last 15 hours without having to think about charging them.  I've had mine for a year and they have literally never run out of charge.  There's a little LED on the case that lights up green orange or red to let you know the charge capacity on the case... once it hits read, drop it on USB for an hour, bam, back in business.  I charge my headphones like once every 3 days.  You'd be surprised how long 15 hours lasts in real usage.

Combine that with auto-connecting with my phone and laptop when I take them out of the case, plus auto-pausing when I take them out of my ear, plus audio controls.... these things feel like I'm living in the future.

The best part is probably that they don't look ridiculous like airpods.

title: They fall out of my ears
content: I ride a road bike.  I have tried all the different sizes and I cannot get them to stay in my ears.  Stopping to pick them up when riding in a peloton is somewhere between dangerous and impossible.  Got to try something else.

title: Listen to the warnings: poor volume and sound quality, no bass, crackling/reception issues,etc
content: Well, this product really sucks. First of all, I’m not an average every day guy, I make a lot of money, I own a Pioneer sound system, four Apple products, drive a Mercedes, etc. You get the picture.Again, mentioning to let you know that I have perspective when it comes to buying higher than average priced electronics and have those expectations as well. Again, this product sucks. The product is marketed brilliantly but offers nothing else. Overpromising and under-delivering. I got sucked-In, I hope that you don’t happen to you as well. I’ve had this product for less than 10 hours and I’m already turning it to Amazon. I had such high hopes for this product. Here’s what sucks: weak volume, virtually no bass as many people mentioned in other reviews, dropped reception, issues with the left ear bud as many people have mentioned in reviews, and no manual included with the product. Seriously, I’m just amazed that people are willing to overlook such poor sound quality to have basically a wireless headset for phone usage. The phone reception was OK although I have nothing really to compare it to. But if you think for second that you’re gonna be happy with an extremely inferior music sound quality just to have a few phone calls and look kind of hip with some interesting new design for ear buds for $200, you’re kidding yourself. This is my first Amazon review, and I felt really compelled to write it because I think it’s insulting that they sell a product like this for this amount of money.  Having read probably 50 reviews on Amazon about this product, I’m realizing that many are willing to overlook the dozens of negative comments about the sound quality and the fact that there’s an issue with the left earbud. I was hoping for the best. Well, I’m returning it. I guess I’ll try the Apple earbuds or whatever they’re called and see what they feel and sound like. The only good note is that I like the design, and they do fit well in my ears but beyond that why don’t I just shove part in my ears. Also, you hear lots of sound so there is basically no sound reduction. #sucks

title: Battery is CRAP
content: I barely used this thing, and it didn’t even last A DAY! When I click on the power button, it was completely dead that indicatation light didn’t even light up!!! I’m sick on buying these types of headphones! I will go back to Beats now...

title: Bad purchase
content: The product worked ok for a month.  After that you cannot hear anything.  The sound quality is extremely poor.

title: do not last and can not hook up to Blue tooth
content:
After a week of pairing to my phone the Jabra Elite 65t have not worked since. the ear buds keep sending a message that they are to far to pair to my phone. The phone was less than a foot away. Then it would message high charge so I did trouble shooting nothing to relate that with.
I am left with a pair of ear buds that I paid Amazon 189$ and spent hrs to try to work.
My last pair which I only spent 43$ were finished in a week and will not recharge.
I am felt these were of a better quality.
Any help on what to do beside return them

title: Cheaply made, cheap plastic cover, difficult to open, sound worse than Apple
content: After reading reviews, Reputable one’s from tech magazines, NYT, I decided to buy the Jabra instead of Apple. Awful! Sound is terrible, the interchangeable buds to fit my ears - none of them fit. Case is difficult to open and cheaply made. I honestly think I received a cheap knock-off.

title: Great for music, not for calls
content: Love the sound, love the comfort. But they simply don't work for conference calls in noisy environments like a coffee bar. People on the other end complain that they can hear very loud background noise. I have played with the settings in the app but to no avail. I love using them to listen to streaming music while I'm working but I can't use them for work calls; quite disappointed about that, as the information Jabra provided indicated that they had excellent noise cancelling and microphone isolation qualities.

title: Life is good
content: Don’t know yet. I bought them for my wife’s Birthday!

title: High Quality Product and Enjoyable Audio Performance
content:
I am totally impressed with this set of Jabra Elite 65t wireless earbuds.  Jabra is an international audio and sound company that has been in business over 100 years and has an impressive website. This earbud kit represents the design wisdom that has accumulated over the years at Jabra. The product arrived in perfect condition. The well-designed and organized box in which the earbuds, carrycase/charger, and the USB charging cable arrived along with brief paper instructions is a keeper. I found the box even better made than the high quality product boxes used by Apple. There is a FREE Jabra App on the Apple App Store which I downloaded to my iPhone. This App opened flawlessly and provides a more detailed user manual and also provides a very basic equalizer to adjust your sound in a range of 700 to 10,000 Hz. The App also helped with setting up my Bluetooth coupling to the earbuds. Enough of this background discussion, Let's move on to the sound quality.

The Jabra Elite 65t fit to my ears reasonably well and pretty much eliminated background noise. The Bluetooth reception from my audio library on my iPhone is amazing: crystal sharp, responsive, and a listening pleasure on a wide assortment of music genres: classical, pop, blues, Cajun, and much more. I love the personal nature of the listening experience and the ease of operation. The earbuds synchronized flawlessly to the Bluetooth signal. They sound better than a pair of wired name brand earbuds that I have been using for three years, I enjoy the fast response, clear sound, volume control on left earbud which controls volume on both earbuds simultaneously, and the on/off switch on the right  earbud. I like the look of the earbuds as well. The only shortcoming so far discovered is that I am having a hard time trying to change the silicon rubber insert to better fit my ear. But, I know that Jabra will help out here and there are YouTube videos which may help me better understand some nuances of using the product.

The charging/storage case is a work of industrial art. It is easy to use and I charged it with an Apple 5v charger. The case opens by lightly depressing the edge. Various color lights indicate items like charging status, etc as explained in the instructions.

I have not yet tried using the microphone portion of the earbuds for phone calls as I prefer to use the iPhone mike. But, I think I will get to like the earbud mike after a few uses. Also, I have had the earbuds in for two hours and did get a little achy in left ear. I think a smaller silicon fitting will solve the problem. Looking forward to enjoyable years of earbud audio.

title: Not acurate descriptions
content: Espect product as described on website and received someting totally different

title: Definitely worth every penny
content: Really comfortable to use and liberating.  Once you get these you'll never go back to using earbuds connected to your phone.

title: Really good headphones. GREAT for phonecalls!
content:
These impressions are still early on, but so far I'm impressed:

The sound quality is fantastic! Everything sounds good so far - music, podcasts, audiobooks - and the range is great, too. My old Bluetooth headset had to be at max volume if I wanted to hear anything if I was outdoors, these I can set to about 35% and still hear everything! The seal is good, but not so tight that I feel unaware of road conditions when I'm on my bike. It does a good job of cutting out wind noise, which is a big plus.

If you make a lot of phonecalls on your headset, then these are definitely worth the money. Every other bluetooth headset mic I've used sounds like, at best, I'm yelling across the room at my phone, but the 65t's 4 mic system captures crisper sound than when I'm using the handset.

It has a lot of neat features, like automatically pausing and restarting audio when one of the ear pieces is removed, and the Jabra App is very useful (but not necessary, if you don't want to use it). I like that I can adjust the volume and change tracks without taking my phone out, and I'm surprised at how often I'm using Google Assistant now (considering that I almost never used it before).

As for cons, there are only 2: The fit is uncomfortable if you have small ears. They are designed to take up your entire ear cavity, so it pinches the crease inside of my left ear. It might be something I get used to, but after wearing it for 2 hours, it starts to feel bruised. The other issue is that the connection drops out whenever I open my refrigerator. I'm not sure why that is, but I was wearing them while cooking, and every time I opened the fridge, the sound went out. Luckily, it picks up right where I left off when I closed it, but I'm worried that it means I'll be dealing with a lot of environmental interference.

Overall, these are the best bluetooth headphones I've used - and I've used a bunch! They are also the most expensive, but if the warranty is to be believed, they should last a lot longer (none of my other headphones have lasted longer than a year).

title: Good buy.
content: My teen nephew bought these and so far 2 months later he still loves these. He's hard to please when it comes to electronic stuff.

title: Works well, hearthough option hissing like mad
content: Just received this today and seems to work fine other than hear though option doesn't really seem to work unless you wanna hearing consist hissing. I would recommend using something opened ear head phones like Backbeat Fits instead if y'all wanna hear around ya while listening to what y'all want

title: Too Large.
content: I was planning on wearing these everywhere - to the gym, at work. The sound is decent but these are just way too big to fit into your ears, and when I could get them to stay they felt awkward like they were in there too tightly. I had the smallest size attachment on the earpieces. I am an average size adult woman, these just disappointed me because the size.

title: Bad for small ears
content: These earbuds sound great. Unfortunately, my ears are small. They hurt and fall out.

title: Love these earphones
content: These are awesome earphones. I love the convenience of being able to just take them out of the box and they automatically connect. It's also great that they connect to two devices. In regards to durability....because of their size, I have dropped one or both of the earphones multiple times onto a hard floor. Each time expecting it to be broken. So far, they are holding up well and I am learning to be more careful.

title: pretty darn good
content: haven't had them for too long, but sound and connection are good. was uncomfortable in ear for a few days, but i naturally adjusted. doesn't hurt at all anymore.  i only wish i could use either piece solo, not just the right one.  also the right one has no volume control so stuck using the phone buttons if only using one.

title: Good quality, nice charging case.
content: Good quality. I've never had other than the kind with wires. I had a bluetooth pair that had a wire to connect to each other. I don't know that they are worth the price. I would like to compare but not enough to buy some cheap ones.

title: Revised:Good for sound terrible for calls
content:
Revised: well they improved it and now you can connect to 2 devices at once. Great improvement in couple of months...

Well, I wanted to love those, it is an amazing listening device but for calls, it is just terrible if you are outside or in the subway. It pick up all sounds 30 feets away so good luck . Apart from that great product.

title: Great sound but fit and call quality are ???
content:
These things feel solidly made. I like the sightly texture surface material - make them easy to handle without sliping out of my fingers. They are not too big, but not small. I think they look better to wear around than AirPods. I've searched for a true wireless solution that sounds better than AirPods without sacrificing voice call quality. The problem is AirPods in my experience are really hard to beat for voice call quality. But the AirPods' sound quality for music isn't what I want. Specifically, lack of noise isolation is a problem. The Jabra Elite Active 65t comes as close as I've found so far. The sound quality begins to approach the Master and Dynamic buds I tried.  It's better to my ear than the Bose. It's full, rich, and detailed with decent isolation of outside sounds - unless you turn on the "Hear Through" feature which is pretty slick. There are two problems.

1. Fit - my ear canals seem to be right between Jabra's medium and large tips. I followed some advice I saw online and ordered foam tips made for the Jabra Elite Sport. The medium size works great for my right ear but it's ever to slightly too small for the left. But the seal is good enough that they make the Active 65t sound better to me than with the gel tips. And if the seal works for you, then disregard this problem.
2. Call quality - it's hit and miss. Sometimes I'm told it sounds just as good as the AirPods while I'm doing A-B tests with family members, better than any other non-AirPod option I've tested. Other times, mid-conversation and standing in the same spot they will tell me they cant hear me anymore??? The 65t also seems to pick up more ambient sounds than the AirPods do.

The case is nice and small (yet about 2x the size of the AirPods case) and has the same non-slip surface as the buds. The app for iPhone works well and gives a lot of options for customizing the sound.

Overall, if not for having experience with AirPods these would seem fantastic to me. As it is, they seem like a close second for my purposes.

title: Disappointment
content: I can't keep the left ear bud working.  I've just come from looking online to find that a lot of other people are having the same problem.  Maybe when they say it's the "best" they mean the most expensive.  Yes, I've done a full reset twice so far but the bud only works for a short time, then off again.  Hence the disappointment.

title: Work great.  Some downsides
content:
These are awesome, the sound is generally pretty good but I mostly listen to podcasts.  They connect quickly.  About the only thing I don't like is their apps.  They work but barely and the headphones seem to operate differently when the app is running in the background.  They don't turn off when removed from the ear is the biggest difference.

Update 092418
Still really enjoying them but I have a couple complaints.  The left ear piece seems to get static of varying levels.  Sometimes it's completely non-existent, then slight background but noticeable and on occasion it's terrible.  Secondly the case that charges it does a good job but is very slick.  I have dropped and scuffed up the case multiple times just cause it slips right out of my fingers.  Battery life is still great and they are by far my favorite headphones.  Just little issues to fix.

title: Battery without charger could be better.
content: Great product!

title: Works great.

title: Comfy, work great
content: Comfy & work great

title: Ear buds not comfortable
content: I had an issue with them staying in my ear. I had to purchase bigger ear pieces to get them to stay in. I wish the volume could get louder

title: They're ok.
content: The music sound is good but you can't really use them for phone calls. It only works about 25 percent of the time when making calls. You won't be able to hear anything. For this price it should work 100 percent of the time.

title: Disappointed
content:
Let me start with the fact that I actually like the earbuds. I thought they worked pretty well, when they worked. However, the support has been nothing short of awful. Right earbud stopped working ~60 days after purchase. No big deal - things happen. I email support, no answer. I call them a day after that, the guy says fill out the warranty replacement request and we'll ship it out right away. I do that (including Amazon order #, etc). About a week passes.....crickets. I email again, no answer. 14 days later I get another email saying they want a picture of the earbuds with the case?!. Sure feels like I am getting the runaround from support. So far it's been 16 days since the original request and the replacement hasn't even shipped. I find this pretty ridiculous and I expect way better from a product at this price level. It certainly wasn't a problem to ship them to me when I bought them.

Summary: earbuds are fine if they work. If you have a problem, doesn't look like the company is interested in keeping it's customers happy, but more interested in delay tactics. Up to you if you think it's a risk worth taking. Keep a set of spares around.

title: good sound quality
content: I can't compare them to any other brand, but these are pretty damn good.

title: Great hardware, worthless (but necessary) companion app
content:
The headset seems to have good sound and the pairing was super simple, they are low profile and they fit very comfortably in the ear.  However, the companion Android Sound+ app is worthless (won't see headset, like hundreds of others have reported on Google Play Store) and therefore headset is not configurable or updatable. Tried uninstalling/reinstalling app and/or JabraService (v 1.8.7), restarting phone, force stopping app, powering headset off and back on... Despite useless canned response in Google Play  reviews from Jabra, no success. Elite 65t is successfully paired to my phone (Huawei P20 Pro) and works with default config, but without being able to configure ANYTHING, they will be going back unless resolved quickly. Way to go Jabra pairing a useless app with what appears to be a solid headset.

Initial hardware impression = 5 stars, worthless (but necessary) companion app, 0 stars.

title: Hard to "Beat"!
content: I spent a lot of time researching ear buds, comparing reviews and specs before purchasing the Jabra Elite 65t for my wife.  Some of the top recommended brands made my decision long and tedious, but the Jabra stood out with all of their features and ability to customize the sound. Once I listened to the quality of sound these gems produced, I decided to purchase a second pair for myself. I can't imagine anyone being disappointed in the Jabra Elite 65t! Good battery life, quality sound, great features, all in a compact case. After a couple of months of usage(gym, yard, ebooks), no complaints from either of us!!

title: Better than airpods
content: Better than airpods, but still a ways to go before this technology catches up to wired headphones

title: Terrific performance, strong Bluetooth connection
content: Just don’t leave them on an airplane like I did.

title: Excellent Alternative to Apple Airpods: Great sound, Comfy Fit and Easy to Use
content:
I was looking for a true wireless alternative to the Apple Airpods, which I found very uncomfortable to wear. After reading many reviews online and on YouTube, I made the decision to purchase the Jabra Elite Active 65t Alexa Enabled True Wireless Sports Earbuds and I am delighted with my purchase.

I paired my Jabras very easily with my iPhone Xs and configured my settings on the Jabra Sound+ app (downloaded from the App Store). The earbuds fit very comfortably in my ear (I need to use the largest tips provided) and provide a tight enough seal to block out a lot of extraneous background noise, which helps the sound cancelling nature of these earbuds. When the earbuds are set to "HearThrough," you have the option of allowing more sound in to be able to hear sounds around you more effectively, should you need/want it.

The sound quality is excellent with music, spoken word (podcasts and audio books) and also with phone calls. As for phone calls, when you receive a call, the number or person's name is announced (if in your contacts) and gives you the option of answering or ignoring the call. The caller sounds very clear to me and when I ask the person I am speaking with if they can hear me well, they always say they can.

The carrying case keeps the earbuds safe and charged up. There is an indicator light inside and outside the case to show the battery levels on the earbuds and the case itself. When I take the earbuds out of my ear, my iPhone automatically stops and will resume again from where I left off with a press of the right earbud. The right and left earbuds have different controls which you can learn from the Jabra Sound + app.

I use the Jabras at the gym and have found no issues with connectivity or staying put during sweaty workouts. I do not have to be right next to my iPhone in order for the earbuds to be connected.

My only complaint is that I cannot connect my Jabra earbuds to both my iPhone and laptop. If I wanted to connect my earbuds to my laptop I would have to unpair from the iPhone first and then connect to the laptop. This is not a huge issue for me, but I wanted to mention it in case people want to have multiple devices connected simultaneously.

I found what I was looking for with the Jabra Elite Active 65t Alexa Enabled True Wireless Sports Earbuds: great sound quality, comfort and ease of use. I recommend the Jabras very highly.
I previously owned the Apple wireless iPods which unfortunately recently lost. I was going to buy another pair of iPods when I ran across the Jabra and the Bose and began to research these 2 options.

title: Best wireless (better than airpods) but find your fit!
content: I love these. I bought them then returned them to try a lot of different ones, only to end up with these again. Sound quality and ability to customize sound is AMAZING. Love that you can customize everything for when you're commuting or doing something, all on the app! I also think they look VERY attractive compared to many others. Battery life is the best for wireless so far (not sure about airpods, but those don't even noise cancel). I can keep the volume on these very low and still hear everything while commuting! I love everything about these earphones even the voice prompts warning you that a call is coming. The only small criticism I have is that it took me quite long to find my fit, and I found out my ears are weird. (Left ear uses large silicone bud but my right uses a medium LOL). I am planning to try these with foam tips because i heard foam tips are even comfier! love the portability of the charging case too. I don't know why people say it snaps open, i have to pry mine open!  Battery indicator on the case for its battery and separate one on the top part for the earphones themselves is also so useful. They can be uncomfy after wearing them for a while but all wireless are like this and i really think foam tips will help. Overall SO SO happy i am debating between keeping these and upgrading to the jabra evolve that will come out soon. LOVE THEM

title: Do not buy
content: The sound quality and overall functionality are good....when it finally connects to your device. I have never experienced any bluetooth accessory that has so much trouble simply connecting to the phone and not losing the connection.  At this price point this is simply unacceptable . Avoid.

title: Great purchase.
content: Works great. I have used it for working out, hiking, etc. has never fallen out. One gripe though, I wish you could choose wether left or right earbud could be dominate bud.

title: Workout worthy
content: I also have the Elite 65t and got the Active version for my daily workouts.  Love them.  Only complaint is that 2 weeks after I got my Active’s Jabra dropped them by $50 for the Holidays.  I think they should refund me the discount.

title: Music isn’t the best
content: These headphones are great! But they lack in the listening to music department and Connectivity is an issue

title: The Jabre Elite Active 65t < the Apple Airpods
content:
First, the width of Jabra Elites needs to be reduced by at least another 30%. There is ear fatigue after a few hours. The Apple Airpods are the clear winners here with there elongated design.

Second, unlike the Apple Airpods where both the left and the right earbuds can be used independent of one another only the right side can be used on the Jabra Elites.

Third, there is a hissing static sound coming from the left earbud when talking which I feel is not a malfunction of the earbuds but the mechanics inside the earbuds working which can be a little distracting.

Fourth, the right and left earbuds cuts out randomly. A little too often in fact.

Fifth, phone calls are okay but unlike the Apple Airpods ambient noise can clearly be heard in the background by other callers.

Sixth, the Jabra Elites Active hear through feature is terrible. Best to turn that feature off and just use the one earbud.

Seventh, why isn't the earbud place holders magnetic to hold the earbuds in place?

Bottem line: is that Apple seems to be years ahead of the competition with their Airpods. Unfortunately, us Android users will still have to wait for something truly great to arrive from the competition.

title: Finally found the ideal Bluetooth buds!!
content: Love it - it’s perfect! So much better than AirPods, which I have been using for 6 months. Volume control on the buds, noise isolation, fit - scores a perfect 100 on each!!

title: Love these
content: I use these for work calls, running and the gym. They stay in my ear great and the sound quality is perfect. Still have a hard time adjusting to them in my ear canal as opposed to resting on the inside of the ear. Hard to keep them in inbetween calls.

title: has issues
content: Quality is not awesome. Sound goes in and out.

title: Expensive and difficult to find flimsy eargel replacements
content: Given how expensive these are, you'd think they'd give you more than one set of the three eargel sizes. Ten dollars a pair, and frankly the earbuds jiggle a lot when I'm jogging.

title: Buy something else.
content:
Bad hissing.
Unbalanced volumes.  Right side very quiet by 6dB
Cheap, large case.
No magnetic holding, the buds just fall out.

Sucks.  Buy something else.  Airpods are better.

title: as good as advertised
content: So far, as good as advertised!

title: Great buy
content: Recommending this to my friends

title: DO NOT PURCHASE
content: This is probably the worst product I've ever purchased.  I bought it and one ear bud broke within a month.  That in itself is bad but Jabra customer service has been horrid. They simply will not respond to my repeated emails.  At this point it has been months and I probably just out the cost.  Avoid this product and anything else Jabra sells.

title: Pop in and listen to the world
content: I have these sucker for a couple of months and love them. Connection is good! Sound quality is good but don’t expected high quality like Bose or Apple AirPods. The best thing is that they are durable if you take care of them.  The only issue I have is that they are not load but then again what is there to expect on such a small speaker. Overall great product. I would buy again since I was disappoint with the Bose that lasted on 2/3 months.

title: They don't work!
content: Right out of the box the left earbud didn't work, and the right one sounded tinny. Horrible product and horrible customer service. I've never written a review before, but this is the worst purchase I've ever made.

title: Bluetooth Reception Getting Worse and Worse!
content: I wish I could give the 65t a better review, because I do like the fit, sound quality and comfort. Unfortunately, there is a problem that began as a rare intermittent cut-off of reception from my various Bluetooth devices that has turned into a full-blown, constantly repeating problem. The earphones always start off fine, then after they've been on for a while, they'll start to lose contact with the other device. It gets progressively worse until I just have to take them out of my ears and resort to my wired earphones. When I first got these, I used to recommend them to everyone who asked me for advice on true wireless earphones (Which is a lot of people since I'm pretty much considered THE gearhead among my social circle). Now I feel like I have to warn people off the 65ts because it's such a fundamental problem that I can't ignore it. I'm hoping to send them in to Jabra (they're still under warranty). Hopefully they can fix whatever the problem is.

title: Disconnects
content: Frequent disconnects

title: Don't expect BASS
content: Sound quality was extremely poor, and the Jabra App+ which includes an "equalizer", is essentially is a yellow line you can play with to supposedly alter bass to treble, but does nothing to alter sound quality.  The App also has various selections for different environments, i.e. noise cancellation for noisy areas.  I tried to use the earbuds in the gym, but I they let too much ambient noise pass through, all I could hear is the gym's music, plus what I was trying to listen to. The volume button is overly "stiff", and difficult to control, and hard to position your finger on the proper side of the center button to increase, or decrease volume.  Don't waste your money on these!

title: These are amazing, until they stop working.
content:
I love these ear buds, but three (!) pairs in a row stopped working after about 2 weeks.  Constant disconnecting, reconnecting, disconnecting, reconnecting, disconnecting. . . . then nothing.  And the app is terrible, too.  It could never tell when the ear buds were on, but kept looking for them when they weren't.

I used these with an LG V40 with the latest Android, so there is no excuse.  How does a company in 2019 make a product that can't keep a stable bluetooth connection??

title: Good Product, Nice Look
content: Going to take some practice working with. Product itself has good, clear sound, seems like well made and look good.

title: Terrible product! Very poor sound!!!
content: Absolutely terrible! Sound quality is terrible!!! They do not stay in the ear like the ads say and the sound is muddy and the “hear thru” feature over-emphasizes the high notes. I prefer the sound of the airpods and they stay in the ear better too!

title: Do you really need wireless?
content:
24 hours after purchase.  They're good but I'm a little disappointed. For many who are moving up from cheap ear buds, these will seem fantastic. For me, I had been using wired noise canceling Bose quietcomforts.  From a sound perspective, they are just okay.  There is a big difference between noise canceling and noise isolation, which these are.  Even with passthrough turned off, you will still hear a lot of ambient sound.

Just make sure that you really need wireless buds.  For the price, they are probably the best you will get.

title: Best earbuds currently available
content:
I love these earbuds.  I've had them 10 months, and have had minimum issues.  The sound, battery life, and convenience is top notch.
The only problem I have had is the left earbud not syncing with the right one after I remove BOTH earbuds and NOT putting them back in the case (putting them on a table).  This was easily resolved by putting BOTH earbuds back in the case, then putting them in my ears.  Kind of a PITA, but it resolved the issue.  Other than that, these earbuds have been great so far.  A co-worker has the exact same pair, and he loves them too.  They work great for us as earplugs in a high noise factory also.  All we have to do is double tap the right earbud to go from silence to hearing someone that we are talking to, then double tap back to silence.  Of coarse you can replace the "silence" with music from your phone... if your place of employment allows that.  But, just saying, they work great as work environment ear plugs also.

title: Excellent Earbuds
content:
They don't fall from your ears, they come with different ear tips to achieve a perfect ear fit. The integration with the jabra application is super cool you can personalize different profiles for your earbuds so they behave in different ways as you wish. The sound is very good, also the battery duration.
Sometimes it doesn't pair super quick with the phone, but you only need to close the case and open it again and they pair perfectly.

title: Everything is great, except for peculiar connectivity problems at the gym.
content: Product is exactly what I was expecting. It is super easy to setup, wasn't incredibly comfortable at first but after testing the different sizes it fits great. I looked at these specifically because of different reviews on the jaybird runs issues with connectivity. Well, these headphones seem to keep connection very well. I don't drop connection with my phone on the other side of the room. I even shower with them on and haven't had any issues with connectivity. However, in the gym it seems to be a different story. I am not sure what's causing the issues but whenever I try to lift weights. Such as bench press, overhead presses, etc. The connection constantly stutters. It's only while the weights are in my hands too. As soon as I put the weights down and rest between sets the connection is fine. I don't know what the cause could be but it's very annoying. Even my $30 Sony WI-300 never had an issue like this. If this issue didn't exist, they'd easily get 5/5 stars

title: Unacceptable
content: These earbuds stopped working all most immediately , the right one lost sound within a month of receiving them. I sent them back to Jabra to have them fixed or replaced and after waiting 5 WEEKS , I received an email saying that it will be another 4 WEEKS before they can be replaced as they are out of stock. That is over 2 months without my $150 earbuds ( unacceptable )..

title: Good calls bad audio music. RESOLVED music low SAMSUNG S8!!! check comments and pics
content:
Amazing. Tried first Samsung earbuds but always problems.
Now Jabra at the beginning amazing I left 5 stars.
After this time calls are amazing BUT music sometimes is lowww
that you cannot hear and somedays works a little.
PRO: calls ok
CON: music no so good.

UPDATE:
first gave 1 star because music low in my Samsung S8.
NOW
Ill give them 5 STARS.
problem was samsung and NOT JABRA.
S8
1.CONNECTIONS
2. BLUETOOTH
3. ADVANCED
4. MEDIA VOLUME SYNC....have to check here and not Dual Audio
5. RESOLVED!!!!!!

title: Great Product, terrible service.
content: Product works good, but I ran into an issue months later with the charging case. I had to wait 20+ minutes for the support line to pickup and there when they sent me a link to warranty my part, no response was given even after 2 weeks. Would recommend the product but if it breaks then you're out of luck.

title: Left earphone dead after 2 days of use.
content: Bought these earphones two days ago and now the left earphone won't charge, turn on, or anything. Very disappointed in this product. Definitely not worth the high price you are paying for it.

title: Great buy, just need to get used to them
content:
I own Grind headphones by Skull Candy but they are old and get to sweaty now. I also gave into to the earbud trend as headphones do mess your hair up and fall off/break easier. I was always udner the notion that they were superior to earbuds but apparently that has changed.

They are kinda big but not as uncomfortable as they look. For some reason the left one starts to bother a little more than the right over time. I do have to adjust a little but I end up finding a spot where they fit good and the sound is good as well. I do use these for workouts mostly and only adjust a little. I was fidgeting with them a lot the first day but I found once you actually get them in right the first time you really don't need to mess with them. The only time they fell off during a workout was cuz I was messing with them and/or did not put them in right.

A lot of people complaining about the left earbud's button push. I noticed it but figured a way to push the buttons without pain in the ear. You really have to hold it with your index finger on the button and your thumb supporing the bottom of the earbud so it doesn't jam into your ear. Problem solved. I just love the fact that it does change through tracks pretty quickly. The speaker, voice control and hearthrough are quite awesome features as well. The hearthrough really works!!

I thought the sound was just OK but then I played with the equalizer on my S8 as well as the Jabra app equalizer. The sound was very nice and allows you to control bass/treble, etc. I then tested it against my plug in earbuds (the ones that come with the S8 which are quite nice) as well as my Skull Candy bluetooth overear phones. These little guys are really really nice in quality. I didn't realize I was listening to such bad quality on my Skull Candy phones. They are crisp and really get you feeling the beats, etc. I don't have to crank the volume up as much either

I think mostly, I just have to keep wearing them to get used to the feel and the fit. Love that they do come with different size buds. I would give 4 1/2 but we can't do half stars. Only a half star off for some learning curve if you aren't used to this brand/size. Plus the fact of the buttons. Maybe they should have been touch but it's a minor inconvenience

title: BEYOND HORRIBLE CUSTOMER SERVICE
content:
The volume in the right earbud was softer than the left. Further, when making a call, the right earbud would rattle and was shrill. Before you buy a Jabra product read the countless reviews of buyers who were unable to have their warranty honored by Jabra. Try to find the address of Jabra’s US location. It simply does not exist on the internet, their website , nor will Customer Service disclose their location.
If you buy from such a retailer, you get what you deserve!

title: Great headphones
content: Works great. Super solid

title: Great wireless headset with nice QoL features, disappointing mic noise isolation
content:
I bought these to go with my Pixel 2 XL rather than using the supplied dongle with my existing headphones and I needed a good wireless headset for calls. They sound great while offering good range, great battery life and some decent quality of life enhancements that not all devices like these have. For instance with the easily toggle-able external sound pass-through so I can hear my surroundings without needing to take the earpiece(s) out of my ear(s). Which brings me to my next favorite feature, the ability to use the right earpiece independently of the left and being able to seamlessly switch to using both and then back as necessary.

My only gripe is the microphone(s), people I call tend to complain that they can hear my surroundings more than when I use the built-in headset. Not sure what more can be done to improve this seeing as though the form-factor of these ear-pieces are so small already but it is slightly disappointing as I bought these with the intent of using them during most of my calls.

Overall a great buy, I see myself using them for a year or at least until the next model comes out, whichever comes first.

title: sad
content: product would not stay in my ears, had to send back

title: Great earbuds - just don't lean over
content: I liked these earbuds from a quality standpoint.  However, I was unable to achieve a proper fit with any of the supplied ear gels.  They are also heavy and have a tendency to fall out of the ear when you lean over.  My suggestion, do wear these into the bathroom to do your business.  That would be a very expensive mistake (no- I did not do this.  I am smarter than that :) ).

title: Terrible product
content: The headphones themselves are pretty good.  The bass is decent, the call quality is above average, and I like the way they fit a lot.  Customer service is abysmal.  Resolving an issue took well over a month, and I still don't have my replacement. This is simply unacceptable for headphones that cost almost $200. I won't be buying another Jabra product.

title: Good for everywhere but the gym
content:
Sound is better than decent, could be louder but noise cancelation is good. Have held up to heavy sweating too. Sometimes the left ear sound drops and buds have to be turned off then on again.
The biggest con to these is how easy they are disrupted when other electronics are close. In the gym is the worst. Anytime there's more than 6 or 7 people around with cell phones and headphones if thier own my phone can't be more than a couple feet away before there is extreme disruption. I tried both apple and Android phones but problem persists. I don't however have the issue with the Samsungs i have. I tried explaining to Jabra support but they weren't any help. Said turn them off then on if that doesn't work just live with it in so many words. Actually told me that would happen with any pair and didn't quite like that my Samsungs, which were half the price, didn't have the same issue. If you're an avid gym goer would say use something else for your music. Not worth the price tag.

title: Perfect for workouts and biking around the city
content: If you want to work out or bike in a city this is definitely what you want. I also bought the premium buds from comply that perfect the fit in my ears. I got a 3 year protection plan so I’m carefree if they break. If you want workout headphones that stay out of your way and never fall out these are amazing. The ambient is perfect for biking around a city.

title: Not A Substitute for Bose
content: Very unsatisfying. Bose is better sound and more comfortable. I really regret this purchase. Bose has spoiled me.

title: Great audio 2
content:
Final verdict: returning mine.

1. Great audio
2. Fantastic noise cancellation customization
3. Very poor call quality despite 4 microphones. Would never use it as microphone for conference calls, Skype, etc. Tested it in quiet room, driving, and on sidewalk - quiet room barely usable and forget call quality with any background noise.

title: Overall excellent product, very comfortable and excellent functionality.
content: I wish they were more noise cancelling, especially because they have the heat through feature which lets you hear everything around you.

title: They check ALL the boxes!
content:
I am a fan of bluetooth and ear buds.  I had a pair of cheap buds that were connected by a wire....which would always stick on clothing.  For what they were they were OK.  I had been keeping an eye out for the perfect set of buds that I could afford and these checked all the boxes.  Sound is excellent especially when you can tweak it with the app (that I find somewhat useful).  The connection has been about 99%, with the rare glitch but MUCH better than anything I have used in the past.  Unobstructed range for me is about 50 feet or so.  Walls reduce distance dramatically as expected.  The bonus for me is call clarity.  I drive a LOT and most people on the other end cannot tell I am driving.  The passthrough feature is nice but I prefer my natural voice instead of processed so when using for phone calls I typically will use just the right bud.

Battery life has been great....haven't gone from full to empty in one sitting so I cannot verify five hour life.  As far as comfort, they fit my ears quite well.  I can understand that they could be uncomfortable for some which would be a bummer!  Listening to music right now....and couldn't be happier!!

title: Left earbud stopped working
content: After a month the left one will not work anymore even though the app shows that it is linked.

title: Awesome
content: I don't know what people are talking about I have beats wireless and these are just as good if not better as far as sound quality

title: Great for music, just ok for phone calls
content: Great product. Convenient and great audio quality. However, I leaned towards this product as this was advertised to be good for phone calls. Its just alright, not great in this department.

title: They work great
content: There good

title: You have to get used to
content: So I tried the böse sport wirelles and earpods and the jabras are the best headphones.

title: iphone
content: dont get these if you have an iphone i have the iphone sx max and when i try to answer another call it disconnects from the ear buds and on top of all that it makes a beeping noise randomly.

title: Mostly good, a few personal quibbles
content:
I don’t think my ear anatomy works best for these earphones. In general, they stay in but are liable to pop out without warning on me. The noise cancelling is so-so (my Bose ones are better, but the caveat is my Bose ones also fit more completely into my ear).

If I use these as headphones to talk while I drive, they let a lot of road noise through (caveat: I drive a loud sports car. My mom says my regular apple earphones do a better job of noise cancelling).

However- I REALLY appreciate the recharging capability if you put them back in the case!

Bottom line: useful for my office to cancel medium noise levels, or being around the house. Not useful for some activities for ME.  YMMV.

title: Very pleased..
content: Very pleased...the auto on/off when removing and replacing to charging case doesn't function consistently. Need to look at firmware and updates.

title: Great Buds, Best out there.
content:
This is my second pair of Jabra buds. I currently owned (own) the Active Sports & there great as well. The Elite Actives sound Great, fit tight & I really like the style look. The function buttons on head set take less effort ( push) to pause or raise volume. I had the Apples for a week & they were brutal, didn’t stay in ear & looked like a broken Q-tip in my ear- Not for me. All reviews point to Jabra as an Elite bud.
So here’s a quick pros & cons between the sports & Elite Active. ( just In case anyone’s wondering?) Actives go deeper in ear, (doesn’t bother me but may some) , easier to function, fully water proof. Biggest flaw is the case- pain to open and buds want to pop out when opened. Sports- less style, and Great/ easy charging case. Both sound awesome, comfortable & connect to Bluetooth flawless.
Best buds on the market in my opinion. Honestly don’t know how anyone can complain about these??

title: Kinda crappy
content: Can only wear for about an hour until you’re ears hurt. Microphone is just okay. FALLS OUT OF YOUR EARS.

title: Great Product if it fits your ear!!!
content:
This is an excellent set up true wireless earbuds.  Right out of the box the connection was simple. The sound quality was excellent. The connectivity and automatic pause was excellent.  I would’ve given this a five star but I had to return it because it doesn’t fit my ear.  My ear is the one percent that it will not fit in and I constantly had to put it back in when I was lifting weights because it would fall out.
 Again this is an excellent product and my ears are unique so I’m not gonna give it a one star because of that

title: Good sound, high quality product
content: Really like these. Comfortable, good sound quality, and the rechargeable case means I am always ready for a workout. A bit tricky to know each time which is the main one to connect since the look identical, but once connected, really nice product.

title: I reeeaaaaally wanted to like these, but....
content: As title states, I really wanted to like these, and went through 3 iterations before finally giving up due to these product flaws: (1) only the right earbud connects to your phone, so the left can’t be listened to independently; (2) the left HAS to be within 8 inches of the right, otherwise it doesn’t work (this is one of the features for some reason); (3) the HearThrough functionality is great, but for some reason in all versions that I received, the left ear bud gets staticy when it picks up noise that’s nearby, which then blasts the static into your ear. This doesn’t happen to the right, so I have to conclude all versions have this quirk in the left ear bud; (4) the left earbud loses connection to the right when you get close to electronic screens/monitors; (5) in the first version I got, the left ear bud stopped working altogether after a week. Everything else is great (connectivity is easy, sound quality is great, controls are easy to use, app is very useful), but these minor quirks just get too annoying and particularly if u use them for workouts, it gets really distracting...

title: Sound quality is not worth the price you pay.
content: I expected a much fuller sound from these.  Difficult to pick out nuance.  I’d honestly say the corded apple ear buds preform better at getting out the deep full sounds than these do.  They could stand to be a hundred dollars cheaper.

title: Don't think twice about these!!
content: Best earbuds on the market. Do not think twice! I went through several different earbuds including AirPods & these outperform any of them. I lost my first out within a week (traveling and totally my fault) & immeditly repurchased then!

title: Excellent for workouts
content:
Highly recommend these if you need headphones for working out. I cannot yet speak to the durability of these because I have only had them for a few months, but during sweaty workouts they stay in unbelievably well and I barely notice they are there.

The main reason I'm writing this review is to point our some differences between these and the less expensive Elite 65t (not the Active model). I was very skeptical of Jabra's marketing, because the products almost seem identical. I went through 2 pairs of the standard 65t Elite before finally deciding to purchase the Active version. There is a huge difference between the two models. My two other pairs failed after around 2 months, with issue most likely related to moisture. In both cases, one of the headphones just stopped working completely. So far, the Actives have outlasted in that regard. Secondly and most importantly to me, while the two models appear the same, there is a tackier coating on the Active model that absolutely makes a difference for keeping them in place during activities like running. I had to reposition Elite 65t every few minutes while running and the Actives need to be repositioned every 30 minutes or so during intense activity.

That said, if you are unsure which model to get, and plan on using them for workouts, save your time and get the Elite Active model.

title: The complete package; robust connectivity, snug fit, above average audio quality
content:
Incredibly well honed functionality.

I bought these after I tried a competitor product, the Bose Sound Sport Free, mostly because of the pedigree of the name "BOSE". What a disappointment! The Bose were complete crap for countless reasons, but mostly because the community.bose.com support staff refuse to admit the problems this product obviously has, and it's real maddening watching them gaslight customers whose earbuds simply don't work.

Now let's talk about Jabra...

These pair easily on the first go. Whether it's to my phone (S8) or my computers, the pairing process was painless and it just worked. Contrast this to Bose, which would not pair to any computer I tried. It's an issue hundreds of Bose customers have, but their support staff deny that there is a problem. If you don't believe me, go look through the reviews here on Amazon, and take note when you hear someone complain about these not working with PCs.

It's hard not to talk about how bad my other experience was, to help highlight how GREAT the Jabras are. Another important plus: video syncs perfectly, with no perceptible lag. That's a big ticket item for these wire-free earbuds, and the Jabras perform flawlessly.

Another item is when the earbuds lose their communication to each other. Jabra handles this very gracefully, and you don't have to listen to a belabored error message voiced in the still-paired earbud while it looks for the other one. Having these in your ear, you can pull the left earbud out, and slowly draw it away from your head. At about 2ft it will lose the connection, automatically pausing your sound application. As you draw the earbud back closer to the right one again, toward your ear, it will re-pair, and unpause the audio. It's really fantastic, I can't stress enough how clear it is that Jabra did their homework making this product do the right thing. ROBUST!

They are light, and even though they don't have dedicated noise cancelling circuitry, their ergonomics do a great job being the right shape to naturally cup over my ear canal, and still feel very comfortable.

Audio quality is great. Disclaimer: I am not an audiophile, but I can hear when things clip, have low sample rates, or represent the sound source poorly in different frequency ranges.. These sound good and the companion app lets you specialize it all with a nice equalizer.

Don't be dumb. Buy them right now. :D

title: Like it
content:
Washing machine 18 min test - passed:)
Sound+ app - very bad((

title: Left earbud emits excessive white noise (known problem)
content: These earbuds are incredibly comfortable and have excellent sound quality! However, the left earbud emits an excessive amount of white noise when playing any sound through the earbuds, completely ruining the listening experience. I googled my issue and found that it is a problem that many customers are experiencing. There is a 'fix' of factory resetting the buds, going into the sound+ app, and updating the language. Unfortunately, this did not work and seems to work for only a select few. I am returning these and waiting for the 75ts to release, check their website and search for them on amazon and you'll see the improvements.

title: Want to love it but you can't
content:
Got these on Black Friday and was really looking forward to it.  Seemed like it had great reviews from every tech site.  I've been using these daily since November.  I really wanted to like these alot but now I've just gotten used to them and am stuck with them because I paid for them.  There are some solid pros but the cons have me depressed about these. So first with the pros:
Pros:
-Truly wireless. It is really nice not having to worry about wires getting caught or tugged.
-Functionality of button control. Real good ease of use with adjusting volume, answering calls, changing tracks
-Great for the gym. No worry about maneuvering your wires
-Battery life is actually really good. I usually have to charge the case once a week with the way I use them which is usually going to and from work and at the gym
-Mic quality is solid. People calling me have no trouble hearing me.

Now the dreaded cons:
1. The bluetooth quality sucks!!!!!! The connection keeps going in and out if the phone is in your pocket.  And it's very inconsistent. Doesn't matter what type of clothes material, pant pocket, jacket pocket.  And even if you have to hold your phone in your hand (which sucks in the winter), the swinging of your arm or if I turn my head will cause connection issues. This drives me nuts!!
2. Keeping these earbuds in for extended periods of time actually can start hurting my ears
3. The sound quality is mediocre at best. There is no bass in these headphones. I didn't realize it until I put on my wooden cased $30 headphones which have much better sound quality.
4. If you put the right ear bud on first, you have to really rush to put the left bud in. If not, then it only makes the right ear bud work. You gotta put it back in. Let it reset. And then try again. Its annoying.

I'm going to ride these out. Will use them exclusively at the gym. However, headphones are made to enjoy your music and I really can't with these headphones so will use my other wired headphones for my walks around the city. Won't buy these again unless they upgrade the connectivity issues and adjust the design.

title: Excellent earbuds
content:
As my first "true wireless earbuds", these have worked out great the first few days. Some things I've noticed:

1. Sound isolation. No one seems to mention this, but these isolate sound as well as some more expensive over the ear bose isolating headphones I've tried, probably because they form such a tight seal. The hear-through feature is really neat and does its job, but I almost wish it could be even more pronounced. I still had to turn the music down quite a bit to listen to conversations, but I'm spoiled to  the point where I would require some sort of "hear-through" feature on future headphones that isolate as well as these. Double-tapping the right earbud to initiate/turn off "hear-through" on earbuds is something I never knew I needed in my life until now.

2. Sound Quality. I'm not an audiophile but would rate these as "good". For reference I switch between wired Sennheiser HD 598 and Audio Technica M50x as my daily drivers. As expected with true wireless earbuds the soundstage doesn't begin to approach the Sennheisers, and the punchy richness isn't as detailed as the Audio Technicas. But they do sound better than my old Jaybird X2 bluetooth earphones, and the sound isolation these provide allowed me to focus on details I hadn't noticed before. They are crisp and clear, with a slight emphasis on the bass/low end and jabra has a great app that allows you to tweak the equalizer to presets such as speech, bass boost, treble boost, smooth, energize, or tweak it manually to your heart's desire, changing the EQ makes a bigger difference than anticipated. As a bonus, the Jabra app also has high quality "soundscapes" like ocean waves, cavern, rain, white noise etc. built in, a handy feature. Overall the Jabra app is definitely one of the better companion apps to all the headphone apps I've used, actually adding important functionality to the earbuds.

3. Call Quality. Testing these outside and inside with fairly minimal background noise, I've asked several callers how I sound and they say "great", one even remarked I sounded better than my cell phone. I can't say how these perform in noisy environments but in most typical settings these seem to perform above average.

4. Comfort. Several reviews mention these are super uncomfortable or don't fit their ear, I've had the opposite experience. They lock in like they were designed to perfectly accomodate my ears contours, and I don't have the slightest hesitation they'll fall out in vigorous workouts. They have definitely been fairly comfortable for me, even after hours of use. This seems to be the biggest random factor though depending on your ear's shape.

5. Build. These feel durable and I'm glad they went with a lighter, all plastic construction. They have an IP55 rating, meaning they are dust-resistant as well as resisting low-pressure water sprays. The buttons have raised ridges to raise/lower volume and are fairly tactile/easy to press. I don't like the feeling of using much pressure on the buttons to push even deeper in my ear canal, so slightly cushion them and press them "away" toward the top of my ear to relieve this feeling and has since not  been an issue. I definitely prefer buttons to 100% touch as they are easier/more responsive in my experience. The charging case is also nice and compact, and much smaller than other earbud cases I've researched, perfect for throwing in my pocket and taking anywhere.

Overall I would recommend these. After researching many brands, these check the most boxes for me as  one of the best "all-around" performers. They have good (probably not best sound quality), good call quality, a good bluetooth 5 connection, a good app, good water/dust protection, sound hear-through mode, good battery life, good  sound isolation, good control buttons, good design etc.

title: Prettyy good but not great.
content: The sound quality is on par with apple earphones. Maybe a little better. I like the look much better than airpods. One issue with the sound is that if you have the hear through option enabled, and you're not currently listening to anything or have something paused, it tends to skip sound for a second every minute or so. Also the casing is not the greatest. It feels like you have to put a bit of pressure on it to actually open and the tab for grip is pretty small. My brother bought this maybe a year ago and the tab on his case already wore off. It would have been much nicer if they just used a magnet to keep it closed.
