The sound quality may not match the Bose wireless buds I returned but I’m happier with these.  They never lose connection.  Both buds fully functional.

title: They get the job done.
content: No really impressive sound here, but they stay in your ears, and the buttons make sense. The battery seems to last forever. Perfect for all-day podcasts and audiobooks.

title: Great wireless earbuds, one of the few out there that can be used for phone calls.
content: It is great for phone calls, I'm by no means an audiophile but music and sound quality is above average by my standard. The hear through technology is awesome, and battery life is great. The only thing I'm not crazy about is the battery case. They way it opens is very stiff at first and kind of a pain to open and close until the plastic wears out a bit.

title: Bad right earbud try another wall charger!
content: I had the product for four days and the right earbud never ever charged. And the emails I got from the support team were..oh try a different wall charger. The most constant thing I got was that! My usb power station that charges all my mobile devices obviously isn’t built for this. So yeah after leaving the buds alone for eight hours much like I was instructed I’d get about ten seconds of. A song. Then the earbud would die. Good riddance.

title: Keeps dropping!!
content: Like others, my Jabras lose their connection even when the "broadcasting" unit (be it cell phone or otherwise) are in close proximity.  It has become so annoying that I reverted back to wired buds (but just ordered Samsung's new BT buds because of recent favorable reviews).  BTW, I did narrow the problem being with the Jabras by using other BlueTooth headsets, etc. with the same "broadcast" units and had ZERO dropouts even up to 30 feet.  I should have returned day one...now they're off to Goodwill or the landfill.  Sad...and at such a great cost!

title: Get AirPods.
content: If you’re going back and forth between these and AirPods, get AirPods. I’ve had these 6 months now and am already having problems. They don’t charge to 100% anymore. They were good when they worked but now the charge can’t be trusted. Get AirPods.

title: All around great product.
content: Bought these for my husband for Christmas and they are wonderful, good sound quality, easy to use, nice for talking on the phone hands free, and nice fit into my ear!

title: Intermittent Connectivity to Apple Watch
content:
Jabra's Active 65t struggled to maintain uninterrupted streaming while paired to the Apple Watch. Connection to the phone was better, but still noticed "crackling" while doing tasks near the paired device. Sound quality and fit are awesome for workouts and running---I did not have to readjust while running from sweat.

However, due to connectivity issues, I would stick with Apple AirPods for a casual settings and go with Bose SoundSport for workouts/running.

title: Fantastic
content: I was looking for a true wireless solution to use at the gym, working out on my indoor cycle trainer etc.  They are comfortable, fit very well (changed to the large ear part) and block noise pretty well.  I love the hear through feature, and use it in the office while listening to music.  Battery life has been as advertised and the charging case is convenient.  I would have loved to see the ear buds magnetically held in the charging case, but that's my only criticism.  I'd buy them again if I lost them.

title: I didn’t want to return them.......but.
content:
Great sound,easy operation, however, I had to send them back. After wearing them for 15 minutes, the right ear started to ache. The eartips are fine, but the plastic body of the 65t, after sitting in my ear they started to irritate the cartilage. My left ear was fine. I tried them again, a few times during the next couple of days but the same thing happened.
The Jabra Elite Active 65t sounded the best out of 2 other Bluetooth EarPods (different company, also not cheap) that I own.
I hated to return them.

title: I really enjoy these ear buds.
content: When I pull them out of the case most of the time they connect right to my phone. I put them in my ear and they tell me they've  connected and it shows me the battery percent on my phone whenever I want to know. If they go out I know I'm only 15 minutes away from enjoying them for several more hours as long as I made sure to charge the case that I feel is really what makes these ear buds possible and such a great experience to deal with. Not to mention they have high quality sound and noise cancellation like you would expect at something in this price range

title: The battery last a long time and the sound is great
content: I use them for when I go for walks and lite workouts. I like them because it sounds great and you can't heard outside noise

title: Awesome quality!
content: I use this when im working or at the gym and it has worked flawlessly. Fits really well, better than the samsung galaxy earbuds I had previously.

title: Would buy again
content: Cool ear buds. Charging case is handy. App is not bad. Features are great.

title: Secure fit, great sound, good bluetooth connection
content:
The short:
- Fit (5/5): Snug, comfortable fit that held up to a 5-mile run without ever becoming loose or falling out.
- Sound Quality (5/5): Excellent sound quality
- Bluetooth Connectivity (4.5/5): 2 brief episodes of Bluetooth connection loss (less than 2 seconds each) in 5+ hours of use.

The long:
I picked these up at Costco a few days ago and was a little apprehensive about them because several reviewers have mentioned unreliable bluetooth connection. But Costco's return policy makes trying them out virtual zero-risk, and since they were the only wireless earbuds they carried, I decided to give them a whirl. So far, I've had a very positive experience with the product:

Fit (5/5):
These earbuds are the "earplug" style (as opposed to the hanging, loose earbud style of Airpods). The earplug style buds have always fit my ears better than Airpods and the like, which fall out of my ears with even modest head movements. In contrast, these earbuds held firmly yet comfortably in my ears for a 5-mile run. They also come with different sized plugs, which helps get the right fit.

Sound Quality (5/5):
Really happy with the sound quality. Nice, full-bodied sound. The only thing I've noticed is that deep bass doesn't come through fully, but I've literally never had earbuds that managed to deliver bass well, and I think that's just a limitation of the small size.

Bluetooth Connectivity (4.5/5):
Other reviewers mentioned the connection dropping frequently, which was my primary concern in buying the product. So far, in 5+ hours of use, it dropped very briefly 2 times for less than 2 seconds each time and spontaneously reconnected. Not perfect, but certainly not a dealbreaker. It also doesn't seem to be related to distance, as both drops happened with my phone in my hand. Conversely, I had my phone connected to a charger in my room and was able to walk freely around my (admittedly small) house without any drops in connection. So it seems to maintain connection over a pretty good distance.

Ease of Use/Ease of setup (4.5/5):
The setup was exceptionally easy. Like 2 steps and 60 seconds of work, and you're good to go. Using the product is pretty simple too; my only issue is that the buttons on the left earbud are fairly small and I find myself fumbling around trying to hit the correct button. They do have small, raised dots on each button that act as tactile guides, but they are very small. It would be nice if the whole button were slightly raised to make locating it easier. Or maybe I'm just ill-coordinated.

Longevity/Durability (???/5):
To be determined. I have not owned them long enough to make a good assessment

I will try to remember to update this review later.

title: Overall - Highly Recommended
content:
My ears are a special case and most earbuds just fall off, no matter what size eartip I use. I am very reluctant to buy earbuds for that reason and so far the apple standard earbuds have worked the best for me, especially while working out.

Having said that, the 65t work pretty well. Not perfect, but they hold well. I'm still on the fence for fit but I am pretty sure the problem is with my ears, not with these earbuds.

What I really like about these is the sound quality though. They did an amazing job over at Jabra with these! Pretty remarkable.

Other than that, there's a nice app and connectivity works well - but sometimes the left earbud won't work and I found that putting them back in the case and then back in my ears fixes that. weird and quite annoying but it doesn't happen that much (so far).

Once these are plugged into my ears, they are very comfortable and can be worn for a long time with no discomfort at all. I have not tried them yet while running or biking so wonder how they hold up. With biking, there's a risk that they fall of and will be very hard to find so I'll have to see about that.

the case maybe a little too thick for a pocket, I wish they had made it a little more compact but overall it's far from being a huge case (about 2/3 the size of a credit card in length and hight but obviously thicker...)

title: Love them but uncomfortable
content: I have small ears - smaller than most people. The earbuds are GREAT but they do not fit me well. My husband can wear them comfortably and have no issues. The fit on me isn't great so they fall out and sometimes hurt after a while. Going to keep then for my husband but need to keep looking for me.

title: Great while it worked, but customer support is truly terrible
content:
These were wonderful for the three months they lasted. Great sound, long battery life, quick to connect, decent microphone sound. For truly wireless earbuds, they were fantastic.

Then at three months the volume on one earbud dropped to the point that it was impossible to use both earbuds at the same time -- either one earbud was too dim to hear, or the other one was too loud to withstand. Tried resetting, updating the firmware, reinstalling the app, changing the language on the earbuds, but nothing helped, so contacted customer support. Took them two weeks to get back to me, telling me to file a warranty claim. Then no further response for over another month in spite of me sending them several follow up emails. Out of the blue, about two months after I first contacted them, I get a shipping notification for a replacement earbud. That was one month ago now, and today I received a notice letting me know that the part is still backordered, and won't be available for shipping for at least another month (with the added kicker that they included a different customer's information on their email to me... any EU citizens might want to follow up under GDPR with Jabra...). In the off chance they actually ship it then, it'll be four months to resolve something that, from what the forums seem to suggest, is a relatively common technical problem with these earbuds. That's longer than these earbuds worked for.

The earbuds might be great, but Jabra's customer support is completely unresponsive -- likely understaffed, underfunded, and undervalued in the company. This was my first Jabra product and, thanks to the company's approach to (not providing) customer support, it's my last as well.

title: Great gift
content: I ordered these earbuds for Christmas for my son and he absolutely love them. He uses them when he is at the gym or just studying or listening to music. He says they are airtight ,and  he can hear everything clearly

title: Pleased and suprised
content: I love these headphones. I will say that they took time to get used to how to get them in and out of my ear comfortably, but now that I have the hang of it, I love them. I commute 1 1/2 hours each way and have never ever had a battery issue. I have gotten feedback that people sometimes can't hear me on the phone, but I don't have long conversations, I use them mostly for music and podcasts. I would recommend these to friends and family. And I like how they look in, not too big or bulky and not like those stupid Apple ones with the white stick hanging out of your ear. I will also say that these do pause/stop working when I go through the subway turnstile. Must be a frequency thing, but it is super quick. . . I use these with my iPhone. Received these as a gift and was happier with them than I initially expected.

title: Had the common issue with left earbud quitting. Customer service replaced them for free.
content:
EDIT 11/2/2019: I got a better review from customer support. After the generic "reinstall firmware" advice, I told them that it didn't work, and they sent me a prepaid return label to send it back to them. Once they received the defective pair, they sent me a new pair that work well. I have done a little research, and it sounds like this issue with the left earbud quitting is actually quite common. I'm wondering if I'll have to repeat this process again at some point in the future. Either way, it looks like it's worth it to register the earbuds in order to get the two-year warranty. I'm giving them three stars for a known issue and the hassle, but they did make it right.

Well, I have had these for not quite a year, and the left earbud has completely quit on me. I sent an email to customer support and got a generic "reinstall firmware" email that did nothing. These earbuds were amazing, but I cannot recommend them if they cannot last more then a few months. I'm very disappointed, I spent a lot of money on reliable earbuds, and here I am with a defective pair. I will update this review if a get a better response from customer support.

title: TERRIBLE call quality! This makes a $5 earbud mic feel like a studio mic.
content:
I wish I had seen reviews on the Jabra 65T Elite's call quality. The person on the other end of the call will hear EVERY bit of background noise. Calls are extremely poor in any place but a dead silent room. Conversations/sound from even 20+ feet away would drive the other person on the call insane. This is completely unacceptable since cheap $5 headphones would produce 100x better calls. The associate even noted that these headphones would have better call quality (obviously knew nothing of this product).

I have HUGE BUYERS REMORSE and can only HOPE an update is released to fix this issue. I will update this review if that ever happens but, until then I do NOT recommend buying this product. *I did buy mines from Best Buy, hence no verified purchase.

title: Battery life is not as promised
content: The fit is fine with the optional ear covers and you'll eventually figure out what is best for you. The noise cancellation is nearly zero unless you can somehow manage a perfect (and I mean perfect) fit in the ear. I cannot cut grass and use these as the engine noise overwhelms the earbuds. The range is pretty good, but easily interrupted by just about any obstruction so I'd rate range lower on the scale. My biggest complaint is the battery life versus the claimed battery life. They promote 5 hours of battery life and I can assure you you'll be lucky to get half of that if in continuous use situations. I use mine almost everyday and have never gotten more the 2.5 hours. From the other reviews 3 hours seems to be the norm. All that said, they're functional and pretty reliable although I would try a different brand for my next set.

title: High sound quality & noise canceling
content: Love the sound quality for music and general conversations. One comment from people on the other end of my phone calls referenced significant background noise, particularly in open or crowded spaces (offices, airports, etc). Although my sound quality and clarity is strong, the challenge is for the receiver being able the hear my voice without having to raise it to a slight yell.  The background noise can be a major distraction. However, In quiet spaces, it’s perfect. I use it it in flight, in my office and while working out. The earbuds stay put! And I particularly enjoy the noise canceling modes that allow some or zero external noise/sound. Worth the spend.

title: Great sound quality
content: I love these earphones...and they don’t look like a q tip dangling out of your ear.

title: Great for home, office, or a run
content:
Whether I'm listening to podcasts with the noise cancelation at work or jogging in active mode, these never fall out or need to be adjusted and deliver quality sound.

I have had some say they can hear a difference in voice quality when I answer a call but nothing detrimental.

When I run, I sweat. Not an issue so far and I like that I can listen to both or turn the left off easily as well as active and deactivate the noise cancelation with a couple taps. So far, best pair I have owned.

title: Love these buds, thanks to amazon for great price and fast delivery
content: Nothing

title: UPDATE
content:
Bought these for my husband! He loves them. He uses them every single day at work. The carrying case charges them. They automatically pause when you take one out. He did tons of research before deciding he wanted these.

****UPDATE***** After 8 months of use the left ear bud has started dropping in volume to the point of barely being able to hear anything in it. I contacted Jabra customer support, which has been useless. Back and forth multiple times, they gave me troubleshooting instructions, all of which have not worked. They then requested I send them a PHOTO of them.... I am unsure how a photo will fix these broken earbuds. All I wanted was a replacement. I won't buy another Jabra item.

I cannot walk more than 1 block without them falling out.  If I make any facial movements it falls out faster.  I watched YouTube videos about the proper way to put them in and twist, I tried all nubs... nothing helped.  I returned them.  Way too expensive for something so frail that I can't even walk around with.

P.S.  I even tried sitting at my desk wearing them and again, any facial movement and it loosens and falls out even when not walking around.

title: Good sound, and comfortable; but don't stay put when active
content:
I gave up on my Bragi The Headphones after the second pair failed. I'd heard similar complaints about the two buds losing contact in Jaybird's RUN, which would normally have been my second choice, and I ended up trying the Jabra Elite 65t instead.

They sound great, and they're comfortable to wear for a long time. Unfortunately, they don't stay in my ears when I'm active, and after stopping to locate and pick them up a few times, I think I'm going to give the RUN a try after all. Still, if you're just sitting or walking around, you could do a lot worse than the Elite 65t; and ears are different; they might fit yours better than they fit mine.

title: Best mic quality
content:
This is the best set, out of three I tried, of wireless headphones I’ve come across.

I walk a lot outside while I’m on the phone and they’re hands down the best at cancelling out wind.

They’re also the best at providing a clear vocal projection from the microphone and really minimize the “tunnel effect” which makes you sound far away on wireless headsets.

Still a little pricey, but if you want the best quality they blow the apple AirPods and the comparable tribits out of the water.

title: VERY GREAT PRODUCT!!!!!
content: I've had these for a while now and I'm very picky when it comes to sound, functionality, comfort, battery life, etc. because I am a DJ. I use these all of the time for everything. The thing that I like most about these is that I can control the volume, and I can skip or go back to a track just using the left pod and having to take my phone out to do so like I did with other pods. It's a bummer when you're working out or running and you have to get your phone out to change the song because the song that came on sucks. With just the touch of a button, it's changed. My workouts last about 4hrs a day and the pods last that long or close to it depending on how loud your volume is. Of course I like mine loud so it's a give or take on the battery life. Sweat during my workout isn't even an issue. They play right through the sweat. The charging pod is amazing. Every true wireless ear pods that I've owned, the charging pod has broken and they don't have many charges in the before they need charging themselves. With the volume maxed out, the sound quality is still there. There's no distortion or anything. Very balanced sound and it puts you in the zone (at least for me it does). There's more than one inner ear cushion and if those doesn't work for you, simply buy some more that fit your ear because everyone's ear is different and what they provide may not fit your ear. I'd just hate for you to miss out on a great quality and sounding product because of something as simple as that. The microphone is pretty good to me. People can hear me with a little background noise but nothing major to complain about. In my opinion, you can't go wrong with this product.

title: Amazing Sound, Secure fit and great features
content:
The sound quality is 1000 times better than the $40 pair of generic ones I owned last and is on par with my Grado Sr80e's headphones.
The ability to isolate the music from the outside world is truly fantastic on these earbuds!  The "past through" feature works well on lower volumes, were I can carry on conversations just fine. However when the volume is 50% or more the effect isn't as noticeable and you would have trouble hearing conversation level noises, but you will hear things like a car honking or a cup falling for example. It gives yo the option to have the music turn off when "pass through" is turned on(double tap right ear bud), that way if someone wants to talk you don't have to turn down the music or take out the buds!
Bass is very good and can be made very loud and deep with the included apps EQ controls.
ONLY small negative is the volume buttons on the left side are a little hard to activate and you have to push hard enough to create some small discomfort,  I just leave them on high and use my phones buttons.
Overall I would buy them again in a heart beat. Mine were Amazon Refurbished and they came in "new" condition.

title: what keeps me from rating these earbuds with 5 stars?
content:
Great Earbuds!
Here is the good news:
These buds connected flawlessly the moment I removed them from the charging case.
took a few minutes to pick the correct size tips for my ears. it's imperative to get the correct size in order to have an excellent tight fit so the sound will be loud and the base will be very good.
if you have a smart watch like I do and like to listen to music while at the gym, be sure you pair the buds using the bluetooth on the watch first before setting up your Jabra using the Sound + App that you downloaded for your smart phone.
I love everything about these earbuds except the three Silicon eartips supplied by Jabra. I can only wear them for no more than 45 minutes at a time because they really hurt my ears. I called the Jabra technicians and asked " don't your engineers wear these before releasing them to the public"??
I called Comply.com and asked if they have the foam tips for the Jabra Elite Active 65t? they told me they are working on it and for me to check back on their website in about a month.
Other than the discomfort of Jabra's Silicon eartips, I highly recommend these outstanding earbuds. Come on Jabra, fix the eartips and you will get five stars for sure.
UPDATE 07/11/2018: As one reviewer noted earlier, the eartips are fine, but the plastic body of the 65t, after sitting in my ears for about 45 minuets  started irritating the cartilage of both my ears. I don't know what can be done to stop that from occurring.

title: Not just great sound. Practical features make a profound difference to the user experience.
content: Let me start by stating that I’m sort of a Bluetooth headphone junkie. Given how subjective the audio quality experience is, over the years I’ve accumulated upwards of 15 or so BT headphones in all form factors due to trial and error attempts to find perfection. I’ve never felt motivated and compelled to write any reviews on any of them until now. This will probably give you some foreshadowing of how impressed I am with these buds. In terms of pure sound quality, the very best I’ve personally purchased and used are a pair of over the ear Sony MDRXB950BT cans with bass boost. Those monsters are simply amazing, but living in Phoenix I can only listen to them in the winter outside because over the ears are just too hot for me in the summer. Hence the quest to find anything close in an in-ear form factor. Now, I also proudly own a set of Powerbeast3 wireless headphones with the wire tether between the ear buds. That set is fantastic for sound quality and battery life. However, I simply can’t put up with the wire catching on my often sweaty neck in the gym or on the driving range. Enter the Jabari Elite 65t. After experimenting with a few cheapie sub-30 dollar “true wireless” headsets that left me gagging with disgust at the audio quality, I decided to up my game and go after the Jabra’s based on the 4 microphone design intended to dramatically improve transmitted audio quality on phone calls along with the reported excellent audio quality for playback. After a week of use, I’m here to claim that these buds are the gold standard for Android compatible in-ears with true wireless capability. If you want to know how I arrive at this conclusion, let me argue that Iron Hand by Dire Straits and Water Under the Bridge by Adele are but two of many, many examples of songs that simply destroy in-ear buds in general. I’m not claiming that the bass sections of these songs are as impressive in the Jabra’s as they are in the overl-the-ear Sony’s, but at the very least you can recongize it as the same song! Actually, the full frequency range of the Jabra’s is quite surprising and exceptional for the size. I’ve searched a long time for just this attribute, and then come the extras. Over multiple sets of BT buds, I’ve never found a set where folks I’ve called didn’t complain about not hearing me well on phone calls. With the Jabra’s so far, no one has even been able to tell the difference between standard cell phone calls and BT ear bud calls. They’re that good. Finally, the devil is in the details. The Jabra Elite 65t includes two features that completely ice the cake: Hear Through and Sidetone. The first lets you adjust how much ambient sounds you hear while playing music and the second lets you hear yourself while on a phone call. Both are slider adjustable through the companion phone app so that they can be fine tuned to your preference. This is a game changer in comfortable usability of the product. So, to summarize, exceptional sound quality for the form factor and at least reminiscent of top line over-the-ear cans for frequency range with outstanding usability as a phone call accessory. I haven’t even mentioned their support of either Amazon Alexa or Google Assistant for voice commands, preferring to save that as a very pleasant Easter Egg for those willing to take the plunge. Cheers and happy jamming.

title: Minor problem combined with poor customer support = major problem.

title: Alexa integration is Perfect!
content:
Purchased these back in April'18. Till then these are my only buds i'm using. i tend to change earbuds very frequent and own a bunch of branded headphones and earbuds but after owning these i never looked back. i use them during travel to work, during work, in gym and in home on weekends and making calls daily. these just integrated in to my lifestyle. good thing is even though i go to 9/10 on treadmill these just sticks to my ear. I recently tried and started using Alexa integration and came to know how much i missed that wonderful feature these long days. So far, I'm satisfied with the audio and call quality.

Drawback:
Most of my friends complain during call they hear the surrounding noise as clear as my voice. talking on a silent Environment is totally fine but if you are a person who talks during walk or at public stations the person on other end will just scream of that sounds. even if you are washing something in kitchen and talking on a call that sound will be transmitted to them in a high pace. i hope, jabra fixes this bug and target on human voice instead of just enhancing the sound the headphones receive.

title: I had high hopes for this one
content:
After a disappointing experience with the Samsung Gear IconX and after watching and reading many reviews of the Jabra Elite 65t earbuds I had high hopes.

Unfortunately, those hopes quickly died. I received my first pair of earbuds (that's right, first) and I immediately encountered issues with a loud hissing noise coming from the left earbud. I contacted Jabra support and they were quick to answer and attempted to fix the issue. I did a reinstall of the firmware but the problem still persisted.

I liked the way these earbuds fitted so I wanted to give them another shot. I placed an order for a replacement and received it the following day. I was greeted by a box that was clearly already open. The earbuds were definitely not brand new. So now, I had to get a replacement for my replacement. I received the new set of earbuds today (this is my third pair for those who are counting) and found it to have the exact same issue as pair number one. Even after updating the firmware.

Needless to say I'm very disappointed by the audio quality of this earbuds. Specially when the build quality and comfort levels were above the Samsung Gear IconX. I also learned that his is a persistent problem that's been happening on this particular set of earbuds at least since October of 2018. I supposed it's back to finding a good pair of wireless earbuds.

title: Great battery life, but otherwise terrible design and worth less than 1/4 the price
content:
Quick Summary:
The audio quality is only as good as true-wireless earphones less than 1/3 the price, connectivity is middling and requires multiple special apps, the physical buttons are stiff and from a low-end product 2 years ago, the charging case doesn't work well and is very hard to get open, and the fit of the earphones in the ears is only slightly above average.  However they do have a lot of features, the passive noise isolation is good, and they have extremely long battery life for true-wireless earphones.  I can't speak to the voice-pickup and voice-isolation of these, which seems to be an off-target feature for true-wireless headphones and their primary claim of quality.

Fit & Feel
----
The earphones themselves are a bit on the larger side for true-wireless earphones, but that's the trade-off for the battery life they provide.  They also don't stick out of your ears like you're the Communications Officer from the Original Star Trek like Bose and Senhauser products do.  They do fit into the arches of your ear very well and comfortably, and seat incredibly solidly.  As long as you have the correct ear-tip that actually fits just into your ear canal as instructed, they fit solidly into your ear with no worries about them coming loose or falling out even under vigorous exercise.
The ear-tips are a bit oddly formed though relative to the industry standard.  They have a more trapezoidal-shape to them rather than a partial-sphere-shape, and it's noticeable in how they feel within your ears.  I'm not sure if the ear-tip shape is supposed to provide better passive noise isolation, but it has no noticeable difference for me, and it actually causes extra pressure within the ears. I've found that the best measure of in-ear headphone quality is how comfortable your ears feel during extended wear, and these Jabras have come up a bit lacking.  I've tried some other true-wireless headphones and been able to wear them completely comfortably for 3+ hours sitting at a desk, at the gym, or on a run.  With the Jabras, my ears start feeling a bit pressed on the inside at around 1.5 hours and I feel like I need to take a break from them to let my ears relax.  I've heard others call this feeling an "itchy" feeling in the ear, and that also describes it well.  This is roughly what I get from middling-quality in-ear headphones made by any manufacturer and not what I'd expect from a product anywhere near this price point.
These earphones also emit a slightly concerning heat from the inner side of them when in use.  It almost feels like the battery inside each earphone gets pretty warm during use, enough that it's noticeable around the area of the earphone body where the battery contacts are located.  I thought I was crazy at first, but I took them out to check, and the inner side of them was definitely noticeably above skin-surface temperature.  It's not hot enough that it's uncomfortable, just noticeable and worth mentioning.  It very well might be related to the "in-ear detection" feature that can be used to auto-pause since I don't see any visible sensors on the inside of the earphones other than the over-sized battery contacts that might be doubling as a resistive sensor.

Controls
----
The control scheme on these earphones is pretty much bland-standard for any Bluetooth device, you have an up and down button on one earphone, and a multi-function button on the other.  The up and down button primarily control volume, but on a long press do next and previous.  The multi-function button is largely a play-pause toggle, or when a call comes in it's a tap to accept and double-tap to reject button.  If you're not on a call, you can also double-tap to toggle the HearThru mode, and long press to trigger the voice assistant.  With an up and down button on an earphone that may be oriented at a different angle for every person, they've smartly added little tactile tick marks to indicate where the center of the up and down areas are.  However instead of the buttons truly being oriented in something approaching an up and down, they're oriented along an upper-back to lower-forward diagonal that will never vary enough from individual to individual to actually approximate up and down or forward and back.  Furthermore, standard control organization generally associates the same functionality with up and forward, and with down and back.  This mixes that up so it always takes a second to think about whether you're pushing an "up" button or a "back" button when you press the upper-back button, buttons that would normally have exactly oppposite effects.
Unfortunately they seem to have tried to shy away from the capacitive/resistive touch buttons completely with this product, instead using stiff physical buttons.  While this makes it less likely you'll accidentally press a button, it works very poorly for true-wireless headphones.  Unlike most headphones, true-wireless headphones have no structure to resist you pushing the earphone deeply into your ear when you have to push a physical button.  With stiff buttons, this problem is even worse.  These earphones are clearly made by someone who doesn't understand that at all, because pushing any of the buttons at all requires enough force to be distinctly uncomfortable both in your ear canal and the area outside your ear.  Double tapping actually becomes nearly impossible because each press moves the earpiece so significantly out of position and into the flesh of your head, that your finger motion is more than that necessary for a key on a standard computer keyboard.  Releasing the button enough to then press it again while trying to blindly maintain your finger's orientation relative to the earphone is extremely difficult as a result, which is the very reason all modern manufacturers use touch-sensitive buttons that require minimal finger motion to tap and double-tap.

Battery Life & Connectivity
----
The battery life on these true-wireless headphones is hugely beefy compared to all other products in the market.  Unfortunately that's not as big a benefit as most people would think, and it seems to largely be a necessity for support of some of the "unique" features they provide.  Most true-wireless headphones have a continuous battery life of about 2-4 hours before they need to be recharged, depending on the product, the volume they're used at, the distance from the phone, and other various specialty features they may have.  Listening to music sitting at a desk with my phone next to me and HearThru mode disabled, I've had these last 6 hours and still report 25% battery life remaining.  However the HearThru mode that plays ambient noise thru the earphones to allow situational awareness seems to have a huge impact on battery life, doing the same with HearThru enabled put me down to 25% battery life in just 3 hours.  However, considering this puts them on the upper end of the industry standard battery life even when a battery hogging feature is on, that's quite impressive.  I haven't test what the impact to battery life is if the step counting mode is also turned on, or if you're mostly making phone calls instead of listening to music/podcasts.  I also haven't tested the impact on battery when you're about 6 feet away from your phone on average and occasionally walk 20 feet away from it to grab something (like when I go to the gym).  However the existing tests do seem to indicate a very respectable battery life could be expected.
Connectivity quality of these earphones is unfortunately a bit shoddy, though not as bad as budget true-wireless devices from years past.  The earphones do consistently and unerringly connect to each other, which is much better than some products, but seem to have issues with the connection to the phone.  This might be an effect of how they've been forced to setup their connection with the phone to support some of their "unique" features, but it's generally unacceptable.  Like almost all true-wireless earphones, one of the earphones is a master device and one's a slave, with the slave earphone connecting only to the master earphone while the master earphone connects to the slave and whatever other devices your "headphones" are connected to.  Like most Bluetooth headphones in general, this requires putting the "headphones" (the master earphone) into a pairing mode, then searching for it as a new device on your phone.  Also like most nice Bluetooth "headphones" that support being paired with multiple devices simultaneously, once paired the "headphones" will maintain a prioritized list of devices with preference given to the most recently paired.  Given the connection issues between the master earphone and the phone however, this process can be rather onerous.  Almost 50% of the time I've used these earphones I've had to forget the device on my phone and repair it to access the "advanced" features it provides.  While I've never had any issues that required re-pairing when just using them like regular headphones, any voice assistant functionality, HearThru toggle, or EQ setting changes (I've never tried the step counting), have required re-pairing the devices so the Jabra apps recognize it properly and provide these functions.  This appears to occur because Jabra actually requires two apps be installed to use the extra features of their earphones, one app to modify the settings and one app to intercept what your earphones send to your phone so it can determine if that should modify your settings, toggle the customizable voice assistant, etc.

Sound & Audio Quality
----
For such a high-cost device, the playback quality on these earphones is suprisingly mediocre, even among true-wireless headphones.  The customizeable EQ settings allow you to add a little more bass or treble, or whatever you feel might be lacking in default output of most headphones, but even cranked to the extremes of the EQ range, none of the differences seem hugely different from the default flat EQ.  In comparison to low-end Bose wireless headphones (not true-wireless Bose) that cost less than these, these Jabra earphones sound completely standard rather than anything approaching high-end or premium like they claim.  They do do a decent job of passive noise isolation, but once again it's only about average.  A number of other average in-ear headphones, wired, wireless, and true-wireless, all have unnoticeably different passive noise isolation.  This includes devices that are less than 1/6th the cost of these Jabra earphones.
It seems one of Jabra's major claims with these is that they provide premium levels of voice isolation with these earphones for when you're talking in a call.  I'm not sure why they've decided to focus on this, since true-wireless earphones aren't really intended for this purpose and are notoriously bad at it during the best of times.  I personally have no use for this, I'll switch to my Plantronics wireless headset that gives me 10x the quality for 1/2 the price if I need voice isolation from the mic.  In fact, them implementing the isolation via 2 mics in each of the earphones working together seems like an odd choice, since most people jumping on a call where they'd need the voice isolation from the mic probably don't want to fiddle with independently putting two separate devcies in their ears and will likely want to put in only the single master device so you can better hear yourself, which won't give you as good of voice isolation.  Furthermore, the focus on voice isolation from the mic seems to have strongly negatively impacted the HearThru feature that seems much more useful to me.

"Unique" Features
----
Alexa as a voice assistant.  Unless you specifically want Alexa as your voice assistant, this actually makes the product worse.  The Bluetooth standard has a common way to trigger the native voice assistant so almost any Bluetooth 5.0 device can do it without an app being required on your phone.  Jabra is trying to make it configurable to select between triggering your native voice assistant (Siri or Google Assistant) and Alexa.  This means they have to use and intercept a non-standard Bluetooth command from the earphones that gets interpreted by the settings app to trigger the right one.  Given the extreme connectivity issues with this intercepting application, it means that instead of simply losing the ability to use some of the highly specialized features they provide, you're also losing the ability to trigger the native voice assistant when the connectivity fails.  If they weren't supporting Alexa as an optional voice assistant, they could use the standard Bluetooth 5.0 command that would always trigger the native voice assistant.

HearThru.  A great idea, allowing situational awareness by replaying the ambient noises without delay so you can effectively cancel the passive noise isolation.  This isn't a unique feature to Jabra, other products like the Samsung Gear X have it also.  Unfortunately Jabra's focus on voice isolation from the mics seems to have severely degraded this much more useful feature.  The audio that comes thru when HearThru mode is enabled is tinny, slightly staticy, and quiet.  It's bad enough that the feature is barely useful, only serving to let you hear particularly loud noises that would normally be reduced to minor background noises by the passive noise isolation of the ear-tips. Most importantly, this doesn't work well enough to enable it and actually have a conversation with someone without feeling like you can't hear yourself, meaning it doesn't implement Jabra's "Hear yourself in calls" feature for real-world interactions.

Hear yourself in calls.  If you're actually trying to use both earphones while in a call, you are going to have problems with the passive noise isolation making your voice sound weird to yourself.  It makes a lot of sense to replay your voice in your own ears in this case.  If you're also going to have heavy voice isolation from the mic, it also makes a lot of sense to supply that audio instead of all ambient audio while you're in the call.  This seems like a minimum necessary feature if someone is actually going to use these earphones for making calls.

Auto-pause on removal.  An interesting feature that doesn't rely on connectivity with the app.  Since the earphones only have a button capable of pausing on the right ear, this makes a lot of sense for the left ear.  Since the button on the right ear is stiff and hard to press, it also makes some sense for the right ear.  This feature could be made completely unnecessary if the buttons were less stiff and a way to pause were provided from both earphones like most products have.
