content: I really wanted to like these but they aren't very comfortable and after 15 minutes they hurt my ears. It is also really annoying that the left doesn't work without the right. So basically the only one that ever gets used is the right one.

title: Too large for most women’s ears
content: These are made for large ears. It’s insane that you can’t find a decent pair of wireless earbuds that are meant for smaller ears. I’m an active woman and I care about sound quality just as much as the next guy. But for some reason, if I want wireless earbuds, the only companies willing to accommodate small ears are on the lower end of the quality spectrum. Even with the smallest rubber fitting, I couldn’t fit these into my ears. They are comically large. This review won’t matter to most guys, but maybe I can save most women’s time. A couple of off-brands that will fit your ears - but lack decent sound quality -  are EnodMini Ring and Enacfire. They aren’t great - they cut out and the battery life is only 2-3 hours tops - but they’ll fit your ears.

title: Cut the cord!
content: I wear these too much. I love them. I especially like making calls with them. When I really want noise cancelled tho, I use my over the ear Sony headphones.

title: comfortable and connects to 2 devices at the same time
content: I got this as a birthday present. I can't use Apple earbuds- they make my eardrums hurt. These are very comfortable. I love getting up from desk without ripping my headphones out. I love being to answer a phone call while I listening to music on my computer - it just smoothly switches over. It can be a little clunky switching back which is the only complaint I have. Battery life is great. I ended up using the smallest rubber inserts for my ears. They never fall out!! Oh, one other issue is that I mostly listen to Amazon Music but Bluetooth on my Mac seems to want to start iTunes all the time. My husband uses Apple earbuds and he says the same thing happens to him SO it's not Jabra. I love these earbuds so much!

title: Not for me
content: Not as expected from the hype and reviews. I don’t have any other wireless ear buds to compare it too. I have wired ear buds and over head wireless earphones which sounds great. I wasn’t impressed by these. Working out in the gym, it fell out my ear a few times. Not worth the price.

title: Great sound, great fit, great overall, ear gels breaks easily
content: overall this product is superb the only problem is that the ear gels breaks easily, I replace them twice while I was trying to find the fit and now the withe part is separated from the red part completely, the replacement tip is 9 dls a pair, too expensive for the quality.

title: Expected much more
content:
Cons: The right ear is slightly quieter than the left side, making the sound come out as unbalanced. It's very distracting and is the main reason for the low score.

The case is poorly designed. It's tough to open, the ear pieces don't snap in like other cheaper headphones, it uses the micro-usb which is nearly obsolete (but the design isn't  new so it's under), and the case can't even stand up correctly.

Pros: Fits very snug in your ear, causing good noise isolation (these are NOT noise canceling headphones). The Jabra+ app is nice and decent features.

title: Great so far.
content: The battery life for these headsets is crazy! Also, the quality of the audio for phone conversations is incredible.  I just wish the phone app let you modify the audio at your own taste instead of having pre-loaded equalizer set-up's.

title: like them a lot
content: Great stuff

title: Love
content: Love this kind of product

title: Connectivity is very sensitive
content: For almost $200, it is very sensitive to motion. Slight movements of it while in ear will cut off sound or pause video because it thinks it is being removed. Cuts video or pauses videos while just wearing the earbuds is very common. Can’t tell if it’s a malfunction or just how the Bluetooth technology is at currently. Been having it less than a week btw.

title: Great headphones!
content: I love these headphones! The first time I put them on I felt nauseous but it was just because it was a different feeling than I’m used to. By day 2 I was perfectly fine with them, and now I use them regularly. They come with different silicone pieces to fit them to your ear, and you can use just the right headphone if you want only one. The battery life is great. Overall great purchase!

title: Good sound when you get good fit
content: Sound is very good when using right size buds - I had to switch to large to get good bass response. Sound isolation is also good. They are comfortable and don’t shift around when walking around town. Phone use is just okay. Location of the mic so far from mouth seems to pick up background noise along with what I’m saying. Not a big deal because I use these as headphones 95% of the time.

title: Jabra 65t are the one to buy.
content: Best overall in price range.  Excellent easy phone app w/lots of options, my favorite is 6 tonal presets plus 5 band graphic equalizer.  Nice easy to read owners manual and instructions in app.  Lots of control with earbud touch controls, easy to use and actually work well just hard to remember all the options they provide.  Didn't test call audio but these have very good reviews.  Zero connections so far and I've tried lots of ways to see if they fail.  Even tested extremely close to wi-fi router to see if I could reproduce the left bud hissing issue.  None whatsoever.  Decent battery life w/ 2 recharges in case.  Even though slightly larger than Galaxy Buds about same comfort level.  About 1 hour for me.  Had more consistent ear seals and bottom end than Galaxy Buds but thought Galaxy Buds sounded slightly better but had to reseal the buds all the time.  Biggest downside on these is not much at all but would include no wireless charging and antiquated USB micro charge connector.  Ironically reviews said it was likely to have left bud hiss issues and connectivity issues but have had none.  It was actually the Galaxy Buds I returned because of connectivity issues.  Also, these have a 2 yrs warranty against dust/water damage, they are IP56 rated.

title: Amazing earphones!!! highly recommend
content:
Ok so this might be an early review since I just got them this morning, So I will give an update if anything changes.
A friend recommended these and i'm very picky about my earphones especially with sound and most importanly comfort and fit since i work, i hate headphones/earphones that pop out. We i decided to finally get them because my Bose sound sport, although great headphones i eventually got tired of the cord.
  These 65t right off the package felt high quality, pairing took 10 seconds, the default earbuds fit perfectly, and the app you can download to make changes is very easy to use.
Sound: Many have said that sounds is pretty decent, coming from bose where i had raise the volume almost all the way up to get good sound, these have much better volume. Noice cancellation works really well and if youre not a fan of it you can always turn it off. Default sounds is actually great, if your a bass freak then youll deff want to adjust the sounds with the equalizer youll notice a small difference but still good. im very happy with Sound
 Fit: as i mentioned earlier these fit amazingly well right out the box so unless you have huge earholes or tiny they have spare earbuds to change to. I run and work out, i havent even tested them out at the gym yet but i can already tell you these will not fall out. i'm extremely happy on that aspect. Comfort will take some getting used to as any other new heaphones so give it some time for your ear to adjust to them.
App: extremely easy to use, not too many options to figure out but the ones on there area very useful. i like hearing ambient sounds when i sleep so i was excited when i see they have an option, big plus for me, shows battery life. Win!
Connection: these paired very fast and easy. i did loose sound to my left ear but i took it off and back on real quick and fixed it. i'm not bothered by it, hopefully it wont happen again. quick fix i'm not bothered by it.
Overall: Yea, maybe my review is not as great as other users but if the other 5 star rating and this one doesn't convince you then youre overthinkin it!! i strongly recommend you purchase these, worth the $190. especially if your into fitness and what not, and even if your not then these wont fail you. Get them!!! Again, i will update if if i have any problems, but i'm confident these will last me a good long while(knock on wood) :)

title: Mediocre sound quality; buy AirPods instead.
content:
The sound quality is mediocre, partially due to how the earpiece is designed. I’ve never used any earbuds with silicone tips that sounded good; very thin and tinny. I bough some foam ear pieces, which helped some, but they will not seat in my ear well enough to create decent sound isolation. The microphones for calls were also weak.

The app for controlling the EQ is laughably I adequate...6 pesets and no ability to save customizations (which with only 4 band eq, you’re already severely limited).  Connectivity is frustrating if paired to multiple devices; it will connect to one, then the other.

title: Great sound quality!
content: I bought these headphones to replace my Airpods. The sound quality is great and they fit snuggly in my ear. The left earpiece does come out of my ear if I am sweating a lot and/or after running for more than 30 mins. This does not happen with my right ear so I think the issue is with my ear instead of the design. After wearing them and noticing the issue with my left ear, I believe the Elite Sport would have been a better fit for me.

title: Great Wireless Earbuds
content:
Always on the go and having a lot of phone calls, owning a set earbuds had become essential. Being an apple guy I started to look at the airport. However, got turned off by the hard plastic feel and the feeling in my ear for a few hours. So I moved to the Jabra, especially for the silicone ear inserts and the sweat/water protection.
Pros
> great in ear comfort
> easy pairing with iPhone
> app
> call quality
> great music playback

Con
> earbuds tend to pop out when opening the charging  case. Would have been great to have some kind of magnet type hold the earbuds in the case.

title: Case
content: Case is horrible

title: Great product, poor Prime delivery
content: They sound great, fit well and hold a good charge. Recurring buzz in left ear but it goes away after reconnect. Pass through sound is a little strange but nice option.  Product is worth the money but the Prime delivery and support was terrible.  Not sure what's going on with the drivers but my deliveries keep getting lost and rather than free 2 day deliver I am waiting a week for redeliveries but I won't let that effect my rating of the product.

title: Maybe good for some sports but not for running.  They stutter/cut out mid-song
content:
I got these a couple days ago after being unhappy with the Apple Air Pods and returning them.  I wore them out of the box for a run tonight.  Left ear seems to fit fine but with my right ear I get feedback with every footfall---quite annoying.  That may be an adjustment issue.

What is less acceptable is, just like the Air Pods, these things cut and stutter.  The seem to lose their signal.  I wear my iPhone on a waist belt, which is not exactly too far from my ear.  If I can't resolve the problem I will return them.

For $200 these things need to be perfect right out of the box.

title: King of all true wireless earbuds
content: Over the past year since true wireless earbuds came to market. I have tried over half a dozen brands of their products. From Bragi Dash, Jaybird Run, Bose Soundsport Free, Zolo, Original Jabra Elite, Regular Jabra 65T and etc. I am very picky listener and user. The Jabra Active 65T is my favorite of them al by a mile. Excellent ID design, comfortable and audio quality. Sound very loud with lots of bass. Crystal clear sound with no disconnections. Chat quality is very very good. Better than the air pods I say. Thank you so much to the Jabra team who worked on this project to give us such a amazing product.

title: They Sound Great... Sometimes
content:
I've had these for about 6 months. Really enjoy the features, looks, and battery life - but have been disappointed with the sound quality at times. I'd say they sound great about 70% of the time, but I have constant issues with crackling/distorting the other 30%. I don't think it is related to a connection issue as it doesn't get better if I move my phone and/or re-position the earbuds. It sounds more like a blown driver or clipping, but the fact that I typically play them at low-ish volumes and that the issue is intermittent makes me think that they're not actually damaged. Seems to get worse as battery runs down.
I'd still recommend them to anyone looking for wireless earbuds, but I'm also taking a hard look at the soon to be released Sennheiser Momentum Wireless earbuds...

title: Great completely wireless ear pods...
content: I love how easy they where to pair, the sound is ok but wen talking on them to someone there is allot of back ground noise.. also being able to use Alexa is not the easy it's on the commercial..even with a galaxy note9... but all around I love them, awesome battery life, and so easy to just put in your ears and start enjoying ur music they easily connect as soon as you put them in your ear..

title: If AirPods don’t work for you, but these!
content: Easy to use, excellent features, good sound quality, and they won’t fall out of your ears!

title: No good in a noisy environment
content:
Bought these to pair with my phone/laptop (i'm on conference calls etc for work 5 hours a day, and wanted to untether).  HOWEVER i'm in an open plan office, and these headphones picked up neighbour colleagues conversations more clearly than my voice.  I have subsequently returned them.  liked everything else about these earbuds.

Positives:
-the dual device pairing works well (phone + laptop for me)
-hear through mode is really handy (although it doesn't work when primary pairing switches to laptop call)
-sound quality and battery life are very good
-easy and comfortable to use.

title: If you’re uncertain...
content: These earbuds are great! I was fortunate to have the ability to try before purchasing but to anyone that may be on the fence, they are worth the investment. The “HearThrough” feature is pretty cool and convenient. My only wish is that they had better mic quality when connected to my computer. Enjoy!

title: Great for sweaty workouts, out in public and relaxing listening
content:
Let me start by saying I have broken other earbuds from the amount I sweat during exercise. I use these all the time during my workouts with no issues.

At first when I got these I was not a huge fan of the sound. As updates came out everything I was struggling with was fixed. There was balance problems, fixed. Strange buzzing or slight disconnects, fixed. I am so glad that Jabra really cares.

The passthrough has to be my favorite feature as it allows me to listen yet be aware of my surroundings. This of course degrades the audio quality however can easily be toggled with a double click of the right bud.

The controls on the buds work great, but could be improved if they were touch pads. Having to mash headphones into your ear to complete actions is never fun. Thankfully these only require a light press compared to other brands I have tried.

I wish there was a better way to keep them in your ears. The large tips hurt, yet medium eventually work their way out of my ears. Be aware of this as there are no wings to help keep them in.

tldr;
Balanced audio quality
Sweet design
Great for exercise
Okay controls
Decent comfort
Good sound cancellation
Amazing passthrough audio
Nice app with EQ
Awesome battery life

These are worth it ;)

title: Extremely Impressive Sound, Especially EQ'd. Instructions Are Lacking
content:
First of all, the aesthetics of the Jabra packaging is exceptional, and similar in style, to how Apple packages their products (clean, minimalist, well integrated and very classy), which may only be important if you are giving them as a gift.

As far as a user manual goes, there are very minimalist line drawings of the pair, with abbreviated instructions on how to turn them on and how to use them (see photos). To kick start them, right out of the box, I placed them in my ears and simultaneously held down the left button on the left earpiece and the only center disc button on the right earpiece for 3 seconds, which turned them on automatically and activated voice prompts in the earbuds on how to pair them. Mine paired very quickly without doing a "scan" for devices on my Samsung. They popped up almost immediately in my "available devices".  And the strength and stability of the signal was very solid.

I found these to be very comfortable and snug in the ear and very stable in gym workouts. Their "in ear fit" is far better than competitive earbuds, which have different shapes and sizes of wing extensions designed to hold them in the ear. I have never liked those because they always seem to unseat themselves, especially when sweating. But not so with this new Jabra. High marks for fit, which also includes 3 alternate sizes of silicone attachments to fit different sizes of ear canals. I used the pair which came mounted on the earbuds.

There are also 4 directional microphones in each ear piece, which I found to produce a very natural sound when making phone calls. I asked those whom I called if they noticed anything different about the sound that they were hearing at the other end and they said, "No, your call sounds normal. Why?"  I explained that I was on earbud mics. So that feature passes the test. The multiple microphones are a part of Jabra's passive noise cancelling over-ride features. Primary noise cancelling occurs passively by virtue of the tight fit of the silicone attachments on the earpieces. But when you want to admit outside sounds for safety or personal reasons you can alter what these do, through a feature that Jabra calls "Hear Through" (which exists only in Jabra's Sound+ app download. For instance, to hear traffic outdoors on a bike or walking, or to be able to hear ambient room noise or voices, such as a P.A. announcements.

If you download the Jabra Sound+ app, you can manipulate your earbuds, on screen, with your smartphone. Some of the feature options in Sound+ are an equalizer, or controlling the way your voice sounds on phone calls, along with more advanced features, such as the aforementioned "Hear Through", which uses an onscreen slider to control how much of the outside sound is channeled through the headset, while listening to music. This phone app also controls default settings for phone use, and also to connect to Siri, Alexa, or Google. And the "Hear Through" feature is activated by a double press of the right earbud. Although music sounds much better without this feature activated, so I will use it rarely. One other feature in the Sound+ app, is the ability to engage or disengage auto pause when removing the earbuds and reinserting them, which is kind of a nice feature, in which you don't have to push any buttons on the earbuds when you take them out and put them back in.

All of the controls are on the small center discs on the outside of both earbuds. On the left earbud are 2 slightly raised "bumps", like those on the "home" keys (F and J) on a keyboard (see photos). The two raised button "bumps" control volume up/down and song "next/previous". To control volume you give quick successive presses which incrementally raises/lowers the volume with each quick press depending on which "bump" you are pressing. And to go back a song or forward to the next, you do long presses. To go back a song, long press the upper (left) button and to go to the next song, you do a long press on the lower (right) button.

The printed instructions (see photos) are erroneous for the right earpiece center disc control, which allows you to pause music and/or for phone calls. While music is playing a single press will pause for taking a phone call and then the instructions wrongly  indicate a double press to return to music. But that is not correct. To return to music, all it takes is another single press, which works as it should.  When I first started using them (due to the erroneous line drawing instructions) I tried to return to music with a double press, as directed, and nothing happened. When I tried a long press as an alternative, it disconnected me from BT, at which point I had to pair the set again in BT settings. So the instructions leave a bit to be desired in their lack of clarity or more in depth explanations. Subsequently I found out that the long press is meant to try to interface with the Jabra Sound+ app on my phone, in order to activate and control "Hear Through" and other features in the app.

And while I was first testing these, with the various button pushing steps above, at one point the volume dropped to a whisper and no matter what I tried, I could not get it to come back up to normal. After some research, which is not apparent in any printed instructions, I realized that it was due to me long pressing the right earbud button, which tried to access the Sound+ app on my Samsung. But since I had not yet downloaded Sound+, the earbuds went into a state of obvious confusion, and apparently dialing the music down in order to be able to "Hear Through". So, by un-pairing and turning the headphones off and then reactivating and renewing BT pairing, they came back to normal.

Regarding battery life, which is claimed to be 5 hours, I have not yet tested these to that limit. But the charging and storage pod which comes with these is really slick. The pod itself charges with a short USB cord (included). On a full charge, you can recharge your earbuds, on the go, through two full re-charges. One thing that I was not able to determine is this. Obviously one wants to store the earbuds in the small hardshell charging pod, when not in use, but I suspect the pod is going to charge the earbuds at all times that they are inserted. So, if the buds are partially depleted and you would prefer that they not be "partially charged" just to put them away, in order to insure that you always have 2 "full recharges" available in the pod, then how do you do that. No way to tell. So I think the moral of that story is, that if you know you are going to be away from a USB charging point for an extended period, then I would fully charge the buds and then remove them from the charging pod and then let the charging pod fully recharge without the buds in them, and then take off to wherever you are going. The pod does alert you to the battery level in the earbuds themselves, when inserted into the pod, with a green LED that briefly shines when inserted, to indicate that they are already fully charged. And on the outside bottom of the pod is an LED indicator light which lets you know the level of charge left in the pod, by way of pulsing red or green (for full charge).

One can potentially run for 15 hours with a fully charged pair, along with the two 5 hour reservoir charges available from the pod. That is far better than most other brands but below industry leading Apple AirPods which offer up to 25 hours.  But for most purposes, I can't imagine that making much of a difference to most users, unless you plan on being "off the grid" for an extended time for something like a wilderness trip.

In order not to lose the short USB cord, when the pod is not charging, I will use a small cinch bag to store the cord and charging pod. A minor detail that Jabra might have considered including. However, if you lose this one, you can use other micro USB chargers since the Jabra cord appears to be a standard micro USB, such as the one on my Samsung phone (but not compatible with Apple USB cords).

These are IP55 rated, meaning they can handle wearing in the rain or during a sweat filled workout, which is arguably better than Apple AirPods, which are reportedly somewhat fragile on that count, not being able to tolerate excessive sweating. And if you are overly concerned about moisture, you can step up to the Jabra Elite Sport, for more the robust resistance to moisture.

Getting to the sound quality on these, I was very impressed overall. I am a real gadget freak and sound devices addict, with many different headphones and headsets, some of which I have received at no charge from Amazon's Vine Program in return for unbiased and honest reviews of items received. Having been in the music business for 15 years with a chain of very large nightclubs nationwide, I have a knowledge of and an appreciation for what constitutes great sound versus run of the mill. And for the last 30 years I have been an avid lover of AKG wired headphones from Austria, as the owner of 4 different models in their lineup. I judge all others by their quality of sound.

As background to that, I was extremely surprised at the depth and quality of the bass response on these. They sounded very natural, unlike Bose headsets which are way overdriven in the bass spectrum, making Bose sound muddy and boomy, as they usually are. The mids and highs on the Jabra are very acceptable, "out of the box". However, I never listen to anything at home or on the go, without engaging manual EQ. I despise most all devices or software "preset" EQ's. They absolutely suck and offer no semblance of great balance which is best achieved with a concave bell curve (i.e. a shallow "U").  All 3 component sound systems in my home are set up with hardware equalizers, in line with amps.

Same on my Samsung and my Apple Air 2. On my Samsung I use what I consider to be the best music player out there, which is "Rocket Player" from JRT Studios. I eventually removed two other players from my phone after extensive use and disappointment for various reasons...Player Pro initially and then PowerAmp...both in favor of Rocket Player. At any rate, Rocket Player has a 10 band equalizer in it, which I can manually set, when listening to music, depending upon what I am listening with, which in this case, of course were the Jabra buds. When you EQ these buds, it takes them to an entirely different level of sound, which you normally could not achieve without spending 2-3xs the price for wired headphones. So I have absolutely no complaints about the quality of sound that these deliver. Listening to them, I feel like I am wearing expensive wired headphones.
Other than the shortcomings in the user instructions, I am very impressed with this set of wireless headphones, because of their sound, and their stable fit "in the ear", in which I barely notice them being there. And I absolutely love the compact clamshell storage and charging pod. Small enough that you don't notice it slipped into your pocket.

I will be using these exclusively on the go, now, instead of two other compact wireless earbuds which I have. One is a Tenergy T20 headset, which has "wrap over the ear" arms and a "behind the ear" vinyl cord, to insure they don't fall off. The T20 is mediocre, (gave them a 3 Star rating due to extremely overdriven bass). The second set of earbuds to be abandoned, is my Jaybird X2 Sport wireless headset, which feature wings which twist into the ear to hold them in place (in a very awkward and unstable way) The Jaybirds had great sound when EQ'd, but I did not like the fit, which took a lot of fiddling with to get them properly seated. I did give the Jaybirds a 5 Star due to their great sound, but I much prefer this new Jabra Elite 65t, as truly exceptional.

Speaking of Jabra, in the past, I have also received a free pair of Jabra's Evolve 75 traditional headphones with microphone set in the Amazon Vine Program (designed for open office use for phone call usage). I gave them a dismal 1 Star rating because I could never get them to connect to my computer with the dongle that they provide, nor could I get them to connect by BT to my phone, which they were supposedly able to do. Never got a chance to test them in action. So it is refreshing to find that these are pretty much flawless

Purchase these. You will not be disappointed.

title: Love my Jabra Elite 65T
content:
I was replacing an older wireless headset when I discovered the Jabra Elite. I compared different models including the Apple Earbuds and finally decided on this model because of the style and sound.
The sound is awesome, the charging case is terrific and the downloadable Jabra app is cleaver. I love the mood sounds that come with the application, I actually use the Perfect Storm while on a plane to quiet out the sounds of people boarding.
The Jabra app allows me to tweak the earbud sound quality and whether or not I want background noise. And, when I take the Earbuds out of the case and place them in my ears they sync automatically with each other, and my iPad and the app.

title: Great pair
content: One of the best that I've purchased. The features and the sound quality are great. You can use either earbud to listen. Most of the other ones I tried would only function with say the left one if it was the master. The charger case is very nice. The headphones have Alex on them which is nice but I don't use much. It has a pass through feature to hear outside noise with them on

title: Not working good
content: No good

title: Crisp, clear, novel
content: These earbuds are pretty much perfect.  They are novel in that they are completely wireless and I like the charging station.  The sound is excellent.  Highly recommended.

title: Excellent for distance runners!
content:
This is actually my second pair of these headphones. I just couldn't pass up a good deal since my initial pair are *just now* starting to show a little age after a year of almost daily use.

I'm a distance runner and these are awesome earbuds. I love that there are no wires. They could be a little louder and they definitely don't cancel out much noise. I do wish they had the small tabs to hold them in place better but it's not terrible. I've run dozens of 6-13 mile runs and had no issues.

title: Excellent execution
content: Jabra's 3rd generation truly wireless earphones are excellently executed. One of the few, and my first Bluetooth 5.0 headphones, are IP55 dust and sweat resistant. Batteries last about five hours and the case provides two extra charges. They come with four microphones (two per unit) for excellent voice calls and noise conditioning. The earphones come with three sizes of ear tips and provide a tight but comfortable fit, with a closed design for passive noise cancellation. The sound is very natural and detailed. Through the companion phone app, there is a five-band equalizer. Earpieces are relatively light and stay on. I find it comfortable to wear through the day. The left earpiece has two controls for volume and tracks, the right piece has a single button for play/pause and calls. Pairing with an iPhone was straightforward, with good range and no drops. Newer phones with BT 5.0 can have better range and power efficiency. IPhone 8 and X supports BT 5.0, but not required. Works perfectly with older phones as well. It can connect to two devices at the same time. While the phone provides a battery indicator for the earphones, the Jabra Sound+ app provides detailed battery info, the five-band EQ, lets you select the voice assistant when pressing the multi-function button on the right earpiece: Siri or Google depending on the phone or Amazon's Alexa (Not yet enabled on iOS), and very neat features like HearThrough and Sidetone: HearThrough: While the headphones provide passive noise cancellation, HearThrough uses the microphones to let some of the external sounds in. This is turned on or off by double-tapping the multi-function button or through the app, which lets adjust the amount of audio through. Sidetone: When on a call, adjusts how much of your own voice is fed back through the earphones. Audio calls work great. With the four mics, it isolates wind noise. Then the little details is what makes these excellent earphones great. When taking the earphones off the case, they start pairing with the phone, and they turn off when back on the case. Then when the earphones are in close proximity of each other (ie in the ears) it resumes playing music. It pauses the music if one takes one of the earpieces off, and resumes again if back within a few seconds. The case is small enough to fit in one hand. It has an LED next to the charge port to indicate charge levels, and another indicator between the earpieces that indicates their charge. GN/Jabra is a Danish company that has been designing professional products for as long as I can remember, and their attention to detail and quality shows in this product.

title: Poor signal
content: Works well enough, except when my phone is in my pocket, technology is just not quite here yet. I do not recommend, stick with analog as long as possible..

title: It's ok.
content: Good sound quality but won't stay in ear.

title: An average pair of earbuds with some lousy design and usability issues
content:
They aren't bad for the price you pay for them. The sound quality is about average, and the battery life seems decent.

The issues are with getting them out of the case. Whoever designed and tested the case should go back to design school. The usability of the case absolutely sucks. The case is made of smooth plastic, with a tiny fingernail notch to open the case.  There are no gripping surfaces to hold the case and open it. So, it's always an adventure to get this thing opened, without the earbuds falling out. It also stands up vertically, and not horizontally, like another reviewer mentioned. Forget about opening these with one hand. The daily usability issues with the case make these earbuds less than desirable.

title: Well worth the money!!

title: Best on the market
content: Have been using for over a year. These are the best earbuds on the market. Some issues, like if I stand too close to a card reader on a bus, they stop working. But apart from that, they are fantastic

Pretty trashy earbuds. Buzz was constant when hering music. Could not get over the buzz when hearin my morning podcast. Cost $200+ but have the material and quality of a $80 earbuds. Very dissapointed

title: Excellent fit and acceptable sound quality, one major design flaw
content:
In terms of fit this is one of the better sets of earbuds I've tried and I've owned and tried quite a few. I usually have an issue with in-ears staying in my ears but these sit rock solid. They do not move a bit. Unfortunately, they have one major design flaw and I ended up returning them.

Sound quality would be ok. Nothing spectacular but acceptable even if you are used to high end headphones. You do need to test the different tip sizes to get the best sound. This was the first set of earbuds where I needed to go with the largest set of tips. With the medium size ear tips I was missing some bass.

But the main issue that made me return them was the imbalance between left and right speaker. If you look through the web you will find quite a few people complaining about the same issue: the left earbud is slightly too loud. This is particularly apparent when you have hear-through enabled. You end up hearing the noise floor primarily on the left side. This is why some people say that there is a hiss on the left earbud. But the problem is actually a consistent imbalance between left and right channels.

It appears that this is an issue on the hardware side. At least Jabra has not yet been able to correct that with a firmware fix, even though the issue has been reported ever since these came on the market.

The imbalance is minor and not completely off-putting. If you are a casual listener you might not even notice. And there are quite a few people who treat the problem by going into the accessibility options of the phone and correcting the imbalance there. But for earbuds that expensive I felt that this was a workaround I was not willing to take. So they had to go back.

title: Defective by design
content:
Six weeks after order the right bud dies.
- Search cell accessory/elex forums for this issue. The threads are incredible!
- This is a known issue for nearly two years.
- TWO firmware updates have been issued for correction, both ineffective.
- Amazon return window is 30 days. They'll e-mail you the GN warranty PDF and tell you "we have procedures.".
- Jabra GN warranty only covers 12 months.
- Several forums indicate warranty returns can't be expected to perform for more than 90 days and take a month to clear.
- The GN help desk is required to collect excessive owner/user PI.
- From one forum comment, "Buy the Bose," if only because the listed phone numbers on their "contact us" page are in SE Asia.

title: Perfect for everyday use or working out
content: Every once in a while the left earpiece doesn't connect/turn on automatically. Otherwise, amazing. Did a lot of research and tested airpods but feel like I got the best ear buds available.

title: Reasonable sound but uncomfortable fit for me
content: I wanted wireless earbuds. After reading reviews from a variety of sources, I bought the Jabra Elite 65t. I listen primarily to rock music. I found the sound a bit tinny on first listen but the application that comes with the earbuds allows for adjustments that ameliorated that. It’s a nice feature. For me, the main issue with these earbuds was comfort. After about an hour, it became uncomfortable to keep them in my ears. I never had that problem with Apple EarPods when I used them with foam covers. If the Jabras had been more comfortable, I might have kept them although they felt a bit loose and a little clunky in my ears, which are somewhat on the large side. The Jabra sound was pretty good with the adjustments. The Bluetooth connection was easy. I returned the Jabras and bought Apple AirPods. Their sound is good and the fit is comfortable for me.

title: Ear Anatomy is Key - Unfortunately Did Not Fit
content:
I truly wanted these earbuds to work out after much online research and assumed with multiple earbud tips that at least one size would fit my ears.  Unfortunately this was not the case.  These buds did not fit the my anatomy - did not stay securely in place - even after trying 2 of the accompanying multiple rubber tip sizes.  I could not get a tight, secure anatomical fit in the ear canal opening and the buds kept slipping and eventually falling out into my one of my waiting hands during a run or gym workout ... just didn't work for me.  Also, the earbud seemed generally larger and felt heavier than other buds I've seen/tried before this purchase.  Disappointing.

To be fair, the sound quality and technical features were very good, and the noise cancellation [choice] worked well to block out overhead gym music and traffic.  Also, setup and pairing time were extremely easy, short and efficient right out of the box - loved this aspect.  However, my 3 star rating was based primarily on the dominant ergonomics and design issue.

Earlier this summer, when these were first delivered, I was travelling extensively and simply did not pause to try the buds, so by the time I did open the box, it was a few weeks later.  Usually, I do check a delivered item immediately upon receipt just in case there's an issue.  Moreover, I wanted to give the buds several 'tries' before passing judgement, ... hoping that these would eventually somehow form to my ear opening.  Therefore, it's now too late to return.  My hope is to sell for a great low price online to try to recoup at least a bit of my cost, as I do think these will fit someone somewhere given the multiple earbud tips.

To note, a positive shout out to Jabra tech service; they were all great - professional, friendly, patient, and helpful.  However, understandably, they do not take returns when their product is purchased through Amazon.  If I would have purchased through Jabra, they may have exchanged for another Jabra model.  They did provide a discount for another Jabra product - unsolicited by me - which was very nice.  But, I will not be buying another earbud product from any company until I can sell these Jabra buds.

title: Competes well with my AirPods.
content: Have AirPods and several inexpensive Bluetooth ear buds. Stays in the ear the best. Pairs as well as AirPods. Louder than AirPods. I use the AirPods for phone calls as I think the mic may be better, but otherwise I am using these whenever I am active. Black Friday price was great.

title: Losing connection while moving
content:
I love everything about it except how it loses connection when I'm moving. I put my phone in my pocket or in my bag and just walking, while listening to my music.
It gets cutoff as you bounce.
I believe somehow the Bluetooth connection distance is really limited or just pretty weak so that it gets disconnected, leaving me with constantly loss of audio.
If I have my phone out, there is no problem.
I did call in for a support and there was a firmware available at that time.
Sadly the problem still exists...
Again, the sound quality and the fit of the earbuds are superb.
Come on, Jabra!

title: Worth it

title: Better than my AirPods
content: These things are awesome.  Fit good for workouts or running.  Great noise cancellation and sounds if you're traveling.  Absolutely awesome.

title: Had these for a while...
content: Sound quality it's better than my previously owned Bose. Battery life is great, but can start to irritate ear after long periods of use 3 Plus hours. Had these for about 3 months the branding is already starting to fade.

title: So far so good...but not perfect.
content:
In general I'd recommend these true wireless, especially to those seeking them for use during exercise. I run 5k every other day with mixed exercise on other days and these have been solid, never slipping, popping out or requiring adjustment during exercise. The sound quality is good, not great, but in line with expectations for a blue tooth set. I do note a couple of small issues that keep these a four star, rather than five star, product.

First they do cut out briefly from time to time. It's usually not more than a fraction of a second but it's noticeable and repetitive under certain circumstances. The left headphone also occasionally fails to connect when turning them on and requires they be returned to the charging kit to "reset" them.

Otherwise they've performed well.

I will also note that the accompanying software (Jabra Sound +) is quite good. The hear through mode works very well and the concentration modes (providing air tight white noise that almost kills ANY background noise) are quite remarkable.

With a firmware update or two these could be a near runaway winner.

title: Not enough bass
content: Not enough bass

title: Sound is quality
content: Sound is perfect and no cables and wires makes it much easier to train in

title: $200 for only a year of use?
content: These earbuds are amazing! ...while they last. After just over 1 year of use the left earbud has stopped working entirely and the right earbud will not hold a charge and dies without any warning. 3 weeks out of warranty. For the $200 that I paid at Bestbuy a year ago they should definitely last longer than one year. You will love these as long as they work though.

title: Designed to break
content:
These are fairly good. Price point is reasonable for this type of tech.

But major problems:
1. Soft touch silicone:  This shows fingerprints and it will liquify and turn tacky within a few years. Thus artificially shortening the life of the product. I don't know why manufactures are still overusing this material.

2. Hard-click buttons: Should have been touch sensitive or accelerometer tech. Your ear will HURT every time you have to press them.

3. Software features: Even in the short time I had them, Jabra modified how HearThrough works. Formerly, you could  modulate the volume louder or softer. Now you can't.

title: Best work out ear buds I’ve ever experienced.
content: I’ve had my Jabra Elite Active 65t for almost two months and I must say they are the best sports ear buds I have ever used.  I run 5 to 7 miles three times a week and right now it is hot and humid in Chicago.  I ask swear a lot when running or working out.  Yet, I have experienced no slippage from my ears, which I still find hard to believe as I check them while running but no movement.  The same applies for working out in the gym.  Sound quality is also excellent, as well as noise cancellations.  I also purchased the non-Active buds for work calls and I also give them an A+.

title: Su fácil conexión y lo prácticos

title: Persistent balance problem
content: I was tremendously happy with these earbuds for the first couple months of ownership.  I was pleased with the sound quality, noise isolation, and calling features.  A month ago, and abruptly, I started having an issue where the volume in the left ear was noticeably louder than the volume in the right ear.  There was a firmware update in mid-October that Jabra claimed would fix that problem.  To be clear, I didn't have this problem before the firmware update or for a couple weeks after installing it.  A quick search will reveal a number of people who are dealing with the exact same problem.  Before contacting Jabra I tried some of the steps suggested to remedy the problem, but none worked so I finally contacted Jabra online because I hate getting tech support over the phone.  It took a week to get a response, and when they responded they suggested the steps I had already tried.  When I wrote back to say that I had tried all of the suggestions and the issue, I got another email back a week later essentially saying "are you sure you followed the directions exactly", which I had on at least 5 occasions.  I responded to that email today and now I'm awaiting their response, which I hope will involve sending in my earphones for replacement.  I strongly suspect that this is a firmware type of defect and not hardware.  Occasionally I get a good balance when I first take the earphones out of the charging case, but it never lasts more than 10 minutes.  I often listen to podcasts with only one earbud when doing stuff around the house and I have to jack the volume up almost to the max to get a normal volume level.  I'll try to come back and make an update to this review with the outcome.  For now I'd say avoid this product, or at least search the issue and see comments from others about the problem.

title: Amazing and worth every penny
content:
I bought these cause I was looking for:

• good sound

These met all of my criteria and have really impressed me. The sound is good and the battery life is great. They’re fine for taking calls also - not as great as my Bluetooth for background noise cancellation but just as good as headphones. I have no complaints on this product and I’ve had them for about 3 weeks. I use them everyday for about 3.5 hours and only have to charge them ever couple of days as long as I store them in their case since it serves as a backup charger. The battery life is fantastic. I tried another cheaper version of a product like this on Amazon. I went by the reviews (4.5 stars) and $50 and I returned them because they would t last more than 1 hour after being charged. These stand out even more because of that point of comparison. I also love that they’re fairly discreet.

title: Buy them
content: Good headphones

title: Jabra Elite Active 65T COULD BE THE BEST....
content:
These true wireless headphones COULD BE the best in-ear option.  I've only used them for a few days now and here's my feedback:

PROS:
- Great sound quality
- Mic WORKS (THIS IS A BIG DEAL)
- Battery lasts
- Setup easy
- App/Customization is nice
- Snug in-ear fitting

CONS:

Seriously... if Jabra fixes the Cons (easy fixes) and these will be THE BEST!

I hope this is helpful.  Will provide an update if I decide to keep or send them back.

title: ATROCIOUS customer service
content:
This things have good sound quality for the few months they work. Then the left earbud will have some wiring issue that causes it to get staticky and cut out randomly.

Here's the real problem: Jabra's customer service is so bad that they'll never fix a single thing for you. I've contacted them maybe half a dozen times, and each time they send me an email saying something to the effect of "due to a high number of requests, we've gone ahead and decided to delete yours."

So if you get these headphones, realize that you're dealing with a company that likely won't ever support its product. Buy warranty services from some third party, because in my experience, the one you get from Jabra is worthless.

title: Easy To Use!
