title: Amazing pair of wireless earbuds, easily the best I've ever tried
content: Great sound quality, superb call quality, decent battery life, compact and well-designed charging case, strong / stable Bluetooth connections and nice on-bud controls. Some reviewers have had trouble with the charging case, finding it difficult to open. However, once you know the trick it's pretty simple (just squeeze the sides of the case and hold down before popping open the top). All in all, great value at this price point and indispensable for my use at work and on commutes. The companion app is reasonably good, though I only used it a few times at the start to configure all the settings the way I wanted them, and then I've not had much reason to open the app again for several months.

title: but easy to lose one or more of the ear buds ...
content: OK,  not loud enough,but easy to lose one or more of the ear buds as case lid is not tight enough, or at least in my case as i lost one on an airplane first time i used them..guess it was 'pilot error'

title: Best truest wireless earbuds
content: Been using this for 2 months and I love it! You can’t beat the value for sure.

title: Sound great but are uncomfortable to wear
content: They sound great but are uncomfortable to wear.

title: Great wireless headphones for the price.
content: They work just as expected. Only downside is that you lose some functionality when only using one headphone, but definitely not a deal breaker.

title: Great product...the time it worked and not to great Customer service
content: I loved these earbuds! They were so much better than the Airpods in sound but lacked in the microphone category so I give that point to the Airpods. Unfortunately the right earbud gave out after 2 months and I messaged Jabra about the situation and they responded the first week telling me how to trouble shoot the device (which did not work) then told me they would replace my ear but after I sent info (which i did)...then that was it. I've emailed them multiple more times but have not gotten anything else. Truly disappointed in such a company with an amazing product. Hope to hear from them soon.

title: Poor audio quality and no noise canceling
content: These were recommended to me as earbuds that won’t fall out of my ears.  They didn’t.  Unfortunately the sound quality, echo and noise canceling were nonexistent when using them in phone calls.  I really wanted these to work, but my colleagues all told me the audio quality was not good.  I have an iPhone 7S plus.  I also had the app from Jabra loaded on my device.  Returned them after using for 1 week.  I suppose I could have called Jabra and troubleshot them, just wanted them to work. They did work well with Audible and Amazon music, just not as a phone extension.  Thanks for the refund, will try Jabra again in the future.

title: Great for the gym or anywhere else
content:
I did some research before purchasing and these came highly recommended to use at the gym which is what I intended to use them for. I love these earbuds. They work wonders at the gym. They stay in place during a workout (with a few adjustments every 20 minutes or so). The sweat proof feature means I don’t have to worry on those days I’m drenched in sweat. The sound quality is great. I would like to be able to turn them up a little louder but the max volume they have is fine. They also do a good job with noise isolation. I see some reviewers saying the Jabras hurt their ears after a while and I can see how they might, but to me it’s no big deal. They are intuitive, simple to use, and well made. They synchronization between the two buds is perfect. Battery life is great. Call quality on both ends is good. There is no lack of good things I can say about these earbuds.
THINGS I DONT LIKE:
The control buttons on the earbuds to me are useless because when you press them you force the earbud into your ear canal which I find very uncomfortable; I would have preferred touch controls.
The earbuds are not held magnetically in the case and will fall out if the case opens up unexpectedly.
These are not Bluetooth 5.0

Other than that I cannot recommend these enough!

title: No disputing sounds quality - But massively uncomfortable
content:
I work on the phone, so I wear headphones for 8-10 hours at a time, with few breaks in between.  I've had three pairs of the wired (together) Bluetooth Bose Soundsport headphones prior to purchasing the Jabra Active 65t.  Consumer reviews slated Jabra as the top contender in Bluetooth in-ear headphones, so I bought them.  (The Bose Soundports were incredibly comfortable and had stellar sound quality, but ended up losing Bluetooth connectivity mid-call somewhat regularly, after a while... additionally, the clips that attach the cord to the back of your shirt are super poorly made, and before replacing each pair of Bose headphones, I probably bought 6-8 replacement clips.  I was tired of replacing clips, without which, the sound is muffled by the mic resting on your shirt collar, unless you hold the mic away from your clothes, at which point, you may as well be on a handset.)

Notwithstanding, there's no disputing the Jabra's sound quality, and I really like the "Hear Through" option, which engages the microphones on the ear buds to amplify the sounds around you, while you have the headphones in (great safety feature when wanting to walk/run, talk/listen to music, and still be aware of your surroundings).  The charging case increases battery life significantly, another positive feature.  The fact that you can customize the EQ is also a lovely option.

I love many things about these headphones, but the Bose are SIGNIFICANTLY more comfortable in-ear headphones.  Even on the smallest ear pad setting on the Jabra, I'm finding it increasingly difficult to sit with these headphones in for prolonged periods of time, not to mention that the act of putting them in/taking them out of my ears is actually becoming increasingly more painful by the day.

None of these headphones are cheap, so my primary complaint with the Jabra 65t's is the comfort (or lack thereof).  For that reason, I will not buy these again unless they redesign the in-ear pad section, and I would encourage others to keep looking unless you know they fit your ears like a glove.

title: Highly recommenced true wireless.
content:
I love my Jabra active 65T, and I use them daily. However,
1. The left ear broke down after 9 months- but luckily still under warranty and it was replaced. Still it was nerve racking.
2. I had to replace the tips with misodiko foam tips to get better isolation.

title: They dont work after the 3 month
content: The sound is lovely the battery life is great but this is the important part. After 3 months they die out. They start to bug out my left ear doesnt even sync to the right ear bud now. So there goes that $200.

title: High Quality, Comfortable
content: I have had these earbuds now for a couple of months and I LOVE them.  I also have a pair of Bose QuetComfort wireless over-ear headphone, which I thought could not be beat.  However, they are bulky and so I splurged on these based on reviews and personal recommendations.  I couldn't be happier and in fact, because of their size and ease of use, they have largely replaced use of my Bose.  They sound great and once you get used to the controls, they are easy to use.  I belive a person with large fingers, might find the subtleties of the buttons a bit challenging because I did at first, myself and I have very small fingers/hands.  With that said, the volume button is easy enough and if you want to stop the music, you just take one of the ear buds out and the music pauses - starting up again when you replace it in your ear, as long as you don't wait a long time.  The battery life is decent.  Certainly enough for a cross-country flight, but not nearly as long as the Bose.  The case that comes with it is compact and serves to charge up the buds when not in use, approximately two full charges in the case itself and you can charge the buds and case simultaneously.  Overall, I am extremely pleased with my purchase and bought another pair as a gift.

title: Doest nold a charge
content: Doesnt charge well

title: good product
content: no issues so far

title: Very Good Wireless Earbuds at a Reasonable Price
content:
I bought these earbuds because I was looking for wireless earbuds, I was tired of untangling corded earbuds. I read several reviews and these seem to foot the bill although I was a bit skeptical after reading several horrible reviews about these earbuds. I’ve used these for about a month and overall I’m very pleased with them. Listed below is what I like and don’t like about these earbuds.

What I like about these earbuds:
- Good sound quality – I’m no audiophile but the sound is crisp and clear.
- In-ear stability - I like how they fit in my ear, I have used them for about a month and I haven’t felt like the earbuds will fall off, they’re very stable.  Please note that at least 2 different women have tried using my earbuds and they WON’T fit them, they’re too big for them.
- Great battery life – I use them roughly 5 hours a day and they haven’t died on my once. I charge them daily just to make sure they’ll be ready to go the following day.

What I don’t like about these earbuds:
- Spotty Bluetooth - When I first got them, they paired without any issues to my cellphone (Huawei Honor 10 Lite). I charged them for the next day, in the morning, I could no longer pair them with the phone. I had to download the app to pair them with my phone. I’ve seen others complaint about this issue.
- Charging case – Very hard to open the case to charge the earbuds, also, there’s no indication on the case as to the percentage charging of the ear buds. If the earbuds have been fully charged, the light should remain green or red if they need charging.
- I have to adjust the sound every time I use them – They should be able to keep my sound settings from the last time I used them.
- Left earbud has to be turned “on” every time I use them – After I turn them on and pair them with the phone, I also have to turn “on” the left earbud as well. It’s annoying having to do this on a daily basis when I get ready to wear them, why can’t both earbuds turn on once you pair them?
- The mic – People have a hard time hearing me, I find myself speaking louder than I normally speak to resolve this issue.

title: Short life span
content:
Great product, when it works. The right earbud has a lifespan of about 3-6 weeks, before it will lose all volume. The left bud works great, but unfortunately that's not the one that's required for the set to work.

If you purchase these, don't use them often to ensure you get a long life out of them and GET THE WARRANTY because you WILL be using it.

title: Excellent true wireless earbuds
content: Very nice true wireless earbuds. Lots of features. Great sound. My daughter loves them.

title: Great sound, poor call quality
content: I bought these instead of the Samsung because I needed to connect to  multiple phones and devices.  I work in an open layout office and the person on the other line can hear background noise or conversations.  I would not recommend.  I will be purchasing the Samsung buds.

title: Manufacture support lacking if you experience issues
content: Headphones worked well, excepting fact that left headphone's volume is only at 75% or so of the right headphone ( tried switching ears to ensure this is a hardware error with headphones and not my hardware). Manufacture refused to provide a replacement, or a method to return product without cost to customer (me or you), though defect was reported within days of receiving product.

title: Great... when they work.
content: These headphones are great when they work. When they break, get ready for the pain. The Jabra customer service is atrocious. It takes days to get email replies (if at all). Multiple 30+ minute hold times to reach anyone customer service. The warranty form on their website doesn't work. Slow UPS ground shipping once they finally agree to take the product in on warranty. It's going to take 3-4 weeks to get a replacement if you need to use the warranty. It's just painful.

title: Excellent quality earphones, with a few issues
content: I've owned the Jabra Elite 65t earphones for almost 2 months now and overall I'm very satisfied. It was money well spent on a pair of truly wireless earphones, with excellent sound quality and more than decent battery life. Additionally, the build quality is quite good and they certainly don't feel cheap like many of the other earphones out there. However, I have a couple of minor gripes/complaints. First of all, the charging case is sturdy enough but feels like the top lid will break easily, as it doesn't close all that tightly. Second, I really don't enjoy the piercing high pitch tone that is emitted when you first place these in your ears. And finally, I wouldn't recommend these too much for outdoor walking/running/jogging as I get a lot of dropouts, as the sound cuts in and out while I'm moving around outside. However, this is somewhat dependent on the outdoor conditions and what type of material/fabric I'm wearing, and I also noticed that after I updated to the latest firmware (by using their official android app), that there have been about 50% less dropouts compared to before. To sum it all up, for anyone out there looking for great quality earphones with overall better sound (especially mids and bass) than apple's airpods, the Jabra Elite are a must buy :)

title: Same Problem Everyone Is Having
content: I cant keep the left earbud connected for the life of me. After I bought them I did the research, my bad, and every manufacturer has a lot of complaints about the same problem. I guess the technology just isn't there yet. I'll go back to my old Jaybird wired Bluetooth earbuds.

title: Woreless, nonstop audio cut out.
content:
First month worked great, sounded nice, held charge well, easy sync to bluetooth, isolated well without overtly giving the stethoscope effect that a corded noise isolation headset would do.

HOWEVER, after 3 month of ownership this product is essentially useless.  The Bluetooth connect quickly but audio cuts out every 2-3 seconds.  Doesn't matter the content, the product I'm connecting to, using inside or outside, near other wireless items or away from all interference.  I have used other Bluetooth headset on the same devices but have zero cutout issues with any of the headsets.  Just these Jabra earbuds.  Maybe it's a software update or something but there has been zero help from the company.  I've done the reset, battery drain and recharge, tried other devices, ect.  It's the headsets.  I want a replacement or refund and will go around the internet reporting this until this is fixed.  These cost too much to be worthless.

title: One of this years favorite purchases...

I like them better than my wife’s air pods. Fit in one ear was a bit painful in the beginning after long use (it was just in one ear, so I will chalk that up to me). Sound is great and the battery life has been solid. I purchased 2 more pairs as gifts.

title: Love them. Game changer
content: It's so nice to have true wireless earbuds. The one touch Amazon Alexa assistant is amazing, as is the ambient sound pass through. I sweat alot, and these things don't move a bit when running. No sweat gets in the air canal. Absolutely amazing. So glad I pulled the trigger on these

title: Compared to the AirPods...
content:
So I bought these as an alternative to the Apple AirPods. My review will use them as a basis of comparison.

The first thing to notice is that the case for these is considerably more bulky than the AirPod case. It doesn’t open as easily and the ear buds do not feel as secure in it.

The next thing to notice is that these fill your ear canal like ear plugs. There is an nice option in the app that allows you to “hear through” them, but it sometimes takes a minute for that feature to kick in when you first put them in your ears. This feature is not a default. You have to turn it on through the app. Otherwise, yes, they cancel out a lot of noise.

They seem to fit pretty snugly in the ear and even though they don’t have the longer stem like the AirPods do, the audio quality seems to be good when talking through them on the phone.

The “ear detection” seems to cheat a little as it sometimes activates just by being in your fingers. It also mean it sometimes won’t auto-pause when you take them out because it thinks it’s still in your ear when it’s actually in your hand.

The controls are a nice touch. The tapping of the AirPods is a slick feature, but has it’s limitations. Having a push-button in your right ear that you can press to play/pause or long hold to bring up Siri is kinda nice. The left ear has tiny volume buttons that you can also long hold to track skip forward or back. I admittedly don’t use them as much as you’d think I would since I got used to using the phone controls with the AirPods.

You can use them in just one ear as I often do. I use the right side typically though it seems like it might work left-ear-only as well.

Overall, I’m not sure that these are necessarily better than the AirPods, though there are a lot of things they do better such as the controls, noise cancelation and they don’t stick out of your ear as much.

If you are looking for an alternative to the AirPods then these are definitely what you are looking for. They are not always as quick to connect and not always as responsive, but they are close enough.

title: Great pair of great sounding headphones.
content: I wouldn’t call myself an professional audiophile, but I can still respect good sound quality. These headphones deliver great sound quality for various music types and frequency ranges. They were a bit uncomfortable at first, but I got used to them after 1-2 days. Stay in your ears throughout workouts and commutes. Bluetooth sometimes gets light interference from elevator and subway motors, but overall they stay connected at all times. Noise cancellation is not 100% but it’s pretty good. I’ve been told that the mic quality is very good on phone calls.

title: Not as great as I expected
content: I was excited to use these when I first took them out of the box since I believed it would be as comfortable and rival the Airpods. While these earbuds were hard to shake out and provide an exceptional noise-cancelling experience, this does not make up for my disappointment for the lack of sound quality and uncomfortableness the Jabra elites were for me. I would give these a 3-stars if I could, but the price is just way too high for a mediocre experience.

title: Great for listening, maybe not so great for phone
content:
Overall I'm very happy with this earbuds. The sound quality is great, I like the Jabra app that allows you to adjust the amount of ambient noise that is transmitted with your music, and I haven't had any issues getting them to connect to my phone.

I have two complaints: 1) the case is such a pain in the neck to open. They say you push this little tab and it will open - that doesn't work. I have to slide my thumb nails in the crack and push up that way. If I painted my nails this would ruin them and that would be annoying. 2) The microphone is too sensitive. I've used them a couple of times to talk on the phone and both people have commented on how loud all the background noise is. I was in the car and my daughter said that the turn signal was extremely loud. I was trying to cook dinner and even trying to be quiet with the pans and things, my mom was having a hard time hearing me. I can't find any way to adjust the sensitivity of the microphone.

As I mainly wanted these to listen to music while commuting and working out, it's not the end of the world. But it is a disappointment that something so expensive has this issue.

This resulted in me wanting to replace the left earbud. They had been dealing with this issue regularly. I placed my warranty order almost 3 full months ago and the shipping was just delayed for another month. This is the 3rd time the shipping has been delayed.

title: Great quality sound, fits small ears, case virtually impossible to open...

Definitely best pair of true wireless earphones I've ever had, but one major annoyance is the charging case. It's very difficult to open!!! It's like you need to find the perfect combo of pressure and patience to snap it open... Drives me nuts and I've destroyed my nails several times. Please improve this case Jabra!

title: Recommend buy
content: Great sound and the whole 9 yards

title: issues with Galaxy S9+
content:
Although I did not purchase from Amazon ( I got from AAFES):

I purchased the Jabra Elite 65T around 05 Jan and I have a Galaxy S9+, so here is my opinion based on scale 1=10:

(fit-9) they fit great straight out of the box. I had Bose which was not secure, however these really no issue.

(connectivity-1). The connection is my issue. Once you take them out of the case it automatically connects. 70% (do)-30%(dont). I notice the sound is off a bit, so either i verify with the app which shows if both buds are connected. Alot of the times one will not so I have to put both in the box and bring them out again. Running/walking-when using during work outs it constantly has a interruption sound (almost every 45 sec). I even had issues with it going out when the phone was in my left pocket. I moved it to my right and it minimized the connectivity interruptions. This happens when I run 5 miles or 2.

 Calls-I was able to walk maybe 10 feet away from my phone and the phone calls were sounding robotic. I even spoke with a Jabra customer agent and she says she noticed the robotic sound. I am in the process of trying her troubleshooting tips, and if it does not work I will send back.

(Music-6): Nothing special. The PowerBeats 3 were awesome for sound. Unlike the Jabra. They sound decent. They do have settings where you can make adjustments within the app. I have had them since like 5 JAN and this is the first time I have had to charge them. I used them off and on every day, but not really that long due to the connectivity issue.

For my final test, I had my wife use them with her Apple device and they worked fine. Music, calls,-worked fine. She walked upstairs around the corner, no issues...

title: Very big
content: They were to huge for my ear they kept falling out

title: Good sound quality but connection issue
content:
I used for a month, don’t know if it was my earbuds or others having same issue, mine was breaking up each time I connected, I contacted Jabra to get it fixed but they keep saying just reconnect from beginning. I did same for 6-8 times but never improved.
I was sitting still with phone in hand and still breaking, while working out most of the time Left earbud keeps disconnecting.
Finally I returned.

title: Great when working
content:
They are comfortable. have great sound, and with the sound app impressive base for buds.  And they won't be mistaken for a medical device. The controls three buttons do everything easily.  So it's all good so far.

Then after two months or so I realized the imbalanced sound was not my hearing or my source but the fading right bud.  It was replaced by Jabra. Good. Then when reading the manual I see that the case is supposed to have a light that indicates state of charge or if an upgrade is in progress. I don't have this and it turns out this will not be taken care of because it's almost six months old.

Great while it lasted

title: Too many problems for the price you pay
content:
I’ve has these headphones now for half a year and these are the pros and cons of them

Pros:
-ability to control when to sound cancel vs hear through
-customize audio
-stays in ear well

Cons:
-headphones randomly loses signal at certain places where likely there’s interference with bluetooth (did not have this issue with AirPods, and Powerbeats pro)
-the left ear being completely dependent on right ear being active and can’t function on its own causes many annoyances, need cause on you at all times if you lose signal with left
-mic is horrible, it heavily picks up background sound rather than your voice, many calls I’ve had people can hear my environment but not me at all! I had to bring my right ear piece down to speak, but then the left ear loses sound due to auto detection feature which you can’t turn off

I had high hopes for these headphones given its technology but am deeply disappointed with the price I paid given the cons are major issues.

title: Stopped Working
content: After six months left bud stopped working.  Seems to be a regular issue with the charging case.  While I understand things happen here is my issue.  Their customer service is terrible. when you email them it takes days to respond and when they do respond it is the same standard reply.  Calling them is a joke.  No one ever picks up the phone.  When they work they are great when they do not buyer beware.  I feel you can spend your money better elsewhere.

title: Amazing Earbuds
content: This are very loud and balanced earbuds. They are great for any watching, movies, music etc... They can get very loud too.

title: 2 month review
content: Ear buds have a hard time making contact when in the case and has issues charging. I left my ear buds at work to charge over night and when i got back to work the charge was the same as when I left. happens more than not. At first I thought that the charging case was not charged but then the next day I left the ear buds inside with the charging case plugged in to charge and same thing. Then I though that it cant charge because the charging case was not charged and cant be plugged in so I left the ear buds in the case with the case charged but not plugged in and same issue. Another thing is I am trying to use these at work so I want to be able to use one ear bud and not the other and be able to swap them out once one of them dies but these ear buds only work the left by itself and not the right one by itself. The right ear bud works by connecting to the left ear bud so you either have to use both ear buds or just the left one on its own. The app is amazing to use as it can tell you how much charge is left on the ear buds and you can edit the sound settings but its really inconvenient for me as I can only use the left one by itself. I am now planning to try out the apple air buds and am willing to lose sound quality for the ability to use either ear bud independently.

title: Didn't fit in my ear, pressing buttons hurt
content:
These seemed like a good choice, but unfortunately they were a bit too tight in my ear (even with the smaller buds on). And the design of the buttons is pretty poorly thought out, because to press down on them means pushing the earbud against your eardrum, which is very uncomfortable and even painful after 10-20mins wearing them. It would be much better to have the button on top or underneath, or be touch sensitive. Also, there was this buzzing sound in one of the earbuds which was annoying; I've heard this from others so it must be a quality control issue.

That said, the noise cancelling is better than competitors; it even sounded decent on the NY subway. But the discomfort they caused, and the buzzing fault, made these unwearable for more than 10mins.

title: Great fit compared to AirPods
content: I’ve tried several truly wireless earbuds including AirPods and Bose Soundsport Free. These are the best overall for me. I couldn’t deal with the size of Bose, even though the sound quality is better with better bass, they just look ridiculously large in my ears, and I have pretty big ears. I loved the convenience and build quality of the AirPods but they just don’t stay in my ears, even after using third party ear hooks to keep them in, they were still loose enough to not make a good seal and therefore sound quality, especially bass diminished compared to when I push them into my ears. The Jabras solve most of these problems, the fit is great and with three sizes of gel tips they should fit most people. Sizewise, they are mush smaller than the Bose, even smaller than I had hoped. They really don’t stick out much at all, and I’m happy with the color compared the white AirPods. Sound quality is decent, but not as good as the Bose. I’m knocking off half a star for somewhat anemic bass, though it is nice that this can be tweaked to a degree using the built in equalizer in the companion app. Also knocking off half a star for build quality, not that I’ve had any issues but they just feel a little “plasticy” compared to the two other brands. I live in an Apple world, so everything gets compared to their fit and finish and to be honest very little stacks up. That being said I don’t foresee any issues. The case is a decent size, not too big, but not as small as AirPods. Considering this I would like to see more than two full charges from the case, but so far battery life seems to be fantastic. Too early to tell, but so far I’m seeing less battery consumption on my commute than the AirPods (I didn’t keep the Bose long enough to judge). I’ve only made a couple of calls, but the first one I made, at the end of the call I asked the person on the other end how I sounded and they were shocked that I was using a headset. Can’t ask for any better than that. Pairing is super easy and I was happy to discover you can be connected to two devices at once, similar to Bose. I also have QC35,s and rally like this feature. Battery indicator shows on iOS lock screen for the buds but not the case, score one for AirPods. There is a small light on the case indicating charge level, score one for Jabra. I also like some of the features of the companion app, you can tweak the sound and save profiles for various environments, normal, commute, focus etc. Thers als o a cool feature I may not ever use where can just turn on ambient sounds, anything from white noise to nature (so far crashing waves is my favorite) to busy street sounds (not sure who this is for). In summary, if you’re looking for truly wireless earbuds with the best all around features give these a try. I got them on sale for 129.00 and feel like that’s a real bargain compared to the competition.

I guess this is the problem just with mine earbuds since nobody else mentioned it but still I have to give 2 stars for Jabra pure quality control. Ordering from Amazon in my country cost arm and leg so not sure if it even make sense to return these for replacement (if I have to pay for shipment expense again than it will cost almost as new pair of same earbuds).

UPDATE: I’ve just read reviews on amazon.co.uk. There are two verified buyer confirming same problem (uneven balance) and also crackling sound in loud environment in left (louder) earbud when pass through is enabled. Both buyer asked for replacement and in one case same problem was present again from beginning and in other case problem appeared after 5 days of use.

Jabra please stay on top of this. Headphones are great but this is clearly problem with production and QA that you need to resolve. Just asked for replacement so I am hoping to get working pair. Will update review once I get them but this is not good. Cases from amazon.co.uk  are suggesting there is possibility of wrongly put together beach of earbuds.

UPDATE 2: I've received replacement pair and it still has more or less same problem. Maybe it has something to do how sound is delivered to the ear canal that is different for some people.  I don't have same problem with any other earphones. Also problem with crackling sound in loud environment in left (louder) earbud when pass through is enabled, still persists.

The charging case fell into some kind of bricking state where it would not charger the Buds, I left the case like this for two days to wait for the battery to die in the case.

After a while my Buds died completely and i hadn't heard back from Jabra support so i ended up opening up the case (very easy to do from the inside as the piece where the buds sit on is rubber and can be pulled out. once i could see the internals the clip for the battery was very obvious and easy to get to, so with some tweezers I disconnected the battery from the board and reconnected it and all was well.

hoping this might help someone else!

title: Great Ear Buds - Use them for workouts as well as at work
content:
I have found these to be very easy to use, I really like the pass through mode, which enables me to have conversations with people and listen for gate announcements at the airport, even though I'm listening to music.  If you have nothing playing and pass through is enabled, you will hear a hiss because it is amplifying background ambient noise.  Just turn off the pass through if it annoys you.  I also like the fact that the earbuds pause playback when you take an earbud out.

I had no problem pairing them with my Galaxy S9+, and haven't had any dropouts and the range is better than 30 ft. No issues either with left and right earbuds not connecting.  I have paired it with my W10 laptop and Chromebook, but I found that if I'm connected to 2 devices at once, then the controls on the earbud don't seem to work predictably.

 The buttons are easy to get used to and I can easily pause playback, control volume, answer calls, etc.  I don't find it painful to press the buttons, unless one of the really long press actions.

The fit seems to be pretty good for me.  During my cardio workouts I sweat a lot and I haven't had any issues with them falling out.  The only time I had an issue was after I worked out and I was stretching and my head was basically sideways and the lower earbud felt very loose.

The case seems rugged and easy to use.  Earbuds drop right in and start charging.  I have dropped the earbuds while taking them out and they seem OK, but I worry about the plastic shell.

The app is pretty good, I like the equalizer.  I had to turn off notifications for the app though because it was annoying to have 2 non-urgent notifications displayed all the time.  I would like to have a little more control of the notifications that are displayed - i.e. only display an icon for things like low battery warning.

All in all, I love them.  Comfortable, sound great, nice usability features.
